nodes.label: Men Living to Age 65 (Percentage)
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of baby boys born in a given year are expected to survive to their 65th birthday based on current death rates. Higher percentages indicate better healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions for men throughout their lives. This matters because longer life expectancy reflects overall quality of life and the effectiveness of a country's health and social systems.

nodes.label: Young Boys Population (Ages 0-14)
nodes.description: This counts how many boys and young males between birth and 14 years old live in a country. Higher numbers indicate more children, which often means the population is growing quickly. A large young population can create opportunities for future economic growth but also requires major investments in schools and healthcare.

nodes.label: Young Girls Population (Ages 0-14)
nodes.description: This counts how many girls and young females between birth and 14 years old live in a country. Higher numbers indicate more children, which often means the population is growing quickly. A large young female population represents future potential but requires investments in education and healthcare to ensure opportunities.

nodes.label: HIV and Sex Education Programs - Upper Secondary Schools
nodes.description: This measures the availability and implementation of HIV prevention and sexual education programs in upper secondary schools (grades 10-12). Higher values indicate more comprehensive programs are available to students. These programs help teenagers make informed decisions about their health and relationships, reducing risks of disease and unplanned pregnancies.

nodes.label: Elementary Schools with HIV/AIDS and Sex Education Programs (%)
nodes.description: This tracks what percentage of elementary schools offer health education programs covering HIV/AIDS prevention and sexual health topics. Higher percentages indicate better health education coverage. These programs matter because they help children learn important information about staying healthy and making safe decisions as they grow up.

nodes.label: School Support Programs for HIV/Sex Education - Middle School
nodes.description: This tracks whether middle schools (grades 7-9) have support programs that provide HIV prevention and sexual health education. Higher availability of these programs is better because they help students make informed decisions about their health. Quality health education in schools reduces risky behaviors and helps students stay healthy during their teenage years and beyond.

nodes.label: Boys' Expected Years in Primary School
nodes.description: This estimates how many total years boys are expected to spend in primary and lower secondary school (grades 1-9) based on current enrollment patterns. Higher numbers indicate boys are staying in school longer. More years of education help boys develop better reading, math, and thinking skills for future success.

nodes.label: Years Boys Spend in Elementary School
nodes.description: This measures the average number of years boys are expected to spend in elementary school over their lifetime. Higher values are better, typically ranging from 0 to 6+ years, indicating boys are getting more basic education. More years in elementary school helps boys develop essential reading, writing, and math skills needed for success in later grades and adult life.

nodes.label: Expected Years of Education Beyond High School for Males
nodes.description: This estimates how many years of post-secondary education (college, university, or technical training) a male student can expect to complete in their lifetime. Higher values indicate better access to higher education and more opportunities for advanced learning. Extended education beyond high school typically leads to better career prospects and higher lifetime earnings.

nodes.label: Expected Years of College for Women
nodes.description: This estimates how many years women can expect to spend in tertiary education (college, university, or vocational training) during their lifetime. Higher numbers indicate better access to higher education for women. When women pursue higher education, they gain skills for better careers and contribute more to economic growth and innovation.

nodes.label: Expected Years of Primary Schooling for Girls
nodes.description: This measures how many years of primary education a girl can expect to complete based on current enrollment patterns in her country. Higher numbers are better because they indicate girls are likely to spend more time learning fundamental skills like reading and math. More years in primary school give girls a stronger foundation for future learning and better life opportunities.

nodes.label: Expected Years of Post-Secondary Education for Women
nodes.description: This estimates how many years of post-secondary education (after high school) a girl can expect to complete in her lifetime, based on current enrollment patterns. Higher values indicate women have more opportunities for advanced education like college or vocational training. This matters because post-secondary education leads to better career opportunities and higher incomes for women, promoting gender equality.

nodes.label: Expected Years of Post-Secondary Education
nodes.description: This measures how many years of education beyond high school (like college, university, or vocational training) a student can expect to complete in their country. Higher numbers indicate better access to advanced education and training opportunities. More post-secondary education typically leads to better job prospects and higher incomes for individuals and economic growth for countries.

nodes.label: Nurses and Midwives per 10,000 People
nodes.description: This measures how many nurses and midwives are available for every 10,000 people in a country. Higher numbers mean better healthcare staffing - for example, 50 means there are 50 nurses and midwives for every 10,000 residents. More nurses and midwives typically means better healthcare access and maternal care for families.

nodes.label: Child DPT Vaccination Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of children ages 12-23 months who received the DPT vaccine, which protects against diphtheria, whooping cough, and tetanus. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages mean more children are protected from these dangerous diseases. This matters because vaccination prevents serious illness and death, keeping children healthy so they can grow and thrive.

nodes.label: Polio vaccination rate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of one-year-old children have received all three required polio vaccine doses. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are much better and indicate stronger disease prevention. High vaccination rates protect children from polio, a serious disease that can cause paralysis.

nodes.label: 1-Year-Old Boys Population
nodes.description: This measures how many boys are exactly 1 year old in a country. Higher numbers indicate more male toddlers, which helps governments plan for early childhood services like daycare and pediatric healthcare. This data is important for understanding population growth and planning family support services.

nodes.label: Male Population at Age 0 (Newborns)
nodes.description: This counts the number of newborn baby boys (age 0) in a country, with missing data filled in using statistical methods. Higher numbers indicate more male births. This data helps governments plan for pediatric healthcare, childcare services, and future school enrollment needs.

nodes.label: Number of 2-year-old boys
nodes.description: This counts how many male children are exactly 2 years old in a country, with estimates filled in for missing data years. The number reflects recent birth rates and early childhood survival. Tracking toddler populations helps governments plan for childcare, early education, and pediatric healthcare services.

nodes.label: Male Population at Age 24
nodes.description: This counts the number of 24-year-old males living in a country, with missing data filled in using statistical methods. The number reflects the size of this specific age group. This data helps governments plan for services like higher education, job training, and military service that typically affect people in their mid-twenties.

nodes.label: Male Population at Age 8
nodes.description: This counts the number of 8-year-old boys living in a country, with missing data filled in using statistical methods. The number reflects the size of this elementary school-age group. This data helps governments plan for primary education services, school facilities, and programs that serve children in early elementary grades.

nodes.label: Number of 5-year-old boys
nodes.description: This counts how many male children are exactly 5 years old in a country, with estimates filled in for years when exact counts weren't available. The number reflects birth rates from 5 years ago and child survival rates. Tracking specific age groups helps governments plan for schools, healthcare, and other services children need.

nodes.label: Number of 9-year-old boys
nodes.description: This measures how many boys are exactly 9 years old in a country. The number reflects birth rates from about a decade ago and can help predict future school enrollment and workforce needs. Higher numbers indicate a larger young population that will need education and jobs in the coming years.

nodes.label: Number of Rural Residents
nodes.description: This counts the total number of people living in rural areas (countryside and small towns) rather than cities. The number depends on both total population and how urbanized the country is, with higher numbers in larger or more rural countries. Rural populations often have different needs for infrastructure, healthcare, and economic opportunities compared to city dwellers.

nodes.label: Total Population
nodes.description: This counts the total number of people living in a country at mid-year, regardless of citizenship status. The number includes everyone physically present in the country. This matters because population size affects everything from economic potential and political influence to resource needs and environmental impact, serving as the foundation for most other social and economic indicators.

nodes.label: Number of Households
nodes.description: This measures the total number of households (families or people living together) in a country or region. The values are in absolute numbers, so higher values mean there are more separate living units. This helps governments plan for housing needs and understand family structures in society.

nodes.label: Population Count per Person
nodes.description: This measures population data expressed on an individual basis for statistical analysis. The values help researchers compare population-related statistics across different groups or time periods. This type of population measurement is important for understanding demographic trends that affect how resources and services are distributed to improve people's lives.

nodes.label: Human Capital Development Index
nodes.description: This measures the knowledge and skills of a country's workforce, based on average years of education and how much those skills contribute to productivity. Higher scores indicate a more educated and skilled population. Countries with higher human capital tend to have stronger economies and better job opportunities for their citizens.

nodes.label: Number of Girls Ages 10-14
nodes.description: This counts the total number of girls between ages 10 and 14 living in a country. Higher numbers indicate a larger population of young females entering adolescence, which affects planning for schools, healthcare services, and future workforce development.

nodes.label: School Attendance Rate - Rural Areas, Upper-Middle Income Families
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of children from upper-middle income families in rural areas actually attend school at the appropriate age. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages mean more children are attending school regularly. High attendance rates indicate that even in rural areas, families with decent incomes are successfully sending their children to school.

nodes.label: Girls in Job Training Programs (Secondary Level)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls in secondary school are enrolled in vocational or technical training programs that teach specific job skills rather than general academic subjects. Higher percentages mean more girls are getting practical training for careers. This matters because vocational training can lead directly to employment and help reduce gender gaps in the workforce.

nodes.label: Housing-Related Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of people's income comes from housing, such as rental income from properties they own. Values are expressed as percentages, with higher numbers meaning housing is a bigger source of income. This indicator shows how important real estate investment is for people's financial well-being in a country.

nodes.label: Tertiary Education Academic Performance Ranking
nodes.description: This shows how students in higher education (college/university) perform on standardized tests compared to international benchmarks, expressed as a percentile ranking. Higher percentiles (closer to 100) mean better academic performance compared to other countries. Strong tertiary education performance indicates a country is developing the advanced skills needed for economic competitiveness and innovation.

nodes.label: High School Graduation Tracking
nodes.description: This measures a country's ability to track and report how many students successfully complete high school. Higher values indicate better data collection and monitoring systems. Good completion monitoring helps governments identify problems and improve education policies to help more students graduate.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate - Rural Wealthy Students (After Middle School)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of students from the wealthiest families in rural areas enroll in college or university after completing middle school (grades 7-9). Higher percentages are better, showing more equal access to higher education. This matters because it reveals whether rural students from wealthy families can overcome geographic barriers to pursue advanced education that leads to better career opportunities.

nodes.label: Share of city residents living in largest city
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of all urban residents live in the country's biggest metropolitan area. Higher percentages indicate more concentration in one major city, while lower percentages suggest more balanced urban development across multiple cities. Extreme concentration in one city can create overcrowding and inequality, while more balanced urban growth often provides better opportunities across regions.

nodes.label: Price Comparison Category 404
nodes.description: This represents a specific category of goods or services used to compare prices and living costs between different countries. The values help economists make fair comparisons of economic conditions. This matters because understanding real price differences helps determine actual living standards and economic well-being across nations.

nodes.label: Teacher Hiring Process
nodes.description: Measures whether teachers are hired based on merit and qualifications or through political connections and favoritism. Higher values indicate more merit-based hiring. Qualified teachers improve education quality, helping students develop skills needed for better jobs and higher living standards.

nodes.label: Teacher Hiring Politics (Original Scale)
nodes.description: Measures how much political connections versus merit determine who gets hired as teachers, using the original survey scale. Higher scores typically indicate more merit-based hiring rather than political favoritism. This matters because fair teacher hiring helps ensure quality education and reduces corruption in schools.

nodes.label: Girls' Education Progress Measure
nodes.description: This measures progress in girls' education access and outcomes, though specific methodology varies by country. Higher values typically indicate better educational opportunities for girls. This matters because educating girls benefits entire communities through improved health, economic growth, and social development.

nodes.label: Primary School Teachers
nodes.description: This counts the total number of teachers working in elementary schools, including both full-time and part-time educators. Higher numbers of teachers generally mean smaller class sizes and better education quality. This matters because having enough qualified teachers is essential for giving children a good start in education and building a skilled future workforce.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Elementary Teacher Training
nodes.description: This compares training rates between male and female elementary school teachers. A value of 1.0 means equal training opportunities, while values below 1.0 indicate male teachers receive less training than female teachers. Equal training ensures all teachers can effectively help young students learn to read, write, and develop other essential skills regardless of the teacher's gender.

nodes.label: Government Services Cost Component (US Constant Prices)
nodes.description: This measures the cost of government services using constant US dollar prices to allow fair comparisons across time and countries. Higher values indicate higher costs for government services. Tracking these costs helps determine if governments are spending taxpayer money efficiently.

nodes.label: Economic Efficiency Level
nodes.description: This measures how efficiently a country uses its workers, machines, and resources to produce goods and services, compared to the United States (set at 1.0). Higher values mean the country is more efficient at turning inputs into outputs. This matters because more efficient economies can produce more wealth and higher living standards for their people.

nodes.label: Government Price Comparison Component
nodes.description: This is a technical component used to compare the cost of government services across different countries, helping economists determine how much government spending actually buys in each place. The values help adjust for price differences between countries. This matters because it allows fair comparisons of government efficiency and public service delivery across nations.

nodes.label: Cooling Degree Days
nodes.description: This measures how many days per year the average temperature is hot enough (above 65°F/18°C) to require air conditioning or cooling. Higher values mean hotter climates that need more energy for cooling buildings. This helps predict energy demand and costs, and shows how climate affects people's daily comfort and energy bills.

nodes.label: Energy efficiency of the economy
nodes.description: This measures how much energy a country uses to produce each dollar of economic output. Lower numbers are better, meaning the country produces more wealth while using less energy. This matters because energy-efficient countries have lower costs, less pollution, and more sustainable economic growth.

nodes.label: Primary Income Payments to Foreigners
nodes.description: This measures money flowing out of a country to pay foreign workers and investors, including wages paid to non-citizen employees and profits sent to foreign companies that invested locally. Higher values mean more money leaving the country to compensate foreigners. This matters because large outflows can reduce the income available for domestic spending and investment.

nodes.label: Gross National Income - Atlas Method, Current USD
nodes.description: This measures the total income earned by a country's residents from all sources, calculated using a special method to reduce currency fluctuations. Values are in current US dollars, with higher amounts indicating greater national wealth. Higher GNI means more resources available for healthcare, education, and infrastructure that improve citizens' lives.

nodes.label: Gross National Income per Capita (2015 constant dollars)
nodes.description: This measures the average income earned by each person in a country, adjusted for inflation using 2015 as the base year. Values are in US dollars, allowing comparison across countries and time. Higher values indicate greater prosperity and living standards, meaning people can afford better housing, healthcare, education, and other necessities.

nodes.label: Gross National Income - Current US Dollars
nodes.description: This measures the total income earned by a country's residents in a year, including money earned from other countries, expressed in current US dollars. Higher amounts generally indicate a wealthier country with more resources available for its people. GNI is important because it shows how much economic value a country generates, which affects living standards and government services.

nodes.label: Refugees Seeking Protection in This Country
nodes.description: This counts the number of refugees living in a country who are officially recognized and protected by the UN refugee agency. Higher numbers may indicate either that the country is generous in accepting refugees or that there are more conflicts in nearby regions. Countries accepting refugees provide safety for people fleeing war or persecution.

nodes.label: Food exports as share of total exports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total exports are food products like crops, meat, and beverages. Higher percentages mean the country relies more heavily on selling food to other nations for income. This indicates how important agriculture is to the country's economy and trade relationships.

nodes.label: Import Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total spending goes to buying goods and services from other countries (imports). Values are expressed as a decimal (like 0.25 = 25%) where higher values mean the country relies more heavily on foreign products. This indicator shows how connected a country is to the global economy and how much it depends on trade.

nodes.label: Exports as Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total economic output comes from selling goods and services to other countries. Values are shown as percentages from 0% to over 100%, and the ideal level varies by country size and development stage. Countries that export more tend to have more diverse economies and stronger international connections, which can boost economic growth and job creation.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 13
nodes.description: This tracks how much money households spend on a specific category of goods or services, measured through international price comparison studies. Higher values mean people spend more on this particular category. This helps understand living standards because spending patterns show what people can afford and prioritize in their daily lives.

nodes.label: Price Comparison Category 40041
nodes.description: This represents a specific category of goods or services used in international price comparisons, helping economists understand cost-of-living differences between countries. The exact category varies but enables fair economic comparisons. This matters because accurate price comparisons help determine real living standards and economic conditions across different nations.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category (Recreation and Culture)
nodes.description: This measures how much households spend on entertainment, sports, cultural activities, and recreational goods as part of international price comparisons. Higher values indicate families can afford to spend more on leisure activities. This matters because recreational spending reflects whether people have enough income beyond basic needs.

nodes.label: Recreation and Culture Spending
nodes.description: This tracks how much households spend on recreational and cultural activities like entertainment, sports, books, and cultural events as part of international price comparison studies. Higher spending indicates more discretionary income for leisure activities. This matters because spending on recreation and culture reflects higher living standards beyond basic needs.

nodes.label: Poverty Gap at $3.65 per Day
nodes.description: This measures how far below the poverty line of $3.65 per day poor people's incomes actually fall, expressed as a percentage of the poverty line. Higher values mean the poor are much poorer, not just slightly below the threshold. This indicator shows the depth of poverty in a country, which determines how much support people need to escape poverty.

nodes.label: Women's Property Rights Score
nodes.description: This measures how well a country's laws protect women's rights to own, inherit, and control property like land, houses, and businesses, scored from 0-100. Higher scores mean women have more equal property rights, which is crucial for economic empowerment and reducing gender inequality.

nodes.label: Average Household Wealth per Adult
nodes.description: This shows the typical amount of wealth (assets minus debts) that each adult in a household owns, including homes, savings, and investments. Values are in the local currency, and higher numbers indicate greater financial security. Higher household wealth means families have more resources to weather economic hardships and invest in their future.

nodes.label: Executive Theft from State (Average)
nodes.description: Measures how often the chief executive steals from the government, averaged across multiple expert assessments. Higher values indicate more frequent theft by top leaders. Executive corruption diverts public money away from essential services like schools and hospitals that benefit citizens.

nodes.label: Business Enterprise Income (Individual)
nodes.description: This measures income that individuals earn from owning or operating their own businesses or enterprises. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate more successful business ownership. This matters because entrepreneurial income contributes to economic growth and individual financial independence.

nodes.label: Non-Corporate Business Income (Individual)
nodes.description: This measures income that individuals earn from businesses that are not organized as corporations, such as sole proprietorships or partnerships. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate more successful small business ownership. This is important because small businesses are key drivers of employment and economic growth.

nodes.label: Minimum Wage Policy
nodes.description: This measures whether a country has minimum wage laws and policies to protect workers from extremely low pay. Higher values indicate stronger minimum wage protections for workers. This matters because minimum wage laws help ensure working people can afford basic necessities and maintain a decent standard of living.

nodes.label: Political Equality in Health Data Availability
nodes.description: This tracks how much data is missing when experts try to assess whether all groups have equal access to healthcare and health-related political representation. Higher scores mean more missing data, indicating less reliable information about health equality. Good data coverage helps researchers and policymakers understand and address health disparities.

nodes.label: Opposition Groups: Average Size
nodes.description: This measures the average size of organized political opposition groups that challenge the current government. Higher values indicate that opposition groups tend to be larger and potentially more influential. This matters because strong opposition groups help ensure competitive politics and give citizens alternative political choices.

nodes.label: Data Quality: Opposition Parties in Legislature
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when experts were asked about opposition parties' ability to participate in the legislature. Higher values indicate more experts couldn't provide answers, meaning less reliable data for that country-year. This data quality indicator helps researchers assess how confident they can be in scores about legislative opposition party participation.

nodes.label: Data Coverage: Opposition Group Size
nodes.description: This measures how often V-Dem experts were unable to provide information about the size of opposition groups in a country. Higher values indicate more missing data, not stronger opposition. This matters because missing data makes it harder to assess how well opposition groups can challenge those in power.

nodes.label: Equal Passport Rights for Women
nodes.description: This measures whether women can apply for passports using the same process as men, scored as 1 for yes and 0 for no. A score of 1 (yes) indicates gender equality in travel rights, while 0 means women face additional restrictions. Equal passport rights are important for women's freedom to travel for work, education, or personal reasons.

nodes.label: Human Development Index
nodes.description: This combines measures of health (life expectancy), education (years of schooling), and income into one score from 0 to 1, where 1 is the highest possible human development. Higher scores mean people live longer, are better educated, and have higher incomes. This is important because it provides a comprehensive view of whether people's overall quality of life is improving.

nodes.label: Average Government Education Spending per Person (Adults 20+)
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on education for each adult aged 20 and older in the country. Higher amounts, measured in local currency, indicate more investment in educational programs and institutions. Greater education spending typically leads to better schools, more educational opportunities, and higher skill levels in the population.

nodes.label: Median Healthcare Spending per Person
nodes.description: This measures the middle amount that people in a country spend on healthcare expenses like doctor visits, medicines, and hospital bills. Values are shown in local currency, and higher values mean people are spending more on healthcare. This matters because it shows how much families need to budget for staying healthy and getting medical care.

nodes.label: Workers' Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total economic output goes to workers as wages and benefits, versus what goes to business owners and investors as profits. Values typically range from 40-70% in developed countries, with higher values meaning workers get a bigger slice. This matters because it shows whether economic growth benefits workers or primarily enriches capital owners.

nodes.label: Workers' Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of the country's total income goes to workers as wages and salaries versus going to business owners and investors as profits. Higher values mean workers receive a larger share of economic output. This matters because a higher labor share typically means better wages and living standards for working families.

nodes.label: Average Worker Pay
nodes.description: This measures the average total pay that workers receive, including wages, salaries, and benefits like health insurance. Values are shown in dollars or local currency per year, where higher amounts mean workers are being paid more for their labor. Higher compensation indicates workers can better afford housing, food, and other necessities for a good quality of life.

nodes.label: Domestic violence laws exist
nodes.description: This indicates whether a country has specific laws against domestic violence, scored as 1 (yes, laws exist) or 0 (no laws). A score of 1 is better because it means legal protections are in place. Strong domestic violence laws help protect people, especially women, from abuse and violence at home.

nodes.label: Defensive Military Alliance Membership
nodes.description: Indicates whether a country belongs to defensive military alliances where members agree to help defend each other if attacked. Higher values mean participation in more defensive agreements. Defensive alliances can provide security and stability, potentially reducing the risk of war and protecting citizens from external threats.

nodes.label: Intentional Homicides per 100,000 People
nodes.description: This measures how many people are murdered per 100,000 population each year. The rate allows comparison between countries of different sizes. Lower rates are much better as they indicate safer communities where people can live without fear of violence, supporting economic development and quality of life.

nodes.label: Child Soldiers - Warlord/Rebel Recruitment
nodes.description: This measures whether armed groups, warlords, or rebel forces recruit children under 18 as soldiers in a country. The value is either 0 (no warlord recruitment of child soldiers) or 1 (warlord recruitment occurs). Higher values (1) indicate worse conditions, as using child soldiers violates human rights and subjects children to violence, preventing them from getting education and normal childhood development.
nodes.label_source: Children of Soldiers Dataset via QoG

nodes.label: Child Soldiers - Personal Recruitment
nodes.description: This measures whether government forces or militias recruit children under 18 as soldiers for personal protection or private armies. The value is either 0 (no personal recruitment of child soldiers) or 1 (personal recruitment occurs). Higher values (1) indicate worse conditions, as recruiting children as soldiers violates their rights and exposes them to violence and trauma.
nodes.label_source: Children of Soldiers Dataset via QoG

nodes.label: Military to Female Fertility Ratio
nodes.description: Compares the number of military personnel to female fertility rates in a country. Higher ratios indicate either larger militaries or lower birth rates relative to each other. This can reflect a country's priorities between defense spending and social development that supports families.

nodes.label: Military and Defense Spending
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country spends on its military, including soldiers' salaries, weapons, equipment, and defense facilities. Higher spending may indicate stronger defense capabilities but also means less money available for education, healthcare, and other social needs.

nodes.label: Military spending as share of economy
nodes.description: This measures how much of a country's total economic output is spent on military forces, defense equipment, and related activities, expressed as a percentage. Values typically range from 1-10%, with higher percentages meaning more resources go to defense rather than other priorities like education or healthcare. The optimal level depends on security needs, but very high military spending can limit resources available for social programs.

nodes.label: Total Import Value
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of goods and services a country imports from other nations in a given year. Higher values indicate more international trade but also greater dependence on foreign goods. This matters because imports can provide access to goods and technology but also reflect economic dependencies.

nodes.label: Military Spending and Activity Level
nodes.description: This measures how militarized a country is by looking at military spending, armed forces size, and weapons compared to other countries. The index ranges from 0 to 1000, where higher scores mean more military focus. Very high militarization can indicate regional conflicts or high defense spending that might take resources away from education, healthcare, and other social needs.
nodes.label_source: BICC (Bonn International Centre for Conflict Studies)

nodes.label: Democracy vs Autocracy Score
nodes.description: This rates how democratic or autocratic a country's government is on a scale from -10 (complete autocracy/dictatorship) to +10 (full democracy). Higher positive scores mean more democratic freedoms and institutions. This is crucial because democratic governance typically provides better protection of rights, accountability, and responsiveness to citizens' needs.

nodes.label: Size of Opposition Groups (Ordinal Scale)
nodes.description: Measures how large and widespread opposition political groups are in a country, rated on an ordinal scale from small to large. Higher scores indicate bigger, more extensive opposition movements. This is important because larger opposition groups can better represent diverse viewpoints and provide stronger checks on government power.

nodes.label: Size of Regime Support Groups
nodes.description: This measures how large the core group of supporters is that keeps the current political regime in power. Higher values indicate the regime relies on a broader base of support, while lower values suggest power is concentrated among a small elite group. Broader support bases typically lead to more stable and responsive governments.

nodes.label: Opposition Party Participation in Legislature
nodes.description: This measures how much opposition political parties are able to participate meaningfully in the national legislature or parliament. Higher values indicate that opposition parties can actively debate, propose laws, and influence decisions, while lower values suggest they are excluded or marginalized. Strong opposition participation ensures diverse viewpoints are heard in government decision-making.

nodes.label: Legislature Oversight of Budget
nodes.description: Measures how effectively the legislature (congress or parliament) can review and control government spending decisions. Higher values indicate stronger legislative oversight of the budget. When elected representatives control spending, taxpayer money is more likely to be used for public benefit rather than personal gain.

nodes.label: Women's Parliamentary Representation
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of seats held by women in national parliaments (the main law-making bodies of countries). Higher percentages mean more women are involved in making important decisions about laws and policies. Greater women's representation in government helps ensure that policies address the needs and perspectives of all citizens, not just men.

nodes.label: Women's Political Participation Index
nodes.description: Measures how much women participate in political life, including voting, running for office, and holding leadership positions. Values range from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate greater gender equality in politics. When women participate equally in politics, government policies better address the needs of all citizens.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Politics Index
nodes.description: Measures how equally women participate in political power and decision-making compared to men. Scores range from 0 to 4, where higher values mean greater gender equality in political representation and influence. Gender equality in politics matters because it ensures government policies reflect the needs and perspectives of all citizens.

nodes.label: Number of Dentists
nodes.description: This counts the total number of licensed dentists working in a country. Higher numbers (especially relative to population size) mean better access to dental care for residents. This matters because dental health affects overall health, nutrition, and quality of life, so having enough dentists ensures people can get the oral healthcare they need.

nodes.label: Number of Pharmacists
nodes.description: This counts the total number of licensed pharmacists working in a country's healthcare system. Higher numbers per population indicate better access to medication services and pharmaceutical care. Having enough pharmacists is important for ensuring people can safely access and properly use their medications.

nodes.label: Number of Nurses and Midwives
nodes.description: This counts the total number of trained nurses and midwives working in a country's healthcare system. Higher numbers indicate better healthcare staffing, though the ratio to population matters most. This is crucial because adequate nursing staff directly affects the quality of medical care people receive and hospital safety.

nodes.label: Number of Medical Doctors
nodes.description: This counts the total number of licensed medical doctors working in a country or region. Higher numbers generally mean better access to healthcare, especially when considered relative to population size. Having enough doctors is essential for treating illnesses, preventing diseases, and maintaining public health.

nodes.label: Number of Midwives
nodes.description: This counts the total number of trained midwives working in a country's healthcare system. Higher numbers mean there are more midwives available to help with pregnancies and births. This matters because having enough skilled midwives helps ensure safer pregnancies and births, reducing risks for mothers and babies.

nodes.label: Measles Cases Reported
nodes.description: This measures the number of measles cases officially reported to health authorities in a given time period. Higher numbers mean more people got sick with measles, which is worse for public health. This matters because measles outbreaks can be prevented with vaccines, and tracking cases helps health officials respond quickly to protect communities.

nodes.label: Government Spending Comparison (US Standard)
nodes.description: This compares how much different countries' governments spend on public services like schools, hospitals, and infrastructure, using the US as a baseline reference point. Higher values mean that country's government spends more relative to the US standard. This matters because government spending on public services directly affects citizens' access to education, healthcare, and basic infrastructure.

nodes.label: Government Services Price Comparison
nodes.description: This measures how expensive government services are in different countries compared to a baseline, helping economists understand cost differences across nations. Higher values mean government services cost more in that country. This matters because it affects how much governments can provide to citizens with their budgets.

nodes.label: Government Spending Comparison Component
nodes.description: This is part of an international comparison that measures specific government expenditures, adjusted to allow fair comparisons between countries with different currencies and price levels. Values help determine whether governments are spending relatively more or less than other nations. Government spending levels affect public services and economic development.

nodes.label: Government Spending Price Comparison (US Base)
nodes.description: This measures how expensive government services and operations are in a country compared to the United States. Higher values mean government spending costs more relative to the US baseline. This matters because it shows how efficiently governments can deliver public services with their budgets.

nodes.label: Civil Society: No Anti-Government Movements
nodes.description: This measures whether there are no significant anti-government social movements in a country (category 0 = no anti-government movements). Higher values indicate the absence of such movements. This matters because the presence or absence of opposition movements reflects citizens' satisfaction with their government and their freedom to organize.

nodes.label: Civil Society Anti-Government Movement Activity
nodes.description: This measures how active civil society organizations are in opposing or criticizing the government, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values indicate more organized civil society opposition to government policies and actions. Strong civil society opposition can help check government power and protect democratic freedoms.

nodes.label: Civil Society Campaign Restrictions
nodes.description: This measures how much the government restricts civil society organizations from running public campaigns or advocacy efforts on political and social issues. The scale runs from 0-4, where higher values indicate fewer restrictions on campaigning. When civil society can campaign freely, citizens get more diverse information and perspectives on important issues.

nodes.label: Religious Group Civil Liberties
nodes.description: This measures how equally different religious groups can practice their faith, build places of worship, and participate in public life. Higher values indicate better protection of religious freedom for all groups, not just the majority religion. This affects whether people can freely practice their beliefs without fear of discrimination.

nodes.label: Women's Political Rights Score
nodes.description: This measures the extent to which women can participate freely in the political process, including voting, running for office, and political expression. Scores typically range from 0-3, with higher scores indicating better protection of women's political rights. This matters because equal political participation is essential for democracy and ensuring women's voices are heard in government decisions.

nodes.label: Media Journalist Training and Professionalism
nodes.description: This measures the quality of journalist training and professional standards in a country's media sector. Higher scores indicate that journalists receive better training and follow stronger professional standards in their reporting. This matters because well-trained journalists provide more accurate and reliable information that citizens need to make informed decisions.

nodes.label: Data Availability on Social Media Arrests
nodes.description: Measures how many expert survey responses were missing for questions about people being arrested for social media posts. Higher scores indicate more missing data, not more arrests. This is a data quality indicator showing how well different countries are covered in surveys about online freedom.

nodes.label: Social Media Regulation Data Availability
nodes.description: Measures how much information is available about government regulation and control of social media platforms. This is a data quality indicator - higher scores mean experts had less information to assess social media regulations. This matters because understanding social media rules helps citizens know their rights to free expression online.

nodes.label: Political Parties: Barriers and Targets Data Coverage
nodes.description: Tracks how often experts were unable to answer questions about barriers facing political parties or government targeting of parties. Higher scores mean more missing data about party restrictions. This measures data availability, not the actual barriers or targeting of political parties.

nodes.label: Media Censorship: Financial Incentives Data Availability
nodes.description: This measures how many experts didn't provide data about government use of financial incentives to influence media coverage, not the censorship itself. Higher values mean less data was available from expert surveys. This indicates how much reliable information is available about subtle forms of media control through economic pressure.

nodes.label: Parliamentary Women's Representation (Upper House)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage or number of women serving in a country's upper house of parliament or senate. Higher values indicate better gender representation in government. This matters because diverse political representation ensures women's perspectives influence laws and policies that affect everyone's daily lives.

nodes.label: Historical Land Use Pattern Changes
nodes.description: This tracks changes in how land was used over time (such as conversion from forests to farmland or cities) based on historical environmental data. Changes can be positive or negative depending on sustainability. This matters because land use changes affect climate, biodiversity, and the environment that supports human communities.
nodes.label_source: Historical Database of the Global Environment

nodes.label: CO2 Emissions from Power Plants (million tons)
nodes.description: This measures how many million tons of carbon dioxide are released into the atmosphere each year from electricity and heat generation facilities like coal, gas, and oil power plants. Higher values mean more greenhouse gas pollution that contributes to climate change. Lower emissions indicate cleaner energy production and better environmental conditions.

nodes.label: Net Migration
nodes.description: This counts how many more people moved into a country than moved out during a specific period, including both citizens and foreigners. Positive numbers mean more people arrived than left, while negative numbers mean more people left than arrived. This matters because migration affects job markets, population growth, and cultural diversity in communities.

nodes.label: Service Industry Value (constant 2015 US$)
nodes.description: This measures the total economic value produced by service industries like retail stores, restaurants, banks, hotels, transportation, healthcare, and education in a country. The value is measured in constant 2015 US dollars, which means it's adjusted for inflation to allow fair comparisons across years. Higher values indicate a larger, more developed service sector, which typically means more jobs and economic opportunities for citizens.

nodes.label: Individual Net Factor Income
nodes.description: This measures the income individuals earn from owning assets like land, buildings, or investments, minus what they pay out to others. Values are in currency amounts, where higher (or positive) numbers mean people earn more from their assets than they pay. This shows how much wealth people have beyond just wages.

nodes.label: Total National Wealth Index
nodes.description: This measures the combined value of all of a country's assets, including buildings, infrastructure, natural resources, and human skills, adjusted for inflation. Higher values indicate greater overall national wealth and economic capacity. Greater national wealth typically means better infrastructure, services, and opportunities that improve people's quality of life.

nodes.label: Cost of Living Index
nodes.description: This measures how much more expensive everyday items like food, housing, and transportation have become compared to prices in 2010 (which equals 100). Numbers above 100 mean things cost more than in 2010, while below 100 means they cost less. Rising costs of living can make it harder for families to afford basic needs.

nodes.label: Population Density
nodes.description: This shows how many people live in each square kilometer of a country's land area. Higher numbers mean people live closer together in more crowded conditions. Moderate population density can indicate good access to services and infrastructure, while very high density may strain resources and infrastructure.

nodes.label: Household Income Distribution Index
nodes.description: This measures how evenly income is distributed among households, with values typically ranging from 0 to 1 where higher numbers indicate more equal income distribution. When the index is higher, it means the gap between rich and poor households is smaller. This matters because more equal income distribution generally leads to better social stability and opportunities for all families.

nodes.label: Wealth from Financial Assets
nodes.description: This measures the total value of financial investments (like stocks, bonds, and bank deposits) owned by people in a country. Higher values indicate more wealth is held in financial markets rather than physical assets. This matters because financial wealth provides income through dividends and interest, and reflects the development of a country's financial system.

nodes.label: Average Pre-tax Wealth of Adults
nodes.description: This measures the average total wealth (assets minus debts) owned by adults before taxes, typically expressed as a percentage of national income. Higher values indicate greater average wealth accumulation in the population. This matters because wealth affects people's financial security, ability to weather economic shocks, and opportunities for their children.

nodes.label: Business Income After Taxes
nodes.description: This measures the amount of income that people earn from businesses and self-employment after paying taxes. Higher values mean entrepreneurs and business owners are keeping more of their profits. Strong business income encourages people to start companies and create jobs for others.

nodes.label: Average Net Wealth of Adults
nodes.description: This measures the average total wealth (assets minus debts) owned by adults in a country, including property, savings, and investments. Higher values indicate adults have accumulated more wealth overall. This matters because wealth provides financial security and opportunities, affecting people's ability to handle emergencies and invest in their future.

nodes.label: Average Adult Income from Work and Assets
nodes.description: This measures the typical income that adults earn from both employment (wages, salaries) and ownership (business profits, rent, investments). Higher values indicate better economic conditions for working-age people. This is important because it shows how much money adults have to support themselves and their families.

nodes.label: Average Industrial Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical income earned by workers in industrial sectors like manufacturing, mining, and construction. Higher values generally indicate better-paying industrial jobs and stronger economic development. Good industrial wages are important for middle-class living standards and economic growth.

nodes.label: Average Social Income for Adults
nodes.description: This measures the average income that adults receive from social programs like unemployment benefits, pensions, and welfare payments. Higher values mean people get more money from government social programs. This matters because social income provides a safety net that helps people maintain basic living standards during hard times.

nodes.label: Average Social Insurance and Transfer Income
nodes.description: This measures the average amount people receive from government social programs like unemployment benefits, pensions, and welfare payments. Higher values mean more generous social support systems. This matters because these payments provide crucial income support during difficult times and help reduce poverty.

nodes.label: Average Income from Work and Assets
nodes.description: This measures the typical income people earn from both working (wages, salaries) and owning things like property or businesses (rents, profits). Higher values indicate better economic well-being for the average person. This matters because it shows how much money the typical person has available to meet their needs and improve their quality of life.

nodes.label: Average Tax Rate on Income and Wealth
nodes.description: This measures the average percentage of income and wealth that people pay in taxes across all income levels in a country. Values are shown as percentages, where higher numbers mean people pay more of their income in taxes. This matters because tax rates affect how much money people keep from their earnings and how much governments can spend on public services.

nodes.label: Average Net Wealth Share
nodes.description: This measures the average share of total national wealth (assets minus debts) held by different income groups after accounting for taxes and transfers. Higher values for a group indicate they hold a larger portion of the country's total wealth. This matters because wealth concentration affects long-term economic inequality and opportunities for future generations.

nodes.label: Average Business Net Wealth
nodes.description: This shows the average net wealth (assets minus debts) of businesses in the economy. Higher values mean businesses are financially healthier on average. This matters because profitable businesses create more jobs and contribute more to economic growth and tax revenues.

nodes.label: Market Consumption Per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much people spend on average for goods and services through market purchases (not including government-provided services). Higher values indicate people can afford to buy more things, showing stronger purchasing power. This matters because consumption levels reflect people's living standards and their ability to meet their needs and wants.

nodes.label: Market Income After Taxes (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from jobs and investments after paying taxes, including everyone in the population. Higher values indicate people have more money to spend after the government takes its share through taxes. This is important because it shows how much money people actually have available for their daily needs and saving.

nodes.label: Total Market Income Share
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of all market income (before taxes and transfers) goes to a particular income group, tracked by the World Inequality Database. Values are percentages, where higher concentrations in top groups indicate greater inequality. This reveals how equally or unequally income from work and investments is distributed in society.

nodes.label: Service Sector Share of Economy
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of a country's economic activity comes from service industries like retail stores, restaurants, banks, hospitals, and schools rather than manufacturing or farming. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate a more developed, modern economy. Service-based economies typically provide more diverse job opportunities and higher living standards.

nodes.label: Money sent abroad by workers and residents
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money that workers and residents send to people in other countries, including wages earned by temporary workers abroad, measured in current US dollars. Higher values indicate more people working internationally or supporting family members in other countries. These outflows can reduce domestic spending but often support families and communities in the recipients' home countries.

nodes.label: Money sent home by overseas workers
nodes.description: This measures the total dollars that people working abroad send back to their home country to support family and friends. Higher amounts indicate more people working overseas and more money flowing into the domestic economy. These payments help families afford basic needs and can significantly boost household income.

nodes.label: Money Sent Home by Workers Abroad (% of Economy)
nodes.description: This measures money that workers living in other countries send back to their home country as a percentage of the total national economy. Higher percentages mean these payments make up a bigger part of the country's income. This matters because money from abroad can significantly boost family incomes and economic development.

nodes.label: Imports from Latin America & Caribbean (% of total imports)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of all goods a country buys from other countries comes specifically from Latin American and Caribbean nations. Higher percentages indicate stronger trade relationships with this region, which can provide economic benefits and more diverse products for consumers.

nodes.label: Women's Legal Mobility Rights Score
nodes.description: This scores how much legal freedom women have to move around, travel, and choose where to live, on a scale from 0 to 100. Higher scores mean women have more legal rights to travel and move freely. Greater mobility rights for women support their ability to work, start businesses, and participate fully in economic life.

nodes.label: Women's Business Rights Score
nodes.description: This scores how easily women can start and run businesses based on legal rights and regulations, on a scale from 0-100. Higher scores mean women face fewer legal barriers to entrepreneurship, such as signing contracts or opening bank accounts. This matters because when women can freely participate in business, it boosts economic growth and promotes equality and prosperity for all.

nodes.label: Self-Employed Men (Percentage)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of working men are self-employed, running their own small businesses or working independently rather than for an employer. The significance of higher or lower values depends on context - it can indicate entrepreneurship or lack of formal job opportunities. Self-employment patterns reflect the structure of the job market and economic opportunities available to workers.

nodes.label: Women Working for Themselves (Percentage)
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of working women are self-employed, running their own small businesses or working independently rather than for an employer. Higher percentages can indicate either entrepreneurial opportunity or lack of formal job opportunities for women. This matters because women's economic participation and business ownership contribute to family income, economic growth, and gender equality.

nodes.label: Equal Pay Law for Men and Women
nodes.description: This measures whether a country has a law requiring employers to pay men and women equally for work of equal value. A score of 1 means the law exists, 0 means it doesn't. Having this law is important for reducing gender discrimination and ensuring fair wages for all workers.

nodes.label: Anti-Gender Discrimination Employment Laws (1=yes, 0=no)
nodes.description: This measures whether a country has laws that prohibit employers from discriminating against workers based on their gender. A value of 1 means such laws exist, while 0 means they don't. Having these laws is important for ensuring equal job opportunities and fair treatment for all workers, regardless of gender.

nodes.label: Paid Paternity Leave Available
nodes.description: This indicates whether fathers are legally entitled to at least one day of paid leave when their child is born, scored as 1 for yes and 0 for no. A score of 1 is better as it supports family bonding and gender equality in parenting responsibilities. Paid paternity leave policies help families adjust to new children while promoting fathers' involvement in childcare.

nodes.label: Economic Value of Male Workforce Skills
nodes.description: This measures the total expected future earnings of all working-age men in a country, representing their combined education, skills, and productivity. Higher values indicate a more skilled and productive male workforce. This matters because human capital represents a country's ability to generate income and economic growth through its people's knowledge and abilities.

nodes.label: Total Employment (Millions of People)
nodes.description: This measures the total number of people who have jobs in a country, counted in millions. Higher numbers indicate more people are working and contributing to the economy. This matters because employment provides people with income to support their families and contributes to a country's economic growth and stability.

nodes.label: Average Household Business Operating Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money households earn from running businesses or other commercial activities. Values are in local currency, with higher amounts indicating more successful household enterprises. This shows how much families benefit from entrepreneurship and small business ownership.

nodes.label: Traditional Media: Government Monitoring (Average)
nodes.description: Measures the average level of government surveillance and monitoring of traditional media outlets like newspapers and TV stations. Higher scores indicate more government monitoring of media. This matters because excessive media surveillance can discourage journalists from reporting freely on important issues.

nodes.label: Executive Embezzlement and Corruption
nodes.description: This measures how often members of the executive branch (president, prime minister, cabinet) steal public money or accept bribes. Lower values indicate more corruption, while higher values mean cleaner government. Reduced corruption means more public resources go to schools, healthcare, and infrastructure instead of politicians' pockets.

nodes.label: External Threats to Political System
nodes.description: This measures threats to the country's political system from outside forces, such as foreign interference or external pressure on government institutions. Higher values indicate more external threats, which can undermine democratic processes and national sovereignty.

nodes.label: Executive Corruption in Public Sector
nodes.description: This measures how much corruption exists within the executive branch of government, including practices like embezzlement, bribery, and misuse of public funds. Higher scores indicate more corruption and abuse of public resources by government officials. Lower corruption means taxpayer money is more likely to be spent on public services that benefit citizens.

nodes.label: Average Income After Taxes and Benefits
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money adults have available to spend after paying taxes and receiving government benefits like unemployment insurance or social security. Higher values mean people have more money for daily expenses. This indicator shows how well government policies help people maintain their standard of living.

nodes.label: HIV Infection Rate Among Adults
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of adults aged 15-49 who are infected with HIV. Values range from 0% to potentially over 20% in severely affected areas, with lower percentages being better. This matters because HIV prevalence indicates both public health challenges and the quality of healthcare systems in preventing and treating infectious diseases.

nodes.label: New Tuberculosis Cases per 100,000 People
nodes.description: This counts how many people develop tuberculosis (TB) each year for every 100,000 people in the population. Lower numbers are better, indicating fewer people are getting this serious lung infection. This matters because TB spreads easily and can be deadly if untreated, so tracking new cases helps measure public health.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison - Category 41927
nodes.description: This measures spending on a specific category of goods or services as part of international price comparisons, which help compare living costs across countries. Higher values mean more money is spent on this category relative to other countries. This matters because it helps us understand how expensive different things are in each country and how far people's money goes.

nodes.label: Historical Environmental Alignment Index
nodes.description: This measures how well a country's environmental policies and practices align with international environmental goals over time. Higher values indicate better alignment with global environmental standards and commitments. This matters because countries that follow environmental best practices help protect the planet and create healthier living conditions for their people.
nodes.label_source: Historical Database of the Global Environment

nodes.label: Produced Capital Value (Excluding Urban Land)
nodes.description: This estimates the total dollar value of all human-made assets in a country, such as buildings, machinery, infrastructure, and equipment, but not including the land under cities. Higher values indicate more physical capital available for production and economic activity. This matters because countries with more capital infrastructure typically have higher living standards and better economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Total Investment in Buildings and Equipment
nodes.description: This measures the total amount a country spends on building new factories, roads, schools, buying machinery, and other investments that will help produce goods and services in the future, expressed in current US dollars. Higher values indicate more investment in future economic growth. Strong investment today creates jobs and improves living standards tomorrow.

nodes.label: Methane emissions from oil and gas leaks
nodes.description: This measures methane gas that escapes into the air from oil drilling, gas pipelines, and energy production, converted to equivalent tons of carbon dioxide. Higher values mean more methane pollution from energy operations. This matters because methane is a powerful greenhouse gas that contributes to climate change and environmental health problems.

nodes.label: Methane greenhouse gas emissions (million tons CO2 equivalent)
nodes.description: This measures how much methane pollution a country produces annually from farming, energy production, and waste, converted to the same scale as carbon dioxide. Higher values mean more greenhouse gas pollution. Methane emissions contribute significantly to climate change and come largely from agriculture and energy production.

nodes.label: Carbon Pollution per Dollar of Economic Output
nodes.description: This measures how many kilograms of carbon dioxide pollution a country produces for every dollar of economic output (GDP). Lower values are better because they mean a country produces less pollution while creating the same economic value. This matters because reducing carbon intensity helps fight climate change while maintaining economic growth and living standards.

nodes.label: Natural Resource Wealth per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total value of a country's natural resources like oil, minerals, forests, and farmland divided by population. Higher values indicate greater natural wealth per person. This matters because countries with more natural resource wealth have greater potential for economic development and improving living standards.

nodes.label: Freshwater availability per person
nodes.description: This measures how much renewable freshwater (from rivers, lakes, and groundwater) is available per person in a country, measured in cubic meters per year. Higher values mean more water is available per person, which is better for meeting drinking, farming, and industrial needs. Countries with more freshwater per person generally have better food security and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Household Energy Use Growth
nodes.description: This measures the annual percentage change in energy consumption by households for heating, cooking, and electricity. Higher growth rates indicate increasing energy use, which could mean improved living standards but also higher environmental impact. This matters because household energy access is essential for basic needs, but rapid growth may indicate unsustainable consumption patterns.

nodes.label: Military Alliance Consultation Agreement
nodes.description: This indicates whether a country has signed treaties requiring it to consult with allies before making major military decisions. Values are typically yes/no or 0/1, where higher values mean stronger consultation commitments. These agreements affect national security cooperation and diplomatic relationships with other countries.

nodes.label: Adult Income Distribution Indicator
nodes.description: This measures some aspect of how income is distributed among adults in a country, though the specific metric is unclear from the code. The values would typically relate to income equality or specific income groups. Income distribution matters because it affects social stability, economic mobility, and overall quality of life.

nodes.label: Government Debt Level
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government owes to creditors as a percentage of the country's total economic output. Higher percentages indicate the government has borrowed more relative to the economy's size. High debt levels can limit government spending on public services and economic programs.

nodes.label: CO2 Emissions
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of carbon dioxide a country releases into the atmosphere, usually expressed in metric tons per person per year. Lower emissions are better for fighting climate change and reducing air pollution. Countries with higher CO2 emissions contribute more to global warming, while those with lower emissions have a smaller environmental impact.

nodes.label: Death Rate per 1,000 People
nodes.description: This measures how many people die each year for every 1,000 people in the population. Lower rates are better as they indicate better healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions. Countries with good medical systems, clean water, and adequate food typically have lower death rates and longer life expectancy.

nodes.label: Fossil Fuel Energy Consumption
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total energy comes from fossil fuels like coal, oil, and natural gas. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean greater dependence on fossil fuels. Lower fossil fuel use typically indicates cleaner air, reduced greenhouse gas emissions, and better long-term environmental sustainability.

nodes.label: Female Employment Rate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of working-age women (usually 15-64 years old) have jobs. The rate is expressed as a percentage, where higher values mean more women are working. Higher female employment rates indicate better economic opportunities for women and contribute to overall economic growth and family financial security.

nodes.label: Middle-Class Agricultural Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical income earned by middle-income families working in farming, livestock, and other agricultural activities. Higher values mean agricultural workers in the middle-income bracket are earning more. This is important because strong agricultural incomes help rural communities thrive and ensure stable food production.

nodes.label: Market Income Distribution Measure
nodes.description: This measures how market income from jobs and investments is distributed among different income groups before government taxes and transfers. The specific scale varies, but it shows patterns of income inequality. This matters because it reveals whether economic opportunities are widely shared or concentrated among fewer people.

nodes.label: Market Income from Production Factors (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures average income people earn from owning or providing basic economic resources like labor, land, or capital to businesses. Higher values indicate people are earning more from their work and assets in the market economy. This is important because it shows how well the economy rewards people for their contributions to production.

nodes.label: Foreign Investment Income Revenue
nodes.description: This tracks the total income a country earns from its investments in foreign businesses and assets. Higher values indicate the country is earning more money from overseas investments. This matters because foreign investment income can boost national wealth and provide funds for domestic development.

nodes.label: Average Environmental Wealth Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average value of environmental assets like forests, clean air, and natural resources that benefit each person. Higher values indicate people have access to more valuable natural resources and environmental benefits. This matters because environmental wealth affects quality of life and provides important economic resources for current and future generations.

nodes.label: External Trade Output (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures how much a country's economy benefits from selling goods and services to other countries, averaged across all people. Higher values mean the country earns more money from exports, which can boost the overall economy. This matters because countries that successfully sell products abroad often have stronger economies and more job opportunities.

nodes.label: Market Income Decline (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures how much income people lose from jobs, businesses, and investments during economic downturns across all income groups. Higher values indicate bigger income losses during tough times. This shows how vulnerable people are to economic shocks and their ability to weather financial crises.

nodes.label: Price Comparison Category 42619
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of a specific category of goods or services when comparing prices between different countries. The exact category depends on international classification systems used for economic comparisons. This matters because understanding price differences helps determine how far people's money goes in different places for maintaining their standard of living.

nodes.label: Household Spending Category 20177
nodes.description: This tracks spending on a specific category of goods or services that households typically purchase, as part of international price and consumption comparisons. The exact spending category would need to be identified from detailed classification systems. This helps compare living costs and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison - Category 20171
nodes.description: This measures spending on a specific category of goods or services as part of international price comparisons, which help compare living costs across countries. Higher values mean more money is spent on this category relative to other countries. This matters because it helps us understand how expensive different things are in each country and how far people's money goes.

nodes.label: Senior Men (65+) Population
nodes.description: This measures the total number of men who are 65 years old or older living in a country. Higher numbers indicate a larger elderly male population, which usually means better healthcare and living conditions that help people live longer. Countries with more senior citizens often need more healthcare services and retirement support.

nodes.label: Total Population 65 and Older
nodes.description: This measures the total number of people aged 65 and above living in a country, counting everyone who actually lives there regardless of citizenship. The number is reported as total people, so larger countries naturally have higher values. A growing elderly population often indicates better healthcare and living conditions, but it can also mean more pressure on healthcare systems and retirement programs.

nodes.label: Elderly Women Population (65 and Older)
nodes.description: This counts how many women aged 65 and older live in a country. Higher numbers often indicate better healthcare and living conditions that help people live longer. A growing elderly population shows social progress but also creates needs for healthcare services and retirement support.

nodes.label: Male Population Ages 55-59
