nodes.description: This counts the number of men between ages 55 and 59 living in a country. Higher numbers indicate a larger population approaching retirement age. This data helps governments plan for retirement benefits, healthcare services for older adults, and the transition of workers out of the labor force.

nodes.label: Male Population Ages 60-64
nodes.description: This counts the number of men between ages 60 and 64 living in a country. The number reflects both the country's total population size and its age structure. This age group matters because these men are typically approaching or entering retirement, affecting healthcare needs, pension systems, and the balance between working-age people and those who need support.

nodes.label: Male Population Ages 50-54
nodes.description: This counts the total number of men between ages 50 and 54 living in a country. The number reflects both the size of this age group and broader population trends. This matters because this age group represents experienced workers nearing retirement, affecting labor markets, healthcare needs, and future pension costs.

nodes.label: Men Aged 65-69 Population
nodes.description: This counts the total number of men between ages 65 and 69 living in a country. The number reflects both overall population size and the demographic structure of older adults. A growing elderly population indicates longer life expectancy, but also means more people may need retirement benefits and healthcare services.

nodes.label: Women aged 70-74
nodes.description: This counts the number of women between ages 70 and 74 living in a country. Higher numbers typically reflect larger populations or better healthcare that helps people live longer. This matters because the size of older populations affects healthcare needs, social services, and family support systems.

nodes.label: Number of Women Ages 65-69
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women between ages 65 and 69 living in a country. The number reflects both the country's total population size and its age structure, with higher numbers in larger countries or those with aging populations. This helps governments plan for healthcare, pensions, and services needed by older women.

nodes.label: Number of men aged 70-74
nodes.description: This counts how many men are between 70 and 74 years old in a country. Higher numbers indicate longer life expectancy and an aging population. This matters because older populations need more healthcare services and retirement support, affecting how societies plan for elder care.

nodes.label: Number of women aged 75-79
nodes.description: This measures the total number of women between ages 75-79 living in a country. Higher numbers can indicate either a larger overall population or an aging society with longer life expectancy. Countries with more elderly women typically need more healthcare services and social support systems, but also benefit from their experience and knowledge.

nodes.label: Male Population Ages 75-79
nodes.description: This counts the number of men between ages 75 and 79 living in a country. Higher numbers can indicate better healthcare and living conditions that allow people to live longer, but also represent increased demand for elderly care services. This matters because this age group typically requires more healthcare and social support, affecting families and government resources.

nodes.label: Number of men aged 45-49
nodes.description: This counts how many men are between ages 45 and 49 in a country. The number shows the size of this middle-aged male population group. Higher numbers mean more men in their late 40s, which helps predict workforce needs and healthcare demands for this age group.

nodes.label: Boys Ages 5-9
nodes.description: This counts the total number of boys between ages 5 and 9 in a country. The number is reported as total people, so larger countries have higher values. This age group represents children in early elementary school years. Tracking this population helps governments plan for school capacity, educational resources, and future workforce needs.

nodes.label: Girls aged 5-9
nodes.description: This counts the number of girls between ages 5 and 9 living in a country. Higher numbers reflect larger populations or higher birth rates from previous years. This matters because the size of school-age populations affects education system needs, family resources, and future workforce planning.

nodes.label: Boys Ages 0-4
nodes.description: This counts the total number of boys between birth and age 4 in a country. The number is reported as total people, so larger countries have higher values. This represents the youngest male population who need healthcare, early childhood programs, and will enter school in coming years. Tracking this helps plan for pediatric healthcare and future educational needs.

nodes.label: Young boys as share of male population
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of all males in a country are young boys between ages 0-4 years old. Higher percentages indicate a younger population with more recent births, while lower percentages suggest an aging population or declining birth rates. Countries with more young children typically need more investment in schools and pediatric healthcare, but also have potential for future economic growth.

nodes.label: Baby Deaths per Year
nodes.description: This counts how many babies die before their first birthday each year in a country. The number is total deaths, where higher numbers indicate more infant deaths and typically reflect poorer healthcare or living conditions. Lower infant deaths usually mean better healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions that help babies survive and thrive.

nodes.label: Newborn deaths in first month
nodes.description: This counts how many babies die before they reach 28 days old (their first month of life). Lower numbers are better, showing that more newborns survive their most vulnerable period. This matters because newborn survival rates reflect the quality of healthcare and conditions for mothers and babies.

nodes.label: Number of baby boy deaths under age 1
nodes.description: This counts how many baby boys die before their first birthday in a country each year. Lower numbers are better, indicating better healthcare and living conditions for infants. This is a key measure of a country's healthcare system quality and overall development level.

nodes.label: Child Death Rate (Ages 10-14)
nodes.description: This measures how many children between ages 10 and 14 die per 1,000 children in that age group each year. Lower rates are better, indicating healthier living conditions and better healthcare systems. This rate reflects a country's ability to protect older children from preventable diseases, accidents, and other health risks.

nodes.label: Births Attended by Skilled Health Personnel
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of births where a trained healthcare worker (like a doctor, nurse, or midwife) is present to help deliver the baby. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because they indicate more professional medical care during childbirth. Having skilled help during birth greatly reduces the risk of complications that could harm or kill mothers and babies.

nodes.label: Maternal Death Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many women die from pregnancy or childbirth-related causes per 100,000 live births in a country. Lower numbers are better, indicating safer healthcare for pregnant women. This reflects the quality of healthcare systems and women's access to medical care during pregnancy and delivery.

nodes.label: Maternal deaths per year
nodes.description: This counts how many women die each year from pregnancy-related causes, including complications during childbirth or within 42 days after giving birth. Lower numbers are much better and indicate safer childbirth conditions. Reducing maternal deaths is crucial for protecting women's health and keeping families together.

nodes.label: Lifetime risk of dying in childbirth
nodes.description: This shows the percentage chance that a 15-year-old girl will eventually die from pregnancy or childbirth complications during her lifetime. Lower percentages are much better, indicating safer healthcare for mothers. This reflects the quality of maternal healthcare and women's access to medical services.

nodes.label: Maternal deaths per 100,000 births
nodes.description: This measures how many mothers die from pregnancy-related causes for every 100,000 live births in a country. Lower values are better, indicating safer childbirth and better healthcare systems - for example, a rate of 10 is much better than 500. Lower maternal mortality rates reflect better access to skilled medical care and healthier outcomes for families.

nodes.label: Life expectancy at birth (years)
nodes.description: This estimates how many years a baby born today is expected to live based on current death rates in the country. Higher numbers indicate better healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions, with most developed countries having life expectancies above 80 years.

nodes.label: Births Attended by Skilled Health Personnel (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of babies born with a trained doctor, nurse, or midwife present during delivery. Higher percentages mean more mothers and babies receive professional medical care during birth, which is safer. This is crucial because skilled birth attendance greatly reduces the risk of mothers and babies dying during childbirth.

nodes.label: Pregnant Women Receiving 4+ Medical Checkups (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of pregnant women who receive at least four medical checkups during their pregnancy from trained healthcare providers. Values range from 0% to 100%, and higher percentages are better as they indicate more women are getting proper prenatal care. Good antenatal care helps prevent complications during pregnancy and childbirth, leading to healthier mothers and babies.

nodes.label: Children Receiving HIV Treatment
nodes.description: This counts the number of children under 15 years old who are receiving antiretroviral therapy to treat HIV infection. Higher numbers indicate more children are getting life-saving treatment. This matters because access to HIV treatment is crucial for child survival and preventing the spread of the disease.

nodes.label: HIV Treatment Coverage
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of people living with HIV are receiving antiretroviral therapy (ART), which are life-saving medicines that control the virus. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because more people are getting treatment. Good HIV treatment coverage saves lives and helps prevent the spread of HIV to others.

nodes.label: People Receiving HIV Treatment
nodes.description: This counts the number of people with HIV who are receiving antiretroviral drugs that help control the virus and prevent AIDS. Higher numbers indicate better access to life-saving treatment. This matters because proper HIV treatment allows people to live normal, healthy lives and prevents the spread of the virus to others.

nodes.label: Deaths from HIV/AIDS
nodes.description: This measures the total number of people who died from HIV/AIDS-related complications in a given year. The number is reported as an absolute count, so higher numbers indicate more deaths and worse health outcomes. This indicator helps track the severity of the HIV/AIDS epidemic and the effectiveness of prevention and treatment programs in saving lives.

nodes.label: Tuberculosis Cases Among HIV-Positive People
nodes.description: This counts the estimated number of new tuberculosis (TB) cases each year among people who also have HIV. Higher numbers indicate more people are getting TB while having weakened immune systems from HIV, which makes TB more dangerous and harder to treat. This matters because TB-HIV co-infection is especially deadly and shows how well a country's health system handles these overlapping diseases.

nodes.label: Estimated Number of People with Tuberculosis
nodes.description: This estimates the total number of people currently living with tuberculosis in a country, including cases that may not be officially diagnosed yet. Lower numbers indicate better TB control. This matters because it shows the true burden of this infectious disease and helps plan treatment and prevention programs.

nodes.label: Newborn Death Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many babies die in their first 28 days of life out of every 1,000 babies born alive. Lower rates indicate better healthcare for mothers and newborns, while higher rates suggest problems with medical care or nutrition. This is crucial because it reflects the quality of healthcare systems and directly impacts families and population health.

nodes.label: Wealth and Financial Assets Indicator
nodes.description: This measures some aspect of how much wealth or financial assets people have, though the specific definition varies by source. Higher values typically indicate greater financial security and accumulated wealth. This is important because having savings and assets helps people weather economic shocks and invest in their future.

nodes.label: Cholera Deaths Reported
nodes.description: This measures the number of people who died from cholera disease as officially reported by health authorities in a country. Higher numbers indicate more deaths from this preventable disease. This matters because cholera deaths reflect problems with water quality, sanitation, and healthcare access that affect everyone's health and safety.

nodes.label: Modern Birth Control Use Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women of childbearing age who use modern contraceptive methods like pills, condoms, or IUDs. Higher percentages mean more women have access to effective family planning tools. This is important because it helps women control when to have children and affects maternal and child health outcomes.

nodes.label: HIV Infection Rate Among Adults
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adults aged 15-49 are infected with HIV. Higher percentages indicate more widespread HIV infection in the population. This is crucial for public health because HIV significantly reduces life expectancy and quality of life, and high rates strain healthcare systems.

nodes.label: Rural population growth rate
nodes.description: This measures how fast the population in rural areas (countryside and small towns) is growing each year, shown as a percentage. A positive number means rural areas are gaining people, while negative means people are leaving for cities. This affects demand for rural services like schools and healthcare in farming communities.

nodes.label: Boys Born Per 100 Girls
nodes.description: This measures how many boys are born for every 100 girls in a country each year. Normal values range from about 103 to 107 boys per 100 girls, with significant deviations potentially indicating gender preferences or demographic issues. This matters because balanced birth ratios are important for healthy population growth and social stability.

nodes.label: Net Migration Rate
nodes.description: This shows the difference between people moving into a country and people leaving, usually per 1,000 residents per year. Positive values mean more people are moving in than leaving. This matters because migration patterns reflect economic opportunities and living conditions that attract or push away residents.

nodes.label: Equal Retirement Age for Men and Women
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women can retire and collect full pensions at the same age in a country's laws. A score of 1 means equal retirement ages, while 0 means different ages for men and women. Equal retirement ages reflect gender equality in the workplace and help ensure fair treatment of workers regardless of gender, promoting economic opportunities for all.

nodes.label: Women with Family Planning Needs Met (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women who want to plan their pregnancies and have access to contraception or family planning services. Higher percentages are better, showing more women can control when to have children. Access to family planning helps women stay healthy, complete their education, and support their families.

nodes.label: Fertility Rate
nodes.description: This measures the average number of children a woman would have in her lifetime based on current birth rates. The number is typically between 1 and 7, where higher values mean more births per woman. Countries with very high fertility rates (above 4) often face challenges providing education and healthcare to rapidly growing populations, while very low rates (below 2) can lead to aging populations and economic challenges.

nodes.label: Military Regime Classification
nodes.description: This indicates whether experts classify a country's government as being controlled by military leaders (coded as 1) or not (coded as 0). This is part of a broader system for categorizing different types of political regimes. Military control of government often limits civilian freedoms and economic development.

nodes.label: Official Length of Secondary School
nodes.description: This measures how many years secondary school (middle and high school combined) is supposed to take according to the country's education system. The number varies by country but typically ranges from 5-7 years. This matters because it shows how much time countries dedicate to preparing students for adult life and work.

nodes.label: Government Stability (Years Since Last Change)
nodes.description: This measures how many years have passed since a country's government system last changed significantly (like through revolution, major reform, or regime change). Higher values indicate longer periods of stable government. This matters because political stability helps create predictable conditions for economic growth and social development.

nodes.label: Healthy Life Expectancy (Ages 2-4)
nodes.description: This measures how many years young children aged 2-4 can expect to live in good health without major illness or disability. Values are in years, with higher numbers indicating better child health outcomes. This reflects the quality of healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions for young children.

nodes.label: Life Expectancy for Ages 2-4 (Males)
nodes.description: This measures how long male children who reach age 2 are expected to live on average, based on current death rates. Higher values (measured in years) indicate better child health and healthcare systems. This matters because it shows how well a country protects its youngest citizens from preventable diseases and malnutrition.

nodes.label: Healthy Life Expectancy for Females (Ages 1-2)
nodes.description: This measures how many years female toddlers (ages 1-2) can expect to live in good health, free from serious illness or disability. Higher numbers mean girls are likely to live longer, healthier lives. This matters because it shows how well a country protects the health of young children, especially girls, through healthcare and nutrition.

nodes.label: Healthy Life Expectancy for Females (Ages 2-4)
nodes.description: This measures how many years female children aged 2-4 can expect to live in good health without major illness or disability. Higher numbers mean young girls are likely to have longer, healthier lives. This matters because it reflects how well a country protects children's health through healthcare, nutrition, and safe living conditions.

nodes.label: Healthy Life Expectancy (Ages 1-2)
nodes.description: This measures the average number of years young children can expect to live in good health, accounting for time spent with disabilities or illnesses. Higher values indicate children are expected to have more years of healthy life. This metric is important because it reflects the overall quality of healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions that affect children's long-term wellbeing.

nodes.label: Life Expectancy (Ages 2-4)
nodes.description: This measures the average number of additional years children aged 2-4 can expect to live based on current health conditions and mortality rates. Higher values indicate better survival prospects for young children. This metric reflects the quality of healthcare, nutrition, safety, and living conditions that directly affect whether children will live long, healthy lives.

nodes.label: Average Government Health Spending per Person (Adults 20+)
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on healthcare for each adult aged 20 and older in the country. Higher amounts, measured in local currency, indicate more generous public healthcare funding. Greater government health spending typically leads to better access to medical care and improved health outcomes for the population.

nodes.label: Average Health Spending per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money is spent on healthcare for each person in the population on average, including all age groups. Higher values indicate more healthcare resources are available per person, which typically means better access to medical services and treatments. This matters because adequate health spending is essential for maintaining population health and quality of life.

nodes.label: Number of newborn girls
nodes.description: This counts the estimated number of female babies (under age 1) in a country's population. Higher numbers simply indicate more baby girls, which reflects birth rates and population growth patterns. This helps governments plan for healthcare, education, and other services these children will need.

nodes.label: Number of 2-Year-Old Girls
nodes.description: This counts how many 2-year-old girls live in a country at a specific time, with estimates filled in for missing data. The number reflects the country's birth rates and child survival rates from two years earlier. This matters for planning healthcare, childcare services, and understanding future population trends that affect a country's development.

nodes.label: Female Population Age 1 (Estimated)
nodes.description: This estimates the number of 1-year-old girls in a country, using statistical methods to fill gaps in census data. This reflects recent birth rates and infant survival rates for girls. This matters because infant girls represent the future population of women and indicate current health conditions, with higher numbers suggesting good maternal and child healthcare.

nodes.label: Number of 6-year-old girls
nodes.description: This measures how many girls are exactly 6 years old in a country. The number is given as a total count of female children at this specific age. Higher numbers indicate more girls in this age group, which helps governments plan for primary school enrollment and child health services.

nodes.label: Female Population Age 9 (Estimated)
nodes.description: This estimates the number of 9-year-old girls in a country, using statistical methods to fill gaps in census data. The number reflects population size and past birth rates. This age group matters because these girls are typically in elementary school, representing the foundation of female education and the future potential of women in the country.

nodes.label: Number of 7-year-old girls
nodes.description: This counts the total number of girls who are exactly 7 years old in a country, with missing data filled in using statistical estimates. This demographic data helps governments plan for elementary schools, healthcare, and other services that young children need.

nodes.label: Total Population
nodes.description: This counts the total number of people living in a country at a specific time. Population size affects everything from political representation to market size and resource needs. This matters because population changes influence economic growth, infrastructure demands, environmental pressures, and a country's role in global affairs.

nodes.label: Population Count
nodes.description: This measures the total number of people living in a country or region at a specific time. The values are in absolute numbers, so higher values mean more people live there. Population size helps governments plan for services like schools, hospitals, and infrastructure that communities need.

nodes.label: Female Population Count
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women and girls in a population. The values represent the actual number of females, with higher numbers indicating more women in the area. This is important for understanding gender balance, planning for healthcare and education services, and measuring gender equality progress.

nodes.label: Male Population Count
nodes.description: This counts the total number of men and boys in a population. The values represent the actual number of males, with higher numbers indicating more men in the area. This helps understand population structure and is essential for planning services and measuring demographic trends.

nodes.label: Population Count (Age Group 50+)
nodes.description: This counts the number of people aged 50 and older in a population. The values represent actual counts of older adults, with higher numbers indicating more senior citizens. This matters for planning healthcare, retirement services, and understanding the aging demographics of a society.

nodes.label: Population Count (Age Group 70+)
nodes.description: This counts the number of people aged 70 and older in a population. The values represent actual counts of elderly individuals, with higher numbers indicating more senior citizens. This is crucial for planning healthcare systems, social services, and understanding the care needs of aging populations.

nodes.label: Population Count (Females Age 25-54)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women between ages 25 and 54 living in a country or region. Higher numbers simply indicate more women in this prime working-age group. This matters for understanding workforce capacity, economic potential, and planning for healthcare and social services.

nodes.label: Population Count (Males, All Ages)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of males of all ages living in a country or region. Higher numbers indicate a larger male population overall. This is important for understanding demographics, planning public services, and analyzing economic and social trends.

nodes.label: Population Count (Females Age 60+)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women aged 60 and older living in a country or region. Higher numbers indicate more elderly women in the population. This is important for planning healthcare services, social security systems, and understanding the aging demographics of a society.

nodes.label: Population Count (Females Age 20-24)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women between ages 20 and 24 living in a country or region. Higher numbers indicate more young adult women in this age group. This matters for understanding educational needs, early career employment opportunities, and planning for future workforce development.

nodes.label: Population Count (All People Age 75+)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of people aged 75 and older living in a country or region, regardless of gender. Higher numbers indicate more elderly people in the population. This matters for planning healthcare services, elder care facilities, and understanding the financial needs of an aging society.

nodes.label: Population Count (Females Age 65+)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women aged 65 and older living in a country or region. Higher numbers indicate more elderly women in the population. This matters for planning retirement services, healthcare for seniors, and understanding the demographic structure as societies age.

nodes.label: Population Count (All People Age 20-24)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of people between ages 20 and 24 living in a country or region, including both men and women. Higher numbers indicate more young adults in this age group. This is important for planning higher education, entry-level job opportunities, and understanding future workforce potential.

nodes.label: Population Count (Males Age 15-64)
nodes.description: This counts the total number of men between ages 15 and 64 living in a country or region. Higher numbers indicate more men in the prime working-age population. This matters for understanding labor force capacity, economic productivity potential, and planning for employment and social services.

nodes.label: Female Population (Top 0.4%)
nodes.description: This counts the number of women in the richest 0.4% of the population by income or wealth. The number depends on the country's total population size, and changes over time show whether more women are reaching the highest income levels. This matters because it reveals gender equality among the wealthiest people, which indicates economic opportunities for women.

nodes.label: Male Population (79.8% Income Level)
nodes.description: This counts the number of men at the 79.8th percentile of income distribution, meaning they earn more than about 80% of all men but less than the top 20%. The actual number depends on the country's population size. This matters because it shows how many men fall into this upper-middle income bracket, indicating economic distribution patterns.

nodes.label: Female Population (Middle 49.9%)
nodes.description: This counts the number of women in the middle-income group, specifically those between the 50th and 99.9th percentiles of income distribution. This represents the bulk of middle-class and upper-middle-class women. This matters because a larger middle-class population typically indicates a healthier economy with more opportunities for decent living standards.

nodes.label: Female Population (64.9% Income Level)
nodes.description: This counts the number of women at the 64.9th percentile of income distribution, meaning they earn more than about 65% of all women. The number varies with total population size and income distribution. This matters because it helps track how many women achieve above-average incomes, showing economic participation and gender equality trends.

nodes.label: Male Population (Top 0.4%)
nodes.description: This counts the number of men in the richest 0.4% of the population by income or wealth. The number depends on the country's total population size, and changes show whether wealth concentration is increasing or decreasing among men. This matters because it reveals how wealth is distributed and whether economic opportunities are expanding beyond a small elite group.

nodes.label: Female Population (Bottom 1.4%)
nodes.description: This counts the number of women in the bottom 1.4% of income distribution, representing those with the lowest incomes. Higher numbers could indicate either more women in poverty or simply a larger population. This matters because it helps identify how many women face the most severe economic hardship and need targeted support programs.

nodes.label: Male Population (29.8% Income Level)
nodes.description: This counts the number of men at the 29.8th percentile of income distribution, meaning they earn more than about 30% of all men but are still in the lower-income range. The number reflects both population size and income distribution. This matters because it shows how many men struggle with low incomes, affecting families' ability to meet basic needs.

nodes.label: Female Population (Top 0.8%)
nodes.description: This counts the number of women in the richest 0.8% of the population by income or wealth. The number depends on total population and shows how many women reach very high income levels. This matters because it indicates whether women have equal access to top economic positions and high-paying careers.

Values are shown as whole numbers of people, and changes over time can indicate growth or decline. Population data is essential for planning public services like schools and hospitals, and helps governments understand how many resources their citizens need.

The values are given as actual population counts, so higher numbers indicate more men in this age group. This demographic data helps governments plan healthcare, social services, and economic policies for middle-aged working populations.

nodes.label: Population Count (Females 70+)
nodes.description: This measures the total number of females aged 70 and older living in a country. The values are actual population counts, with higher numbers meaning more elderly women. This information is crucial for planning elder care services, healthcare systems, and retirement support programs.

nodes.label: Population Count (Males 40-44)
nodes.description: This measures the total number of males aged 40-44 years old living in a country. The values are actual population counts, so higher numbers mean more men in this prime working-age group. This demographic information helps plan employment policies, housing needs, and family support services.

nodes.label: Total Population Count
