Population size affects everything from economic growth potential to resource needs and political representation.

nodes.label: Population Count (Females 10-14)
nodes.description: This measures the total number of females aged 10-14 years old living in a country. The values are actual population counts, with higher numbers indicating more girls in this age group. This data helps plan educational services, healthcare programs, and policies to support adolescent girls' development.

nodes.label: Population Count (Ages 20+)
nodes.description: This measures the total number of adults aged 20 and older living in a country. The values are actual population counts, with higher numbers indicating larger adult populations. This represents the working-age and older population who drive economic activity and need adult-oriented services.

nodes.label: Total Population
nodes.description: Measures the total number of people living in a country at a given time, typically counted in millions. This is a straightforward count with no "better" or "worse" direction, but larger populations may face different challenges in providing services. Population size matters because it affects everything from resource needs to economic potential and environmental impact.

nodes.label: School Life Expectancy Gender Gap - Primary
nodes.description: This compares how many years girls versus boys are expected to stay in primary school by dividing girls' years by boys' years. A value of 1.0 means equal time in school, while values above 1.0 mean girls stay longer. Equal school life expectancy helps ensure both boys and girls get the same educational foundation for their futures.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Expected Years of Schooling
nodes.description: This measures whether girls and boys can expect to spend the same number of years in school from primary through tertiary education. A value of 1.0 means girls and boys have equal expected school years, while values below 1.0 indicate girls expect fewer years and values above 1.0 mean girls expect more years. Equal educational opportunities for both genders lead to better economic prospects and social development for everyone.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Elementary School Years
nodes.description: This measures whether boys and girls spend equal amounts of time in elementary school over their lifetimes. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, below 1.0 means girls spend fewer years in school than boys, and above 1.0 means girls spend more years than boys. Equal school time for both genders helps ensure all children develop the basic skills needed for future success.

nodes.label: Secondary Education Completion - Location Gap
nodes.description: This compares the percentage of adults (age 25+) who completed secondary school between urban and rural areas. A value of 1.0 means equal completion rates, while values above 1.0 mean rural areas have higher completion rates. Reducing location gaps in education helps ensure people have equal opportunities regardless of where they grew up.

nodes.label: Rural-Urban Education Gap for Adults with High School
nodes.description: This measures the difference in high school completion rates between rural and urban adults aged 25 and older. A value of 1.0 means equal rates, below 1.0 means rural areas lag behind urban areas. This matters because large gaps indicate unequal access to education based on where people live.

nodes.label: Urban-Rural Gap in Middle School Education (Adults 25+)
nodes.description: This compares middle school completion rates between rural and urban adults age 25 and older. A value of 1.0 means equal completion rates, below 1.0 means fewer rural adults completed middle school compared to urban adults, and above 1.0 means more rural adults completed it. Reducing this gap helps ensure people have similar opportunities regardless of where they live.

nodes.label: Urban vs. Rural Gap in Catch-Up Programs (Middle School)
nodes.description: This compares access to special catch-up education programs between urban and rural areas for out-of-school middle school-age children. A value of 1.0 means equal access; values below 1.0 indicate rural areas have less access. Equal access to second-chance education helps ensure no child is permanently left behind due to their location.

nodes.label: Education Inequality Between Rich and Poor Adults
nodes.description: This compares how many rich versus poor adults (25+) completed upper secondary school or higher. A value of 1.0 means equal education levels between rich and poor, while lower values mean poor adults have much less education than wealthy ones. Reducing this education gap is important because it helps create more equal opportunities for good jobs and higher incomes.

nodes.label: Primary Education Completion Gap Between Rich and Poor Adults
nodes.description: This measures how much more likely wealthy adults (ages 25+) are to have completed primary school compared to poor adults in the same country. A value of 1.0 means equal completion rates between rich and poor, while higher values mean bigger gaps favoring the wealthy. This indicator reveals whether a country's education system provides equal opportunities for all economic backgrounds, which affects social mobility and reducing poverty.

nodes.label: Urban-Rural Gap in Elementary Education Completion
nodes.description: Compares education completion rates between people living in cities versus rural areas among adults aged 25 and older. Values near 1.0 indicate similar education levels in cities and rural areas; higher values mean rural residents are less educated. Reducing this gap ensures all people have equal access to basic education regardless of where they live.

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Education Gap Between Rich and Poor Adults
nodes.description: This measures how equally lower secondary education completion is distributed between wealthy and poor adults aged 25 and older. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, while values closer to 0 indicate bigger gaps between rich and poor. Reducing educational inequality is important for giving everyone fair chances at economic success regardless of family wealth.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Out-of-School Primary Age Programs
nodes.description: This measures whether girls and boys have equal access to educational programs designed for primary school-age children who are not in regular school. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, while values below 1.0 indicate fewer girls than boys participate, and values above 1.0 mean more girls participate. Gender equality in alternative education programs ensures all children get learning opportunities regardless of their circumstances.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Alternative Middle School Programs
nodes.description: This compares how many girls versus boys are enrolled in out-of-school education programs for middle school age students. Values near 1.0 indicate equal participation, while values above or below show more girls or boys participating. Gender equality in second-chance education ensures both boys and girls who missed regular schooling have equal opportunities to catch up and improve their futures.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Middle School Education (Rural Adults 25+)
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women in rural areas have equal rates of completing at least middle school (grades 7-9) education. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, below 1.0 means fewer women than men completed middle school, and above 1.0 means more women than men completed it. Gender equality in education helps ensure all people have equal opportunities for better jobs and higher incomes.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Urban Catch-Up Programs for Middle School
nodes.description: This compares how many girls versus boys in urban areas are enrolled in special programs to complete middle school when they're older than usual. A value of 1.0 means equal participation; below 1.0 means more boys participate, above 1.0 means more girls participate. Equal access to second-chance education programs helps ensure both genders can complete their schooling and improve their life prospects.

nodes.label: University Education Gender Parity (Age 25+)
nodes.description: Compares the percentage of men versus women aged 25+ who completed university-level education. A value of 1.0 means equal educational attainment between genders, while values above 1.0 favor women and below 1.0 favor men. Gender parity in higher education creates more equal economic and social opportunities.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Lower Secondary Education - Rural Adults
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women in rural areas over age 25 completed lower secondary school (grades 7-9) at equal rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, below 1.0 means fewer women than men completed school, and above 1.0 means more women completed school. Gender equality in education helps ensure that both men and women in rural communities have the skills needed for economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Gender Gap in Elementary Education Completion - Urban Adults
nodes.description: Compares how many men versus women aged 25 and older in cities have completed at least elementary school. A value of 1.0 means equal numbers of men and women finished elementary school; values below 1.0 indicate fewer women completed school. Gender equality in basic education is crucial for ensuring all adults have fundamental literacy and numeracy skills.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Rural Alternative Middle School Programs
nodes.description: This measures whether girls and boys have equal access to alternative education programs for middle school-age children in rural areas. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender balance, while values below 1.0 indicate fewer girls participate than boys. Equal access to alternative education helps ensure both girls and boys in remote areas can continue learning even when regular schools aren't available.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in High School Education Among Urban Adults
nodes.description: This compares the percentage of adult men versus women (age 25+) living in cities who completed at least some high school education. A value of 1.0 means equal educational attainment, below 1.0 means fewer women than men completed high school, and above 1.0 means more women did. Gender equality in educational attainment reflects past progress and current opportunities for economic participation.

nodes.label: Urban Education Gender Gap (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This compares how many men versus women in urban areas (ages 25+) completed lower secondary education or higher. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, below 1.0 means fewer women than men completed school, and above 1.0 means more women completed school. Gender equality in education is crucial for fair economic opportunities and social development.

nodes.label: Wealth Gap in Rural Access to Higher Education
nodes.description: This measures whether students from rich and poor families in rural areas have equal access to tertiary education (college/university). A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, while lower values show that wealthy students are much more likely to access higher education than poor students. Equal access to higher education helps rural communities develop local talent and reduce inequality.

nodes.label: Higher Education Access Equality - Urban Areas
nodes.description: Measures how equally students from rich and poor urban families access higher education after completing high school. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, while values below 1.0 show that poor students have less access than wealthy ones. Equal access to college helps ensure that talent, not just family wealth, determines educational opportunities.

nodes.label: Primary School Access Gap Between Rich and Poor - Rural Areas
nodes.description: This compares how many children from poor families versus wealthy families in rural areas are not attending primary school. Values closer to 1.0 indicate equal access, while higher or lower values show inequality between rich and poor families. Reducing this gap ensures all children, regardless of family wealth, can get the basic education they need for a better future.

nodes.label: Wealth Gap in High School Access (Rural Areas)
nodes.description: This compares high school attendance rates between poor and wealthy families in rural areas. A value of 1.0 means children from poor and wealthy families attend high school at equal rates, while values below 1.0 mean fewer poor children attend compared to wealthy children. Reducing this wealth gap helps ensure all children have equal chances for success regardless of their family's income.

nodes.label: Wealth Equality in Rural Primary School Participation
nodes.description: This compares primary school attendance rates between children from poor and wealthy rural families. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, while values below 1.0 indicate fewer poor children attend school compared to wealthy children. Equal access to primary education regardless of family wealth is fundamental for giving all rural children a fair start in life.

nodes.label: College Enrollment in Rural Areas - Rich vs Poor Gap
nodes.description: This compares college enrollment rates between rich and poor families in rural areas, shown as a ratio. Values closer to 1.0 mean more equal access to higher education regardless of family wealth. This matters because rural students often face extra barriers to college, and reducing wealth gaps creates more opportunities.

nodes.label: Rural Education Gap by Family Wealth
nodes.description: This compares how family wealth affects middle school attendance rates in rural areas, measuring the gap between rich and poor families. Values closer to 1.0 mean wealth matters less for school attendance. Reducing wealth-based education gaps ensures all rural children get equal chances to learn.

nodes.label: Reading Skills Inequality Between Rich and Poor Youth
nodes.description: This compares literacy rates (ability to read and write) between wealthy and poor young people aged 15-24. A value of 1.0 means equal literacy between rich and poor youth, while lower values mean poor youth have much lower reading skills. Equal literacy is crucial because reading skills are essential for almost all jobs and full participation in modern society.

nodes.label: Gender Gap in Adult Literacy Rates
nodes.description: This compares literacy rates between adult women and men aged 15 and older. A value of 1.0 means equal literacy, while lower values indicate fewer women can read and write compared to men. Equal literacy rates mean both men and women can participate fully in economic opportunities and civic life.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Adult Literacy (Ages 25-64)
nodes.description: This measures whether working-age men and women have equal literacy rates by comparing the female rate to the male rate. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, while values below 1.0 indicate fewer adult women can read and write compared to men. Equal literacy between genders is essential for women's economic participation and family well-being.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Youth Literacy (Ages 15-24)
nodes.description: This measures whether young men and women ages 15-24 have equal literacy rates by comparing the female rate to the male rate. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, while values below 1.0 indicate fewer young women can read and write compared to young men. Equal literacy between genders is important for ensuring all youth have the same opportunities for education and employment.

nodes.label: Reading and Writing Skills - Poor Young Adults (15-24) (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of young adults aged 15-24 from the poorest families can read and write basic text. The value is a percentage, and higher numbers are better because they show more people have essential literacy skills. This is crucial because being able to read and write is necessary for almost any job and for participating fully in society.

nodes.label: Reading and Writing Skills Among Richest Youth
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of young people aged 15-24 from the wealthiest families can read and write. Higher percentages mean more wealthy youth have basic literacy skills. Strong literacy skills among all economic groups, including the wealthy, contribute to a more educated society and stronger economy.

nodes.label: Literacy Rate for Poor Young Men (Ages 15-24)
nodes.description: Shows the percentage of males aged 15-24 from the poorest families (bottom 20% income) who can read and write. Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all poor young men are literate. Literacy is essential for escaping poverty and accessing better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Reading and Writing Skills - Young Women from Poorest Families
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of young women aged 15-24 from the poorest families can read and write at a basic level. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better. Literacy among young women from poor families is crucial for breaking cycles of poverty and improving health and economic outcomes for future generations.

nodes.label: Literacy Rate - Young Women from Wealthy Families
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 15-24 from the wealthiest families can read and write. Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all young wealthy women are literate. This matters because literacy is essential for participating fully in modern society and the economy.

nodes.label: Women's Primary-Level Literacy Rate
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of women ages 15+ who can read and write at a primary school level. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better and indicate more literate female populations. High female literacy rates are essential for reducing poverty, improving child health, and promoting economic development in communities.

nodes.label: Women's Literacy Rate (Ages 25-64)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 25 to 64 can read and write at a lower secondary level. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. This matters because literacy skills help women participate more fully in work, family decisions, and community life.

nodes.label: Basic Literacy Rate - Young Women
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 15-24 can read and write at a basic level. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. Young women who can read and write are more likely to participate in their communities, make informed decisions about their health and families, and find better economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Literacy Rate - Older Men (65+)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of men aged 65 and older can read and write basic texts. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. Higher literacy rates among older adults indicate past educational success and help these individuals stay engaged in society and maintain their independence.

nodes.label: Literacy Rate Among Older Women
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women aged 65 and older who can read and write. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate more older women have basic literacy skills. Literacy among older adults reflects historical access to education and is important for their ability to access information, services, and participate fully in society.

nodes.label: Primary School Duration (years)
nodes.description: This measures how many years of elementary or primary school education are officially required in a country's education system. Most countries have between 4-8 years of primary education. Longer primary education typically provides children with stronger basic skills in reading, writing, and math, which are essential for future learning and success.

nodes.label: Average Years of Higher Education
nodes.description: This measures how many years the average person spends in higher education (colleges, universities, and advanced programs). Higher numbers mean people are getting more post-secondary education. This matters because higher education typically leads to better jobs, higher incomes, and improved quality of life.

nodes.label: Average Years of College Education - Men
nodes.description: This measures the average number of years men have spent in college or university education in a country. Values typically range from 0-8 years, where higher numbers indicate men have completed more advanced degrees on average. Higher values suggest better access to higher education and more skilled workers in the economy.

nodes.label: Men's Primary Education Completion - Location Gap
nodes.description: This compares the percentage of adult men (age 25+) who completed at least primary school between urban and rural areas. A value of 1.0 means equal completion rates, while higher values indicate rural areas have better completion rates than urban areas. Equal educational achievement across locations helps reduce inequality and improves economic opportunities for all men.

nodes.label: Urban Men Who Completed Lower Secondary Education
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of urban men aged 25 and older have successfully completed at least lower secondary school (through grade 9). Higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes in past generations. Men with secondary education typically earn higher wages and have more opportunities for skilled employment.

nodes.label: Urban Men Over 25 Who Completed Elementary School
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of urban men aged 25 and older have completed elementary school (typically grades 1-6). Higher percentages are better, showing that more men have basic reading, writing, and math skills. Having at least an elementary education is crucial for getting decent jobs and participating fully in society.

nodes.label: Urban Men's Lower Secondary Education Completion Rate
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of urban men ages 25+ who completed at least lower secondary school (grades 7-9). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes. This matters because educated urban male populations typically drive economic growth and innovation in cities, affecting overall national development.

nodes.label: Men Who Completed Lower Secondary School
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of men over age 25 have completed at least lower secondary education (grades 7-9). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. Men with lower secondary education typically have better job prospects and higher incomes than those who only completed primary school or less.

nodes.label: Urban Men with High School Education or Higher
nodes.description: Measures the percentage of men aged 25 and older living in cities who have completed at least high school. Higher percentages indicate more men have finished their basic education. This matters because high school completion is typically the minimum education needed for most jobs and higher education opportunities.

nodes.label: Men Age 25+ Who Completed Lower Secondary School
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of men aged 25 and older who have completed at least lower secondary education (typically grades 7-9, around ages 12-14). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better, indicating more men have basic secondary education. This matters because completing lower secondary school provides essential skills for decent jobs and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Elementary Education Level - Urban Men (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of men age 25 and older living in cities have completed at least elementary school (grades 1-6). Higher percentages are better, showing more men achieved basic literacy and numeracy skills. This matters because elementary education provides the foundation for all future learning and better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Wealthy Men's Secondary Education Completion
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adult men (age 25+) from the richest 20% of families completed at least lower secondary school (through grade 9). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes. High completion rates among wealthy men often highlight educational inequalities between rich and poor families.

nodes.label: Primary Education Completion Among Poor Adult Women
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 25 and older from the poorest 20% of households have completed at least primary school (elementary education). Values range from 0-100%, with higher values being better. This matters because it shows educational progress among the most disadvantaged women, which affects their economic opportunities and quality of life.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Among Poorest Men
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of adult men (age 25+) from the poorest 20% of families who completed at least primary school. Higher percentages are better because they indicate that even poor men got basic education. When men from poor families complete primary school, they're more likely to find stable work and support their children's education.

nodes.label: Poor Men with Elementary Education (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of men age 25 and older from the poorest families who completed at least elementary school. Higher percentages are better, indicating more men from poor backgrounds received basic education. When poor men get elementary education, they have better chances of escaping poverty and providing for their families.

nodes.label: Adults Who Completed At Least Elementary School
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adults (age 25 and older) have finished at least elementary school education. Higher percentages indicate a more educated adult population. Basic education levels in the adult population affect a country's economic development and quality of life.

nodes.label: Educational Achievement - Adults from Wealthy Families
nodes.description: This measures the highest level of education completed by adults age 25 and older from the wealthiest families. Higher values indicate these adults achieved more years of schooling, from primary through university levels. Educational achievement among wealthy adults shows how advantages can compound across generations and influence a country's overall human capital.

nodes.label: Adults with Basic Education - Poorest Families
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of adults age 25+ from the poorest 20% of families who completed at least primary education (elementary school). Higher percentages are better, showing that even poor families can access basic education. This matters because education helps break the cycle of poverty across generations.

nodes.label: Adults with Middle School Education - Poorest Families
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of adults age 25+ from the poorest 20% of families who completed at least lower secondary education (middle school). Higher percentages are better, showing poor families can access education beyond elementary school. Education helps people escape poverty and build better lives for their children.

nodes.label: Adult Men with Middle School Education - Poorest Families
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of men age 25+ from the poorest 20% of families who completed at least lower secondary education (middle school). Higher percentages are better, showing that even poor men can access education beyond elementary school. Education helps men support their families and contribute to their communities.

nodes.label: College Education Among Wealthy Adults
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of adults aged 25 and older from the richest families who completed at least lower secondary school (grade 7 or higher). Higher percentages mean more wealthy adults have formal education beyond elementary school. This indicator helps show educational inequality, as differences between rich and poor educational attainment affect social mobility and economic opportunity.

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Education Completion Rate Among Wealthiest Adults
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of adults ages 25+ from the richest 20% of households who completed at least lower secondary school (grades 7-9). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better and indicate more educated wealthy populations. This matters because it shows how well a country's education system serves its most privileged citizens, which can indicate the overall quality of educational opportunities available.

nodes.label: Educational Achievement of Wealthy Women (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This measures the highest level of education completed by women aged 25 and older from the wealthiest 20% of families, typically shown as percentages reaching different education levels. Higher education levels indicate better outcomes. This matters because it shows whether wealthy families are investing in women's education, which affects economic growth and gender equality.

nodes.label: Wealthy Men Age 25+ Who Completed Primary School
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of men aged 25 and older from the richest 20% of households who have completed at least primary education (typically grades 1-6, around ages 6-11). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate better educational achievement among wealthy men. This helps show whether even the richest families ensure their sons get basic education, which is fundamental for literacy and future learning.

nodes.label: Poor Women Age 25+ Who Completed Primary School
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women aged 25 and older from the poorest 20% of households who have completed at least primary education (typically grades 1-6). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate better educational achievement among poor women. This is critical because primary education provides basic literacy and numeracy skills that help women escape poverty and support their families.

nodes.label: Richest Women with Middle School Education - Age 25+ (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women age 25+ from the wealthiest families who completed grades 7-9 as their highest education level. Lower percentages may be better here, as it could mean more wealthy women continued to higher education. This helps show whether economic advantages translate into greater educational opportunities for women.

nodes.label: Middle School+ Education Level - Wealthy Men (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of men age 25 and older from the wealthiest families have completed at least middle school (grades 7-9) or higher education. Higher percentages are better, though wealthy men typically have high completion rates. This matters because it shows whether economic advantages translate into educational achievement for men.

nodes.label: Primary Education Among Poorest Women
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 25 and older from the poorest families have completed at least primary school. Higher percentages mean more women from poor backgrounds got basic education. When poor women receive education, it breaks cycles of poverty and improves family health and income.

nodes.label: High School Education Among Poorest Adults
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adults aged 25 and older from the poorest families have completed at least high school. Higher percentages mean more people from poor backgrounds finished secondary education. When poor adults have high school diplomas, they can access better jobs and improve their family's living conditions.

nodes.label: College Education Levels Among Rural Adults
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adults aged 25 and older living in rural areas have completed tertiary education (college or university). Values range from 0-100%, with higher values indicating better educational outcomes. This matters because higher education in rural areas helps reduce urban-rural inequality and supports local economic development.

nodes.label: Basic Education Achievement - Rural Adult Men
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of rural men aged 25 and older have completed at least primary education (grades 1-6 or higher). Higher percentages indicate better educational achievement in the population. Men with basic education can access better jobs and are more likely to support their children's education, improving whole family outcomes.

nodes.label: Rural Men with Lower Secondary Education (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of men aged 25 and older living in rural areas who completed at least lower secondary education (roughly grades 7-9). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because they show more men have basic education skills. Higher education levels in rural areas help reduce poverty and improve community development.

nodes.label: Rural Women with High School Education - Adults 25+ (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adult women (25 and older) living in rural areas have completed at least high school education. The value is a percentage, and higher numbers are better because they show more rural women have solid educational backgrounds. This is especially important because rural women often face extra barriers to education but need it to access economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Women's Education Level in Rural Areas (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of women aged 25 and older in rural areas who completed at least some lower secondary education (grades 7-9). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. This matters because women's education levels strongly predict their children's health, education, and overall family well-being.

nodes.label: Urban Women Who Completed Lower Secondary School
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of adult women (age 25+) living in cities who completed at least lower secondary school (typically grades 7-9). Higher percentages are better because they indicate more women have basic education credentials. Women with secondary education tend to have better job opportunities, healthier families, and more influence in community decisions.

nodes.label: College Education Achievement - Urban Adult Women
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of urban women aged 25 and older have completed higher education (college or university degrees). Higher percentages indicate better educational achievement in the population. Women with college degrees typically have better job opportunities and higher incomes, contributing to family well-being and economic growth.

nodes.label: Adults with Middle School Education (25+)
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of adults age 25 and older who completed at least middle school (grades 7-9). Higher percentages mean more adults have basic secondary education, which typically ranges from 0% to 100%. A more educated adult population supports economic development and helps communities make better decisions about health, finances, and civic participation.

nodes.label: Adults with Middle School Education (Age 25+)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of adults age 25 and older who have completed at least lower secondary education (roughly grades 7-9 or middle school). Higher percentages are better, showing more adults have basic education beyond elementary school. This matters because completing middle school gives people essential skills for better jobs and higher incomes.

nodes.label: Adults with Doctorate Degrees
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of adults aged 25 and older who completed doctoral-level education (PhD or equivalent). Higher percentages mean more adults have the highest level of formal education. Having educated adults with advanced degrees in a community is important because they often drive innovation, research, and economic development.

nodes.label: Women's Educational Achievement Rate (Age 25+)
nodes.description: Shows the percentage of women aged 25 and older who completed at least lower secondary education (through grade 9). Higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes, with 100% meaning all women finished at least middle school. This reflects women's access to education and predicts their economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Women with High School Education - Adults 25+ (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adult women (25 and older) have completed at least high school or equivalent education. The value is a percentage, and higher numbers are better because they show more women have foundational education. This matters because educated women typically have better job opportunities, earn more money, and can better support their families.

nodes.label: Women with High School+ Education - Adults 25+ (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adult women (25 and older) have completed high school or higher levels of education. The value is a percentage, and higher numbers are better because they indicate more women have strong educational foundations. This is important because education helps women access better jobs, earn higher wages, and have more choices in life.

nodes.label: Women with Elementary Education - Age 25+ (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women age 25 and older who completed at least elementary school (grades 1-6) as their highest level of education. Higher percentages indicate more women received basic education, though it also means they didn't continue to higher levels. Basic education helps women participate more fully in their communities and economy.

nodes.label: High School Education Level - Urban Women (Ages 25+)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women age 25 and older living in cities have completed at least high school education. Higher percentages are better, showing more women achieved this important education milestone. This matters because women with high school education or more have greater economic opportunities and can better support their families.

nodes.label: 12-Year-Old Boys Population
nodes.description: This counts the number of boys who are exactly 12 years old in a country at a given time. The number reflects the size of this specific age group and helps governments plan for middle school services and youth programs. Larger numbers mean more resources needed for this age group's education and development.

nodes.label: 13-Year-Old Boys Population
nodes.description: This counts the number of boys who are exactly 13 years old in a country. The number helps governments plan for middle school and teenage services like education and youth programs. Larger populations of 13-year-old boys indicate a need for more resources focused on early teenage development and schooling.

nodes.label: Number of 20-Year-Old Men
nodes.description: This estimates the number of men who are exactly 20 years old in a country, calculated using statistical methods to fill gaps between census years. The number reflects population size and birth rates from two decades earlier. This age group is important for planning military service, higher education, and entry-level job markets.

nodes.label: Number of 10-year-old boys
nodes.description: This measures how many boys are exactly 10 years old in a country. This age group is typically in elementary school and represents future workforce potential. Higher numbers indicate a larger young population that will need educational resources now and job opportunities in about a decade.

nodes.label: Number of 25-year-old men
nodes.description: This measures how many men are exactly 25 years old in a country. This age group is typically finishing education and entering peak working years. Higher numbers indicate more young men entering their most productive phase, which can boost economic growth if jobs are available.

nodes.label: Number of 11-year-old boys
nodes.description: This counts the total number of boys who are exactly 11 years old in a country, with missing data filled in using statistical estimates. This demographic data helps governments plan for schools, healthcare, and other services that this age group needs.

nodes.label: Number of men aged 25-29
nodes.description: This counts how many men are between ages 25 and 29 in a country. The number shows the size of this young adult male population group. Higher numbers mean more men in their late twenties, which helps predict workforce size and housing demand since this age group is typically starting careers and families.

nodes.label: Number of women aged 25-29
nodes.description: This counts how many women are between 25 and 29 years old in a country. This age group is typically at peak childbearing years and establishing careers. A higher number means more women in their prime productive years, which can drive economic growth if they have access to education and employment opportunities.

nodes.label: Female Population Ages 35-39
nodes.description: This counts the number of women between ages 35 and 39 living in a country. This age group typically represents women in their prime working and family-raising years. This matters because women in this age range are often key contributors to the economy while also caring for children and aging parents, affecting workforce participation and family welfare.

nodes.label: Number of men aged 35-39
nodes.description: This counts the total number of men between ages 35 and 39 in a country. This age group is typically in their prime working years, so larger numbers can indicate more people contributing to the economy and supporting families.

nodes.label: Number of Women Ages 30-34
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women between ages 30 and 34 living in a country. Higher numbers simply reflect larger population size and aren't inherently good or bad. This age group is important for understanding workforce size and family planning, as these women are often in their peak career and childbearing years.

nodes.label: Working-Age Men
nodes.description: This counts the total number of men between ages 15 and 64, which represents the typical working-age population. The number is reported as total people, so larger countries have higher values. A larger working-age population can support more economic growth and provide for children and elderly people, improving overall living standards.

nodes.label: Working-Age Women
nodes.description: This counts the total number of women between ages 15 and 64, which represents the typical working-age population. The number is reported as total people, so larger countries have higher values. A larger working-age population can contribute more to economic growth and support children and elderly people, improving overall living standards.

nodes.label: Number of 12-Year-Old Girls
nodes.description: This counts how many 12-year-old girls live in a country at a specific time, with estimates filled in for missing data. This number helps track the size of the population entering their teenage years and secondary school age. This is important for planning middle schools, healthcare programs, and understanding the future workforce and reproductive health needs.

nodes.label: Number of 20-year-old women
nodes.description: This counts how many women are exactly 20 years old in a country. This age group is typically entering college or the workforce and starting families. A higher number suggests more young women entering their most productive years, which can boost economic growth if they have access to education and job opportunities.

nodes.label: Female Population Age 10 (Estimated)
nodes.description: This estimates the number of 10-year-old girls in a country, using statistical methods to fill gaps in census data. The number reflects both population size and birth rates from a decade earlier. This specific age group matters because these girls are typically in elementary or middle school, representing the country's investment in educating the next generation of women.

nodes.label: Number of 11-year-old girls
nodes.description: This counts the total number of girls who are exactly 11 years old in a country, with missing data filled in using statistical estimates. This demographic data helps governments plan for schools, healthcare, and other services that this age group needs.

nodes.label: Adult Learning Participation - Ages 55-64
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of adults aged 55-64 participated in any learning or education programs in the past 12 months. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate more lifelong learning. Adult education helps older workers update their skills and stay competitive in changing job markets.

nodes.label: Young Men Attending Elementary Programs (Ages 15-24)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of young men ages 15-24 who are currently enrolled in elementary-level education programs. Higher percentages can indicate either good access to catch-up programs for those who missed school earlier, or concerning delays in educational progress. These programs help young men gain basic literacy and numeracy skills essential for employment and daily life.

nodes.label: Young Adult Participation in Primary Education Programs
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of people aged 15-24 who participated in primary-level education programs in the past year. Higher percentages mean more young adults are getting basic education they may have missed earlier. This matters because it gives young people a second chance to learn essential reading, writing, and math skills needed for jobs and daily life.

nodes.label: Young Adult Participation in Primary-Level Learning Programs
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of people ages 15-64 who participated in primary-level education or literacy programs in the past 12 months. Higher percentages indicate more adults are pursuing basic education they may have missed. This matters because adult literacy and basic education programs help people develop skills needed for better employment and full participation in society.

nodes.label: Adult Learning Gender Balance - Basic Education
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women ages 15-64 participate equally in basic adult education programs. A value of 1.0 means equal participation, while other values show which gender participates more. Equal access to adult learning helps both men and women improve their job skills and economic opportunities throughout their lives.

nodes.label: Students per Qualified High School Teacher (Ratio)
nodes.description: This measures how many students each qualified teacher handles in high school classrooms on average. Lower numbers are better because they mean smaller class sizes and more individual attention. When teachers have fewer students, they can provide better instruction and support, leading to improved learning outcomes.

nodes.label: Students Per Qualified Teacher - Elementary
nodes.description: Measures how many primary school students (grades 1-6) are assigned to each qualified teacher on average. Lower numbers are better because teachers can give more individual attention - for example, 15 students per teacher is better than 40 per teacher. Smaller class sizes with qualified teachers help children learn to read and do math more effectively.

nodes.label: Students per Qualified Teacher - Middle School
nodes.description: This measures how many middle school students (typically grades 7-9, ages 12-14) there are for each qualified teacher. Lower numbers are better, meaning smaller class sizes and more individual attention. This matters because students learn better when teachers can give them more personal attention and support.

nodes.label: Students Per Qualified Teacher - Pre-Primary
nodes.description: This measures how many pre-primary students (ages 3-5) are assigned to each qualified teacher in early childhood programs. Lower ratios are better because they mean more individual attention for each child. nodes.label: Government Spending per Girl in Middle School
nodes.description: This shows how much money the government spends per girl enrolled in middle school (grades 7-9), usually measured in local currency or US dollars. nodes.description: This measures how much money the government spends on each girl enrolled in pre-primary education (ages 3-5). nodes.label: Government Spending Per Female Post-Secondary Student
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government spends on each female student in post-secondary education (colleges, universities, and vocational schools). Adequate funding for women's higher education helps ensure they can develop advanced skills and compete for well-paying careers.

nodes.description: This tracks how much government money is spent on education for each female student in programs beyond high school (like community college or technical training). Higher spending typically means more resources, better facilities, and more support services per student. Adequate funding for women's post-secondary education helps close gender gaps in career opportunities and earning potential.

nodes.label: Government Spending Per Female High School Student
nodes.description: This tracks how much government money is spent on each female student in high school education. nodes.label: College Education Costs for Female Students

nodes.label: Cost Per Female Primary Student

nodes.label: Primary School-Age Children Out of School Rate

nodes.label: Elementary and Middle School Dropout Rate
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of children who should be in primary or lower secondary school (typically ages 6-14) are not enrolled in any school. nodes.label: Middle School Students Not in School

Lower percentages are better, meaning more children are getting an education. nodes.label: Children Not in Primary School (%)

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Girls Not Attending School

nodes.label: Boys Not Attending Primary School

nodes.label: Gender Gap in Primary School Attendance
nodes.description: This compares the rates of boys versus girls who are not attending primary school. nodes.label: Boys in Job-Training Programs After Middle School
nodes.description: Measures the enrollment rate of boys in vocational or technical training programs that prepare them for specific careers, typically after completing middle school. Higher rates mean more boys are getting hands-on job skills training. These programs matter because they provide practical skills that lead directly to employment opportunities.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Vocational Education After High School
nodes.description: This measures whether women and men are equally enrolled in job-focused training programs that require completing high school first. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender balance, below 1.0 means fewer women than men, and above 1.0 means more women than men are enrolled. Gender balance in vocational training helps ensure all people have equal opportunities to develop job skills for economic success.

nodes.label: Enrollment in Job-Focused Training After High School
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of people enrolled in vocational or technical training programs designed to teach specific job skills after completing high school. Higher percentages indicate more people are gaining practical skills for employment in trades, technology, or other specialized fields. Vocational training provides pathways to good-paying jobs and helps meet workforce needs in various industries.

nodes.label: Vocational Training Enrollment in Grades 7-9
nodes.description: This measures enrollment in vocational and technical education programs for students in grades 7-9, shown as a percentage that can exceed 100% if over- or under-age students are enrolled. Higher values indicate more students are getting hands-on job training alongside regular academics. This matters because vocational skills help students find good jobs even if they don't attend college.

nodes.label: Women in Post-High School Job Training (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women enrolled in vocational programs after high school that teach specific job skills like nursing or mechanics. Higher percentages mean more women are getting practical training for careers. Job training programs help women enter skilled trades and earn better wages.

nodes.label: Girls-to-boys ratio in elementary school
nodes.description: This measures how many girls are enrolled in elementary school compared to boys, where 1.0 means equal enrollment. Values below 1.0 mean fewer girls than boys are in school, while values above 1.0 mean more girls are enrolled. This matters because equal education access for both genders leads to better economic opportunities and social development.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Gender Gap
nodes.description: This compares college and university enrollment rates between men and women by dividing the female rate by the male rate. A value of 1.0 means equal enrollment, while values above 1.0 mean more women are enrolled than men. Gender equality in higher education helps ensure both men and women have equal opportunities for advanced careers.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Middle School Enrollment
nodes.description: This measures whether boys and girls enroll in lower secondary school (grades 7-9) at equal rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls than boys are enrolled. This matters because equal enrollment ensures both boys and girls have the same opportunities to continue their education.

nodes.label: Gender Gap in Primary School Enrollment
nodes.description: This measures how equally boys and girls of proper age are enrolled in primary school, shown as a ratio. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls are enrolled than boys, and above 1.0 means more girls than boys. Equal enrollment ensures all children get the same opportunity to start their education.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Upper Secondary Enrollment
nodes.description: This compares how many girls versus boys are enrolled in upper secondary school at the appropriate age. A value of 1.0 means equal enrollment, below 1.0 means fewer girls, and above 1.0 means more girls are enrolled. Equal access ensures both genders can develop the advanced skills needed for leadership roles and professional careers.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Middle School Entry
nodes.description: This measures whether boys and girls enter middle school (grades 7-9) at equal rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls than boys enter middle school, and above 1.0 means more girls than boys enter. Equal access to middle school helps ensure both boys and girls can develop the skills needed for high school and future careers.

nodes.label: Primary School Entry Gender Equality
nodes.description: This measures how equally boys and girls enter primary school at the right age. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality between boys and girls, while values above 1.0 mean more girls enter than boys, and values below 1.0 mean more boys enter than girls. Gender equality in school entry is important because it shows whether all children have equal opportunities to start their education.

nodes.label: Middle School Gender Equality in Enrollment
nodes.description: This measures how equally girls and boys are enrolled in middle school (grades 7-9) by comparing their enrollment rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls than boys are enrolled, and above 1.0 means more girls than boys are enrolled. Gender equality in education matters because it ensures all children have equal opportunities to learn and succeed regardless of their sex.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Lower Secondary School Enrollment
nodes.description: This measures whether girls and boys enroll in lower secondary school (grades 7-9) at equal rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls than boys are enrolled, and above 1.0 means more girls are enrolled. This indicator is crucial because equal educational access for both genders leads to better economic opportunities and social development for entire societies.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Primary School Enrollment
nodes.description: This measures whether girls and boys enroll in primary school at equal rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls than boys are enrolled, and above 1.0 means more girls are enrolled. Gender equality in primary education is fundamental because it ensures both boys and girls get the basic skills needed for further learning and productive lives.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Lower Secondary School Enrollment
nodes.description: This measures how equal girls' and boys' enrollment rates are in lower secondary school (grades 7-9), shown as a ratio where 1.0 means perfect equality. Values closer to 1.0 are better, while values much above or below 1.0 show gender inequality. This matters because equal access to education for both genders promotes fairness and stronger economic development.

nodes.label: Gender Gap in Elementary School Enrollment
nodes.description: Compares enrollment rates between boys and girls of elementary school age (6-11 years). A value of 1.0 means equal enrollment; values below 1.0 indicate fewer girls are enrolled than boys. Equal enrollment for both genders is crucial because elementary school provides the foundation skills in reading, writing, and math that all children need for future success.

nodes.label: High School Enrollment Gender Balance
nodes.description: This measures whether girls and boys enroll in high school at equal rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender balance, while values below 1.0 indicate fewer girls are enrolled than boys. Equal enrollment ensures both girls and boys have the same opportunities to complete their education and prepare for careers or higher education.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Elementary School Enrollment
nodes.description: This compares enrollment rates of boys versus girls in elementary school (grades 1-6). A value of 1.0 means equal enrollment, below 1.0 means fewer girls are enrolled, and above 1.0 means more girls are enrolled than boys. Equal access to elementary education for both genders is fundamental for creating fair opportunities throughout life.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Early School Enrollment
nodes.description: This compares enrollment rates between boys and girls in primary school, including students who may be older or younger than typical. A value of 1.0 means equal enrollment by gender. Gender-balanced enrollment ensures both boys and girls have equal access to basic education from an early age.

nodes.label: Primary School Enrollment Rate for Girls (%)
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of school-age girls who are enrolled in primary school at the appropriate age for their grade level. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better since they mean more girls are getting timely access to education. When girls start school at the right age, they're more likely to stay in school and succeed academically.

nodes.label: Net Enrollment Rate - Upper Secondary, Male
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys of official upper secondary school age (typically 15-17) who are enrolled in upper secondary education. The rate is calculated relative to the total male population of that age group. Higher percentages indicate better educational access for teenage boys. This matters because secondary education is crucial for future employment and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Girls Enrolled in Primary School at Right Age
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of primary school-age girls (typically ages 6-11) who are actually enrolled in primary school. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because they mean more girls are getting education at the appropriate age. When girls attend primary school, they gain essential literacy and math skills that improve their future job prospects and health decisions.

nodes.label: Primary School Enrollment Rate - Boys
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of school-age boys (typically ages 6-11) are enrolled in primary school at the right age for their grade level. Higher percentages are better, with 100% being the maximum since it only counts children at the appropriate age. This indicates whether boys are starting school on time, which affects their future educational success.

nodes.label: Primary School Enrollment Rate - Age-Appropriate Students
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of children who are enrolled in primary school at the right age (typically 6-11 years old). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better, showing more children start school on time. Starting school at the appropriate age helps children learn alongside peers their own age and builds a strong foundation for lifelong learning.

nodes.label: Female Students in Higher Education After Upper Secondary (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of young women who enroll in college or university programs after completing upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Higher percentages indicate more women are continuing their education beyond high school. This is important because higher education opens doors to better career opportunities and helps reduce gender inequality in professional fields.

nodes.label: Percentage of Middle School Age Students in College-Prep Programs
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of students who are middle school age (typically 12-14) are enrolled in tertiary or college-preparatory programs. Higher percentages indicate more academically advanced students are getting accelerated education. While this represents high achievement, very high rates might suggest the regular school system isn't challenging enough for bright students.

nodes.label: Primary School Enrollment Rate for School-Age Girls
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of girls at the official primary school age (typically 6-11) who are actually enrolled in primary school. Values range from 0-100%, where 100% means all school-age girls are enrolled. High enrollment rates for girls are crucial because primary education provides foundational skills that affect lifelong learning, health, and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Primary School Enrollment Rate - Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys who are the right age for primary school (typically ages 6-11) are actually enrolled in school. The value ranges from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because they mean more boys are getting an education. When more children attend primary school, they develop basic reading and math skills that help them succeed in life and find better jobs.

nodes.label: Primary School Enrollment Rate (Age-Appropriate Students)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of children at the right age for primary school (typically ages 6-11) are actually enrolled in primary school. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. This matters because primary school provides essential basic skills that children need for all future learning and work opportunities.

nodes.label: Age-Appropriate Students Enrolled in Upper Secondary School
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of students who are the right age (typically 15-17) and enrolled in upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean more students are progressing through school at the expected pace. Students completing upper secondary education have much better chances of accessing higher education and skilled jobs.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate - Boys (After Elementary)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys who completed elementary school (grades 1-6) eventually enroll in college or university programs. Higher percentages are better, showing educational pathways are working effectively. This matters because it reveals whether boys can progress from basic education to higher education that opens doors to professional careers.

nodes.label: Male Student Mobility Rate - Tertiary
nodes.description: This measures how often male college and university students move between institutions or countries for their education. Higher rates indicate more students are studying abroad or transferring schools. Student mobility can improve education quality by exposing students to different teaching methods and cultures.

nodes.label: Middle School Entry Rate - Girls
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of girls successfully enter lower secondary school (grades 7-9) at the appropriate age, adjusted for those who may have started late. Higher percentages are better, showing more girls transition from primary to middle school. This transition is critical for girls because middle school dropout often means they never return to education.

nodes.label: Grade Repetition Rate - 4th Grade Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys repeat 4th grade instead of advancing to 5th grade. Values range from 0-100%, where lower percentages are better, indicating more boys are progressing normally through school. Low repetition rates show that boys are mastering fundamental reading and math skills needed for future academic success.

nodes.label: Girls Repeating 4th Grade
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of girls who must repeat 4th grade instead of advancing to 5th grade. Lower percentages are better, showing more girls are progressing normally through school. Grade repetition can discourage students from continuing their education and delays their learning progress.

nodes.label: Percentage of Girls Repeating 8th Grade
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of girls have to repeat 8th grade (typically age 14) instead of moving up to 9th grade. Lower percentages are better, as they mean more girls are successfully progressing through school on schedule. High repetition rates can lead to girls dropping out of school entirely, limiting their future earning potential and life choices.

nodes.label: Middle School Grade Repetition Rate
nodes.description: Measures the percentage of students in lower secondary school (grades 7-9) who must repeat a grade instead of advancing. Values range from 0% to potentially high percentages, where lower is better - meaning students are progressing normally. High repetition rates signal problems with education quality or student support systems.

nodes.label: Students Repeating Lower Secondary Grades
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of students in lower secondary school (grades 7-9) have to repeat a grade because they didn't meet requirements to advance. Values range from 0% to 100%, where lower percentages are better because they indicate students are successfully progressing through school. High repetition rates suggest problems with education quality or student support that can lead to students dropping out entirely.

nodes.label: Boys Repeating Lower Secondary School (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys in grades 7-9 (ages 12-14) who have to repeat their grade level instead of moving up to the next grade. Higher percentages indicate more boys are struggling academically and having to redo their year. This matters because high repetition rates signal problems in education quality and can lead to boys dropping out of school entirely.

nodes.label: High School Enrollment Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many students are enrolled in upper secondary school (typically grades 10-12) compared to the number of teenagers who should be at that level. Values can exceed 100% when older or younger students also enroll. Higher rates generally indicate better access to high school education, which prepares students for college or skilled jobs.

nodes.label: Modified College Enrollment Rate - Men
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of men enrolled in higher education (colleges and universities) compared to the total population of college-age men. Values can exceed 100% when older or younger students also enroll. Higher rates indicate more men are pursuing advanced education, which typically leads to better career prospects and higher earnings throughout their lives.

nodes.label: Modified Primary School Enrollment Rate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of primary school-age children are enrolled in school, adjusted for special circumstances like emergencies or data collection issues. The rate can exceed 100% if older or younger children are also enrolled in primary grades. Higher rates indicate more children have access to basic education, which is essential for developing literacy, numeracy, and critical thinking skills needed for future success.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate - Women
nodes.description: This measures how many women are enrolled in universities and colleges compared to the number of women of typical college age in the population. Values can exceed 100% when older or younger students also enroll, and higher percentages are better. Strong female participation in higher education leads to more women in professional careers and leadership roles.

nodes.label: Women's Enrollment Rate in Post-High School Technical Programs
nodes.description: This measures how many women are enrolled in technical or vocational programs that come after high school but before college. Numbers above 100% are possible when older or younger students also enroll. Higher rates generally indicate more women are gaining practical job skills, which is important for economic independence and career advancement.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate - Adjusted (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of college-age people are enrolled in higher education programs (universities, technical colleges, etc.), adjusted for special circumstances like delayed entry or extended programs. Values are given as percentages, and higher numbers are better because they show more people getting advanced education. This is important because college education typically leads to higher-paying careers and better economic opportunities.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate for Men
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of men are enrolled in colleges and universities, which can exceed 100% if older or younger students are also enrolled. Higher percentages generally indicate better access to higher education. This matters because college education typically leads to better job opportunities and higher lifetime earnings.

nodes.label: High School Enrollment Rate for Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of high school-age girls are enrolled in school, which can exceed 100% if older or younger students are also enrolled in high school programs. Higher percentages indicate more girls are accessing education, though over 100% might suggest students are starting late or repeating grades. Girls' high school enrollment is critical for reducing gender inequality and improving economic opportunities.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate (All Ages)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of college-age people are enrolled in universities, colleges, or other higher education programs. Values can exceed 100% when older or younger students also enroll. Higher rates are generally better, showing strong access to higher education. This matters because college education typically leads to better jobs and higher incomes.

nodes.label: Modified College Enrollment Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of college-age students actually enrolled in higher education programs, adjusted for certain factors. Values can exceed 100% if students outside the typical age range are enrolled. Higher rates indicate better access to college and university education, which is important for developing skilled workers and reducing poverty.

nodes.label: College Graduation Rate - Men (Bachelor's and Master's)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of men graduate with bachelor's or master's degrees compared to the typical graduation age population. Values are expressed as percentages and can exceed 100% when older or younger students also graduate. Higher rates indicate more men are completing college degrees, which typically leads to better job opportunities and economic growth.

nodes.label: College Graduation Rate - Women (Bachelor's and Master's)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women graduate with bachelor's or master's degrees compared to the typical graduation age population. Values are expressed as percentages and can exceed 100% when older or younger students also graduate. Higher rates show more women are completing college degrees, which improves gender equality and economic development.

nodes.label: College Graduation Gender Equality Index
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women graduate from college at equal rates by dividing the female graduation rate by the male graduation rate. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, below 1.0 means fewer women graduate, and above 1.0 means more women graduate than men. Values closer to 1.0 indicate better gender equality in higher education access.

nodes.label: Test Score Ranking for Middle School Boys
nodes.description: This shows how well boys in middle school (grades 7-9) perform on standardized tests compared to other students, expressed as a percentile ranking. Higher percentiles mean better academic performance relative to peers. Strong test performance indicates boys are gaining the knowledge and skills they need for future education and career success.

nodes.label: Primary School Test Scores for Boys
nodes.description: This measures how well first-grade boys perform on standardized academic tests compared to other students. Higher percentiles mean boys are scoring better relative to their peers. Tracking early academic performance by gender helps identify if boys or girls need additional support to succeed in their foundational learning years.

nodes.label: Boys' Test Scores in Early Elementary School
nodes.description: Measures how well boys in grades 1-6 perform on standardized tests compared to other students, shown as a percentile ranking from 0 to 100. Higher percentiles mean boys are scoring better than more of their peers (50th percentile = average, 90th percentile = better than 90% of students). Strong test performance indicates boys are gaining essential reading and math skills needed for future success.

nodes.label: Boys' Test Scores in Elementary School
nodes.description: Measures how well boys in elementary school (grades 1-6) perform on standardized tests compared to all students, shown as a percentile ranking from 0 to 100. Higher percentiles mean boys are outperforming more of their peers (75th percentile = better than 75% of students). Strong elementary test scores indicate boys are mastering basic reading and math skills essential for future academic success.

nodes.label: Academic Achievement Ranking - Boys
nodes.description: This measures where boys rank on standardized academic tests compared to other students, shown as a percentile from 0-100. Higher percentiles mean boys are performing better academically relative to their peers. This matters because strong academic performance in early grades sets the foundation for success in higher education and future careers.

nodes.label: Primary School Test Scores - Boys
nodes.description: This measures how well boys perform on standardized tests in primary school compared to other students. Higher scores indicate better academic achievement. Strong test performance by boys shows they are learning essential reading, writing, and math skills needed for future success in school and work.

nodes.label: Test Score Ranking - College Men
nodes.description: This measures how well men in post-secondary education perform on standardized tests compared to other students, expressed as a percentile ranking. Higher percentiles mean better performance relative to peers. This matters because academic achievement in college affects career prospects and earning potential.

nodes.label: Student Test Score Ranking
nodes.description: This shows how students in a country perform on standardized tests compared to students in other countries, expressed as a percentile from 0-100. Higher percentiles mean students are performing better relative to their international peers. Strong academic performance indicates students are gaining the knowledge and skills they need to compete in the global economy and pursue higher education.

nodes.label: Elementary School Test Score Rankings
nodes.description: This measures how well elementary students perform on standardized tests compared to other countries or regions, shown as a percentile ranking from 0-100. Higher percentiles mean students are performing better relative to others being compared. Strong test performance indicates students are learning essential skills that will help them succeed in higher grades and future careers.

nodes.label: First Grade Test Scores
nodes.description: This measures how well first-grade students perform on standardized tests, typically shown as percentile rankings. Higher scores indicate better early academic achievement. Strong performance in first grade sets the foundation for future learning success and helps identify students who may need extra support.

nodes.label: Primary School Test Score Rankings
nodes.description: Measures how primary school students (ages 6-11) perform on standardized tests compared to other countries, shown as a percentile ranking. Higher percentiles mean better performance relative to global standards. Strong primary education test scores indicate students are building essential reading and math skills for future learning.

nodes.label: Elementary School Test Score Rankings
nodes.description: This shows how well elementary school students perform on standardized tests compared to other students, ranked from 1-100. Higher numbers mean better academic performance relative to peers. Strong test performance in elementary school indicates students are learning basic reading and math skills needed for success in higher grades and future careers.

nodes.label: Student Test Performance - Primary School
nodes.description: This measures how well primary school students perform on standardized tests compared to other students, shown as a percentile ranking. Higher percentiles mean students scored better than more of their peers. Strong academic performance in primary school indicates students are building the fundamental skills they need for success in higher grades and future learning.

nodes.label: Elementary School Test Score Rankings
