nodes.description: This measures how elementary students in a country perform on standardized tests compared to students in other countries, shown as a percentile ranking. A score of 50 means the country performs better than half of all countries, while 90 means better than 90% of countries. Strong elementary education performance indicates students are building solid foundations in reading, math, and critical thinking skills.

nodes.label: Primary School Girls' Test Score Rankings
nodes.description: This shows how girls in primary school perform on standardized tests compared to other students, expressed as a percentile ranking from 0-100. Higher percentiles mean girls are scoring better relative to their peers on tests measuring skills like reading and math. Strong academic performance by girls indicates they're getting quality education and developing skills needed for future success.

nodes.label: Female Upper Secondary Test Score Ranking
nodes.description: This shows where female students in upper secondary school (grades 10-12) rank on standardized tests compared to other students, expressed as a percentile from 0 to 100. Higher percentiles mean girls are performing better academically. Strong academic performance helps young women access higher education and professional careers.

nodes.label: Girls' Test Scores in Elementary School
nodes.description: This measures how well girls perform on standardized tests in elementary school, typically shown as a percentile ranking. Higher scores indicate better academic achievement compared to other students. Strong elementary performance, especially for girls, helps ensure equal educational opportunities and future career success.

nodes.label: Girls' Test Score Rankings in Lower Secondary
nodes.description: This measures how well girls in lower secondary school (typically grades 7-9) perform on standardized tests compared to other students, shown as a percentile ranking. Values range from 0 to 100, where 50 means average performance and higher numbers mean better test results. Strong academic performance helps girls access better educational and career opportunities later in life.

nodes.label: Girls' Test Score Rankings in Elementary School
nodes.description: This shows how well girls in elementary school (typically grades 1-6) perform on standardized tests compared to other students, expressed as a percentile ranking from 0-100. Higher percentiles mean better performance. Strong early academic achievement for girls is important because it sets the foundation for continued education and future career opportunities.

nodes.label: Post-Secondary Student Test Score Rankings
nodes.description: This shows how post-secondary students (in college, university, or vocational programs) perform on standardized tests compared to their peers, expressed as percentile rankings from 0-100. Higher percentiles indicate better academic performance and stronger mastery of advanced skills. Strong performance at this level suggests students are well-prepared for professional careers and can contribute effectively to their country's economy.

nodes.label: Pre-Primary Test Scores (percentile ranking)
nodes.description: This measures how well children in pre-school (ages 3-5) perform on standardized tests compared to other children globally, shown as a percentile ranking from 0-100. Higher percentiles mean better performance relative to other countries. Strong early learning outcomes help children succeed when they enter elementary school and throughout their educational journey.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate for Girls
nodes.description: Measures the percentage of girls who successfully finish lower secondary education (grades 7-9, ages 12-14). Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all girls complete middle school. Completing middle school gives girls better chances for continued education and economic independence later in life.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in High School Completion Rates
nodes.description: This compares how many girls versus boys successfully finish high school. A value of 1.0 means equal completion rates; below 1.0 means more boys complete high school, above 1.0 means more girls complete. Equal completion rates are important because both genders need full secondary education to access good jobs and contribute equally to society and the economy.

nodes.label: Percentage of Girls Finishing High School
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of girls successfully complete all of high school (grades 9-12, typically ages 15-17). Higher percentages are better, indicating more girls are getting the full secondary education needed for college or skilled jobs. Completing high school dramatically improves a woman's earning potential and gives her more choices in life.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate for Boys
nodes.description: Shows the percentage of boys who successfully finish upper secondary education (grades 10-12, typically ages 15-17). Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all boys complete high school. Completing high school is crucial for boys' future job prospects and earning potential.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate - Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys successfully finish middle school (grades 7-9). Higher percentages are better, showing more boys are completing this crucial education level. This matters because middle school completion is essential for boys to continue to high school and eventually find stable, well-paying jobs.

nodes.label: Boys Who Complete Lower Secondary School
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys who successfully finish lower secondary education (typically grades 7-9, around ages 12-14). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better, showing more boys are completing this crucial education level. Completing lower secondary school gives boys essential skills and knowledge needed for further education or skilled work.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate - Boys
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of boys successfully complete lower secondary education (grades 7-9, typically ages 12-14). Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all boys finish middle school. Completing middle school is essential because it provides the foundation needed for high school and helps boys develop skills for better-paying jobs.

nodes.label: Boys Completing Upper Secondary School
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys who successfully finish upper secondary education (roughly grades 10-12). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because they mean more boys are completing their full secondary education. High completion rates help ensure young men have the skills needed for good jobs and higher education.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate - Boys (%)
nodes.description: This tracks what percentage of boys successfully complete middle school (typically grades 7-9). Higher percentages indicate that more boys are finishing this critical stage of education. Middle school completion is important because it prepares students for high school and helps them develop the skills needed for good jobs.

nodes.label: Middle School Graduation Rate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of students successfully complete middle school (typically grades 7-9). Higher percentages mean more students are finishing this crucial stage of education. Completing middle school is essential for students to continue to high school and develop the skills needed for good jobs.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate (%)
nodes.description: This tracks what percentage of students successfully complete high school (grades 10-12). Higher percentages indicate that more young people are finishing their secondary education. High school completion is critical because it significantly increases a person's chances of finding good jobs, earning higher wages, and continuing to college or vocational training.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of students who successfully finish primary school (usually through grade 5 or 6). Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better since they indicate more children are completing their basic education. Higher completion rates mean more people have fundamental reading, writing, and math skills needed for better jobs and life opportunities.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate - Upper-Middle Income Girls
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of girls from upper-middle income families (4th wealth quintile) who successfully finish high school. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better. High school completion dramatically improves girls' chances of attending college, getting skilled jobs, and having greater control over their life choices and economic independence.

nodes.label: Middle School Graduation Rate (Wealthy Girls)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from the wealthiest families (top 20%) complete middle school. Higher percentages are better, though wealthy students typically have high completion rates already. Comparing this to poorer students helps identify how much family income affects educational success.

nodes.label: Elementary School Completion Rate - Wealthy Boys
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of boys from the wealthiest families successfully complete elementary school. Higher percentages indicate more wealthy boys are finishing their basic education. While wealthy students typically have advantages, tracking their completion rates helps ensure that even privileged children are getting the fundamental education they need.

nodes.label: High School Graduation Gap Between Urban and Rural Areas
nodes.description: This compares high school completion rates between urban and rural students. A value of 1.0 means equal completion rates, while values below 1.0 indicate rural students are less likely to graduate. Reducing this gap ensures that where students live doesn't determine their chances of completing high school and accessing higher education or better jobs.

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Completion Gap Between Urban and Rural Areas
nodes.description: This measures how equally lower secondary school completion is distributed between urban and rural areas. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality between cities and countryside, while values farther from 1.0 indicate bigger gaps. Reducing geographic education gaps ensures that where children live doesn't determine their access to learning opportunities and future success.

nodes.label: High School Completion Gender Equality Index
nodes.description: This compares high school completion rates between girls and boys, where 1.0 means perfect equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls complete, and above 1.0 means fewer boys complete. Values closer to 1.0 are better as they indicate equal educational opportunities. Gender equality in education leads to more balanced economic development and reduced inequality.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Primary School Completion
nodes.description: This compares how many girls versus boys complete primary school, with values around 1.0 indicating equal completion rates between genders. Values below 1.0 mean fewer girls than boys finish primary school, while values above 1.0 mean more girls than boys complete it. Equal completion rates show that both boys and girls have fair opportunities to gain basic literacy and numeracy skills.

nodes.label: Gender Gap in Lower Secondary Completion (Grades 7-9)
nodes.description: This measures how equally boys and girls complete lower secondary school (grades 7-9), shown as a ratio. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, below 1.0 means fewer girls complete school than boys, and above 1.0 means more girls complete than boys. Equal completion rates for both genders ensures all young people have fair opportunities for education and future careers.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate - Rural Areas
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of students in rural areas successfully complete middle school (typically grades 7-9, ages 12-14). Higher percentages are better, showing more rural students finishing lower secondary education. This matters because middle school completion prepares students for high school and better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Students Finishing High School - Rural Areas (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of students in rural areas who complete all years of high school (grades 10-12, ages 15-17). Higher percentages are better, showing more rural students are getting a complete secondary education. This matters because rural students often face extra challenges reaching school, and high school completion opens doors to better opportunities.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate - Rural Girls
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of girls in rural areas successfully complete lower secondary education (grades 7-9, typically ages 12-14). Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all rural girls finish middle school. This is especially important because rural girls face extra barriers to education, but completing middle school dramatically improves their life prospects.

nodes.label: Rural Girls' Upper Secondary Completion Rate
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of girls in rural areas successfully finish upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Rates range from 0% to 100%, with higher values indicating better educational outcomes. When rural girls complete secondary education, they gain skills needed for better jobs and become leaders in their communities.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate - Rural Boys (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys in rural areas successfully complete middle school (typically grades 7-9). Higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes. When rural boys finish middle school, they're more likely to continue their education and have access to better job opportunities later in life.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate - Rural Boys (%)
nodes.description: This tracks what percentage of boys in rural areas successfully complete high school (grades 10-12). Higher percentages show better educational outcomes for rural communities. High school completion is crucial because it opens doors to college, vocational training, and jobs that require advanced skills.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate - Rural Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls in rural areas successfully complete primary school (typically grades 1-6, ages 6-11). Higher percentages are better, showing more rural girls finishing basic education. This matters because educated girls have better health outcomes and economic opportunities throughout their lives.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate - Rural Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys in rural areas successfully complete primary school (typically grades 1-6, ages 6-11). Higher percentages are better, showing more rural boys finishing basic education. This matters because primary education provides essential skills boys need for further schooling and decent jobs.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate - Rural Wealthy Boys
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys from the wealthiest families in rural areas who successfully finish high school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages indicate more boys are completing their secondary education. High school completion significantly improves young men's chances of getting well-paying jobs and continuing to college.

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Completion Rate - Rural Wealthy Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from the wealthiest families in rural areas complete grades 7-9 (lower secondary school). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better, showing more girls finish this critical education level. High completion rates indicate that even girls in remote areas can access quality education when families have resources.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion - Rural Rich Boys
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys from the richest 20% of rural families who complete lower secondary education (middle school). Higher percentages are better, showing successful completion of this education level. Completing middle school gives students the foundation needed for high school and future career opportunities.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate - Rural Boys from Wealthiest Families (%)
nodes.description: This tracks what percentage of boys from the richest 20% of families in rural areas successfully finish elementary school (typically grades 1-6). Higher percentages are better, showing that wealthy rural boys are completing their basic education. This matters because primary school completion provides the foundation for all future learning and job opportunities.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate - Rural Girls from Wealthiest Families (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from the richest 20% of families in rural areas successfully finish high school. Higher percentages are better, showing that wealthy rural girls are completing their secondary education. High school completion gives girls the qualifications needed for higher education and professional careers.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion - Wealthy Rural Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from the wealthiest families in rural areas successfully complete primary school. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. Even among wealthy families in rural areas, girls may face barriers to finishing school, so tracking completion helps ensure all children get the education they need for future success.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate - Rural Girls from Middle-Income Families
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from middle-income families (third income group) living in rural areas successfully complete high school. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better. Tracking rural girls' high school completion helps identify barriers to education in less populated areas where schools and resources may be limited.

nodes.label: Upper Secondary Completion - Rural Higher-Income Students
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of higher-income students living in rural areas complete upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Higher percentages mean more well-off rural students are finishing high school. This helps identify whether students in rural areas have the same educational opportunities as those in cities, even when family income is similar.

nodes.label: Elementary School Completion Rate for Rural Upper-Middle Income Families
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of children from upper-middle income rural families (fourth richest group) successfully finish elementary school. Higher percentages are better, showing more children are mastering basic skills like reading and math. Even relatively wealthy rural families can face challenges with school access, so tracking this helps ensure all children get essential early education.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate (Rural Rich Students)
nodes.description: Shows the percentage of students from the wealthiest families (top 20% income) living in rural areas who complete lower secondary school (grades 7-9). Higher percentages are better, indicating that even wealthy rural students can access quality education. This reveals whether rural location limits educational success regardless of family income.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate - Wealthy Rural Students (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of students from the wealthiest families in rural areas actually finish high school. The value is a percentage, and higher numbers are better because they show more students completing their education. This matters because it reveals whether even wealthy rural students face barriers to education that urban students don't experience.

nodes.label: Middle School Graduation Rate - Rural, Upper-Middle Income Families (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of rural students from upper-middle income families (4th wealth quintile) successfully complete middle school. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better since more students are finishing their education. Completing middle school gives students the foundation needed for high school and prevents them from entering the workforce too early.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate in Cities
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of children in urban areas who successfully complete primary school (typically grades 1-6). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes. When more children finish primary school, they build the foundation skills needed for further education and better-paying jobs as adults.

nodes.label: Middle School Graduation Rate - Urban Areas (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of urban students successfully complete middle school (grades 7-9). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better since more students are finishing this crucial education level. Completing middle school gives students the skills and knowledge needed to succeed in high school and avoid dropping out of the education system.

nodes.label: High School Graduation Rate - Urban Areas (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of urban students successfully complete high school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better since more students are earning their diploma. High school graduates have access to better jobs, higher wages, and opportunities for college or technical training.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate for Urban Girls
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of girls living in cities who successfully finish high school (grades 9-12). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better since they show more urban girls are completing their secondary education. Girls who finish high school have much better chances of getting good jobs, continuing to college, and supporting their families.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate - Urban Girls
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of urban girls who successfully finish primary school (typically ages 6-11). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better, indicating more girls are completing their basic education. When girls complete primary school, they're more likely to develop essential literacy and math skills that improve their future job opportunities and quality of life.

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Completion Rate - Urban Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys living in cities complete grades 7-9 (lower secondary school). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better, showing more boys finish these critical middle school years. High completion rates indicate urban boys are successfully transitioning from childhood to adolescence with proper educational foundation.

nodes.label: Percentage of Urban Boys Finishing High School
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of urban boys successfully complete all of high school (grades 9-12). Higher percentages are better, showing more boys are getting the full secondary education needed for college or skilled jobs. Boys who complete high school have much better chances of finding stable employment and supporting themselves and their families.

nodes.label: Girls' Lower Secondary Completion Rate in Cities
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls in urban areas successfully finish lower secondary school (typically grades 7-9, ages 12-14). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. This matters because completing lower secondary education gives girls better job opportunities and helps break cycles of poverty.

nodes.label: Boys Finishing Elementary School - Cities (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys in urban areas who successfully complete all years of elementary school (typically grades 1-6, ages 6-11). Higher percentages are better, showing more boys are getting a complete basic education. This is important because finishing elementary school gives boys the foundation they need for higher education and better jobs.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate for Middle-Income Urban Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from middle-income urban families successfully finish lower secondary school (typically grades 7-9). Values range from 0-100%, with higher values being better. This matters because completing middle school is essential for girls to continue their education and access better career opportunities.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Rate for Lower-Middle-Income Urban Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from the second-poorest income group in urban areas successfully finish lower secondary school (grades 7-9). Values range from 0-100%, with higher values being better. This matters because completing middle school opens doors to further education and better job prospects for girls from low-income families.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate for Lower-Middle-Income Urban Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from the second-poorest income group in urban areas successfully finish upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0-100%, with higher values being better. This matters because high school completion is crucial for girls to access higher education and skilled employment opportunities.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion - Urban Middle-Income Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of middle-income girls living in cities complete primary school (grades 1-6). Higher percentages indicate more urban middle-class girls are finishing elementary education. This helps track whether girls from different economic backgrounds have equal opportunities to complete their basic education.

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Completion Rate - Urban Middle-Income Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys from middle-income families in cities complete grades 7-9 (lower secondary school). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better, showing more boys finish this important education level. High completion rates indicate that urban boys from average-income families can successfully navigate middle school.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion - Urban Lower-Income Boys
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys from the second-poorest 20% of urban families who complete lower secondary education (middle school). Higher percentages are better, showing successful completion of this critical education level. Completing middle school opens doors to high school and better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Upper Secondary Completion Rate for Middle-Class Urban Boys
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of urban boys from middle-income families (3rd quintile) who complete upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes. This matters because upper secondary completion is often required for good jobs and college admission, affecting young men's economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Upper Secondary Completion - Low-Income Urban Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys from poor families (second-lowest income group) in urban areas successfully complete upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher is better. Boys from low-income families often struggle to finish high school due to financial pressures, but completing upper secondary education greatly improves their chances of finding stable, well-paying jobs.

nodes.label: Upper Secondary Completion Rate: Upper-Middle Income Urban Girls
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from upper-middle income families living in cities successfully finish upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher is better. This matters because upper secondary completion greatly improves girls' chances of getting good jobs or continuing to college.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Among Lower-Income Urban Boys
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys from lower-middle income urban families (second poorest 20%) who complete primary school (typically grades 1-6). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. This shows whether boys from modest-income city families are getting basic education, which is essential for breaking cycles of poverty and building stronger communities.

nodes.label: Upper-Middle Income Boys Finishing High School - Cities (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys from upper-middle income families in cities who complete grades 10-12 (ages 15-17). Higher percentages are better, showing more boys in this income group are getting a complete high school education. This matters because high school completion opens doors to college and career opportunities.

nodes.label: Elementary Completion Rate - Urban Girls from Lower-Income Families
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of girls from lower-income families (second-poorest income group) living in cities successfully complete elementary school. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better. Tracking completion rates for disadvantaged groups helps identify where additional support is needed to ensure all children finish their basic education.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion - Urban Middle-Class Boys
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of boys from middle-income urban families who successfully finish primary school. Higher percentages mean more boys complete their basic education. Primary school completion gives boys the foundation they need for further education and better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate - Urban Poor Boys
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys from the poorest families in cities successfully complete primary school (typically grades 1-6, ages 6-11). Higher percentages are better, showing more boys finishing their basic education. This matters because completing primary school gives children fundamental reading and math skills needed for future success.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion Rate - Urban Poor
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of children from the poorest 20% of families in cities successfully complete primary school (grades 1-6, typically ages 6-11). Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all poor urban children finish primary school. This shows whether the most disadvantaged urban children are getting basic education, which is essential for breaking the cycle of poverty.

nodes.label: Lower Secondary Completion - Urban Middle-Income Students
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of middle-income students living in cities complete lower secondary school (grades 7-9). Higher percentages mean more urban middle-class students are finishing this education level. Tracking completion by income and location helps identify whether different groups of students have equal access to educational opportunities.

nodes.label: Primary School Completion - Urban Poorest Students
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of the poorest students living in cities complete primary school (grades 1-6). Higher percentages indicate more low-income urban children are finishing elementary education. This is crucial because completing primary school provides the foundation all children need for future learning and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Elementary Graduation Rate (Urban Middle-Income Students)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of elementary students from middle-income families (3rd quintile) living in urban areas complete elementary school. Higher percentages indicate better educational outcomes for this specific group. This helps track whether middle-class urban families are successfully supporting their children's basic education.

nodes.label: High School Completion Rate for Urban Lower-Middle Income Students
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of urban students from lower-middle income families (second poorest group) successfully finish high school. Higher percentages are better, showing these economically disadvantaged students are overcoming barriers to complete their education. Finishing high school is essential for breaking out of poverty and accessing better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Upper Secondary Completion Rate: Middle Income Urban Students
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of students from middle-income families in urban areas successfully finish upper secondary school (grades 10-12). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. This matters because completing upper secondary school opens doors to better employment and higher education opportunities.

nodes.label: Elementary School Completion Rate - Urban Lower-Middle Income Families
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of children from lower-middle income families living in cities successfully complete elementary school. Higher percentages are better, showing more children are finishing their basic education. This matters because children from lower-income families often face barriers to completing school, yet education is key to breaking cycles of poverty.

nodes.label: Poorest Students Finishing Middle School - Cities (%)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of children from the poorest families in urban areas who complete grades 7-9 (ages 12-14). Higher percentages are better, showing more poor children are finishing middle school despite economic challenges. This matters because completing middle school helps break the cycle of poverty by giving children better future opportunities.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate - Urban Poorest Families
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of young people from the poorest 20% of urban families who are enrolled in tertiary education (college or university). Higher percentages are better, showing that even poor urban youth can access higher education. College education dramatically improves earning potential and life opportunities.

nodes.label: College Enrollment Rate for Urban Lower-Middle Income Families (High School Level)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of urban students from lower-middle income families (second poorest group) are enrolled in college-level programs while still in high school age. Higher rates are better, showing these students are getting advanced education despite economic challenges. This matters because it helps break the cycle of poverty by giving disadvantaged students access to higher education.

nodes.label: Middle School Completion Wealth Equality Index (Rural)
nodes.description: This compares middle school completion rates between rich and poor students in rural areas, where 1.0 means perfect equality and lower values mean bigger gaps between wealthy and poor families. Values closer to 1.0 are better as they show all children have equal chances regardless of family income. Reducing wealth-based education gaps helps break cycles of poverty.

nodes.label: Wealth Gap in Rural High School Completion
nodes.description: This measures whether rich and poor students in rural areas complete high school at similar rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality between wealth groups, while lower values indicate that poor students are much less likely to finish high school than wealthy students. Reducing wealth-based education gaps helps break cycles of poverty and creates more equal opportunities.

nodes.label: Rural vs. Urban Elementary Graduation Gap
nodes.description: This compares elementary school completion rates between rural and urban areas, showing if there's an equality gap. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality; below 1.0 means rural students graduate at lower rates. Reducing this gap ensures all children have equal educational opportunities regardless of where they live.

nodes.label: Wealth Gap in Urban Middle School Completion
nodes.description: This measures whether rich and poor students in cities complete lower secondary school (typically grades 7-9) at similar rates. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality between wealth groups, while lower values indicate poor students are much less likely to finish middle school than wealthy students. Reducing this gap ensures all urban children can build skills needed for high school and future careers.

nodes.label: Wealth Gap in Urban Upper Secondary Completion
nodes.description: This measures how equally rich and poor students in cities complete upper secondary school (grades 10-12), shown as a ratio. A value of 1.0 means students from all income levels complete at equal rates, while lower values indicate poorer students complete less often. Equal completion across income levels ensures economic background doesn't determine educational opportunities.

nodes.label: Elementary Completion Equality Between Rich and Poor in Cities
nodes.description: This compares elementary school completion rates between the poorest and richest families in urban areas. A value of 1.0 means equal completion rates, while lower values indicate bigger gaps between rich and poor families. Reducing wealth-based education gaps in cities helps ensure all children have equal opportunities regardless of their family's economic situation.

nodes.label: Length of high school education (years)
nodes.description: This counts how many years students spend in secondary school (like middle school and high school combined) in a country's education system. More years typically means more comprehensive education, though the quality of those years also matters. Adequate secondary education duration helps ensure students gain the skills needed for jobs and higher education.

nodes.label: Students in general high school programs
nodes.description: This counts how many students are enrolled in regular high school programs that prepare them for college, not including technical or vocational training. Higher numbers indicate more students getting general secondary education. This matters because high school education provides essential skills for higher-paying jobs and further education opportunities.

nodes.label: Total Students in High School
nodes.description: This measures the total number of students enrolled in secondary school (roughly grades 9-12 or ages 12-18) in both public and private schools. Higher numbers indicate more young people are getting education beyond elementary school, though this depends on a country's population size. Access to secondary education is crucial for developing job skills and reducing poverty.

nodes.label: Education: Pluralistic Content
nodes.description: Measures whether schools teach multiple perspectives on controversial topics rather than just one official viewpoint. Higher scores indicate more diverse viewpoints are presented in education. This matters because exposure to different ideas helps students develop critical thinking skills and make informed decisions.

nodes.label: Math Education Policy Approach
nodes.description: Identifies the most common approach to mathematics education policy in the country, such as standardized curricula, local control, or mixed systems. This is a categorical measure showing the dominant policy model. This matters because education policies affect how well students learn essential skills needed for economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Years of Free Public Education (Primary through Lower Secondary)
nodes.description: This measures how many years of free public education a country provides, covering elementary school through 9th grade (roughly ages 6-14). The number represents total years, typically ranging from 6-12 years, where higher numbers mean more free education is guaranteed by law. More years of free education helps ensure all children can attend school regardless of their family's income.

nodes.label: Research Scientists per Person
nodes.description: This measures how many full-time research scientists and engineers work per 1,000 people in the population. Higher numbers indicate more researchers working on scientific discoveries and innovations. This matters because research drives technological progress, medical advances, and economic development that improve people's lives.

nodes.label: Centralized Control of School Textbooks
nodes.description: Measures how much the national government controls what textbooks are used in schools across the country. Higher values indicate more centralized government control over educational content, while lower values suggest local schools or regions have more freedom to choose their own textbooks. This matters because it affects whether students learn diverse perspectives or mainly government-approved viewpoints.

nodes.label: Government Control of School Curriculum
nodes.description: This measures how much central government controls what is taught in schools versus allowing local control or academic freedom. Higher values typically indicate more centralized curriculum control. The right balance of oversight ensures quality education while allowing teachers to meet local community needs.

nodes.label: Education: Centralized Textbook Control
nodes.description: This measures how much the national government controls what textbooks schools can use. Higher values indicate the central government has more authority to decide which textbooks are approved or required in classrooms across the country. More centralized control can limit local input into education but may ensure consistent standards nationwide.

nodes.label: Central Government Curriculum Control (Original Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how much the central government controls what is taught in schools versus allowing local communities or schools to decide curriculum. Values on the original survey scale show the degree of centralized control. The right balance ensures quality education standards while allowing local flexibility to meet community needs.

nodes.label: Critical Thinking in Education (Expert Ratings)
nodes.description: Measures how much the education system encourages students to think critically and question ideas, using experts' original survey responses. Higher values indicate schools better teach students to analyze information, form independent opinions, and challenge assumptions. Critical thinking education helps citizens make informed decisions and resist propaganda or misinformation.

nodes.label: Educational Pluralism - Expert Rating
nodes.description: This measures how much educational systems present multiple viewpoints rather than just government-approved perspectives, using the original rating scale that V-Dem experts used. Higher values indicate more diverse, pluralistic education. Pluralistic education is important because it helps students develop critical thinking skills and understand different perspectives on important issues.

nodes.label: Centralized Curriculum Control Data Availability
nodes.description: This tracks how much data is missing when experts try to assess government control over school curricula and educational content. Higher scores mean more missing data about educational centralization. Good data coverage helps evaluate whether educational systems allow diverse learning approaches that serve student needs.

nodes.label: Education: Political Rights Content
nodes.description: This measures whether educational systems teach students about their political rights and democratic participation. Higher scores indicate that schools more effectively educate students about voting, civic participation, and their rights as citizens. This matters because civic education helps create informed citizens who can participate effectively in democracy.

nodes.label: Political Education in Primary Schools (Average)
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of political education taught in elementary schools across different regions or time periods. Higher scores indicate more teaching about government, voting, and civic duties. Early political education helps prepare young citizens to participate effectively in democracy as adults.

nodes.label: Education: School Patriotism Curriculum (Ranked Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how much schools are required to teach patriotic content or promote national loyalty, using a ranked ordering system. Higher values indicate schools must include more patriotic themes, national symbols, or pro-government messages in their curriculum. More required patriotism can limit critical thinking but may strengthen national unity.

nodes.label: Education: School Patriotism Curriculum
nodes.description: This measures how much schools are required to teach patriotic content or promote loyalty to the country and government. Higher values indicate schools must include more patriotic themes, national symbols, or pro-government messages in their lessons. Required patriotism can strengthen national identity but may limit students' exposure to diverse viewpoints.

nodes.label: Education: Teacher Autonomy (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures how much freedom teachers have to decide what and how to teach in their classrooms, using experts' original ratings. Higher values indicate teachers have more independence to choose teaching methods, adapt curriculum, or express different viewpoints. Greater teacher autonomy can improve education quality by letting teachers respond to their students' specific needs.

nodes.label: Ideological Control of Education
nodes.description: This measures how much the government controls what political ideas are taught in schools and universities. Higher values indicate more government control over educational content and less academic freedom. This matters because educational freedom helps students develop critical thinking skills and learn diverse perspectives.

nodes.label: Teacher Professional Autonomy
nodes.description: Measures how much freedom teachers have to make decisions about curriculum, teaching methods, and classroom management without government interference. Higher scores indicate greater teacher autonomy. This matters because professional freedom helps teachers provide better, more creative education tailored to their students' needs.

nodes.label: Education System Promotes Multiple Viewpoints
nodes.description: Measures whether a country's education system encourages students to learn about different political and social perspectives rather than promoting only one official viewpoint. Higher values (on a 0-4 scale) indicate that schools teach multiple perspectives and critical thinking. This matters because exposure to diverse ideas in education helps create more informed citizens and stronger democracies.

nodes.label: Patriotic Education in Schools (Ranked Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how much schools emphasize love of country and national pride in their curriculum, rated on a ranked scale. Higher scores indicate more patriotic content is required in education. The level of patriotic education affects how students learn about their country's history and their role as citizens.

nodes.label: Executive Theft from Public Sector
nodes.description: This measures how much government executives steal money or resources from public institutions for personal gain. Higher values indicate more theft and corruption by top government officials. Low levels of executive theft help ensure public resources go toward services that benefit all citizens.

nodes.label: Executive Financial Conflicts of Interest (Ordinal Scale)
nodes.description: This measures whether the chief executive (president or prime minister) has financial conflicts of interest that could influence their government decisions. The ordinal scale typically runs 0-4, where higher values indicate fewer conflicts of interest. Lower conflicts matter because they mean leaders make decisions based on public benefit rather than personal financial gain.

nodes.label: Executive Compliance with High Court - Ordered Scale
nodes.description: This measures how often the executive branch follows high court decisions that go against government interests, converted to an ordered scale where higher values mean better compliance. When executives ignore court rulings, it undermines the rule of law. Judicial independence is essential because courts need to be able to check government power and protect citizens' rights.

nodes.label: Teacher Union Rights
nodes.description: Measures how freely teachers can form and participate in labor unions to advocate for better working conditions and education policies. Higher values indicate stronger union rights. Teacher unions help improve education quality by advocating for resources and policies that benefit students and schools.

nodes.label: Educational Equality (Ordered Scale)
nodes.description: This measures whether all social groups have equal access to quality education, ranked on an ordered scale from lowest to highest equality. Higher scores indicate that education opportunities are more equally distributed across different social, economic, and ethnic groups. Equal access to education helps ensure everyone can develop their potential regardless of background.

nodes.label: Education: Teacher Union Influence (Most Common)
nodes.description: This shows the most commonly reported level of influence that teacher unions have over education policy in a country. Higher values indicate stronger teacher union influence on educational decisions. This matters because teacher unions can advocate for better school conditions and teaching quality, which directly affects the education children receive.

nodes.label: Teacher Union Strength
nodes.description: This measures how strong and influential teacher unions are in a country's education system. Higher values indicate that teachers have more collective bargaining power and influence over education policy. Strong teacher unions can help improve working conditions and education quality, but may also make education reforms more difficult to implement.

nodes.label: Teacher Union Strength (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures how strong and influential teacher unions are, using the original expert survey responses before statistical processing. Higher values indicate that teachers have more collective bargaining power and influence over education policy. Strong teacher unions can advocate for better schools and teaching conditions, which can improve education quality for students.

nodes.label: Teacher Union Independence Data Quality
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when experts are asked about teacher union independence from government control. Higher values mean more experts couldn't or didn't answer questions about this topic. Good data coverage helps researchers and policymakers understand education systems that support quality schooling.

nodes.label: Teacher Union Strength
nodes.description: Measures the average strength and influence of teacher unions in advocating for education policies and teacher rights. Higher scores indicate stronger, more influential teacher unions. This matters because strong teacher representation can lead to better working conditions and education policies that benefit both teachers and students.

nodes.label: Education Data: Teacher Union Information Availability
nodes.description: This measures how much information experts had available to answer questions about teacher unions in education systems - it shows data quality, not the unions themselves. Higher values mean experts had less information to work with. This matters because reliable data helps researchers and policymakers understand education systems better.

nodes.label: Equal Access to Higher Education (Average Score)
nodes.description: Measures whether all social groups have equal opportunities to attend universities and colleges, regardless of their background, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values (0-4 scale) indicate more equal access to higher education. This matters because education access affects people's career opportunities and lifetime earnings, impacting social mobility and economic development.

nodes.label: Education: Equal Access to Quality Education
nodes.description: This measures whether all social groups have equal access to high-quality education regardless of their background, income, or social status. Higher values indicate more equal educational opportunities. This is crucial because equal access to education gives everyone a fair chance at success and strengthens society overall.

nodes.label: Educational Equality (Original Expert Scale)
nodes.description: This measures whether all social groups have equal access to quality education, using the original scale that experts used in their assessments. Higher scores indicate that education opportunities are more equally distributed across different social, economic, and ethnic groups. Equal access to education helps ensure everyone can develop their potential regardless of background.

nodes.label: Female Students Studying Abroad - Tertiary
nodes.description: This counts how many female students are studying at colleges or universities in foreign countries for the first time. Higher numbers indicate more women are accessing international higher education opportunities. International education helps women gain valuable skills and experiences that can improve their career prospects.

nodes.label: Women Leaving Country for College for First Time
nodes.description: This counts how many women are going to another country for college-level education for the first time. While this can indicate students seeking better opportunities, very high numbers might suggest the home country's universities aren't meeting students' needs. International education can bring valuable skills back to the home country, but brain drain is a concern if students don't return.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in International College Students
nodes.description: This measures how equally male and female college students study abroad in other countries. A value of 1.0 means equal numbers of men and women study internationally, while higher values mean more women than men study abroad. Equal international education opportunities matter because studying abroad can lead to better career prospects and global understanding.

nodes.label: Women Studying Abroad for First Time
nodes.description: This counts female students leaving their home country for the first time to pursue college or university education abroad. Higher numbers indicate more women have opportunities for international education experiences. Studying abroad is valuable because it provides women with global perspectives, language skills, and networks that enhance career prospects.

nodes.label: New Student Survey Response Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many first-year college students respond to education surveys compared to how many were asked to participate. Higher percentages mean better data collection, which helps education officials understand student needs and improve programs. Reliable survey data is essential for making good decisions about education policies and funding.

nodes.label: First-Year Student Response Rate
nodes.description: Measures how well new college students respond to or engage with their higher education programs during their first year. Higher response rates typically indicate better student support systems and engagement. Strong freshman engagement is crucial because it predicts whether students will stay in college and graduate.

nodes.label: New Student Response Rate Data
nodes.description: This measures how well countries respond to UNESCO's data requests about new students entering the education system. Higher values indicate better data reporting, which helps track educational progress. Reliable education data is essential for governments and organizations to make informed decisions about improving schools and helping more children succeed.

nodes.label: College Freshman Survey Response Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many college freshmen respond to UNESCO education surveys out of those contacted. Higher percentages (closer to 100%) mean better data collection and more reliable education statistics. Good response rates help governments and organizations make informed decisions about improving education systems.

nodes.label: Government Response Rate on Education Data
nodes.description: This measures how often governments respond to UNESCO's requests for education data and statistics. Higher response rates mean better data availability for tracking education progress. This matters because accurate data helps identify education problems and guide improvements to school systems.

nodes.label: Full-Time Teachers in Middle School Vocational Programs
nodes.description: This measures the number or percentage of teachers working full-time in vocational and technical programs at the middle school level. Higher numbers indicate more dedicated teaching staff for hands-on training programs. More full-time vocational teachers means students get better preparation for technical careers and practical job skills.

nodes.label: Full-Time High School Teachers
nodes.description: This counts the number of teachers working full-time in upper secondary schools (grades 10-12). Higher numbers generally indicate better educational resources and smaller class sizes. Having enough full-time teachers means students get more attention and consistent instruction, leading to better learning outcomes and graduation rates.

nodes.label: Qualified Full-Time Teachers in Grades 7-9
nodes.description: This measures how many full-time teachers working in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9) have the proper training and qualifications to teach. Higher numbers indicate more qualified teachers in classrooms, which is better for student learning. Having well-trained teachers is essential for ensuring students receive quality education during these formative middle school years.

nodes.label: Qualified Full-Time Teachers - Upper Secondary
nodes.description: This measures how many full-time teachers in upper secondary schools (grades 10-12) have the proper qualifications and training to teach. Higher percentages are better because qualified teachers provide higher quality education. Students learn more effectively from qualified teachers, which better prepares them for college or careers after graduation.

nodes.label: Full-Time High School Teachers
nodes.description: This counts the number of teachers working full-time in high schools (grades 10-12) who have proper training. Higher numbers mean more qualified teachers are available to teach older students. Well-trained full-time teachers provide better instruction and help students prepare for college or careers.

nodes.label: Full-Time Qualified Primary Teachers
nodes.description: This measures the number of full-time teachers in primary schools (grades 1-6) who have proper training and qualifications to teach. Higher numbers indicate more qualified teachers are available to educate young children. Having more qualified full-time teachers means students get better instruction and more consistent learning experiences.

nodes.label: Number of Full-Time Elementary School Teachers
nodes.description: This counts how many teachers work full-time in elementary schools (grades 1-6). Higher numbers are generally better, especially relative to the number of students, because it means more dedicated teaching attention. Having enough full-time teachers is crucial for giving young children the foundation skills they need for all future learning.

nodes.label: Full-Time Teachers with Bachelor's Degrees
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of full-time teachers who have completed at least a bachelor's degree. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate better-qualified teaching staff. Well-educated teachers are crucial because they provide higher-quality instruction and better prepare students for future success.

nodes.label: Female Teacher Support in Pre-Primary Education
nodes.description: This measures the level of support and outreach provided to female teachers working in pre-primary education (ages 3-5). Higher values indicate better support systems for female educators. Strong teacher support improves education quality and helps ensure young children get the foundation they need for future learning success.

nodes.label: Teacher Training Programs for Female Post-Secondary Educators
nodes.description: This measures outreach efforts to train female teachers for post-secondary education (college/university level). Higher values indicate more programs to prepare women as college instructors. This matters because having qualified female educators provides role models and helps ensure quality higher education for all students.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach Programs - Elementary Female Teachers
nodes.description: Measures efforts to recruit, train, or support female teachers for primary education (grades 1-6, typically ages 6-11). Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher support programs. Having qualified female teachers in elementary school is important because they often serve as role models and can help both girls and boys develop strong learning foundations.

nodes.label: Female Teachers Doing Community Outreach (Middle School)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of female middle school teachers who participate in community outreach programs to help students outside of regular classroom hours. Higher percentages indicate more teachers are going beyond basic teaching duties to support student success. This extra support can significantly improve learning outcomes for struggling students.

nodes.label: Female Teacher Training in Post-Secondary Education
nodes.description: This measures programs to train female teachers for post-secondary education (after high school). Higher values indicate more women being prepared to teach at advanced levels. This matters because having qualified female teachers provides role models and helps ensure equal educational opportunities for all students.

nodes.label: Female Primary Teachers Outreach Rate
nodes.description: Measures the availability and reach of female teachers in primary schools (grades K-6, ages 6-11). Higher values indicate better access to female teaching staff. Having female teachers is important because they serve as role models and may better support girls' educational participation and achievement.

nodes.label: Female Teacher Training in Secondary Education
nodes.description: This measures efforts to train and support female teachers working in secondary schools (grades 7-12). Higher values typically indicate more professional development opportunities for women teachers. This matters because well-trained female teachers serve as important role models and help create supportive learning environments for all students, especially girls.

nodes.label: Female Teacher Outreach Programs in Elementary Schools
nodes.description: Measures efforts to recruit, support, or retain female teachers in elementary schools (grades 1-6). Higher values indicate more programs or activities aimed at encouraging women to become elementary teachers. Having more female teachers matters because it provides diverse role models and can improve educational outcomes, especially for girls.

nodes.label: Female Teacher Outreach in Middle Schools
nodes.description: This measures efforts to recruit, support, or provide outreach for female teachers in middle schools through special programs. Higher values indicate more comprehensive support for female educators. Having female teachers provides important role models for girls and helps create more balanced and inclusive learning environments.

nodes.label: Female Teachers in High School Education Programs
nodes.description: This counts how many female teachers work in high school-level programs that train future educators. Higher numbers mean more women are involved in preparing the next generation of teachers. Female teacher trainers provide important role models and perspectives for students entering the teaching profession.

nodes.label: Male Teacher Support in Primary Education
nodes.description: This measures the level of support and professional development provided to male teachers working in primary schools. Higher values indicate better support systems for male educators. Well-supported teachers provide better instruction and serve as positive role models, especially important for young boys who may lack male mentors.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach Programs - Middle School Male Teachers
nodes.description: Measures efforts to recruit, train, or support male teachers for lower secondary education (grades 7-9, typically ages 12-14). Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher support programs. Having qualified male role models in middle school helps all students, especially boys, stay engaged during this critical transition period.

nodes.label: Men's Access to Teacher Training Programs
nodes.description: This measures the rate at which men participate in teacher training programs across all education levels. Higher rates indicate more men are preparing to become teachers, which helps provide diverse role models for students. Having male teachers is especially important for encouraging boys' educational engagement and providing balanced perspectives in schools.

nodes.label: Male Teacher Coverage in Public High Schools
nodes.description: This measures how well public high schools are staffed with male teachers, often looking at teacher-to-student ratios or coverage across different subjects. Better coverage usually means lower ratios and more adequate staffing. This matters because adequate teacher coverage ensures students get proper attention and instruction, and male teachers provide important role models especially for male students.

nodes.label: Male Teacher Outreach Programs - Secondary Schools
nodes.description: This measures efforts to recruit and support male teachers in secondary schools (grades 7-12) through special programs. Higher numbers indicate more active recruitment efforts. Having male teachers matters because it provides diverse role models for students and can help address teacher shortages in certain subjects or regions.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach Programs for Elementary Boys
nodes.description: This measures how well teacher outreach programs serve boys in elementary school (typically grades 1-6). Higher values indicate better coverage and support for male students who may need extra help staying engaged in school. Effective outreach is important because early intervention helps prevent boys from falling behind or dropping out later.

nodes.label: Male Teachers in Higher Education Programs
nodes.description: This counts how many male teachers are working in college and university-level education programs that train future educators. Higher numbers indicate more men are involved in preparing the next generation of teachers. Having diverse teachers helps ensure students from all backgrounds see role models in education.

nodes.label: Teacher Training and Support Programs
nodes.description: This measures efforts to provide training, professional development, and outreach to teachers at all education levels. Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher support programs. This matters because well-trained teachers provide better education quality, which directly impacts student learning and success.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach in Early Education
nodes.description: This measures efforts to train or support teachers working in early childhood education programs. Higher values typically indicate more teacher training and support activities. This matters because well-trained early childhood teachers help young children develop crucial learning foundations that affect their entire educational journey.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach in Pre-Primary Education
nodes.description: This measures how well teachers reach and serve students in pre-primary education (ages 3-5). Higher values indicate better teacher coverage and support for young children. Good teacher outreach in early childhood is crucial because it helps ensure all young children get the educational foundation they need for later school success.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach in Upper Secondary Public Schools
nodes.description: This measures how well teachers reach and serve students in public high schools (grades 10-12). Higher values indicate better teacher coverage and support for older students. Good teacher outreach in high school is important because it helps ensure students get the guidance and instruction they need to graduate and prepare for college or careers.

nodes.label: Teacher Training Programs - Lower Secondary
nodes.description: This measures the availability and extent of teacher training and professional development programs for lower secondary school teachers (grades 7-9). Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher training programs. Well-trained teachers provide better education quality, helping students learn more effectively and prepare for their futures.

nodes.label: Teacher Training Programs - Lower Secondary
nodes.description: This measures the availability and extent of teacher training and professional development programs for lower secondary school teachers (grades 7-9). Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher training programs. Well-trained teachers provide better education quality, helping students learn more effectively and prepare for their futures.

nodes.label: Teacher Support Programs in Lower Secondary Schools
nodes.description: This measures the extent of programs designed to help teachers reach and support students in lower secondary education (typically grades 7-9). Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher outreach efforts, which can include training, mentoring, or community engagement programs. Strong teacher support leads to better instruction and improved learning outcomes for students.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach Programs for Grades 7-9
nodes.description: This measures how well teacher outreach programs serve students in grades 7-9 (typically ages 12-14). Higher values indicate better coverage and effectiveness of programs that help teachers reach and support students in lower secondary education. Strong teacher outreach programs are important because they help ensure students get the support they need to stay in school and succeed academically.

nodes.label: Primary Teacher Outreach Coverage
nodes.description: Measures how well primary schools (grades K-6) are staffed with teachers and whether those teachers can reach all students who need education. Higher values indicate better teacher coverage and access. Good teacher outreach ensures all children can access quality primary education regardless of location or background.

nodes.label: Primary School Teacher Training and Support
nodes.description: This measures efforts to train and support teachers working in primary schools (grades 1-6). Higher values typically indicate more teacher development programs and resources. This matters because well-trained primary school teachers help children master fundamental reading, writing, and math skills that form the foundation for all future learning.

nodes.label: College and University Teacher Training Programs
nodes.description: This measures efforts to train and support teachers and professors working in colleges and universities. Higher values typically indicate more professional development and training programs for higher education faculty. This matters because well-trained college instructors provide better education quality, helping students develop advanced skills needed for professional careers.

nodes.label: Teacher Support Programs in Primary Schools
nodes.description: This measures the extent of programs designed to help teachers reach and support students in primary education (typically grades 1-6, ages 6-11). Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher outreach efforts, including training, resources, and community connections. Strong teacher support improves the quality of instruction and helps ensure all children get a solid foundation in basic skills.

nodes.label: Teacher Outreach Programs - Elementary School
nodes.description: This measures the extent of programs that help elementary school teachers reach and support students outside traditional classroom settings. Higher values indicate more comprehensive teacher outreach efforts. This matters because teachers who can connect with students beyond the classroom help improve learning outcomes and keep more children engaged in school.

nodes.label: Primary School Support Programs (Water/Sanitation)
nodes.description: This measures the availability of school-based support programs that provide basic services like clean water and sanitation facilities in primary schools. Higher values indicate better school infrastructure and support services. Schools with proper facilities help students stay healthy, attend regularly, and focus on learning rather than basic needs.

nodes.label: School Meal Programs - Primary School
nodes.description: This measures whether primary schools (grades 1-6) provide meal programs or other nutrition support to students. Schools with these programs help ensure students get proper nutrition, which is essential for learning and concentration. School meals are especially important for helping low-income families and improving student attendance and academic performance.

nodes.label: School Toilet Facilities - Primary School
nodes.description: This measures whether primary schools (grades 1-6) have proper bathroom and sanitation facilities for students. Schools with adequate toilets provide a healthier learning environment and help keep students, especially girls, attending school regularly. Proper sanitation facilities are essential for student health, dignity, and consistent school attendance.

nodes.label: Out-of-School Education Programs for Urban Girls - Middle School Age
nodes.description: This measures how many urban girls of middle school age (12-14) are enrolled in alternative education programs because they're not in regular school. Higher numbers indicate more girls are getting second-chance education opportunities, which is positive for those who missed traditional schooling. These programs help girls catch up on their education and develop skills needed for better jobs and life opportunities.

nodes.label: Out-of-School Middle School Students in Catch-Up Programs
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of middle school-age children who aren't in regular school are enrolled in special education programs designed to help them catch up. Higher percentages mean more out-of-school kids are getting a second chance at education. This matters because it helps prevent young people from being left behind permanently.

nodes.label: Urban Adults in Lower Secondary Catch-Up Programs
nodes.description: This counts adults in urban areas who are enrolled in programs to complete lower secondary education (grades 7-9) that they missed earlier in life. Higher numbers indicate more people getting second chances at education, which is generally positive. This matters because adult education programs help people gain skills needed for better jobs and can reduce urban poverty and inequality.

nodes.label: Adults in Lower Secondary Catch-Up Programs
nodes.description: This counts all adults enrolled in programs to complete lower secondary education (grades 7-9) that they missed earlier in life. Higher numbers indicate more people getting second chances at education, which is generally positive. Adult education programs are important because they help people gain basic skills needed for employment and civic participation.

nodes.label: Alternative Education Programs for Girls (Grades 7-9)
nodes.description: This measures how many girls who should be in grades 7-9 but aren't in regular school are enrolled in alternative education programs instead. Higher values mean more out-of-school girls are getting second-chance education opportunities. This matters because it helps girls who missed regular schooling still gain important skills and qualifications.

nodes.label: School Support Programs in Lower Secondary
nodes.description: This measures the availability of programs that help students succeed in lower secondary school, such as tutoring, counseling, or meal programs. Higher values indicate more comprehensive support systems. These programs help students stay in school and succeed academically, especially those facing challenges like poverty or learning difficulties.

nodes.label: Upper Secondary School Water Access Programs
nodes.description: This measures whether high schools (grades 10-12) have programs to provide clean water access for students. Higher values mean more schools have water support programs. Access to clean water at school is important because it keeps students healthy, helps them attend school regularly, and creates a better learning environment.

nodes.label: Upper Secondary School Sanitation Programs
nodes.description: This measures whether high schools (grades 10-12) have programs to provide proper bathrooms and hygiene facilities for students. Higher values mean more schools have sanitation support programs. Good sanitation at school is important because it promotes student health, dignity, and regular attendance, especially for female students.

nodes.label: High School Student Support Programs
nodes.description: This measures the availability of school-based support programs (like tutoring, counseling, or financial aid) for high school students. Higher values indicate more comprehensive support systems are available to help students succeed. These programs help students overcome challenges that might otherwise cause them to drop out before graduating.

nodes.label: School Support Programs - Middle School
nodes.description: This measures the availability of extra support services (like tutoring, counseling, or meal programs) in middle schools (grades 7-9). Higher values indicate more comprehensive support systems are available to help students succeed. This matters because students with additional support are more likely to stay in school and perform better academically.

nodes.label: School Support Programs - Middle School
nodes.description: This measures the availability of special support programs in middle schools to help students succeed academically. Higher values indicate more support services available to students. This matters because extra help and resources improve student learning and reduce dropout rates.

nodes.label: Boys in Urban Areas Taking Catch-Up Programs for Middle School
