nodes.description: This measures how many urban boys are enrolled in special education programs designed to help them complete middle school grades (ages 12-14) when they are older than the typical age. Higher numbers indicate more boys need extra help to catch up, which could mean the regular school system isn't working well for them. These programs are important because they give students a second chance to get the education they need for better jobs and life opportunities.

nodes.label: Alternative Education Programs for Out-of-School Boys (Middle School Age)
nodes.description: Tracks participation of boys in alternative education programs designed for those who missed regular lower secondary school (ages 12-14). Higher participation indicates better second-chance educational opportunities. These programs help boys who dropped out get back on track for completing their education.

nodes.label: Female Teacher Training Rate - Lower Secondary
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of female teachers in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9) have received proper training to teach. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. Well-trained female teachers provide better education and serve as important role models for students, especially girls.

nodes.label: Teacher Training Completion - Secondary Male Teachers
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of male teachers in secondary education (grades 7-12) have completed proper teacher training programs. Higher percentages are better, with 100% meaning all male secondary teachers are properly trained. Well-trained teachers provide better education quality, helping students learn more effectively and stay in school.

nodes.label: Female Teacher Training in Lower Secondary Schools
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of female teachers in grades 7-9 who have received proper training to teach. Higher percentages mean more female teachers are well-prepared for their jobs. Well-trained female teachers are important because they serve as role models for girls and help create supportive learning environments for all students.

nodes.label: Middle School Teacher Training Programs (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of middle school teachers receive ongoing professional training to improve their teaching skills. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better since trained teachers are more effective. When teachers receive regular training, they learn new methods and stay current with their subjects, leading to better student learning outcomes.

nodes.label: Qualified Female Pre-Primary Teachers
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of female teachers in pre-primary programs (ages 3-5) have proper training and qualifications. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. Well-qualified early childhood teachers help young children develop important learning and social skills that prepare them for elementary school.

nodes.label: Qualified Female Teachers - Upper Secondary (%)
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of female teachers in upper secondary schools (grades 10-12) who have proper training and qualifications to teach. Higher percentages mean more female teachers are well-prepared to provide quality education. Having qualified female teachers is important for providing good role models and ensuring effective teaching for all students.

nodes.label: Percentage of Female Primary Teachers Who Are Qualified
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of female teachers in primary schools have the proper training and credentials required by the country's education system. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better. Well-trained female teachers serve as role models and provide quality instruction that helps all students, especially girls, succeed in school.

nodes.label: Qualified Female Middle School Teachers (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women teaching in middle schools (grades 7-9) have the proper training and qualifications for their job. Higher percentages mean students are learning from better-prepared teachers. Well-qualified teachers are important because they can provide higher-quality education that helps students succeed academically.

nodes.label: Qualified Male Teachers in Middle School
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of male teachers in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9) have the proper training and credentials to teach. Higher percentages are better because qualified teachers provide better instruction and help students learn more effectively. Well-trained teachers, regardless of gender, create better learning environments that help students succeed academically.

nodes.label: Qualified Male Teachers in Middle Schools
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of male teachers in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9) who meet official training requirements. Higher percentages are better, meaning students learn from properly trained teachers. Well-qualified teachers are essential for students to gain the knowledge and skills they need for success.

nodes.label: Qualified Male High School Teachers (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of male teachers in high schools have the proper training, certification, or qualifications to teach. The value is a percentage, and higher numbers are better because qualified teachers provide higher quality education. This matters because students learn more effectively from teachers who are properly trained in their subjects and teaching methods.

nodes.label: Qualified Male Elementary Teachers (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of male elementary school teachers have proper training and credentials. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better since qualified teachers provide more effective instruction. Having qualified male teachers gives young students positive male role models and ensures all teachers can effectively teach reading, math, and other fundamental subjects.

nodes.label: Qualified Teachers - Lower Secondary (%)
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of teachers in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9) who have proper training and qualifications to teach. Higher percentages mean more teachers are well-prepared to provide quality education to students. Having qualified teachers is essential for helping students learn effectively and prepare for their future education and careers.

nodes.label: Percentage of Qualified High School Teachers
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of high school teachers have the proper training, education, or certification required to teach their subjects. Higher percentages are better, indicating more teachers meet professional standards. Having qualified teachers matters because students learn more effectively from teachers who have proper training in both their subject area and teaching methods.

nodes.label: Qualified Middle School Teachers (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of middle school teachers (grades 7-9) have the proper training and credentials to teach effectively. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better since qualified teachers provide better instruction. Students learn more and perform better when taught by teachers who have proper training in their subjects and teaching methods.

nodes.label: Percentage of Qualified Elementary School Teachers
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of elementary school teachers have the proper training and credentials required by their country's education standards. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better. Having qualified teachers in elementary grades is crucial because these early years build the foundation for all future learning and development.

nodes.label: Gender Balance Among Qualified Middle School Teachers
nodes.description: This measures whether male and female teachers in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9) are equally likely to have proper training and qualifications. A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, with deviations indicating gender imbalances in teacher qualifications. This matters because having qualified teachers of both genders ensures quality education and diverse role models for students.

nodes.label: Qualified Teachers Gender Balance (Lower Secondary)
nodes.description: Compares the percentage of qualified male versus female teachers in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9). A value of 1.0 means equal representation of qualified teachers by gender, while other values show imbalances. Having qualified teachers of both genders creates better learning environments and role models for all students.

nodes.label: Gender Gap in Qualified Elementary Teachers
nodes.description: Compares the percentage of qualified male versus female elementary school teachers. A value of 1.0 means equal percentages of male and female teachers are properly qualified; other values indicate gender differences in teacher qualifications. Having qualified teachers of both genders matters because it provides diverse role models and ensures all students receive quality instruction.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Post-Secondary Teacher Training
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women have equal access to teacher training programs beyond high school level. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality, while values below 1.0 indicate fewer women than men in these programs, and above 1.0 means more women. Gender balance in teacher training helps ensure diverse role models and teaching approaches for future students.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Primary Teacher Training
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women have equal access to primary school teacher training programs, with values around 1.0 indicating perfect gender balance. Values below 1.0 mean fewer women than men are being trained, while values above 1.0 mean more women than men. Balanced teacher training helps ensure diverse role models and teaching perspectives for all students.

nodes.label: Middle School Teacher Gender Balance Index
nodes.description: Compares the ratio of female to male teachers in lower secondary schools (grades 7-9, ages 12-14). A value of 1.0 means equal numbers of male and female teachers, while values above or below 1.0 show imbalances. Gender-balanced teaching staff provides better role models and learning environments for all students.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in High School Teaching Staff
nodes.description: This measures whether male and female teachers are equally represented in high school teaching positions. A value of 1.0 means equal numbers of male and female teachers, while other values show imbalances. Balanced teaching staff matters because students benefit from having diverse role models and perspectives from both male and female educators.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Primary School Teacher Access
nodes.description: This measures whether primary school boys and girls have equal access to trained teachers and teaching resources. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender equality in teacher access, while other values indicate disparities. Equal teacher access for both genders is crucial because it ensures all children get quality instruction, leading to better learning outcomes and reduced gender gaps in education.

nodes.label: Teacher Training Gender Balance - Pre-Primary
nodes.description: This measures whether male and female teachers receive equal access to training in pre-school education (ages 3-5). A value of 1.0 means perfect equality, while values above or below 1.0 show which gender gets more training opportunities. Balanced teacher training ensures both boys and girls have well-prepared teachers who can provide quality early childhood education.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Teacher Outreach (Grades 7-9)
nodes.description: This compares how equally male and female students benefit from teacher outreach programs in grades 7-9. A value of 1.0 means boys and girls receive equal support, below 1.0 means girls receive less support, and above 1.0 means girls receive more support. Equal access to teacher support helps ensure all students can succeed regardless of gender.

nodes.label: Gender Balance in Higher Education Teaching
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women are equally represented among teachers in college-level education programs. A value of 1.0 means perfect gender balance, while values above or below 1.0 show an imbalance. Gender-balanced teaching staff provides diverse perspectives and role models for future educators.

nodes.label: Government Spending Price Comparison Factor
nodes.description: This measures how much government spending costs in one country compared to others, adjusting for different price levels. It helps economists compare government budgets fairly across countries with different costs of living. This matters because it shows how efficiently governments can provide public services with their budgets.

nodes.label: Government Spending Comparison (UK Standard, Adjusted)
nodes.description: This compares government spending levels to UK standards while adjusting for differences in what money can buy in each country. Higher values mean that country's government spends more than the UK benchmark. This is important because it shows whether governments are investing enough in public services that citizens depend on for healthcare, education, and safety.

nodes.label: Government Spending Price Comparison (Construction)
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of government construction and infrastructure projects compared to other countries, adjusted for purchasing power. Lower values indicate government can build infrastructure more affordably. This matters because cost-effective government spending means more infrastructure projects can be completed with the same budget, benefiting more citizens.

nodes.label: Government Services Price Comparison
nodes.description: This compares the cost and availability of government services between countries, adjusting for what money can buy in each place. Higher values typically indicate government services cost more or are more extensive. This matters because it helps measure how much value citizens get from their government and taxes compared to other countries.

nodes.label: Government Construction Spending (Price-Adjusted)
nodes.description: This measures how much governments spend on construction projects like roads, schools, and hospitals, adjusted so amounts can be fairly compared across countries with different price levels. Higher spending means more investment in public infrastructure. This matters because government construction creates jobs and builds the facilities that support economic growth and quality of life.

nodes.label: Government Construction Spending Comparison
nodes.description: This measures how much governments spend on construction projects (like roads, bridges, and public buildings) compared to other countries, adjusted for price differences. Higher values indicate more government investment in infrastructure. This matters because good infrastructure supports economic growth and improves quality of life through better transportation, utilities, and public facilities.

nodes.label: Multi-Year Government Spending Comparison
nodes.description: This tracks government spending patterns over a 2-3 year period compared to US standards, showing whether public investment is increasing or decreasing. Higher values indicate sustained higher government spending on public services. This matters because consistent public investment helps build better schools, roads, and healthcare systems that benefit everyone.

nodes.label: Government Construction Cost Comparison
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of government construction projects across countries, helping compare what public infrastructure spending actually achieves in different places. Values show price differences between countries. This matters because it helps evaluate whether governments are getting good value for taxpayer money spent on roads, schools, and other public buildings.

nodes.label: Government Construction Spending Comparison
nodes.description: This compares how much governments spend on construction projects like roads, schools, and hospitals, adjusted to allow fair comparisons between countries. Higher values indicate more government investment in infrastructure. Strong public construction spending typically improves quality of life through better facilities and services for citizens.

nodes.label: Government Spending Comparison Index
nodes.description: This measures how much a country's government spends compared to other countries, adjusted for differences in local prices. Higher values mean the government spends more relative to other nations. This matters because government spending affects public services like healthcare, education, and infrastructure that impact citizens' daily lives.

nodes.label: Government Construction Price Comparison
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of government construction projects when comparing between countries, helping understand how expensive it is for governments to build infrastructure. Higher values mean construction costs more in that country. This matters because construction costs affect how much infrastructure like schools, hospitals, and roads a government can build with its budget.

nodes.label: Total Factor Productivity Level
nodes.description: This measures how efficiently a country uses its resources (labor, capital, technology) to produce goods and services, adjusted for purchasing power. Higher values indicate the country is better at turning inputs into outputs through innovation and good organization. Higher productivity typically leads to faster economic growth and rising living standards.

nodes.label: Capital Stock Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the value of productive assets (buildings, machines, infrastructure) available per person in the country, adjusted for purchasing power differences. Higher values mean each person has access to more tools and infrastructure to be productive. More capital per person usually leads to higher wages and better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Share of Labor Costs in GDP
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total economic output goes to paying workers' wages and salaries. Higher values mean workers receive a larger share of the economic pie relative to business profits and other income. This indicates how well economic growth translates into benefits for working people.

nodes.label: Price Level of Human Capital
nodes.description: This measures how expensive skilled labor is in a country compared to other countries, reflecting the relative cost of educated workers. Higher values indicate that skilled workers command higher wages relative to the global average. This affects a country's competitiveness in industries that require educated workers.

nodes.label: Government Services Price Comparison Component
nodes.description: This measures how expensive government services are in one country compared to other countries, adjusting for currency differences. Higher values mean government services cost more relative to other countries. This is important because it helps compare the true cost and efficiency of government services across different nations.

nodes.label: Government Services Price Comparison Component
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of government services when comparing purchasing power between countries. Higher values indicate government services are more expensive in that country. Efficient government spending helps ensure citizens get good value from their tax dollars.

nodes.label: Government Spending Purchasing Power
nodes.description: This measures how much government spending can actually buy in a country after adjusting for local prices. Higher values mean government budgets can purchase more goods and services. This matters because it shows how far public money goes in providing services like healthcare and education to citizens.

nodes.label: UK Government Services Price Comparison
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of government services in the UK compared to other countries for purchasing power calculations. Higher values mean UK government services cost more relative to other countries. This matters because it affects how we compare living standards and government efficiency across different nations.

nodes.label: Government Services Price Comparison Component
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of government services in a country compared to other countries, adjusted for purchasing power. Lower values indicate government services cost less relative to local income levels. This matters because affordable government services mean citizens can access essential public services without financial hardship.

nodes.label: Income per Person (US$)
nodes.description: This measures the average annual income earned per person in a country, including money earned from investments abroad, expressed in current US dollars. Higher values indicate people have more money available for spending and saving on average. This is a key measure of living standards and economic well-being.

nodes.label: Price Comparison Factor for Consumer Goods
nodes.description: This shows how much local currency equals one international dollar when buying consumer goods, helping compare living costs across countries. Lower numbers mean goods are cheaper relative to international prices, while higher numbers mean goods cost more. This matters because it helps determine how far people's income actually goes in buying everyday necessities like food, clothing, and household items.

nodes.label: Total Domestic Spending Power
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money a country's residents spend on goods and services within their borders, adjusted for what money can actually buy in that country. Higher values mean people and businesses are spending more money domestically, which usually indicates a stronger economy. This matters because higher domestic spending typically means people have more money to meet their needs and improve their living standards.

nodes.label: Real Consumption Spending
nodes.description: This measures how much money people in a country spend on goods and services, adjusted for different price levels between countries so amounts can be fairly compared. Higher values mean people are spending more money, which usually indicates better living standards and economic well-being. This matters because higher consumption typically means people can afford more of what they need and want for a good quality of life.

nodes.label: Infrastructure Wear and Replacement Costs
nodes.description: This measures how much of a country's total income goes toward replacing worn-out infrastructure like roads, buildings, and equipment. Higher percentages indicate more resources are needed just to maintain existing infrastructure, leaving less money available for new investments and improvements.

nodes.label: Total energy consumption
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of energy used by all sectors of a country's economy - homes, businesses, factories, and transportation. Higher values mean more energy use, which can indicate economic activity but also environmental impact. This matters because energy access enables modern life, but excessive consumption can strain resources and harm the environment.

nodes.label: Household spending on goods and services
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money that households and nonprofit organizations spend on goods and services in a year, measured in current US dollars. Higher values indicate people are spending more money on things like food, housing, healthcare, and entertainment. Higher household spending usually reflects better living standards and economic well-being.

nodes.label: Government spending as share of economy (%)
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on day-to-day operations like paying employees, buying supplies, and providing services, compared to the country's total economic output. Higher percentages indicate larger government involvement in the economy, which can provide more public services but may also mean higher taxes.

nodes.label: Household Spending as Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total economic output comes from families and individuals buying goods and services. Higher percentages indicate that consumer spending drives more of the economy. Strong household consumption typically reflects good employment and income levels that support living standards.

nodes.label: Government Spending on Individual Services
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on services that directly benefit individual citizens, such as healthcare, education, and housing assistance. Higher spending typically means more public services available to residents. This matters because government investment in individual services can improve quality of life, reduce inequality, and provide essential support for citizens' basic needs.

nodes.label: Average Household Spending
nodes.description: This measures how much money the typical household spends in a year on goods and services like food, housing, and transportation. Values are in currency amounts, where higher numbers mean households spend more. This indicates living standards and shows whether families have money left over after covering basic needs.

nodes.label: Average Household Spending on Personal Goods
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average household (family or people living together) spends on personal items for all household members, including food, clothing, and entertainment. Higher values indicate households can afford to buy more things for their family members. This matters because it shows whether families have enough money to provide for everyone's basic needs and some comforts.

nodes.label: Average Household Spending
nodes.description: This measures how much money the typical household spends on goods and services like food, housing, clothing, and entertainment in a year. Values are in local currency, and higher amounts generally indicate households have more money to spend on their needs and wants. This is important because household spending drives economic growth and reflects living standards.

nodes.label: Average Household Consumption (National Currency)
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average household spends on goods and services like food, housing, and transportation, shown in the country's local currency. Higher values mean families can afford to buy more, indicating better living standards. This matters because household consumption reflects families' ability to meet their needs and wants, showing overall economic well-being.

nodes.label: Average Household Consumption (Fixed Currency)
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average household spends on goods and services, adjusted for inflation or shown in a standard currency for comparison across time and countries. Higher values mean families can afford more goods and services. This matters because it shows real improvements in living standards and families' ability to meet their needs over time.

nodes.label: Disposable Income Comparison (1992 Prices)
nodes.description: This compares disposable income levels over time using constant 1992 prices to remove the effects of inflation, focusing on adults only. Higher values mean people have more real purchasing power after taxes and benefits. This matters because it shows whether people's actual spending power is improving or declining over time, affecting their ability to afford goods and services.

nodes.label: Disposable Income Comparison
nodes.description: This compares how much money people have left to spend after paying taxes and receiving government benefits, measured as a ratio or percentage. Higher values typically indicate people have more spending money available. This matters because disposable income directly affects living standards and people's ability to buy goods and services beyond basic necessities.

nodes.label: Government and Household Net Income
nodes.description: This measures the combined income of both government and households after accounting for taxes, transfers, and other financial flows between them. Higher values indicate more total income available in the economy. This matters because it shows the overall financial resources available for both public services and private consumption that affect quality of life.

nodes.label: Combined Government and Household Income from Production
nodes.description: This measures the total income that both government and households earn from producing goods and services in the economy. Higher values indicate the country is generating more income from productive economic activities. This matters because productive income creates the foundation for improving living standards and funding public services.

nodes.label: Average Social Security Contribution Rate
nodes.description: This measures the average percentage of income that workers and employers pay into social security systems for benefits like pensions and unemployment insurance. Higher percentages mean larger contributions to social programs. This matters because these contributions fund safety nets that protect people during retirement, job loss, or disability.

nodes.label: Average Social Security Benefits
nodes.description: This measures the average amount people receive from government social security programs like pensions, unemployment benefits, and disability payments. Higher values indicate more generous social safety nets that provide better financial support. This matters because strong social security helps protect people from poverty during unemployment, illness, or old age.

nodes.label: Total Capital Stock Value
nodes.description: This measures the total value of all productive assets in a country, including buildings, machinery, equipment, and infrastructure, adjusted for purchasing power. Higher values indicate a country has more physical assets available for producing goods and services. More capital stock typically leads to higher productivity and better living standards for citizens.

nodes.label: Total Tax Burden (Market-Based Index)
nodes.description: This measures the total percentage of income that goes to all types of taxes combined, adjusted for purchasing power differences between countries. Values are expressed as an index where higher numbers mean heavier overall tax burdens. Moderate tax levels can fund good public services while still leaving people enough money for their personal needs.

nodes.label: Private Investment per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money individuals invest in private assets like stocks, bonds, or business ownership on average. Values are typically shown in dollars or local currency, where higher amounts indicate more individual wealth being invested in the economy. Higher private investment suggests people have extra money to invest and confidence in economic growth, which can lead to job creation and improved living standards.

nodes.label: Investment Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total economic output goes toward investment in things like new factories, equipment, and infrastructure rather than immediate consumption. Higher percentages typically lead to faster economic growth over time. Countries that invest more today usually have better living standards in the future.

nodes.label: Government Assets as Share of National Wealth
nodes.description: This measures what portion of a country's total wealth is owned by the government in the form of buildings, infrastructure, land, and other public assets. Values are shown as percentages, where higher values mean the government owns a larger share of national wealth. This matters because it shows how much public infrastructure and services a country has invested in for its citizens.

nodes.label: Individual Social Capital Income
nodes.description: This measures income that individuals receive from community connections and social networks, like support from family or community organizations. Values are in currency amounts, where higher numbers mean people benefit more financially from their social relationships. This shows how social connections can provide economic security and opportunities.

nodes.label: Individual Investment and Property Income
nodes.description: This measures how much money individuals earn from investments like stocks, bonds, rental properties, or business ownership. Values are typically in local currency, with higher amounts indicating more investment income. This shows wealth concentration and how much people benefit from owning assets rather than just working.

nodes.label: Property Income Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures what portion of a country's total income comes from owning property, investments, and other assets rather than from working. Values are shown as percentages, where higher values mean more national income comes from ownership rather than wages. This matters because it shows how much economic inequality exists between property owners and workers.

nodes.label: Current Property Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what portion of national income currently comes from owning property, stocks, bonds, and other assets rather than from wages and salaries. Values are percentages, where higher values mean more income flows to asset owners versus workers. This matters because it indicates the level of economic inequality between those who own wealth-generating assets and those who depend on paychecks.

nodes.label: National Investment Level (Global Comparison)
nodes.description: This compares how much a country invests in productive assets like factories and infrastructure relative to other countries, with the US set as the reference point of 1.0. Higher values mean more investment relative to the US level. This is important because countries with higher investment typically have stronger economic growth and better job opportunities.

nodes.label: Total Value of Country's Infrastructure and Equipment
nodes.description: This measures the total value of all physical assets like buildings, roads, factories, and equipment in a country, adjusted for price differences between countries. Higher values indicate more infrastructure and productive capacity. More capital stock typically means better economic opportunities and higher living standards for residents.

nodes.label: Economic Productivity Compared to US
nodes.description: This measures how efficiently a country produces goods and services compared to the United States (set at 1.0). Higher values mean the country is more productive per worker or unit of input. Higher productivity typically leads to higher wages and better living standards for workers.

nodes.label: Business Investment in Equipment and Infrastructure
nodes.description: This measures how much companies and organizations invest in machinery, buildings, technology, and other productive assets using local prices. Higher values mean more business investment in tools and infrastructure that boost productivity. This is important because business investment creates jobs and helps the economy grow, leading to higher wages and living standards.

nodes.label: Average Property Value Gains Per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person gains when the value of their property (like houses, land, or stocks) increases due to market changes. Higher values mean people are building more wealth through their investments and property ownership. These gains help people become more financially secure and can spend or invest more in the future.

nodes.label: Average Individual Property Value Gains
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person gains when the value of their property or investments increases over time, such as when house prices or stock values go up. Higher values mean people's assets are growing in value more quickly. This is important because property gains can significantly increase wealth and provide financial security over time.

nodes.label: Property Investment Gains per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average amount individuals earn when their property investments like stocks, bonds, or real estate increase in value over time. Values are in local currency per year, and higher amounts mean people are making more money from their investments. This matters because investment gains can significantly boost people's wealth and financial security beyond their regular job income.

nodes.label: Market Segment Classification (Individual)
nodes.description: This indicator categorizes individuals into different economic market segments based on their income level or economic characteristics. The classification helps identify which income group a person belongs to (like low, middle, or high income). Higher segment numbers typically indicate higher income levels. This matters because it shows how people are distributed across different economic classes in society.

nodes.label: Average Property Value Gains
nodes.description: This measures how much the average person's property (like houses, land, or other real estate) has increased in market value over time. Higher values mean people's property is becoming more valuable, which increases their wealth. This matters because property value gains can significantly improve people's financial security and overall wealth.

nodes.label: Average Housing Property Gains
nodes.description: This measures how much the average person's housing property has increased in market value over time. Higher values mean people's homes are becoming more valuable, boosting their wealth. This is important because housing often represents the largest asset for most families, affecting their financial security and ability to build wealth.

nodes.label: Individual Market Income Category
nodes.description: This identifies which income group or market segment an individual person belongs to based on their earnings. Different values represent different income brackets or economic classes. Understanding income distribution helps policymakers address inequality and target programs to help different economic groups.

nodes.label: Corporate Tax Revenue as Share of GDP
nodes.description: This measures how much money a government collects from business taxes compared to the country's total economic output. Higher percentages mean businesses contribute more to government revenue through taxes. Corporate tax revenue matters because it funds public services like schools, roads, and hospitals that benefit everyone.

nodes.label: Social Security Contributions as Share of GDP
nodes.description: This measures how much money flows into social security and pension systems compared to the country's total economic output. Higher percentages mean more resources are dedicated to supporting elderly and disabled citizens. Strong social contributions matter because they provide financial security when people can no longer work due to age or disability.

nodes.label: Government Tax Revenue from Business Income
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government collects in taxes from business profits, property income, and other non-wage sources. Higher values mean the government has more revenue to spend on public services like schools and hospitals. This is important because it shows the government's ability to fund programs that improve people's lives.

nodes.label: Market Income Before Taxes
nodes.description: This measures the total income people earn from market activities like jobs and investments before any taxes are taken out. Higher values indicate stronger earning potential from economic activity before government redistribution. This matters because it shows the underlying economic opportunities available to people and how much wealth the economy generates before taxation.

nodes.label: Property and Financial Income (Net)
nodes.description: This measures income people earn from owning property and financial assets like stocks, bonds, and rental properties, after subtracting related costs. Higher values mean people earn more money from their investments and property ownership. This matters because investment income often separates the wealthy from others and affects overall income inequality.

nodes.label: Government Spending per Girl in Lower Secondary School
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends per female student in lower secondary education (typically grades 7-9), adjusted for local purchasing power. Higher spending usually indicates better resources, facilities, and teaching quality available to girls. Adequate funding is crucial for providing girls with quality education that can break cycles of poverty and inequality.

nodes.label: Cost per Female Elementary Student
nodes.description: This measures how much money is spent per girl enrolled in elementary school, adjusted for local purchasing power. Higher values indicate greater investment in girls' education. Adequate spending on girls' education is important because it ensures they have the resources, materials, and support needed to learn effectively.

nodes.label: Household Cost Per College-Age Woman
nodes.description: This measures how much families spend on each woman's higher education (college/university), adjusted for purchasing power differences between countries. Higher costs can create barriers to women's higher education, especially for poorer families. Understanding these costs helps identify whether financial barriers are preventing women from accessing advanced education and career opportunities.

nodes.label: Government Spending Per Female Student - Upper Secondary
nodes.description: This measures how much government money is spent per female student in upper secondary school (grades 10-12), adjusted for cost of living. Higher values indicate greater public investment in girls' education at the high school level. Adequate government funding helps ensure all students can access quality education regardless of their family's economic situation.

nodes.label: Government Cost Per Primary School Girl
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government spends on each girl's primary education, adjusted for purchasing power differences between countries. Higher amounts can indicate better-funded education systems, though efficiency matters too. Understanding these costs helps governments plan education budgets and ensure girls receive adequate educational investment.

nodes.label: Cost Per Female Student - Lower Secondary (Grades 7-9)
nodes.description: This measures how much money is spent per female student in lower secondary school (grades 7-9), adjusted for cost of living differences between countries. Higher values mean more money is being invested per female student, which typically indicates better resources like teachers, books, and facilities. Adequate funding per student is crucial for providing quality education that helps students succeed.

nodes.label: Cost Per Girl Student - Pre-Primary School
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government spends on each girl enrolled in pre-school (ages 3-5), adjusted for local purchasing power. Higher spending can indicate greater investment in early childhood education for girls. Adequate funding for pre-primary education helps ensure girls get a strong start that prepares them for success in later schooling.

nodes.label: Elementary School Entry Rate (Age-Appropriate)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of children enter elementary school at the right age (typically age 6). Values closer to 100% are better, showing most kids start school on time. When children start school at the proper age, they're more likely to succeed academically and complete their education.

nodes.label: Boys Starting Primary School on Time (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys enter primary school (around age 6) at the right age, adjusted for those who may have repeated grades or started late. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages are better, indicating more boys are starting their education on schedule. When boys start school on time, they're more likely to complete their education and develop skills needed for better jobs.

nodes.label: Gross National Income
nodes.description: This measures the total income earned by all residents of a country in one year, including money earned by citizens working abroad but excluding income earned by foreigners working in the country. Higher values indicate a wealthier nation overall. GNI shows how much income a country's people actually earn, which directly relates to their potential standard of living and ability to afford goods and services.

nodes.label: Total National Income
nodes.description: This measures the total income earned by all residents of a country in one year, including money earned from other countries, converted to US dollars using a special method that smooths out exchange rate fluctuations. Higher values indicate a wealthier country overall. Higher national income typically means better living standards and more resources for public services.

nodes.label: Total national income in local currency
nodes.description: This measures the total income earned by all residents of a country in one year, including money earned from other countries, expressed in the country's own currency. Higher values indicate a wealthier economy with more total income available to its people. Countries with higher national income typically offer better opportunities for jobs, education, and public services.

nodes.label: Agricultural Income Distribution
nodes.description: This tracks how income from farming and agricultural activities is distributed among different groups in the population. Values show the percentage or share of total agricultural income earned by specific income groups. This is important because agricultural income distribution affects rural poverty levels and food security in developing countries.

nodes.label: Import Share of GDP
nodes.description: This measures how much a country spends on imported goods and services as a percentage of its total economic output. Higher values indicate greater reliance on foreign products and more integration with the global economy. This affects domestic industries and shows how connected a country is to international trade networks.

nodes.label: Private lending as share of economy
nodes.description: This measures how much money banks and financial institutions lend to private businesses and individuals, expressed as a percentage of the country's total economic output. Higher percentages generally indicate a more developed financial system that helps people and businesses access credit. Better access to loans helps people start businesses and buy homes.

nodes.label: Bank Lending to Private Businesses
nodes.description: This measures how much money banks lend to private companies and individuals as a percentage of the country's total economic output. Higher percentages mean banks are lending more money relative to the economy's size, which can help businesses grow and people buy homes. More lending usually supports economic growth and job creation.

nodes.label: Bank Lending to Private Businesses (Percentage of Economy)
nodes.description: This measures how much money banks and financial institutions lend to private companies and individuals compared to the size of the country's total economy. Higher percentages indicate a more developed banking system that helps people start businesses and buy homes. This matters because access to credit allows people to invest in education, businesses, and homes, driving economic growth and opportunity.

nodes.label: Total Domestic Credit in Local Currency
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money that banks and financial institutions have lent to the government and private borrowers within the country, in local currency. Higher values can indicate more available credit for businesses and individuals, but may also suggest higher debt levels. This matters because credit availability affects people's ability to start businesses, buy homes, and invest in their futures.

nodes.label: Bank Lending to Businesses and Individuals
nodes.description: This measures how much money banks and other financial institutions lend to private businesses and individuals as a percentage of the country's total economic output. Higher percentages indicate businesses and people can more easily get loans to start companies or buy homes. Access to credit helps economies grow and gives people opportunities to improve their lives.

nodes.label: Financial Regulation Period
nodes.description: Measures the time period or duration of financial regulatory frameworks in a country. Higher values may indicate longer-lasting or more established financial oversight systems. Stable financial regulation helps protect people's savings, prevents economic crises, and maintains trust in the banking system.

nodes.label: Stock Market Price-to-Dividend Ratio
nodes.description: This measures how much investors pay for stocks relative to the dividends those stocks pay out, indicating whether the stock market might be overvalued or undervalued. Higher ratios suggest stocks are more expensive relative to their dividend payments. This matters because it reflects the health and stability of a country's financial markets.

nodes.label: Foreign Trade Integration
nodes.description: This measures how much a country's economy depends on international trade by looking at imports and exports as a share of total economic activity. Higher values indicate the country is more connected to global markets. This is important because trade integration can boost economic growth but also makes countries more vulnerable to global economic shocks.

nodes.label: Foreign Trade Integration
nodes.description: This measures how much a country's economy is connected to international trade through imports and exports as a share of total economic activity. Higher values indicate greater integration with global markets. Trade integration can boost economic growth and provide access to more goods and services, but it also makes countries more vulnerable to global economic problems.

nodes.label: Government Size in Economy
nodes.description: This measures how large the government sector is relative to the overall economy, typically through government spending as a percentage of GDP. Higher values indicate larger government involvement in the economy through spending on services, welfare, and public programs. The right size of government affects how many public services are available and how much economic freedom individuals and businesses have.

nodes.label: Financial Regulation Quality
nodes.description: This measures how well a country regulates its banking and financial sector, including oversight of banks, stock markets, and other financial institutions. Higher scores indicate stronger regulatory frameworks that better protect consumers and maintain financial stability. Good financial regulation prevents economic crises and ensures people can safely save and invest their money.

nodes.label: Executive: Removal by Legislature
nodes.description: This measures how easily a country's legislature (like Congress) can remove the chief executive (like a president or prime minister) from office through legal means. Higher scores mean the legislature has stronger powers to check executive authority. This matters because it prevents leaders from becoming too powerful and ensures accountability to elected representatives.

nodes.label: Head of Government Removal Procedures
nodes.description: This measures how easily the head of government (like a prime minister) can be removed from office through legal procedures. Higher values typically indicate stronger democratic checks on executive power. Clear removal procedures help prevent leaders from becoming too powerful or staying in office against the public's will.

nodes.label: Executive Foreign Policy Control Time Horizon
nodes.description: This measures the time frame over which the chief executive can make binding foreign policy decisions without legislative approval. Higher scores indicate the executive has longer-term authority to conduct international relations independently. This affects how quickly and consistently a country can respond to international crises and maintain diplomatic relationships.

nodes.label: Executive Corruption in Public Sector
nodes.description: This measures how much government executives engage in corrupt practices in the public sector, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values indicate more executive corruption and misuse of public office. Low corruption helps ensure government resources are used effectively for public services rather than personal gain.

nodes.label: Executive Protection of Political Parties
nodes.description: This measures how well the executive branch protects the rights and activities of different political parties to operate freely. Higher scores indicate the executive better safeguards opposition parties from harassment or restrictions. Strong protection of all parties is important for fair elections and giving citizens real political choices.

nodes.label: Executive Protection of Democratic Institutions
nodes.description: This measures how well the executive branch protects and upholds democratic institutions and processes, using original expert survey responses. Higher scores indicate the executive better defends democratic norms and institutions from threats. Strong executive commitment to democracy helps maintain fair elections, rule of law, and citizen rights.

nodes.label: Head of State Control (Category 0)
nodes.description: Measures whether the head of state (like a president or monarch) has a specific level of control over government, with this being the lowest control category. Lower categories typically mean less personal control by the head of state. Balanced executive power helps ensure that no single person can make decisions that affect everyone's lives without proper checks.

nodes.label: Executive Branch Behavior (Expert Ratings)
nodes.description: Captures expert evaluations of specific executive branch behaviors or characteristics, using their original survey responses. The scale and interpretation depend on the specific behavior being measured, but this represents the raw expert judgment before statistical adjustments. Understanding executive behavior helps assess whether government leaders act in citizens' best interests.

nodes.label: Executive Respect for Constitutional Limits (Ranked Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how well presidents or prime ministers follow constitutional rules and limits on their power, rated on a ranked scale. Higher scores indicate executives respect legal boundaries and don't exceed their authority. Leaders who follow constitutional limits help maintain democratic checks and balances that protect citizens' rights.

nodes.label: Legislative Questioning of Executives
nodes.description: This measures how much the legislature questions and scrutinizes executive branch officials, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values indicate more legislative oversight of the executive branch. Strong legislative questioning helps ensure government leaders are held accountable for their decisions and actions.

nodes.label: Government Administration Quality Type
nodes.description: This measures what type or style of government administration a country has, looking at how well organized and professional the government bureaucracy is. Different values represent different administrative approaches or quality levels. This matters because better-run governments provide more reliable public services and create better conditions for economic growth.

nodes.label: Government Tax Collection Ability
nodes.description: This measures how effectively a government can collect taxes and generate revenue from its citizens and businesses. Higher scores indicate stronger fiscal capacity, meaning the government is better at gathering the money it needs to function. This matters because governments with good tax collection can better fund essential services like healthcare, education, and infrastructure that improve people's daily lives.

nodes.label: Judicial Accountability (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This is the original expert assessment of how accountable judges and courts are for their decisions and conduct, before statistical processing. Values typically range from 0-4, where higher scores indicate more accountable judiciaries. Accountable judges help ensure fair treatment under the law and reduce corruption in the justice system.

nodes.label: Government Control of Print Media (Ranked)
nodes.description: Measures how much the government controls newspapers and print publications, using a ranked scale. Higher values typically indicate more government control over print media content and ownership. When governments heavily control media, citizens may not get accurate information needed to make informed decisions about their lives and leaders.

nodes.label: State Fiscal Capacity (Ranked Scale)
nodes.description: Measures the government's ability to collect taxes and manage public finances effectively, presented on an ordered ranking scale. Higher values indicate stronger capacity to fund public services through taxation and efficient budget management. Good fiscal capacity allows governments to provide essential services like healthcare, education, and infrastructure that improve citizens' lives.

nodes.label: Aid Money Received from the United Kingdom
nodes.description: This measures how much development aid money (in US dollars) a country receives from the United Kingdom each year. Higher values mean more financial assistance for development projects like schools, hospitals, or infrastructure. This matters because aid can help poorer countries improve living conditions and economic opportunities for their citizens.

nodes.label: Aid Money from France
nodes.description: This measures how much development aid money France gives to other countries each year, reported in US dollars. Higher values mean France is providing more financial assistance for development projects like building schools, hospitals, or improving agriculture. This aid helps poorer countries improve living conditions and economic opportunities for their people.

nodes.label: Aid received from Canada
nodes.description: This measures how much development aid money a country receives specifically from Canada each year, in current US dollars. Higher amounts mean more Canadian financial support for development projects. This matters because this aid can fund important programs like healthcare, education, and infrastructure that improve people's daily lives.

nodes.label: Foreign aid received (millions US$)
nodes.description: This measures how much development aid money a country receives from wealthy donor nations, after subtracting any loan repayments. Higher amounts mean more international support for reducing poverty and building infrastructure. Foreign aid can help developing countries improve education, healthcare, and economic opportunities for their citizens.

nodes.label: Development Aid Received from United States
nodes.description: This measures the net amount of development assistance money a country receives from the United States each year, including grants and low-interest loans minus loan repayments. Higher values indicate more U.S. support for economic development, which can improve infrastructure, healthcare, and education.

nodes.label: Aid received from Germany
nodes.description: This measures how much development aid money a country receives from Germany each year in US dollars. Higher amounts mean more German financial support for development projects like schools, hospitals, or infrastructure. This aid can significantly improve living standards and economic opportunities in recipient countries.

nodes.label: Development Aid from Japan
nodes.description: This measures the net amount of development assistance money that Japan gives to other countries, calculated as new aid minus loan repayments from previous years. Higher positive values mean Japan is providing more financial support for development projects. Foreign aid helps recipient countries build infrastructure, improve healthcare and education, and reduce poverty.

nodes.label: Foreign aid received
nodes.description: This measures how much financial assistance a country receives from wealthy nations and international organizations to support development projects, shown in constant 2021 US dollars. Higher amounts mean more aid flowing in to fund schools, hospitals, infrastructure, and poverty reduction programs. This matters because foreign aid can help improve basic services and living conditions, especially in poorer countries.

nodes.label: Foreign aid received
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country receives in foreign aid - grants and low-interest loans from wealthy countries and international organizations to help with development. Higher amounts mean more external financial support. This matters because foreign aid can help fund schools, hospitals, infrastructure, and poverty reduction programs.

nodes.label: Foreign investment coming into the country
nodes.description: This measures how much money foreign companies and investors put into a country each year, shown in current US dollars. Higher positive values mean more foreign money is flowing in, while negative values mean more is leaving. This matters because foreign investment can create jobs, build infrastructure, and boost economic growth.

nodes.label: Foreign investment leaving the country (% of economy)
nodes.description: This shows how much money domestic companies invest in other countries, measured as a percentage of the country's total economic output. Higher percentages mean more domestic investment is going abroad rather than staying home. This can indicate either strong domestic companies expanding globally or money leaving due to poor local conditions.

nodes.label: Foreign Aid as Percentage of National Income
nodes.description: This measures how much foreign aid a country receives compared to its total national income, expressed as a percentage. Higher percentages indicate greater dependence on international assistance, which can help development but may also signal economic challenges. Foreign aid can support important services like healthcare and education, especially in developing countries.

nodes.label: Development Aid Received per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much development aid money a country receives per citizen each year in US dollars. Higher values mean more international assistance per person for development projects. This matters because aid can help fund essential services like education, healthcare, and infrastructure that improve living conditions, especially in lower-income countries.

nodes.label: Currency Exchange Rate with China (Purchasing Power)
nodes.description: This shows how much local currency equals one Chinese yuan, adjusted for what money can actually buy in each country. A higher number means the local currency is weaker compared to the yuan in terms of purchasing power. This matters because it affects how expensive Chinese goods are for local consumers and how competitive local exports are in Chinese markets.

nodes.label: Trade Balance as Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures whether a country exports more than it imports (trade surplus) or imports more than it exports (trade deficit), compared to its total national income. Positive values mean the country sells more abroad than it buys, while negative values mean it buys more than it sells. This matters because it shows whether a country is living within its means in global trade.

nodes.label: How expensive things are compared to the US
nodes.description: This compares how much everyday goods and services cost in a country versus the United States, where 1.0 means prices are equal. Values below 1.0 mean things cost less than in the US, while values above 1.0 mean things are more expensive. This matters because it shows how far people's money goes in purchasing basic necessities and affects living standards.

nodes.label: Inflation rate (% change per year)
nodes.description: This measures how much prices for everyday goods like food, housing, and transportation increased compared to the same time last year, adjusted for seasonal patterns. Higher values mean faster price increases, making things more expensive for consumers. Moderate inflation is normal, but high inflation reduces purchasing power and makes it harder for families to afford necessities.

nodes.label: Currency Exchange Rate
nodes.description: This shows how many units of a country's currency equal one US dollar in the foreign exchange market. For example, if the rate is 100, then 100 units of local currency equals $1 USD. Higher values mean the local currency is weaker, making imports more expensive but exports cheaper, which affects the cost of living for residents.

nodes.label: Consumer Price Level Comparison
nodes.description: This measures how expensive goods and services are for consumers in one country compared to international averages. Higher values mean things cost more in that country relative to others. When prices are too high, families have less money left over after buying basic necessities.

nodes.label: Economic Productivity Growth Rate
nodes.description: This measures how efficiently a country uses its workers, factories, and resources to produce goods and services, tracking whether the economy is getting better at creating value over time. Higher productivity growth means the country can produce more with the same inputs. This matters because productivity improvements drive long-term economic growth and rising living standards.

nodes.label: Cost of Living Comparison
nodes.description: This measures how expensive goods and services are in a country compared to what you could buy with the same money elsewhere. Higher values mean things cost more relative to other countries, while lower values mean you can buy more for your money. This helps explain why the same salary might provide a very different standard of living in different countries.

nodes.label: Cost of Living Index
nodes.description: This compares how expensive goods and services are in a country relative to international prices, focusing on what people actually buy and consume. Higher values mean things cost more compared to other countries. This matters because it affects how far people's incomes go in purchasing basic needs and maintaining their standard of living.

nodes.label: Sales Tax Burden Relative to Income
nodes.description: This measures how much a country collects in sales taxes, import duties, and similar taxes compared to the total income of all its people. Values are shown as a ratio, where higher numbers mean the government relies more heavily on these types of taxes. This matters because it shows how much of people's purchasing power goes to taxes on goods they buy.

nodes.label: Real Consumer Spending per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total amount people in a country spend on goods and services per person, adjusted for inflation and using national price levels. Higher values indicate people are consuming more goods and services. This matters because higher consumption typically reflects better living standards and economic well-being.

nodes.label: Real Domestic Spending Power
nodes.description: This measures how much goods and services a country's residents can actually buy with their money, adjusted for inflation and using local prices. Higher values mean people can afford more things and have better purchasing power. This matters because it shows whether people's standard of living is improving or declining over time.

nodes.label: Imports from other developing countries
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of a country's imported goods come from other developing nations outside their region. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean more trade with distant developing countries rather than nearby ones or wealthy nations. This indicates how globally connected a country's economy is to other developing markets.

nodes.label: Imports from South Asia Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imported goods comes from South Asian countries like India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages mean stronger trade ties with South Asia. This matters because diverse trading partnerships can provide more economic opportunities and help ensure stable access to needed goods and materials.

nodes.label: Imports from Europe & Central Asia developing countries (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imported goods come specifically from developing countries in Europe and Central Asia. Higher percentages indicate stronger trade relationships with that region. Diverse trade partnerships can provide countries with more product choices and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Share of imports from wealthy countries
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imported goods come from high-income countries like the US, Germany, or Japan. Higher percentages might indicate access to high-quality products but could also mean dependence on expensive imports. Countries that import more from wealthy nations may have access to advanced technology and quality goods, but may also face higher costs.

nodes.label: Regional trade dependence
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imports come from other developing countries in the same region. Higher percentages mean the country trades more with nearby developing nations rather than wealthy countries. This shows how connected a country is to its regional neighbors economically.

nodes.label: Imports from East Asia & Pacific Region
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total imported goods come from developing countries in East Asia and the Pacific region. Higher percentages indicate stronger trade ties with this region. This matters because import sources affect the variety and prices of goods available to consumers, as well as the country's economic relationships and supply chain security.

nodes.label: Total import spending
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of goods a country buys from other nations each year. Higher values mean more imports, which can indicate either strong purchasing power or dependence on foreign goods. Imports help provide goods and services that improve living standards but also require foreign currency to purchase.

nodes.label: Imports from Unspecified Partners (% of Total Imports)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of goods imported from countries or trading partners that aren't clearly identified in trade records. Lower percentages are generally better because they indicate more transparent and well-documented trade relationships. Clear trade records help governments make better economic policies and ensure proper collection of taxes and tariffs.

nodes.label: Total Goods Imported
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of all physical products (like cars, electronics, food, and raw materials) that a country buys from other countries. Higher values can indicate either a growing economy that needs more goods or potential trade imbalances. Importing goods helps countries access products they can't produce locally, improving living standards and business operations.

nodes.label: Total Value of Imported Goods
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of physical goods (like cars, computers, food, and clothing) that a country buys from other countries each year. Higher values can indicate either strong consumer demand or dependence on foreign products, which affects economic growth and trade relationships.

nodes.label: Household Spending Category 25003
nodes.description: This measures how much households in a country typically spend on a specific category of goods or services (the exact category would need to be identified from ICP documentation). The values show spending amounts, usually in international dollars for comparison across countries. Household spending patterns reveal living standards and what goods and services people can access.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 25007
nodes.description: This tracks how much households spend on a specific category of goods or services in international price comparison studies. Higher spending indicates greater consumption in this category. These spending patterns reveal what products and services are most important to families' quality of life.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 25005
nodes.description: This tracks household expenditure on a particular type of goods or services within the International Comparison Program framework. Values represent spending amounts in local currency, where higher numbers mean more money is being spent on this category. Understanding spending patterns helps measure economic well-being and quality of life across nations.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison - Category 25057
nodes.description: This measures how much money people in different countries spend on a specific category of goods or services, adjusted so prices can be compared fairly across countries. Higher values mean people spend more on this category. This helps show what people prioritize in their spending and how living costs compare between nations.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 25051
nodes.description: This measures spending on a specific category of goods or services as part of international price comparison studies. The exact category depends on the coding system, but it tracks how much households spend on particular items. This helps compare living costs between countries and understand how people allocate their money.

nodes.label: Price Comparison Category 25056
nodes.description: This represents spending or price data for a specific category of goods or services used in international comparisons, though the exact category is unclear. These comparisons help understand cost of living differences between countries. This matters because price levels affect how far people's income goes in purchasing necessities and improving their quality of life.

nodes.label: Spending Category 25055
nodes.description: This represents spending on a specific category of goods or services as part of international price comparisons between countries. The exact category depends on the classification system, but higher values mean more money is spent in this particular area. This matters because it helps compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 21500
nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 25053
nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Spending on Public Transportation
nodes.description: This measures how much money households and governments spend on public transportation services like buses, trains, and subways, adjusted for international price differences. Higher spending typically indicates better public transit systems and greater usage. Good public transportation reduces traffic, pollution, and transportation costs for families.

nodes.label: Household Equipment Spending
nodes.description: This tracks how much households spend on furniture, appliances, and other home equipment as part of total consumption. Higher values indicate families are spending more on household items. This matters because it reflects living standards and whether people can afford to improve their home environments.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison Category 41915
nodes.description: This represents spending data for a specific category of goods or services used to compare costs between countries. The values show relative price levels, where higher numbers mean this category costs more compared to other countries. This matters because it helps determine the real purchasing power and cost of living people experience in different places.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category (Transport Services)
nodes.description: This measures how much households spend on transportation services like public transit, taxis, and vehicle maintenance as part of international price comparisons. Higher values mean families spend more money on getting around. This matters because transportation costs affect how much money families have left for other needs.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 41906
nodes.description: This measures how much money households spend on a specific category of goods or services, used to compare living costs between countries. Higher values mean people spend more money on this particular category. This helps understand what people can afford and how they prioritize their spending across different countries.

nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.
