nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Spending on Restaurant and Hotel Services
nodes.description: This measures how much money people spend on restaurants, cafes, hotels, and other hospitality services, adjusted for international price differences. Higher spending often indicates higher disposable income and a more developed service economy. This reflects people's ability to afford leisure activities and services beyond basic necessities.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 200101
nodes.description: This measures how much money households spend on a specific category of goods or services, used to compare living costs between countries. Higher values mean people spend more money on this particular category. This helps understand what people can afford and how they prioritize their spending across different countries.

nodes.description: This measures how much money households spend on a specific category of goods or services, based on international price comparison studies. Higher values mean people in that country spend more money on this particular category. This helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 20082
nodes.description: This measures how much households spend on a specific category of goods or services as part of international price comparisons. Higher values indicate more spending on this particular category. This data helps compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison Category 20083
nodes.description: This represents spending data for a specific category of goods or services used in international cost comparisons. Higher values indicate this category is more expensive relative to other countries. This matters because understanding price differences helps compare true living standards and economic conditions across different nations.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category
nodes.description: This represents a specific category of household spending tracked in international price comparisons, though the exact type of goods or services isn't specified. These categories help compare what people buy and how much they spend across different countries. Understanding spending patterns helps measure living standards and economic priorities.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 20065
nodes.description: This measures how much money households spend on a specific category of goods or services, based on international price comparison studies. Higher values mean people in that country spend more money on this particular category. This helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 20071
nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 20076
nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison - Category 20077
nodes.description: This measures spending on a specific category of goods or services as part of international price comparisons, which help compare living costs across countries. Higher values mean more money is spent on this category relative to other countries. This matters because it helps us understand how expensive different things are in each country and how far people's money goes.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison - Category 999988
nodes.description: This measures how much money people in different countries spend on a specific category of goods or services, with prices adjusted for fair comparison across nations. Higher spending values may indicate either higher living costs or greater purchasing power for this category. Understanding spending patterns helps show what people can afford and prioritize in different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category (Net Purchases Abroad)
nodes.description: This measures the difference between what residents spend when traveling abroad versus what foreign visitors spend locally, used in international price comparisons. Positive values mean residents spend more abroad than foreigners spend locally. This matters because it reflects tourism patterns and international purchasing power.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 999973
nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison - Category 10404
nodes.description: This measures spending on a specific category of goods or services, with prices adjusted to compare fairly across different countries. Higher values show more spending in this particular area. Understanding these patterns helps reveal differences in living costs and consumption priorities between nations.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison Category 10406
nodes.description: This represents spending data for a specific category of goods or services used to compare how much things cost between different countries. The values show relative price levels, where higher numbers mean that category is more expensive compared to other countries. This matters because it helps understand the true cost of living and purchasing power people have in different places.

nodes.label: Spending on Medical Products and Equipment
nodes.description: This measures how much money people spend on medical supplies, prescription drugs, and health equipment like wheelchairs or hearing aids. Values are typically in dollars per person, and higher values can indicate either better access to healthcare or higher medical costs. This matters because it affects people's ability to maintain their health and treat medical conditions.

nodes.label: Financial Assets Share of Private Wealth
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of people's private wealth comes from financial investments like stocks, bonds, and bank accounts, rather than physical assets like real estate. Values range from 0-100%, with higher percentages meaning more wealth is held in financial form. A mix of financial and physical assets helps protect people's wealth from different types of economic risks.

nodes.label: Private Pension Wealth
nodes.description: This measures the total value of private pension assets and retirement savings held by individuals, separate from government social security programs. Higher values indicate people have more private retirement savings. This matters because private pension wealth helps ensure people can maintain their living standards in retirement and reduces dependence on government benefits.

nodes.label: Private Financial Wealth per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average value of financial assets (like stocks, bonds, and bank accounts) owned by private individuals in a country, covering all age groups. Higher values indicate more financial wealth per person, which generally suggests greater economic prosperity and financial security. This matters because financial assets provide economic stability and opportunities for investment and growth.

nodes.label: Government Revenue Compared to National Wealth
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government collects in taxes and other revenue compared to the country's total wealth (all assets minus debts). Higher values mean the government is collecting more revenue relative to the nation's wealth. This matters because it shows the government's capacity to fund public services and infrastructure relative to the country's overall economic resources.

nodes.label: Trade Balance Using Exchange Rates
nodes.description: This measures whether a country exports more than it imports using current exchange rates to convert different currencies, shown as a share of national income. Positive values mean the country has a trade surplus, while negative values indicate a trade deficit. This matters because it shows a country's competitiveness in international markets and its financial relationship with the rest of the world.

nodes.label: Wealth Impact of Social Security Contributions
nodes.description: This tracks how social security contributions (payments into retirement and benefit systems) affect overall national wealth, shown as an index over time. Higher values indicate social contributions have a larger impact on wealth accumulation. This matters because it shows how well the social security system is building resources to support future retirees and benefit recipients.

nodes.label: Wealth Impact of Consumption Taxes
nodes.description: This measures how taxes on goods and services affect the country's total wealth, tracked as an index over time. Higher values indicate these taxes have a larger impact on national wealth. This matters because it shows how tax policy on everyday purchases influences the country's overall economic resources and wealth accumulation.

nodes.label: Wealth Taxes as Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total national income comes from taxes on wealth (like property taxes or inheritance taxes). Higher values mean wealth taxes make up a larger portion of government revenue, indicating more redistribution from wealthy individuals to public services. This matters because it shows how much a country relies on taxing wealth to fund public programs and reduce inequality.

nodes.label: Government Economic Freedom Score
nodes.description: This measures how much a government interferes in the economy through regulations, taxes, and controls, with higher scores indicating less government interference and more economic freedom. Higher scores suggest more market-oriented policies and business-friendly environments. This matters because it affects how easily people can start businesses, find jobs, and make economic choices.

nodes.label: Wealth Inequality Threshold
nodes.description: This measures the minimum amount of wealth needed to be considered among the wealthiest people in a country. Higher thresholds indicate that even the wealthy need more assets to rank highly, suggesting greater overall prosperity but potentially high inequality. This matters because it shows how wealth is distributed and whether economic growth benefits everyone or just a few.

nodes.label: Government-Owned Wealth and Assets
nodes.description: This measures the total value of assets owned by the government, such as land, buildings, and businesses. Higher values indicate the government owns more valuable resources. This matters because government assets can be used to provide public services and support economic development for citizens.

nodes.label: Public Wealth Share by Income Group
nodes.description: This measures what portion of a country's total public wealth (government assets like infrastructure, land, and investments) is effectively controlled by different income groups. Higher values for lower-income groups indicate more equal access to public resources. This matters because public wealth distribution affects how fairly government resources serve all citizens.

nodes.label: Government Share of National Wealth
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total wealth (land, buildings, infrastructure, etc.) is owned by the government versus private individuals and companies. The percentage can vary widely between countries based on their economic systems. This matters because it shows the balance between public and private ownership in an economy.

nodes.label: Government Wealth Share (Men)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of total government-held wealth belongs to men in the population. Higher values indicate men control a larger share of public wealth. This matters because it reveals gender inequality in economic power and access to government resources and positions.

nodes.label: Total National Wealth per Person
nodes.description: This measures a country's complete wealth - including natural resources, infrastructure, and financial assets - divided by its population, shown in current US dollars per person. Higher values indicate greater overall wealth and resources available to support each citizen's well-being. This comprehensive measure helps assess a country's true capacity to provide prosperity and opportunities for its people.

nodes.label: Average Total Wealth Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total value of everything the average person owns, including houses, savings, investments, and other valuable items, minus what they owe in debts. Higher values mean people have more financial security and assets they can use in emergencies or retirement. Greater wealth provides families with more opportunities and protection against economic hardship.

nodes.label: Average Individual Fixed Asset Wealth
nodes.description: This measures the average value of long-term physical assets that individuals own, such as real estate, buildings, machinery, or equipment that hold value over time. Higher values mean people own more valuable long-term assets. This matters because owning valuable assets provides financial security and can be sold or used to generate income when needed.

nodes.label: Average Total Personal Wealth
nodes.description: This measures the average total value of everything a person owns (like houses, savings, investments) minus what they owe in debts. Higher values mean people have more accumulated wealth and financial assets. This is important because greater personal wealth provides financial security and more opportunities for education, healthcare, and quality of life improvements.

nodes.label: Average Annual Wealth Growth
nodes.description: This measures how much the average person's total wealth (assets minus debts) grows each year through investments, property appreciation, and savings. Higher values mean people's wealth is increasing faster over time. This is important because steady wealth growth helps families build financial security and improve their long-term economic prospects.

nodes.label: Wealth Share of Bottom 50% (Individual)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total wealth is owned by the poorer half of all individuals. Values range from 0% to 50%, where higher percentages mean wealth is more equally distributed. This matters because when the bottom 50% owns very little wealth (often less than 10%), it indicates high inequality and fewer opportunities for economic mobility.

nodes.label: Government Wealth per Person
nodes.description: This measures the value of government-owned assets like public buildings, infrastructure, and investments divided by the population. Values are shown in dollars or local currency per person, where higher amounts indicate the government owns more valuable public assets. Greater government wealth can mean better public infrastructure and services that benefit everyone's quality of life.

nodes.label: Real Estate Share of Total Wealth
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of people's total wealth comes from real estate like homes and property, versus other assets like stocks or savings. Values range from 0-100%, with higher percentages meaning real estate makes up more of people's wealth. A balanced wealth composition protects families from losing everything if one type of investment loses value.

nodes.label: Housing Share of Total National Wealth
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total wealth is made up of housing and real estate assets. Higher percentages mean housing represents a larger portion of national wealth compared to other assets like financial investments or business capital. This is important because it shows how much of a country's economic value is tied up in property, affecting both economic stability and housing affordability.

nodes.label: Social Group Equality in Justice System
nodes.description: Measures whether all social groups (regardless of race, religion, class, or ethnicity) receive equal treatment in the court system and from law enforcement. Higher values mean the justice system treats all groups fairly, while lower values indicate some groups face discrimination or bias. Equal justice is essential because it ensures all citizens have the same legal protections and rights.

nodes.label: Political Equality: Economic Group Access to Power
nodes.description: This measures whether different economic groups (poor, middle class, wealthy) have equal access to political power and influence over government decisions. Higher values indicate more equal access across economic classes. This matters because when only wealthy groups can influence politics, policies may ignore the needs of working families and increase inequality.

nodes.label: Economic Political Equality - Expert Rating
nodes.description: This measures how equally people with different economic backgrounds can participate in politics, using the original rating scale that V-Dem experts used (typically 0-4). Higher values mean greater economic equality in political participation. This matters because when only wealthy people can effectively participate in politics, government policies may ignore the needs of ordinary citizens.

nodes.label: Political Equality by Social Group - Average Score
nodes.description: This measures the average level of political equality across different social groups (like ethnic, religious, or economic groups) in a country. Higher values indicate that all social groups have more equal opportunities to participate in politics. Equal political participation matters because when some groups are excluded from politics, their needs and interests may be ignored by government.

nodes.label: Political Equality: Equal Political Voice Across Economic Classes (Average)
nodes.description: This measures whether people from different economic backgrounds have equal influence in politics, or if wealthy people have more political power than poor people, averaged across expert ratings. Higher scores indicate more equal political influence regardless of wealth. This is crucial because economic equality in politics ensures all citizens can shape government decisions, not just the wealthy.

nodes.label: Political Group Equality (Original Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures whether different political groups have equal opportunities to participate in politics, using the original scale that expert evaluators used. Higher scores mean more equal treatment of various political parties and movements. Equal treatment of political groups ensures fair competition and prevents any single group from unfairly dominating the political system.

nodes.label: Political Equality: Geographic Representation Balance (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures how fairly different geographic regions are represented in political power and decision-making, using experts' original ratings. Higher values indicate better balance, meaning rural and urban areas, or different provinces, have more equal influence in government. Fair geographic representation ensures all parts of a country have a voice in politics.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Political Participation (Original Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how equally men and women participate in political activities like voting, campaigning, and holding office, using V-Dem's original survey scale. Higher values indicate greater gender equality in political involvement. This matters because equal participation ensures government policies reflect the needs of all citizens.

nodes.label: Data Quality: Asian Political Equality Assessment
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when experts were asked about political equality issues specifically relevant to Asian contexts. Higher values indicate more experts couldn't provide answers, suggesting less reliable data for those assessments. This data quality measure helps researchers understand the reliability of political equality scores in Asian countries and regions.

nodes.label: Access to Justice by Economic Class (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures whether wealthy and poor people have equal access to fair treatment in the court system, using experts' original ratings before statistical adjustments. Higher scores mean less difference between how rich and poor people are treated by courts. Equal access to justice is essential for protecting everyone's rights regardless of their income level.

nodes.label: Social Group Access to Political Power
nodes.description: This measures how equally different social groups (like ethnic minorities, religious groups, or economic classes) can access political power and influence government decisions. Higher values indicate more equal access across social groups. Equal political access helps ensure all citizens can participate in democracy regardless of their background.

nodes.label: Power Distribution Across Social Groups
nodes.description: Measures how equally political power is shared among different social groups (ethnic, religious, regional) in society, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values indicate more equal power sharing. Equal representation helps ensure all citizens have a voice in government decisions that affect their lives.

nodes.label: Social Group Access to Justice
nodes.description: This measures how equally different social groups (like ethnic minorities, women, or poor people) can access fair treatment in the legal system. Higher scores mean all groups have similar access to courts and justice. Equal access to justice is crucial because it ensures everyone can protect their rights regardless of their background or social status.

nodes.label: Equal Access to Political Power Across Social Groups
nodes.description: This measures how equally different social groups (based on class, ethnicity, religion, etc.) can participate in and influence politics in a country. The scale runs from 0-1, where higher values mean more equal access to political power regardless of your background. Equal political participation helps ensure all groups have a voice in decisions that affect their lives.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Political Power
nodes.description: This measures how equally men and women can access political power and influence government decisions, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values indicate more equal political participation between genders. Gender equality in politics helps ensure government policies reflect the needs and perspectives of all citizens.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Social Group Justice
nodes.description: Assesses how equally different genders are treated by the justice system and social institutions, averaged across expert opinions. Higher values (0-1 scale) indicate more equal treatment regardless of gender. Equal justice for all genders is fundamental for a fair society where everyone has the same opportunities and protections.

nodes.label: Political Power by Geographic Region
nodes.description: This measures how evenly political power and influence are distributed across different geographic regions within a country. Higher values indicate that people from all regions have roughly equal political influence, while lower values suggest certain regions dominate politics. Balanced regional representation helps ensure all citizens have fair access to political power regardless of where they live.

nodes.label: Geographic Political Equality (Average Score)
nodes.description: This measures how equally people from different geographic regions (urban vs rural, different provinces) can participate in politics and influence government decisions. The mean score averages expert assessments to show overall geographic political equality. Equal regional representation ensures government policies consider the needs of people from all areas, not just major cities.

nodes.label: Social Group Equality in Society
nodes.description: Measures whether different social groups (based on race, religion, ethnicity, or class) have equal opportunities and treatment in society. Higher values indicate all groups enjoy similar rights and opportunities, while lower values suggest significant inequality between social groups. This matters because social equality affects everyone's chances for education, jobs, and a good quality of life.

nodes.label: Geographic Political Equality (Ordinal Scale)
nodes.description: This measures whether people from different regions or geographic areas within a country have equal political power and representation. Higher scores on this ordinal scale mean better geographic equality in political influence. This matters because it ensures rural and urban areas, or different provinces, all have fair representation in government decisions.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Political Participation (Ranked)
nodes.description: Measures how equally men and women can participate in politics, using a ranked scale from low to high equality. Higher values indicate more equal political participation between genders. Equal political participation ensures that policies address the needs and interests of all citizens regardless of gender.

nodes.label: Political Equality: Power Distribution by Social Class
nodes.description: This measures how evenly political power is distributed across different social and economic classes in society. Higher scores (on a 0-4 scale) mean political power is more equally shared between rich and poor citizens. This matters because unequal power distribution can lead to policies that only benefit wealthy elites while ignoring ordinary citizens' needs.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Political Power
nodes.description: This measures how equally men and women can access and exercise political power, including running for office, voting, and influencing policy decisions. The scale runs from 0-4, where higher values indicate greater gender equality in politics. Equal political participation by gender leads to policies that better represent everyone's needs and experiences.

nodes.label: Political Participation Across Social Groups (Ordinal Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how equally different social groups (based on class, ethnicity, gender, etc.) can participate in political activities like voting, campaigning, and running for office. Values range from 0-4, where higher scores indicate more equal participation across groups. Equal political participation ensures all citizens have a voice in decisions that affect their lives.

nodes.label: Gender Political Equality in Public Service (Average)
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women have equal opportunities to work in government jobs and public service positions, averaged across expert assessments. Higher scores (0-1 scale) indicate better gender equality in public sector employment. Equal access to public service jobs ensures diverse perspectives in government and provides equal career opportunities for all citizens.

nodes.label: Gender Political Participation Data Quality
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when experts are asked about women's participation in political life. Higher values mean more experts couldn't or didn't answer questions about this topic. Good data coverage helps track progress toward equal political representation that benefits all citizens.

nodes.label: Social Group Political Participation
nodes.description: Measures how equally different social groups (based on class, ethnicity, religion, etc.) can participate in politics. Higher scores indicate more equal political participation across all social groups. This matters because equal participation ensures that government policies represent the needs of all citizens, not just privileged groups.

nodes.label: Political Participation Equality Data Availability
nodes.description: Measures how much information is available about equal political participation across different groups in society. This is a data quality indicator - higher scores mean experts had less information to assess political equality. This matters because equal participation ensures all citizens have a voice in decisions that affect their lives.

nodes.label: Political Equality Across Geographic Areas (Average)
nodes.description: Measures the average level of political equality between different geographic regions within a country, such as urban vs. rural areas or different provinces. Higher values indicate people have more equal political power regardless of where they live. Geographic political equality ensures all citizens can influence government decisions, not just those in major cities or wealthy regions.

nodes.label: Equal Political Participation Across Social Groups
nodes.description: This measures whether different social groups (based on class, ethnicity, religion, etc.) have equal opportunities to participate in politics. Higher scores indicate more equal participation across different communities. Equal political participation ensures that all groups in society can influence decisions that affect their lives.

nodes.label: Political Equality: Power Distribution by Social Class
nodes.description: This measures whether political power is equally distributed across different economic and social classes, or if wealthy and upper-class groups have disproportionate influence. Higher values indicate more equal political power across social classes. This matters because when power is concentrated among the wealthy, policies may favor the rich while ignoring the needs of working families.

nodes.label: Power Distribution by Socioeconomic Status
nodes.description: Evaluates how political power is distributed across different income and social class levels in society. Higher values (0-4 scale) indicate more equal distribution of power regardless of wealth or social status. Equal political power across economic classes ensures that government policies serve all citizens, not just the wealthy.

nodes.label: Political Power Distributed Equally Across Regions
nodes.description: Measures whether political power is shared fairly among different geographic regions within a country, or if one area dominates the others. Higher values (0-4 scale) indicate more equal regional representation in government. This matters because when some regions are excluded from power, it can lead to conflict and unequal development across the country.

nodes.label: Political Power Distribution Data Coverage
nodes.description: This tracks how many experts declined to answer V-Dem's questions about how political power is distributed among different social groups in a country. Higher values mean more experts didn't respond, possibly indicating the topic is sensitive or information is limited. Better data coverage helps understand whether all citizens have equal political influence.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Political Power
nodes.description: This measures whether men and women have equal opportunities to hold political power and influence government decisions. Higher scores indicate greater gender equality in political leadership and decision-making roles. Equal political representation helps ensure that policies address the needs of all citizens regardless of gender.

nodes.label: Equal rights for spouses to manage property
nodes.description: This measures whether married couples have equal legal rights to control property and assets during marriage, scored as 1 for yes and 0 for no. A score of 1 is better, meaning both spouses can make financial decisions equally. This reflects gender equality and women's economic empowerment in a country.

nodes.label: Equal Property Rights for Women and Men
nodes.description: This measures whether women and men have the same legal rights to own land, houses, and other property, scored as 1 for equal rights and 0 for unequal rights. A score of 1 means both genders can legally own, buy, and sell property without discrimination. This is crucial because property ownership gives people economic security, access to credit, and the ability to build wealth for their families.

nodes.label: Female Economic Activity Rate (Ages 35-44)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 35-44 are working or actively looking for work in the labor force. Higher percentages indicate greater female participation in the economy during prime working years. This is important because women's economic participation boosts family incomes and overall economic growth.

nodes.label: Female Employment Rate (Ages 15-24)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of young women aged 15-24 who have jobs or are actively working. Higher percentages mean more young women are employed and economically active. Female youth employment matters because it gives young women financial independence and helps families and communities prosper economically.

nodes.label: Female Economic Activity Rate (Ages 65+)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 65 and older are still working or looking for work. Higher percentages indicate more older women remain economically active. This reflects both economic necessity and opportunity for older women, and affects overall economic productivity and retirement security.

nodes.label: Female Economic Activity Rate (Ages 55-64)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women aged 55-64 are working or actively looking for work in the labor force. Higher percentages indicate that older women have more economic opportunities and are participating more in paid employment. This matters because it shows whether women can maintain financial independence and contribute their skills throughout their careers.

nodes.label: Government Revenue as Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government collects in taxes and other revenue compared to the country's total income. Higher percentages mean the government collects a larger share of the nation's income. This matters because it indicates the government's capacity to fund public services, infrastructure, and social programs that benefit citizens.

nodes.label: Total Government Tax Revenue
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money a government collects from all types of taxes, including income taxes, sales taxes, and business taxes. Higher tax revenue gives governments more money to spend on public services like education, healthcare, and infrastructure. This matters because adequate tax revenue is essential for funding the services that support citizens' quality of life.

nodes.label: Average Government Revenue per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money the government collects from all sources (taxes, fees, etc.) divided by the population. Values are shown in local currency, and higher values mean the government has more resources per person to spend on public services. This matters because it indicates how well-funded public services like schools, roads, and healthcare are likely to be.

nodes.label: Average Household Tax Payment
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average household pays in taxes to the government each year, including income taxes, property taxes, and other government fees. Higher values could mean either that people earn more money or that tax rates are higher. Tax payments fund public services like schools, roads, and healthcare that benefit everyone.

nodes.label: Average Tax Paid per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much tax the average individual pays to the government each year, including income taxes, sales taxes, and other government fees. Values are in local currency, and higher amounts mean people are paying more in taxes. This matters because tax payments fund public services like schools, hospitals, and roads that improve quality of life.

nodes.label: Average Tax Paid per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much tax the average individual pays to the government each year, including income taxes, sales taxes, and other government fees. Values are in local currency, and higher amounts mean people are paying more in taxes. This matters because tax payments fund public services like schools, hospitals, and roads that improve quality of life.

nodes.label: Tax Revenue from Households
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of taxes collected from households (not businesses) in a country, typically shown in local currency or as a percentage of total income. Higher values mean households are paying more taxes, which could indicate either higher tax rates or higher household incomes. This matters because it shows how much families contribute to government funding for public services like schools, hospitals, and infrastructure.

nodes.label: Average Household Tax Payments
nodes.description: This measures how much the average household pays in taxes to the government each year. Values are shown in dollars or local currency, where higher amounts mean families are paying more of their income in taxes. Tax revenue is important because it funds public services like roads, schools, and healthcare that improve everyone's quality of life.

nodes.label: Pre-Tax Income Distribution per Worker
nodes.description: This measures how income from work is distributed among employees before taxes and government transfers, shown as an index comparing different income levels. Higher index values indicate greater inequality in worker pay. This matters because it shows how fairly wages and salaries are distributed across different jobs and skill levels in the economy.

nodes.label: Pre-Tax Income Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total income an individual earns before any taxes are subtracted. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate better gross earnings. This is important because it shows earning capacity and helps compare income levels before government policies affect take-home pay.

nodes.label: Average Pre-Tax Income from Work and Business
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from jobs, self-employment, and business activities before taxes are taken out. Higher values indicate people are earning more money from their work and business ventures. This matters because higher pre-tax earnings typically lead to better living standards and more financial security for families.

nodes.label: Average Household Pre-Tax Income from Work and Investments
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money households earn from jobs, businesses, and investments before paying taxes. Values are in local currency, with higher amounts indicating better economic conditions. This reflects the overall economic well-being and earning potential of families in a country.

nodes.label: Tax Burden as Share of Income (Rate Index)
nodes.description: This measures how much of a country's total income goes to taxes, expressed as an index where 100 represents a baseline year. Higher values mean people pay a larger portion of their income in taxes. A higher tax burden can mean better public services but less money in people's pockets for personal spending.

nodes.label: Total Tax Burden on National Income
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of the country's total income goes to all types of taxes combined, shown as an index tracking changes over time. Higher values mean taxes take up a larger share of national income. This matters because the total tax burden affects how much income is available for private spending and investment, influencing economic growth and living standards.

nodes.label: Sales and Consumption Tax Rate
nodes.description: This measures how much a country collects from taxes on goods and services (like sales tax or VAT) compared to its national income, using market exchange rates. Values are shown as percentages, where higher values mean heavier taxation of purchases. This matters because it affects how expensive everyday goods are for consumers and how much purchasing power people have.

nodes.label: Tax Burden from Goods and Services
nodes.description: This measures how much people pay in taxes on goods and services (like sales tax or VAT) compared to their total income. Higher values mean people are paying more of their income toward these consumption taxes. This matters because high consumption taxes can make basic goods more expensive for everyone, especially affecting lower-income families who spend more of their income on necessities.

nodes.label: Tax Revenue from Income
nodes.description: Measures how much money a government collects from income taxes as a percentage of total government revenue or GDP. Higher values indicate the government relies more heavily on income taxes to fund public services. This matters because income tax collection shows a government's ability to fund education, healthcare, and infrastructure that improve citizens' quality of life.

nodes.label: Government Tax Revenue from Goods and Services
nodes.description: This measures how much money a government collects from taxes on goods and services (like sales tax or VAT), usually shown as a percentage of total government revenue or GDP. Higher values mean the government relies more heavily on these types of taxes rather than income taxes or other sources. This matters because it affects how fairly the tax burden is shared across different income groups in society.

nodes.label: Government Tax Revenue from Mixed Sources
nodes.description: This measures government income from various tax sources including businesses, individuals, and mixed economic activities. Higher values mean the government collects more tax revenue relative to the economy. This is important because tax revenue funds public services, infrastructure, and social programs that benefit citizens.

nodes.label: Government Tax Revenue from Wealth
nodes.description: This measures how much tax revenue the government collects from wealth-based taxes like property taxes, inheritance taxes, and capital gains taxes. Higher values indicate governments rely more on taxing wealth rather than income. This affects inequality because wealth taxes can help redistribute resources from rich to poor.

nodes.label: Government Wealth from Tax Revenue
nodes.description: This measures how much wealth the government accumulates through collecting taxes from individuals and businesses. Higher values mean the government is building up more financial resources through taxation. This matters because government wealth from taxes provides the funding needed for public services, infrastructure, and social programs that benefit everyone.

nodes.label: Average Pre-Tax Income (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn before paying taxes, including wages, business profits, and investment returns across the entire population. Higher values mean people earn more before taxes are deducted. This matters because pre-tax income shows the underlying earning power and economic opportunities available to residents.

nodes.label: Average Pre-tax Income (All Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the average income earned by all adults in a country before taxes, including wages, business profits, and investment returns. Higher values mean people are earning more money on average. This matters because pre-tax income determines people's ability to afford housing, food, education, and other necessities before government policies redistribute wealth.

nodes.label: Average Pre-tax Pension Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average amount people receive from pensions and retirement savings before taxes across all income levels. Higher values mean retirees have more financial security. This is crucial for understanding whether people can maintain a decent quality of life after they stop working.

nodes.label: Average Pre-tax Government Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average income people receive from government jobs and programs before paying taxes. Higher values mean more people work for the government or receive government payments. This shows how big a role government plays in providing income and employment in a country.

nodes.label: Average Pre-Tax Income (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of income people earn before paying taxes, including wages, business income, and investment returns. Values are typically in thousands of dollars per person, and higher values mean people earn more before taxes. This matters because it shows how much economic opportunity exists before government redistribution through taxes.

nodes.label: Average Pre-tax Income (Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the average income that adults earn before paying taxes, providing a picture of earnings across the adult population. Higher values indicate better earning opportunities and economic prosperity. Pre-tax income levels are important because they show the underlying strength of the job market and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Average Pre-tax Income of Adults
nodes.description: This measures the average income earned by adults from all sources (wages, business, investments) before paying taxes, usually expressed relative to the national average. Higher values indicate greater average earnings. This matters because pre-tax income determines people's standard of living and their ability to afford housing, education, and other necessities.

nodes.label: Average Pre-Tax Income (Working-Age Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the average income that working-age adults earn from jobs and investments before paying taxes. Higher values indicate people earn more from their economic activities. This shows the market value of people's work and investments before government policies redistribute income through taxes and benefits.

nodes.label: Average Mixed Household Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical yearly income that households earn from multiple sources, like wages, business profits, and investments combined. Values are in currency amounts, where higher numbers mean households have more total income. This shows how well families can afford housing, food, and other necessities.

nodes.label: Average Individual Mixed Income
nodes.description: This measures the total average income a person receives from multiple sources, combining wages from jobs, profits from businesses, and other income streams. Higher values mean people have more total income coming in from various sources. This is important because having multiple income sources can provide more financial security and higher overall living standards.

nodes.label: Mixed Income per Individual
nodes.description: This measures the average income that individuals receive from owning and working in their own businesses (like farmers, shop owners, or freelancers), typically shown in local currency. Higher values mean people earn more from self-employment and small businesses. This matters because mixed income often provides economic independence and can indicate a thriving entrepreneurial economy.

nodes.label: Individual Social Security Income
nodes.description: This measures how much money individuals receive from government social programs like unemployment benefits, disability payments, or retirement pensions. Values are in currency amounts, where higher numbers mean people get more government support. This shows how well the social safety net protects people during hard times.

nodes.label: Average Individual Social Security Income
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of money a person receives from government social programs like unemployment benefits, disability payments, or retirement funds. Higher values mean people receive more government assistance when needed. This is important because these programs provide a safety net that helps people maintain basic living standards during difficult times.

nodes.label: Average Net Savings per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person has left over after paying for expenses and taxes. Values are shown in dollars or local currency, where higher amounts indicate people are able to save more money. Higher net surplus means individuals have more financial security and can better handle emergencies or invest in their future.

nodes.label: Average Worker Pay Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average total payment workers receive for their jobs, including wages, salaries, and benefits like health insurance or retirement contributions. Higher values mean workers are earning more and have better job benefits, leading to improved living standards. Good compensation helps people afford necessities and save for the future.

nodes.label: Average Household Wage Income
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of money households earn from wages and salaries from jobs each year. Values are in local currency, and higher amounts mean households are earning more from employment. This is important because wage income is usually the main source of money families use to pay for housing, food, education, and other necessities.

nodes.label: Individual Wage and Salary Income
nodes.description: This measures the average amount individuals earn from their jobs in wages, salaries, and employee benefits each year. Values are in local currency, and higher amounts mean people are earning more from their employment. This matters because employment income is typically people's main source of money for covering their daily living expenses and building financial security.

nodes.label: Average Individual Mixed Work Earnings
nodes.description: This measures the average income a person earns from combining different types of work, such as having both a regular job and running a small business on the side. Higher values mean people are earning more from their various work activities. This is important because it shows how much people can earn when they combine employment with self-employment or business ownership.

nodes.label: Mixed Income per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average income that individuals earn from both working for wages and running their own small businesses or freelance work. Values are typically in local currency per year, and higher amounts mean people are earning more from their combined work activities. This matters because it shows how much people can earn when they mix different types of work to make a living.

nodes.label: Armed Conflict Minimum Severity
nodes.description: Measures the minimum level of armed conflict or violence occurring within a country in a given year. Higher values indicate more severe conflict, with scale typically ranging from 0 (no conflict) to higher numbers representing increasing levels of violence and warfare. This matters because armed conflict destroys lives, displaces families, and prevents economic development and social progress.

nodes.label: Armed Conflict Female Casualties (Age 40+)
nodes.description: Measures the number or rate of women aged 40 and older who are casualties in armed conflicts. Higher values indicate more older women are being killed or injured in warfare. Tracking these casualties is important because it shows how conflict affects vulnerable civilian populations and families.

nodes.label: Armed Conflict Leader Age
nodes.description: This measures the average age of leaders involved in armed conflicts or wars in a country. The age of conflict leaders can influence how wars are fought and resolved. This matters because leadership characteristics in conflicts affect civilian safety and the likelihood of peaceful resolution.

nodes.label: Armed Conflict Area Coverage
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of a country's territory is affected by armed conflict or warfare. Higher values indicate conflict covers more of the country's area. Understanding conflict coverage is important because widespread fighting disrupts basic services, displaces families, and prevents economic development.

nodes.label: Peaceful Election Campaign Period
nodes.description: Measures whether the election campaign period was free from significant political violence, including attacks on candidates, supporters, or campaign events. Higher scores indicate more peaceful campaigns. This matters because violence during campaigns prevents fair elections and can intimidate voters from participating in democracy.

nodes.label: Elections: Peaceful Conduct (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures how free elections are from violence, intimidation, and threats, using experts' original ratings. Higher values indicate more peaceful elections where voters and candidates can participate without fear of harm. Peaceful elections are essential for democracy because violence prevents people from freely choosing their leaders.

nodes.label: Election Violence Level (Ordinal Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how much violence occurs during election campaigns and voting, from harassment to physical attacks on candidates or voters. Higher scores (0-4 scale) indicate more peaceful elections, which ensures people can participate in democracy without fear for their safety.

nodes.label: Civil Society Organizations in Universities
nodes.description: Measures whether civil society organizations (like student groups, advocacy groups, or NGOs) can operate freely within universities. Higher scores indicate greater freedom for these organizations to function on campus. This is important because universities with active civil society foster critical thinking and prepare students to participate in democratic society.

nodes.label: Civil Society: Violence Against Organizations
nodes.description: Measures how often civil society organizations (like activist groups, charities, or unions) face physical violence or harassment. Higher scores indicate more violence against these groups. This matters because when civic organizations can operate safely, they can better advocate for citizens' needs and rights.

nodes.label: Civil Society Freedom and Openness
nodes.description: This measures how freely civil society organizations (like charities, advocacy groups, and community organizations) can operate without government interference. Higher scores (0-1 scale) indicate that these groups can form, speak out, and pursue their goals more freely. This matters because active civil society organizations help protect citizens' rights and provide important community services.

nodes.label: Religious Organization Freedom
nodes.description: This measures how freely religious groups can organize, worship, and participate in public life without government interference. Higher scores indicate religious organizations face fewer restrictions on their activities. Religious freedom allows diverse faith communities to contribute to society and protects an important aspect of personal liberty.

nodes.label: Civil Society Organization Mobilization Ability
nodes.description: This measures how easily civil society groups (like unions, advocacy organizations, and community groups) can organize people and mobilize support for their causes. The scale runs from 0-1, where higher values mean these groups face fewer restrictions. Strong civil society helps citizens organize around issues they care about and influence government decisions.

nodes.label: Civil Society: Religious Group Repression
nodes.description: This measures how much the government restricts, harasses, or represses religious organizations and their activities. Higher values indicate more severe government repression of religious groups. This matters because religious freedom is a basic human right, and repression can limit people's ability to practice their faith and participate in community life.

nodes.label: Civil Society: Freedom of Assembly
nodes.description: This measures whether people can freely gather, protest, and hold public meetings without government interference or fear of punishment. Higher values indicate greater freedom to assemble peacefully. This is essential because the right to gather and protest allows citizens to express their views and influence government decisions.

nodes.label: Pro-Democracy Civil Society Activity
nodes.description: Measures how actively civil society organizations work to promote democratic values and institutions. Higher values indicate more organizations actively supporting democracy. Strong pro-democracy groups help protect citizens' rights and hold government accountable when it overreaches its authority.

nodes.label: Civil Society: Organizational Structure Type
nodes.description: This measures a specific type of organizational structure within civil society groups like charities, advocacy organizations, and community groups (category 3 on the scale). Higher values indicate this particular structure is more common. This matters because diverse civil society organizations help communities address local problems and give citizens ways to participate in public life.

nodes.label: Civil Society Structure (Category 0)
nodes.description: This measures one specific type of civil society organization structure, with '0' representing a particular category of how these groups are organized. Different organizational structures affect how well civil society groups can represent citizens' interests and hold government accountable, which impacts democratic quality of life.

nodes.label: Civil Society Repression (Average Score)
nodes.description: This measures the average level of government harassment, violence, or other repression faced by civil society organizations like NGOs, advocacy groups, and community organizations. The scale runs 0-1, where higher values indicate more severe repression. Less repression matters because it allows citizens to organize freely to address community problems and advocate for their interests.

nodes.label: Democratic Civil Society Mobilization Data Quality
nodes.description: This tracks missing data for questions about how well civil society groups can organize to support democratic causes and elections. Higher values mean more experts couldn't answer these questions, indicating less reliable information about democratic organizing in that country.

nodes.label: Civil Society Gender Mobilization (Data Availability)
nodes.description: Measures how many experts didn't respond to questions about gender-based mobilization in civil society, not the mobilization itself. Lower values mean better data coverage, as more experts provided answers about women's political participation and gender equality movements. Good data coverage helps researchers and policymakers understand the true state of gender equality in different countries.

nodes.label: Civil Society Confrontational Mobilization (Average)
nodes.description: Measures how often civil society groups use confrontational tactics like protests, strikes, or demonstrations to influence government, averaged across expert assessments. Higher scores indicate more confrontational activism. This is important because it shows whether citizens can effectively pressure their government for change when normal political channels fail.

nodes.label: Constitutional Civil Rights Protection
nodes.description: Measures whether a country's constitution includes strong protections for basic civil rights like freedom of speech, religion, and assembly. Higher values indicate more comprehensive constitutional guarantees of individual freedoms. These protections are crucial because they establish the legal foundation for personal liberty and human dignity.

nodes.label: Constitutional Social Rights Protection
nodes.description: This measures whether a country's constitution guarantees social rights like healthcare, education, housing, or social security. Higher scores mean the constitution provides stronger protection for citizens' social and economic welfare. Constitutional social rights matter because they legally require governments to provide basic services that help people meet their fundamental needs.

nodes.label: Civil Society Entry and Exit - Freest Level
nodes.description: This measures whether civil society organizations can form and dissolve completely freely in a country. A value of 1 means the country allows maximum freedom for groups to organize. Free civil society is crucial for democracy because it allows citizens to organize around shared interests and advocate for change without government interference.

nodes.label: Civil Society: State of Emergency (Category 6)
nodes.description: This indicates whether a country declared a state of emergency that falls into a specific category of emergency powers. The value shows if this particular type of emergency declaration occurred. This matters because emergency powers can suspend normal rights and freedoms, affecting citizens' daily lives and democratic participation.

nodes.label: Civil Society State of Emergency Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how much data is missing about civil society conditions during states of emergency. Higher values indicate more missing information, not better civil society conditions. Complete data coverage is important because it helps track whether governments properly protect civil society rights even during emergency periods.

nodes.label: Civil Society: Trade Union Strength
nodes.description: This measures how strong and independent trade unions are in representing workers' interests and influencing workplace conditions. Higher values indicate more powerful and autonomous unions. This is important because strong unions help protect workers' rights and ensure fair wages and working conditions.

nodes.label: Trade Union Independence (Average Score)
nodes.description: This measures how free and independent labor unions are from government control, averaged across expert assessments. Higher scores (0-1 scale) mean unions can operate more freely to represent workers' interests without interference. Independent unions matter because they help protect workers' rights and give ordinary people a voice in economic decisions.

nodes.label: Civil Society Consultation in Policymaking
nodes.description: This measures how often government officials consult with civil society organizations when making policy decisions. Higher scores indicate that community groups, advocacy organizations, and other civilian groups are regularly included in policy discussions. This matters because public input leads to policies that better address citizens' actual needs and concerns.

nodes.label: Civil Society Entry and Exit
nodes.description: This measures how easily organizations like charities, advocacy groups, and community associations can form and operate without government interference. Higher scores indicate that civil society groups can organize more freely to pursue their goals. A vibrant civil society gives citizens more ways to address community problems and hold government accountable.

nodes.label: Environmental Organizations Can Operate Freely (Average Score)
nodes.description: Measures how freely environmental groups can organize, advocate, and operate without government interference, averaged across multiple expert assessments. Higher values (0-4 scale) indicate environmental organizations face fewer restrictions. This matters because environmental groups play a key role in protecting natural resources and public health that affect everyone's quality of life.

nodes.label: Civil Society: Government Consultation
nodes.description: This measures how often governments consult with civil society organizations (like nonprofits, advocacy groups, and community organizations) when making policies. Higher scores mean governments regularly seek input from these groups. This matters because consultation leads to better policies that reflect citizens' needs and concerns.

nodes.label: Freedom of Academic and Cultural Expression
nodes.description: This measures how freely academics, artists, and cultural figures can express their views without government interference. Higher values on this scale indicate greater freedom for intellectual and cultural expression. When scholars and artists can work freely, societies benefit from more innovation, critical thinking, and cultural development.

nodes.label: Religious Organization Control - Expert Rating
nodes.description: This measures how much the government controls religious organizations, using the original rating scale that V-Dem experts used. Higher values typically indicate more government control over religious groups. Religious freedom matters because it allows people to practice their beliefs without fear and prevents the government from forcing specific religious views on citizens.

nodes.label: Civil Society: Confrontational Mobilization (Original Survey Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how often civil society groups use confrontational tactics like protests or demonstrations to push for political change. Values use the original expert survey scale, where higher numbers typically indicate more confrontational activities. Active civil society participation, even when confrontational, can lead to positive changes in government policies that benefit citizens.

nodes.label: Civil Society Mobilization Capacity (Original Scale)
nodes.description: Measures how easily civil society organizations like charities, advocacy groups, and community organizations can mobilize people for collective action. This uses the original expert rating scale. Strong civil society helps communities solve problems, advocate for their interests, and hold governments accountable to citizens' needs.

nodes.label: Civil Society Gender Participation (Expert Ratings)
nodes.description: Measures how equally women participate in civil society organizations compared to men, using experts' original survey responses before statistical processing. Higher values indicate more equal participation by women in non-governmental organizations, advocacy groups, and community associations. Equal participation in civil society helps ensure women's voices are heard in public debates and policy discussions.

nodes.label: Gender Civil Liberties
nodes.description: This measures the extent to which men and women enjoy equal civil liberties and freedoms, including freedom of movement, expression, and association. Values typically range from 0-4, where higher scores indicate more gender equality in civil rights. Equal civil liberties for all genders promotes fair treatment and opportunities for everyone in society.

nodes.label: Political Civil Liberties Data Coverage
nodes.description: This tracks how many experts provided responses when V-Dem surveyed about political civil liberties in a country. Higher values indicate more experts declined to answer, suggesting either limited knowledge about the country or sensitive political conditions. Good data coverage (lower non-response rates) means more reliable information about citizens' political freedoms.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties Gender Equality (Data Availability)
nodes.description: Tracks how many experts didn't respond to questions about gender equality in civil liberties, rather than measuring the civil liberties themselves. Lower values indicate better data quality, meaning more experts answered questions about women's legal rights and freedoms. Reliable data on gender equality helps identify where women face discrimination and need stronger legal protections.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties: Gender Equality in Civil Liberties (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures how equally men and women can exercise basic civil rights like free speech, assembly, and movement, using the original expert rating scale. Higher scores mean more equal treatment between genders. This is important because equal civil liberties for all citizens strengthens democracy and human rights.

nodes.label: Political Killings Freedom
nodes.description: Assesses how free people are from political killings by government or its agents, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values (0-1 scale) indicate better protection from political violence and murder. Freedom from political killing is fundamental to human security and allows people to participate in political life without fear for their lives.

nodes.label: Freedom of Religion
nodes.description: This measures how free people are to practice their religion, change religions, or have no religion at all without government interference. Higher values indicate strong religious freedom where people can worship as they choose, while lower values suggest government restrictions on religious practice. Religious freedom is essential for personal dignity and helps prevent conflicts between different faith communities.

nodes.label: Access to Justice
nodes.description: This measures how easily ordinary citizens can use the court system to resolve disputes and seek legal remedies when their rights are violated. Higher scores (0-4 scale) indicate better access to courts, affordable legal help, and fair treatment regardless of wealth or status. Good access to justice ensures everyone can protect their rights and resolve conflicts peacefully through the legal system.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties: Property Rights for Men
nodes.description: This measures how well men's property rights are protected by law and in practice, including the right to own, buy, sell, and inherit property. Values range from 0-4, where higher scores indicate stronger property rights protection. Secure property rights help people build wealth and economic security, contributing to overall prosperity and stability.

nodes.label: Access to Justice for Men
nodes.description: This measures how easily men can access fair treatment in the court system, including hiring lawyers and getting impartial hearings. Higher values indicate better access to justice for men. Equal access to justice ensures that all people can protect their rights and resolve disputes fairly.

nodes.label: Property Rights Data Availability
nodes.description: Measures how much information is available about citizens' property ownership rights and protections. This is a data quality indicator - higher scores mean experts had less information to assess property rights. This matters because secure property rights help people build wealth and invest in their communities.

nodes.label: Academic Freedom Data Quality
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when experts are asked about academic freedom and university autonomy. Higher values mean more experts couldn't or didn't answer questions about this topic. Reliable data on academic freedom helps track whether students and faculty can learn and research without political interference.

nodes.label: Freedom of Movement Data Quality
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when experts are asked about citizens' freedom to move and travel within their country. Higher values mean more experts couldn't or didn't answer questions about this topic. Reliable data on movement rights helps track whether people can freely relocate for work, education, or personal reasons.

nodes.label: Religious Freedom
nodes.description: Measures the freedom of citizens to practice their religion, including worship, religious expression, and religious organization activities, averaged across expert responses. Higher scores (0-4 scale) indicate greater religious freedom. This matters because religious liberty allows people to live according to their beliefs without fear of persecution.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties: Equal Access to Justice (Average Score)
nodes.description: This measures whether all people can equally access courts and legal services regardless of their wealth, social status, or background, averaged across expert assessments. Higher scores indicate more equal access to justice. This is vital because fair access to courts ensures everyone can defend their rights and resolve disputes legally.

nodes.label: Religious Group Workers Freedom (Category 4)
nodes.description: This measures a specific level of freedom for religious organization workers to operate without government interference. The value indicates whether religious workers experience this particular level of freedom in their activities. Religious freedom helps ensure all people can practice their beliefs and participate in faith-based community organizations.

nodes.label: Religious Group Workplace Choice: Moderate Restrictions
nodes.description: This measures whether religious groups face moderate restrictions in choosing their employees and workplace practices. This specific category tracks situations where some but not severe limitations exist, affecting religious organizations' ability to operate according to their beliefs.

nodes.label: Religious Group Worker Rights (Category 1)
nodes.description: Indicates whether workers affiliated with religious groups enjoy full labor rights and protections (coded as category 1). A value of 1 means religious workers have equal rights, 0 means they face discrimination. Equal worker rights regardless of religious affiliation ensures fair economic opportunities and prevents workplace discrimination.

nodes.label: Religious and Worldview Freedom (Category 3)
nodes.description: This measures a specific aspect of how freely people can practice their religion or express their worldview without government interference. This represents one category within a broader scale of religious freedom protections. Strong religious freedom allows people to live according to their beliefs and participate fully in society.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties: Religious Group Restrictions
nodes.description: This measures a specific level of government restrictions on religious groups and practices (category 8 on the scale). Higher values indicate more severe restrictions on religious freedom for certain groups. This matters because religious freedom is essential for people to practice their beliefs and maintain their cultural identity without fear of persecution.

nodes.label: No Religious Workplace Discrimination
nodes.description: Measures the absence of workplace discrimination based on religious beliefs. Higher scores indicate that people face no job discrimination because of their religion. This matters because religious freedom in employment ensures all citizens can work and earn a living regardless of their personal beliefs.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties: Religious-State Relationship (Hostile Category)
nodes.description: This measures whether a country's government is actively hostile toward religious groups and institutions. Higher values indicate more cases where the government restricts, persecutes, or oppresses religious organizations. A higher score means worse civil liberties, as it shows the government interferes more with people's freedom to practice their religion.

nodes.label: Religious Groups Face State Harassment (Category 6)
nodes.description: Indicates whether a country falls into the highest category of religious group harassment by the state, where governments severely restrict or persecute religious organizations. A value of 1 means the country is in this worst category, while 0 means it's not. This matters because religious freedom is a basic human right that affects millions of people's daily lives and well-being.

nodes.label: Religious Civil Liberties (Category 21)
nodes.description: This measures a specific aspect of religious freedom and civil liberties, representing one category from V-Dem's detailed religious rights survey questions. It examines how freely people can practice their religion without government interference. Strong religious civil liberties ensure people can worship and express their beliefs freely, contributing to a tolerant and diverse society.

nodes.label: Religious Worker Civil Liberty Protections
nodes.description: This measures the level of civil liberty protections specifically for religious workers (like priests, ministers, imams) in a country. This is one category within a broader assessment of civil liberties for different professional groups. Strong protections help ensure religious freedom and prevent persecution based on faith-based work.

nodes.label: Social Group Civil Liberties Data Coverage
nodes.description: This tracks survey response rates for questions about civil liberties protections for different social groups. Higher values mean more experts didn't provide information about minority rights and freedoms in that country. This measures data availability rather than the actual level of civil liberties protection.

nodes.label: Freedom for Social Groups (Average Score)
nodes.description: This measures the average level of freedom that different social groups have to organize, meet, and express their views publicly. Higher scores (0-1 scale) mean greater freedom for all groups in society, which helps ensure equal participation and representation for everyone.

nodes.label: Freedom from Political Violence for Social Groups
nodes.description: This tracks how often different social groups face political violence or harassment from government or other groups. Lower values indicate more violence against social groups, while higher values mean better protection. When all groups are safe from political violence, people can participate fully in society and the economy.

nodes.label: Political Civil Liberties (Original Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how well a country protects civil liberties related to political participation, including freedom of assembly, association, and expression in the political sphere. Scored on the original V-Dem expert scale, where higher values indicate stronger protection of political civil liberties. This matters because these freedoms allow citizens to participate in democracy and hold governments accountable.

nodes.label: State Ownership of Economy - Expert Rating
nodes.description: This measures how much of the economy is owned and controlled by the government rather than private individuals or companies, using the original expert rating scale.
