nodes.description: This measures how often experts could not provide information about which groups are most important or influential in the country's political system. Higher scores mean more missing data about key political actors and power structures. This indicates data availability rather than measuring the actual influence of important groups.

nodes.label: Regime: Support Group Type
nodes.description: This measures a specific type of group that supports the current political regime or government (category 6 on the scale). Higher values indicate this particular type of support group is more prominent. This matters because the types of groups supporting a government can indicate whether it relies on broad popular support or narrow special interests.

nodes.label: Regime Support from Religious Groups
nodes.description: This measures whether the current government receives strong support from religious organizations and leaders in the country. This is a specific category (3) that focuses on religious group backing. Strong religious support can help legitimize a government, but may also indicate that the regime favors certain faiths over others in policy decisions.

nodes.label: Regime Support Groups (Category 5)
nodes.description: Measures whether a specific type of social group supports the current political regime or government. This is one category in a classification system of different support groups. Understanding which groups back the government helps explain political stability and how well different parts of society are represented in politics.

nodes.label: Data Coverage: Government Support Group Size
nodes.description: This measures how often V-Dem experts were unable to provide information about the size of groups that support the government. Higher values indicate more missing data, not stronger government support. This matters because missing data limits our understanding of the political coalitions that shape government policies.

nodes.label: Opposition Group Activity (Category 2)
nodes.description: This measures a specific level of activity that opposition political groups can engage in without government interference or punishment. The score indicates whether opposition groups can operate at this particular level of political activity. Active opposition groups are important because they provide alternatives to current leaders and help ensure competitive elections.

nodes.label: Opposition Group Activities (Category 11)
nodes.description: Measures a specific type of activity that opposition political groups can engage in under the current government system. Higher scores typically indicate greater freedom for opposition groups to operate. This matters because allowing opposition groups to function freely is essential for healthy competition of ideas and preventing authoritarian control.

nodes.label: Opposition Groups Allowed (Category 1)
nodes.description: Indicates whether opposition political groups are permitted to operate freely (coded as category 1). A value of 1 means opposition groups can function, while 0 means they face severe restrictions. Allowing opposition groups is crucial for democracy and ensures citizens have political choices beyond the ruling party.

nodes.label: Opposition Group Activities Data Coverage
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when V-Dem experts were asked about opposition political groups' activities. Higher values mean more experts couldn't or didn't provide information about this topic. Complete data helps researchers understand how free opposition groups are to organize and operate.

nodes.label: Opposition Group Restrictions (Category 6)
nodes.description: This measures specific restrictions placed on political opposition groups, focusing on one particular category of limitations. Higher values typically indicate more severe restrictions on opposition activities like rallies, fundraising, or media access. This affects whether citizens have real political choices and competitive elections.

nodes.label: Opposition Groups Activity Level - Highest Category
nodes.description: This measures whether opposition political groups in a country are extremely active and unrestricted in their activities. A value of 1 means the country falls into the highest category where opposition groups can operate completely freely. Active opposition groups are essential for democracy because they provide alternatives to the ruling party and hold government accountable.

nodes.label: Opposition Groups Data Coverage
nodes.description: Measures how many experts declined to answer questions about opposition political groups in a country. Higher scores mean more experts couldn't or wouldn't provide information. This indicates data quality issues, possibly because the topic is too sensitive or dangerous to discuss in that country.

nodes.label: Anti-Regime Activity
nodes.description: This measures the level of organized activity aimed at overthrowing or fundamentally changing the current political system. Higher values indicate more anti-regime movements and activities. Understanding anti-regime activity helps assess political stability and the legitimacy of current governing systems.

nodes.label: Pro-Regime Bias Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how often V-Dem experts were unable to answer questions about pro-regime bias in a country's political system. Higher values mean more missing data, indicating less reliable information about government favoritism. Good data coverage is important because it helps researchers and citizens understand how fairly political systems operate.

nodes.label: Pro-Regime Mobilization
nodes.description: Measures how much the government mobilizes citizens to actively support the current political regime through rallies, campaigns, or other activities. Higher values (0-4 scale) indicate more government efforts to generate public support. Excessive pro-regime mobilization can indicate authoritarian tendencies and limits genuine political choice for citizens.

nodes.label: Anti-Regime Activities Data Coverage
nodes.description: Measures how much data is missing when V-Dem experts were asked about anti-government activities in a country. Higher values mean more experts couldn't or didn't answer questions about this topic. Good data coverage helps researchers understand how governments respond to opposition.

nodes.label: Local Government Support Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how much survey data V-Dem collected about local government support and legitimacy. Higher values mean more experts didn't respond to questions about local government effectiveness in that country. This indicates data quality rather than actual government performance at the local level.

nodes.label: Local Government Support
nodes.description: This measures how much popular support and legitimacy local governments have among citizens in their communities. Higher values indicate stronger public trust and approval of local government performance. This affects whether local policies are accepted and whether communities cooperate with government initiatives.

nodes.label: Legislature: Service Provision Data Coverage
nodes.description: Tracks how often experts were unable to answer questions about whether legislators help constituents access government services. Higher scores mean more missing data, indicating less reliable information available. This measures data quality, not the actual service provision by legislators.

nodes.label: Legislature Staffing Data Availability
nodes.description: This measures how much data is missing from expert surveys about legislative staff and resources available to lawmakers. Higher scores mean more experts didn't respond to questions about legislative capacity. This is important because missing data makes it harder to assess whether legislators have adequate support to do their jobs effectively.

nodes.label: Legislature Committee System Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how much data is missing or unavailable about the legislature's committee system in expert surveys - it's about data quality, not the committees themselves. Lower non-response rates mean more complete information is available about how legislative committees operate. Good data coverage helps researchers and citizens better understand how their legislature functions.

nodes.label: Legislature Lower House Dissolution Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how often experts could not provide information about whether the legislature's lower house was dissolved by the executive. Higher values indicate more missing data, not better democracy. Good data coverage helps researchers and citizens understand how democratic institutions actually work.

nodes.label: Legislative Oversight Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how often V-Dem experts couldn't provide information about the legislature's ability to oversee government actions. Higher values indicate more gaps in data collection about parliamentary oversight powers. Complete data matters because legislative oversight is crucial for preventing government abuse of power and ensuring accountability.

nodes.label: Legislative Process Data Availability
nodes.description: This tracks how much data is missing about how laws are made and passed through the national legislature or parliament. Higher values mean experts had less information available to assess legislative procedures, indicating poor data coverage rather than poor legislative processes. Complete data helps researchers understand how well democratic lawmaking institutions function.

nodes.label: Legislature Funding Data Quality
nodes.description: This measures how often experts could not provide information about legislative funding when surveyed by V-Dem researchers. Higher scores mean more missing data, indicating less reliable information about how the legislature is funded. This is a data quality indicator, not a measure of actual legislative funding levels.

nodes.label: Legislature Voting Data Availability
nodes.description: Measures how much data is available about legislative voting procedures and transparency. This is a data quality indicator - higher scores mean experts had less information to assess legislative voting practices. This matters because transparent voting records help citizens hold their representatives accountable.

nodes.label: Legislature Question Time Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how much data is missing about legislative question time practices - when lawmakers can question government ministers. Higher values indicate more missing data, not better democratic practices. Good data coverage matters because it helps researchers and citizens understand how well legislatures hold governments accountable through questioning.

nodes.label: Legislature Dominance Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how much data is missing when V-Dem experts were asked about legislative dominance in a country. Higher values mean more experts didn't respond to the questions, indicating less reliable data coverage. Good data coverage is important because it helps us better understand how well a country's democratic institutions are functioning.

nodes.label: Legislature Disability Access Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how many experts answered questions about whether people with disabilities can participate in the national legislature (parliament or congress). Higher values mean fewer experts responded, indicating less reliable data. Good data helps track whether democratic institutions are accessible to citizens with disabilities.

nodes.label: Legislature Investigative Powers: Data Availability
nodes.description: This measures how many experts didn't provide information about the legislature's ability to investigate government actions, not the investigative powers themselves. Higher values indicate less data was available from expert surveys. This shows the completeness of information about legislative oversight capabilities in different countries.

nodes.label: Legislative Corruption Data Coverage
nodes.description: Measures how many experts declined to answer questions about corruption in the country's legislature or parliament. Higher scores mean less data availability, often because corruption is too sensitive or dangerous to discuss. This reflects the difficulty of gathering reliable information about government corruption.

nodes.label: Legislature: Corruption Level
nodes.description: Measures how corrupt members of the legislature are, including taking bribes or using office for personal gain. Higher scores indicate more legislative corruption. This matters because corrupt legislators prioritize personal profit over citizens' needs, leading to poor laws and wasted public money.

nodes.label: Legislative Corruption (Original Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This measures how much corruption exists among legislators (like bribery, vote-buying, or misuse of public funds), using the original scale that expert evaluators used. Higher scores typically indicate more corruption in the legislature. Low legislative corruption is crucial because it ensures lawmakers make decisions based on public interest rather than personal gain.

nodes.label: Legislature Funding Adequacy
nodes.description: This measures whether the national legislature (parliament or congress) has enough money and resources to do its job effectively, including conducting research, hiring staff, and carrying out oversight duties. The scale runs from 0-4, where higher values mean the legislature is better funded and more capable. Well-funded legislatures can better represent citizens' interests and check government power.

nodes.label: Legislative Service Delivery (Ranked Scale)
nodes.description: Measures how effectively the legislature serves citizens' needs and interests, presented on an ordered ranking scale. Higher values typically indicate the legislature better represents constituents, passes useful laws, and provides government oversight. Effective legislative service ensures citizens' concerns are addressed through the democratic process.

nodes.label: Legislature Funding Adequacy
nodes.description: This measures whether the national legislature (like Congress or Parliament) has enough money and resources to do its job effectively, including staff, research, and operations. Higher scores (0-4 scale) indicate the legislature is better funded and equipped to represent citizens and check government power. Well-funded legislatures are crucial for democracy because they can better investigate issues, write good laws, and hold leaders accountable.

nodes.label: Legislative Internal Bloc Cohesion
nodes.description: Measures whether members of the national legislature (like Congress or Parliament) vote together in organized groups or parties rather than as individuals. Higher scores indicate more party-based voting patterns. This matters because organized legislative blocs can more effectively represent different policy positions and check executive power.

nodes.label: Dominant Chamber of Legislature
nodes.description: Identifies which chamber or house of the legislature (like Senate vs. House of Representatives) has more power in making laws and governing. This helps understand how political power is distributed within a country's lawmaking body. This matters because the balance of power between legislative chambers affects how well different regions and groups are represented in government.

nodes.label: Constitutional Prohibition of Slavery
nodes.description: This measures whether a country's constitution explicitly prohibits slavery and forced labor. Values are typically yes/no or 0/1, where higher values indicate stronger constitutional protections against slavery. This reflects fundamental human rights protections and legal frameworks for personal freedom.

nodes.label: Constitutional Social Development Mandate
nodes.description: This measures whether a country's constitution requires the government to actively work on building social programs and improving citizens' welfare. Higher scores indicate stronger constitutional commitments to social development like healthcare, education, and poverty reduction. This matters because constitutional mandates can ensure governments prioritize improving living standards for all citizens, not just the wealthy.

nodes.label: Executive: Resource Control Data Coverage
nodes.description: Tracks how often experts were unable to answer questions about the executive branch's control over government resources and spending. Higher scores mean more missing data about executive resource control. This measures data quality, not the actual level of executive control over resources.

nodes.label: Executive Legitimacy Performance Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how often experts could not provide information about the executive branch's legitimacy and performance. Higher values indicate more missing data, not better executive performance. Complete data coverage helps citizens and researchers evaluate how well their government leaders are performing.

nodes.label: Executive Controls Legislature (Highest Level)
nodes.description: Measures whether the chief executive (president/prime minister) has the highest level of control over the legislature, meaning lawmakers rarely act independently. A value of 1 means this level of control exists, 0 means it doesn't. Strong executive control can limit democratic checks and balances that protect citizens' rights.

nodes.label: Executive Branch: Embezzlement and Theft
nodes.description: This measures how often members of the executive branch (president, prime minister, cabinet ministers) steal public money or resources for personal use. Higher values indicate more frequent embezzlement by top government officials. This matters because corruption reduces funding available for public services like schools, hospitals, and infrastructure that improve people's lives.

nodes.label: Executive Ideological Legitimacy Type
nodes.description: This measures a specific type (category 2) of ideological justification that the country's executive leadership uses to claim legitimate authority. This could relate to particular political philosophies or belief systems the government promotes. How leaders justify their authority affects public trust and political stability in the country.

nodes.label: Executive Embezzlement Data Coverage
nodes.description: This measures how many democracy experts chose not to answer or said they didn't know enough about executive embezzlement (stealing public funds) in a country. Higher values mean more experts couldn't provide ratings, indicating less reliable data. Good data coverage helps researchers and citizens better understand corruption levels.

nodes.label: Head of Government Gender
nodes.description: This records whether the head of government (like a prime minister or president) is male or female. This helps track women's representation in the highest levels of political leadership, which affects policy priorities and demonstrates equal opportunities in government.

nodes.label: Executive Legitimacy Ratio (Average Score)
nodes.description: Measures the ratio between how much legitimacy or public support the executive branch has versus other political institutions, averaged across expert assessments. Higher values suggest the executive has disproportionately more legitimacy compared to other branches of government. Balanced legitimacy across institutions matters because it prevents any one branch from becoming too powerful and undermining democratic checks and balances.

nodes.label: Executive Legitimacy Ideology (Data Availability)
nodes.description: Tracks missing expert responses about the ideological basis for executive power, rather than measuring legitimacy itself. Lower values indicate more experts answered questions about what ideas or beliefs justify the government's authority. Understanding the basis of government legitimacy helps explain political stability and citizen support for their leaders.

nodes.label: Executive Removal by Legislature (Category 2)
nodes.description: Measures a specific method or condition under which the legislature can remove executive officials from power. This represents one category from a broader question about legislative oversight powers. The ability of elected representatives to remove executives provides an important check on government power and helps ensure accountability to citizens.

nodes.label: Executive Legitimacy: Ideology-Based Claims (None)
nodes.description: This measures whether a country's executive leader does not use ideological claims to justify their right to rule (category 0 = no ideological legitimacy claims). Higher values indicate this type of legitimacy claim is absent. This matters because how leaders justify their power affects whether citizens accept their authority and policies.

nodes.label: Executive Power: Leader's Ideological Legitimacy
nodes.description: This measures how much the country's top leader bases their authority on a particular political ideology or belief system rather than elections or tradition. Higher scores indicate stronger ideological justification for power. This affects how leaders make decisions and whether they respond to public opinion or ideological principles.

nodes.label: Executive Legitimate Leadership (Average)
nodes.description: This measures the average level of legitimate authority and public acceptance that presidents or prime ministers have, calculated across regions or time periods. Higher scores indicate leaders have stronger legitimate authority and public support. Legitimate leadership helps ensure stable governance and public trust in democratic institutions.

nodes.label: Government Officials Taking Bribes
nodes.description: Measures how commonly government executives and their agents take bribes or other illegal payments in exchange for favors. Higher scores (0-4 scale) indicate less bribery and corruption. This matters because corruption wastes public resources and means government services may only go to those who can pay extra.

nodes.label: Executive Branch Officials Take Bribes (Original Scale)
nodes.description: Measures how commonly members of the executive branch (president, prime minister, cabinet members) accept bribes or other corrupt payments, on the original expert assessment scale. Higher values indicate more widespread corruption among top government officials. This matters because executive corruption wastes public resources and undermines trust in government institutions that provide essential services.

nodes.label: Executive Bribery
nodes.description: This measures how often members of the executive branch (president, prime minister, cabinet) give or receive bribes to influence policy decisions. Values typically range from 0-4, where higher scores indicate more frequent bribery. Lower bribery levels mean government decisions are more likely based on public interest rather than private payments, leading to better services for citizens.

nodes.label: Government Establishment Specialization
nodes.description: Measures how specialized and professional government institutions are in carrying out their specific functions. Higher scores indicate government agencies have clearer roles, better expertise, and more professional staff. Specialized government institutions deliver better public services and make more effective policies that improve people's lives.

nodes.label: Upper House Seats in Parliament
nodes.description: This counts the total number of seats in a country's upper house of parliament (like the U.S. Senate). Higher numbers simply mean more representatives in the upper chamber. This matters because it shows how legislative power is distributed and how many elected officials represent citizens at the national level.

nodes.label: Government Effectiveness Score
nodes.description: This measures how well a country's government creates and implements good policies and delivers public services. Higher scores indicate more effective governments that are better at running the country and serving their citizens. Effective government matters because it leads to better public services like healthcare, education, and infrastructure that improve people's daily lives.

nodes.label: Government Presence and Capacity
nodes.description: This measures how present and capable the government is throughout the country, including its ability to provide services and maintain order in all regions. Higher scores indicate stronger government presence and capacity. Strong government presence matters because it ensures all citizens can access public services and legal protection regardless of where they live.

nodes.label: Effective Number of Political Parties
nodes.description: Measures how many political parties actually have meaningful influence in a country's government, accounting for their relative strength. Higher numbers indicate more parties share power, while lower numbers suggest dominance by fewer parties. This matters because multiple competing parties can better represent diverse citizen interests and prevent any single group from becoming too powerful.

nodes.label: Average Capital Returns on Residential Property
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from owning residential properties, such as rental income and property value increases. Higher returns mean property owners are making more money from their real estate investments. This matters because property returns affect housing affordability and wealth building opportunities for both owners and renters.

nodes.label: Average Agricultural Value Added
nodes.description: This measures the average economic value created by farming, fishing, and forestry activities across all income groups in a country. Higher values indicate agriculture contributes more to the economy per person. This matters because agricultural productivity affects food security, rural incomes, and overall economic development in many countries.

nodes.label: Agricultural Land Under Irrigated Crop Requirements
nodes.description: This measures how much farmland needs irrigation systems to grow crops successfully. Higher values indicate more land requires artificial watering rather than relying on rainfall. Proper irrigation is crucial for food security, especially in dry regions where crops might otherwise fail.

nodes.label: Agricultural Land Use Ratio
nodes.description: This measures how efficiently a country uses its agricultural land for food production relative to its total available farmland. Higher values typically indicate more intensive or productive use of agricultural resources. This matters because efficient agricultural land use helps ensure food security and supports rural livelihoods.

nodes.label: Government Internal Autonomy
nodes.description: Measures how much freedom the national government has to make decisions without interference from other powerful groups like the military, religious leaders, or foreign governments. Higher values mean the elected government has more independence to govern, while lower values suggest outside forces heavily influence government decisions. This matters because it affects whether elected leaders can actually deliver on their promises to voters.

nodes.label: Terrorist Monitoring of Citizens
nodes.description: Measures the extent to which terrorist or extremist groups monitor and track citizens' activities and communications within a country. Higher values (0-4 scale) indicate more extensive monitoring by non-state terrorist organizations. This matters because terrorist surveillance creates fear, restricts freedom, and can lead to violence against civilians going about their daily lives.

nodes.label: Liberal Democracy Index
nodes.description: This is V-Dem's comprehensive measure of liberal democracy, combining free elections with protection of individual rights and rule of law. Higher scores (0-1 scale) indicate stronger liberal democratic institutions and practices. Liberal democracy matters because it protects both majority rule and minority rights, ensuring everyone has political voice and personal freedoms.

nodes.label: Legislative-Executive Relations in Direct Democracy
nodes.description: Measures the relationship between legislative and executive branches specifically in the context of direct democratic processes like referendums. Higher values indicate more balanced power sharing in direct democracy mechanisms. Balanced institutional relationships ensure that direct democracy tools serve citizens rather than being manipulated by any single branch of government.

nodes.label: State Territory Control Data Coverage
nodes.description: This tracks how many experts declined to answer questions about whether the government controls all of its territory or faces challenges from armed groups or separatist movements. Higher non-response rates may indicate sensitive security situations or limited expert knowledge. Good data coverage helps assess state stability and security.

nodes.label: Government Corruption Index
nodes.description: This measures the overall level of corruption in government institutions and public officials. Higher scores typically indicate lower levels of corruption (less corrupt government). This matters because corruption wastes public resources and reduces citizens' trust in government and public services.

nodes.label: Direct Democracy: Legislative Referendum Process
nodes.description: This measures whether citizens can directly vote on laws through referendums, where the public votes to accept or reject legislation passed by lawmakers. Higher values indicate stronger citizen power to override legislative decisions through direct voting. This gives ordinary people more direct control over the laws that govern their daily lives.

nodes.label: Egalitarian Democracy Index
nodes.description: Measures how well a country achieves equal political participation across different social groups, ensuring that wealth, gender, race, or social status don't determine political influence. Higher scores indicate more equal democracy where all citizens have similar political power. This matters because unequal political systems often ignore the needs of disadvantaged groups.

nodes.label: Educational Competition (Comprehensive Measure)
nodes.description: This measures the level of competition and choice in a country's education system, including both public and private options. Higher values indicate more educational competition and alternatives for students and families. Greater educational competition can lead to improved school quality and better learning outcomes for students.

nodes.label: Deliberative Democracy Index
nodes.description: Combines multiple measures to show how well a country's political system encourages thoughtful discussion and debate before making important decisions. Higher values indicate politicians and citizens engage in respectful dialogue and consider different viewpoints, while lower values suggest decisions are made without meaningful consultation. This matters because better deliberation leads to policies that work better for everyone.

nodes.label: Overall Democracy Level
nodes.description: A composite score combining multiple measures to classify countries as closed autocracies, electoral autocracies, electoral democracies, or liberal democracies. Higher scores (0-3 scale) indicate more democratic governance with free elections, civil liberties, and checks on power. This matters because democratic countries typically provide better protection of rights and more responsive government.

nodes.label: Executive Party Control Index
nodes.description: This composite index measures how much the ruling political party controls or influences the executive branch of government. Higher scores indicate stronger party control over executive decisions and appointments. Balanced party influence helps ensure government serves broader public interests rather than just partisan goals.

nodes.label: Local Election Quality Index
nodes.description: This combines multiple factors to measure how free, fair, and competitive local elections are in a country. Higher values indicate that local elections are well-run with genuine competition and voter choice, while lower values suggest problems like fraud, restrictions, or lack of real competition. Quality local elections ensure communities can choose their own leaders and hold them accountable.

nodes.label: Free and Fair Elections Index
nodes.description: This composite index measures how free and fair national elections are, including whether campaigns are conducted fairly, votes are counted accurately, and results are respected. Values range from 0-1, where higher scores indicate more free and fair elections. Free and fair elections ensure citizens can choose their leaders and hold them accountable for their performance.

nodes.label: Liberal Democracy Index
nodes.description: Measures how well a country protects individual rights and limits government power through institutions like independent courts, free press, and constitutional constraints. Higher scores indicate stronger liberal democratic institutions. This matters because liberal democracy protects people from government abuse and ensures leaders cannot easily violate citizens' basic freedoms.

nodes.label: Liberal Democracy Index
nodes.description: Measures how well a country protects individual rights and limits government power through laws and institutions. Scores range from 0 to 4, with higher values indicating stronger protection of personal freedoms and constitutional limits on authority. Liberal democracy matters because it prevents government abuse and protects citizens' fundamental rights and freedoms.

nodes.label: Political Party Strength Index
nodes.description: This measures how well-organized and institutionalized political parties are in a country's democratic system. Higher scores (on a 0-1 scale) indicate stronger, more stable political parties that can effectively represent citizens' interests. Strong political parties are important because they help organize democratic competition and give voters clear choices.

nodes.label: Political Party Strength Index
nodes.description: This measures how well-developed and stable the political party system is in a country, rating factors like party organization and voter loyalty. Higher scores indicate stronger, more institutionalized political parties that provide clearer choices for voters. Strong party systems help create more predictable governance and better representation of citizen interests.

nodes.label: Local Election Quality Index
nodes.description: Measures how free, fair, and competitive local elections are in a country. The scale runs from 0 to 4, where higher scores mean better local democratic processes with genuine competition and voter choice. Strong local elections matter because they give communities a real voice in decisions that directly affect their daily lives.

nodes.label: Local Election Quality Index
nodes.description: This measures how free, fair, and competitive local elections are in a country. Higher scores (on a 0-1 scale) indicate better-quality local elections with genuine voter choice and fair procedures. Good local elections matter because they ensure communities can choose their own leaders and hold local officials accountable.

nodes.label: Local Election Quality Index
nodes.description: This measures the quality and fairness of local elections in a country, looking at factors like whether elections are free, fair, and competitive. Higher scores mean local elections are more democratic and trustworthy. Fair local elections matter because they give citizens a real voice in choosing leaders who make decisions about schools, roads, and services in their communities.

nodes.label: Civil Society Participation Index
nodes.description: Measures how much civil society organizations (like charities, advocacy groups, and community organizations) can freely operate and influence politics. Scores range from 0 to 4, with higher values meaning civil society groups have more space to work without government interference. A vibrant civil society helps ensure government serves people's needs and interests.

nodes.label: Liberal Democracy Index
nodes.description: This measures how well a country combines democratic elections with protection of individual rights and freedoms, including minority rights and rule of law. Higher scores (on a 0-1 scale) indicate stronger liberal democratic institutions. This is important because liberal democracy protects both majority rule and individual freedoms.

nodes.label: Public Sector Corruption Level
nodes.description: This measures how much corruption exists in government offices and public services, including bribery, misuse of public money, and abuse of power. Lower scores indicate less corruption and cleaner government. Reducing corruption matters because it means public money goes to schools, hospitals, and roads instead of politicians' pockets.

nodes.label: Democratic Deliberation Index
nodes.description: Measures the quality of public debate and discussion in political decision-making processes. Scores range from 0 to 2, where higher values indicate more thoughtful, reasoned, and respectful political dialogue. Good deliberation leads to better policies because it ensures decisions are based on evidence and consider different viewpoints.

nodes.label: Deliberative Democracy Index
nodes.description: This measures how much a country's political system encourages respectful debate, compromise, and reasoned discussion in making decisions. Higher scores (on a 0-1 scale) indicate more deliberative democracy where different views are heard and considered. This matters because deliberative processes lead to better policies and reduce political polarization.

nodes.label: Deliberative Democracy Index
nodes.description: This measures the quality of public debate and discussion in political decision-making, including whether different viewpoints are heard and respected. The index ranges from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate more thoughtful, inclusive political discussions. Good deliberative democracy matters because it leads to better-informed decisions that consider the needs and perspectives of all citizens.

nodes.label: Deliberation in Legislature
nodes.description: This measures the quality of debate and discussion within a country's legislature, including whether lawmakers engage in respectful dialogue and consider different viewpoints. The index ranges from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate better deliberation. Quality legislative debate is important because it leads to better laws that are more carefully thought through and consider various perspectives.

nodes.label: Mobile Phone Subscriptions per 100 People
nodes.description: This measures how many mobile phone subscriptions exist for every 100 people in a country. The number can exceed 100 when people have multiple phones or accounts. Higher numbers indicate better communication infrastructure and technology access, which helps people connect with family, access information, and participate in the modern economy.

nodes.label: Broadband Internet Subscribers
nodes.description: This counts the number of people with high-speed internet connections per 100 residents. Higher numbers indicate better internet infrastructure and greater digital access across the population. More broadband access improves education opportunities, enables remote work, and helps people access government services and healthcare information online.

nodes.label: Internet Expenditure
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money spent on internet services in a country, typically expressed in current US dollars. Higher values indicate greater investment in digital infrastructure and internet usage. More internet spending often leads to better connectivity and digital services that improve education, business opportunities, and access to information.

nodes.label: Male Employment Rate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of working-age men (usually 15-64 years old) have jobs. The rate is expressed as a percentage, where higher values mean more men are working. Higher male employment rates indicate a strong economy with job opportunities and contribute to family income and economic stability.

nodes.label: Net Migration Rate
nodes.description: This measures the difference between people moving into a country and people leaving, usually per 1,000 residents. Positive values mean more people are moving in than leaving, while negative values mean more are leaving. Countries with positive migration often have strong economies and opportunities, while negative migration may indicate economic or political challenges.

nodes.label: Birth Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many babies are born per 1,000 people in a country each year. Values typically range from about 8 to 50 births per 1,000 people. Very high birth rates can strain resources and services, while very low rates may indicate an aging population that could face future economic challenges.

nodes.label: Telephone Subscriptions
nodes.description: This measures the number of telephone lines (landline and/or mobile) per 100 people in a country. Values can exceed 100 when people have multiple devices. Higher values indicate better communication infrastructure. Good telephone access helps with business development, emergency services, and keeping families connected.

nodes.label: Power Plant Nitrous Oxide Emissions
nodes.description: This measures how much nitrous oxide pollution power plants release into the atmosphere each year, converted to an equivalent amount of carbon dioxide for comparison. Higher numbers mean more greenhouse gas emissions that contribute to climate change. This matters because these emissions affect air quality and global warming, impacting everyone's health and environment.

nodes.label: Methane Pollution from Transportation
nodes.description: This measures methane gas emissions from cars, trucks, ships, planes, and trains, converted to an equivalent amount of carbon dioxide pollution for comparison. Higher values indicate more greenhouse gas pollution from the transportation sector contributing to climate change. This matters because reducing these emissions is essential for protecting the environment and preventing harmful climate change that affects everyone's future.

nodes.label: Methane Emissions from Power Plants
nodes.description: This measures how much methane gas is released into the atmosphere each year from electricity and heat generation, converted to equivalent carbon dioxide impact in million tons. Lower values are better for the environment since methane is a powerful greenhouse gas that contributes to climate change. Reducing these emissions helps countries meet climate goals and protect air quality.

nodes.label: CO2 emissions from transportation
nodes.description: This measures carbon dioxide pollution from all forms of transportation - cars, trucks, planes, trains, and ships - measured in millions of tons per year. Higher numbers mean more transport-related pollution contributing to climate change. This matters because transportation emissions affect air quality and climate, impacting public health and the environment.

nodes.label: Percentage of People with Electricity Access
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's population has access to electricity in their homes or communities. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better for quality of life. Access to electricity is essential for modern living, enabling education, healthcare, communication, and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Urban Population with Electricity Access
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of people living in cities and towns have access to electricity in their homes or communities. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better. This matters because electricity access is essential for modern life, affecting everything from lighting and cooking to communication, education, and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Rural Population with Electricity Access
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of people living in rural areas have access to electricity in their homes and communities. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better. This matters because electricity access is essential for education, healthcare, communication, and economic opportunities that improve quality of life.

nodes.label: Electricity from Clean Energy Sources
nodes.description: This measures how much electricity is generated from renewable sources like solar, wind, water, and biomass, expressed in gigawatt-hours (GWh). Higher values indicate a country relies more on clean energy that doesn't pollute the air or contribute to climate change. Clean energy helps protect the environment and can reduce electricity costs over time.

nodes.label: Total Electricity Generation
nodes.description: This measures how many gigawatt-hours of electricity all power plants in a country produce in a year. Higher numbers indicate more electricity available for homes, businesses, and industry. Adequate electricity generation is essential for economic development, modern living standards, and access to technology.

nodes.label: Government Energy Consumption
nodes.description: This measures how much energy the government uses for its operations, measured in gigawatt hours (a very large unit of electricity). Higher values mean government buildings, services, and operations consume more energy. This matters because government energy use affects both public spending on utilities and the country's overall environmental impact.

nodes.label: Clean Energy Share of Electricity
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of a country's electricity comes from renewable sources like solar, wind, or water power instead of fossil fuels. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean cleaner, more sustainable energy. Countries with higher renewable energy shares have less air pollution and contribute less to climate change.

nodes.label: Coal Industry Profits (% of GDP)
nodes.description: This measures how much profit the coal mining industry generates compared to the country's total economic output. It's calculated as the difference between what coal sells for on world markets and what it costs to mine. Higher percentages mean coal mining contributes more to the national economy, though this also indicates greater dependence on fossil fuel industries.

nodes.label: Airline Passengers Carried
nodes.description: This counts the total number of passengers who flew on airlines registered in the country, including both domestic and international flights. Higher numbers generally indicate better transportation infrastructure and economic activity. Good air transport connections support tourism, business, and personal mobility, helping people access opportunities and services that improve their lives.

nodes.label: Air Freight Volume
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of cargo transported by air, calculated as tons of freight multiplied by kilometers traveled. Higher values indicate more air freight activity, which can signal economic trade and connectivity but also higher transportation costs and emissions. Strong air freight networks support international business but require balancing economic benefits with environmental impacts.

nodes.label: Airline Departures by National Carriers
nodes.description: This counts how many flights take off worldwide by airlines registered in a specific country, including both domestic and international departures. Higher numbers indicate larger national airline industries and more air travel connectivity. This matters because air transport connects people to jobs, education, and family while supporting tourism and business that boost economic growth.

nodes.label: Manufactured Goods as Share of Imports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imported products are manufactured items like machinery, chemicals, and consumer goods rather than raw materials. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages typically indicating more advanced economic development and consumer purchasing power. Countries importing more manufactured goods often have populations with higher living standards and more diverse consumer needs.

nodes.label: Manufactured Goods as Share of Total Exports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's exports are manufactured products like machinery, chemicals, and processed goods rather than raw materials like crops or minerals. Higher percentages generally indicate a more developed, diversified economy. This matters because countries that export more manufactured goods typically have higher-paying jobs and more stable economies.

nodes.label: Export earnings (seasonally adjusted)
nodes.description: This tracks the total value of goods a country sells to other nations, measured in millions of US dollars and adjusted for seasonal patterns like harvest cycles. Higher values indicate stronger export performance and more foreign currency earnings. Strong exports help countries afford imports and invest in development.

nodes.label: Value of Goods Exported
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of physical goods (like cars, food, or electronics) that a country sells to other countries each year, in millions of US dollars. Higher values mean the country exports more products and earns more money from international trade. Strong exports help create jobs and boost a country's economy.

nodes.label: Value of imported goods
nodes.description: This measures the total value of physical goods (like cars, machinery, food, and clothing) that a country imports from other countries, measured in millions of current US dollars. Higher values can indicate strong domestic demand and purchasing power, or dependence on foreign products. The impact on quality of life depends on whether these imports provide essential goods or crowd out domestic production.

nodes.label: Imports from Middle East & North Africa as Share of Total Imports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imported goods come from developing countries in the Middle East and North Africa region. Higher percentages indicate stronger trade relationships with this region, which can affect economic partnerships and cultural exchange.

nodes.label: Merchandise Imports (Seasonally Adjusted)
nodes.description: This tracks the total value of physical goods (like cars, food, electronics) that a country buys from other countries each month, adjusted to remove predictable seasonal patterns. Values are in millions of US dollars, and higher numbers mean more imports. This matters because it shows how much a country depends on foreign goods and affects jobs and prices for consumers.

nodes.label: Imports as Percentage of Economy
nodes.description: This shows how much a country spends on foreign goods and services compared to the size of its entire economy. Higher percentages mean the country relies more heavily on imports for consumption and business needs. This matters because heavy import dependence can make a country vulnerable to supply disruptions and affect local job creation.

nodes.label: Money Sent to Other Countries
nodes.description: This tracks how much money flows out of a country when residents send money to family or friends in other countries, measured in millions of US dollars. Higher values mean more money is leaving the country through these personal transfers. This matters because large outflows can indicate many citizens working abroad to support families, or it might show economic connections between countries.

nodes.label: Transportation Services Imported (% of Service Imports)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of all imported services consists of transportation services like shipping, air transport, and postal services. This shows how much countries rely on foreign companies for moving goods and people. Efficient transportation services are essential for trade and travel, connecting countries to global markets and opportunities.

nodes.label: Transportation services as share of service exports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's service exports come from transportation activities like shipping, airlines, trucking, and postal services. Higher percentages indicate the country earns more foreign income from moving people and goods. Countries with strong transportation service exports often have strategic locations or well-developed logistics industries that support economic growth.

nodes.label: Transportation Services as Share of Service Imports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imported services consists of transportation services like shipping, air transport, and postal services. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages indicating greater reliance on foreign transportation providers. Countries with good domestic transportation networks typically import fewer of these services.

nodes.label: Tourism Revenue Share of Service Exports
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of a country's service exports comes from tourism and travel-related spending by foreign visitors. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean tourism is a bigger part of the economy. Countries with higher tourism shares often have more jobs in hotels, restaurants, and entertainment industries.

nodes.label: Travel Services Share of Service Exports (%)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's service exports comes from tourism and travel-related services like hotels, restaurants, and tour guides serving foreign visitors. Higher percentages indicate the country relies more heavily on tourism for foreign income. Strong tourism can provide jobs and economic growth, especially for developing countries.

nodes.label: Technology Services Imports Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's imported services comes from communications, computers, and information technology. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages mean the country relies more on imported tech services rather than producing them domestically. This matters because it shows how dependent a country is on foreign technology expertise, which affects economic competitiveness and innovation capacity.

nodes.label: Technical Assistance Grants Received
nodes.description: This measures the dollar amount of free technical help and expertise that a country receives from other countries or international organizations. These grants don't need to be paid back and focus on transferring knowledge, skills, and technology. Higher amounts indicate more international support for building the country's capabilities, which helps improve government services and economic development.

nodes.label: Commercial Service Imports
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of commercial services (like banking, insurance, telecommunications, and business consulting) that a country buys from other countries. Higher values can indicate either a growing economy needing more services or lack of domestic service capabilities. Imported services help businesses operate efficiently and give consumers access to specialized services.

nodes.label: Total imports of goods and services
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of everything a country buys from other countries - both physical goods and services like tourism or banking. Higher values mean more international purchasing. This matters because imports can provide access to products, technology, and services that aren't available locally, potentially improving living standards.

nodes.label: Money Spent on Service Imports
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country spends buying services (like banking, tourism, or shipping) from other countries, shown in US dollars. Higher values mean the country is purchasing more services from abroad, which could indicate either strong economic activity or dependence on foreign services. This matters because it shows how connected a country's economy is to the global marketplace and affects the country's trade balance.

nodes.label: Money Earned from Exports
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country earns by selling physical goods (like crops, manufactured products, or raw materials) to other countries, shown in US dollars. Higher values indicate a country is successful at producing and selling products internationally. This matters because export earnings provide foreign currency that countries need to buy imports, pay international debts, and fund development projects.

nodes.label: Service Exports Revenue
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country earns by selling services like tourism, banking, consulting, or transportation to other countries, in US dollars. Higher values mean the country is more competitive in the global service economy. Strong service exports create jobs and bring foreign currency into the country.

nodes.label: Industrial output value
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of output from all industries including manufacturing, mining, construction, and utilities, adjusted for inflation using 2015 prices. Higher values indicate a larger, more productive industrial sector. Strong industry provides jobs and helps countries build wealth and economic stability.

nodes.label: Industrial Sector Output (Local Currency)
nodes.description: This measures the total economic value created by all industrial activities including manufacturing, mining, construction, and utilities, expressed in the country's own currency. Higher values indicate a larger and more productive industrial sector. A strong industrial sector typically provides jobs, exports, and economic growth that supports higher living standards.

nodes.label: Manufacturing Economic Output
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value created by all manufacturing activities in a country, such as making cars, electronics, clothing, and processed foods. Higher values indicate a stronger manufacturing sector. A robust manufacturing industry provides jobs, exports, and economic diversification that can improve living standards and reduce dependence on raw material exports.

nodes.label: Manufacturing Output Value
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of goods produced by manufacturing industries like factories making cars, electronics, or processed foods, adjusted for inflation using 2015 prices. Higher values indicate a stronger manufacturing sector. A robust manufacturing industry typically provides more jobs and contributes to higher living standards through economic growth.

nodes.label: Money supply as share of economy
nodes.description: This measures all the money and easily-spent financial assets in a country compared to the size of its economy, shown as a percentage. Higher percentages mean more money is available relative to economic output. This matters because the money supply affects inflation, lending, and economic stability that impact everyone's financial well-being.

nodes.label: Financial system deposits as share of economy (%)
nodes.description: This measures how much money people and businesses have deposited in banks and other financial institutions compared to the country's total economic output. Higher percentages suggest people trust and use the banking system more, which helps the economy grow by making it easier to save money and get loans.

nodes.label: Banking System Liquid Assets
nodes.description: This measures the total value of easily accessible money and assets in a country's banking system, in constant 2000 US dollars. Higher values indicate a larger, more liquid financial system that can better support lending and economic activity. A robust banking system with liquid assets helps businesses and individuals access credit and financial services.

nodes.label: Overall Price Inflation Rate
nodes.description: This measures how much prices across the entire economy increased compared to the previous year, expressed as a percentage. Moderate positive values (2-4%) are generally healthy, while very high or negative values can indicate economic problems. This matters because inflation affects the cost of living and people's purchasing power - high inflation makes everything more expensive and reduces what families can afford.

nodes.label: Consumer Price Index (Not Seasonally Adjusted)
nodes.description: This tracks how much the average cost of everyday goods and services changes over time, like groceries, gas, and housing. Higher numbers mean prices are rising (inflation), making things more expensive for families. Stable, moderate price increases indicate a healthy economy, while rapid increases hurt purchasing power.

nodes.label: Government Spending Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total economic output (GDP) comes from government spending on goods and services. Values are typically expressed as percentages where higher values mean government plays a larger role in the economy. This shows the balance between government and private sector activity in providing jobs and services.

nodes.label: GDP Component: Financial Services Interest
nodes.description: This measures how much financial services and interest payments contribute to a country's total economic output (GDP). Higher values indicate that banking, insurance, and financial activities make up a larger share of the economy. This matters because it shows how important the financial sector is to the country's overall economic health and job creation.

nodes.label: Total Government Spending
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of money a government spends on everything, including salaries, infrastructure, social programs, defense, and debt payments. Values are typically in billions of dollars or as a percentage of the country's total economic output, and the optimal level varies by country needs. This is important because government spending directly affects public services, economic stability, and citizens' quality of life.

nodes.label: Government Spending on GDP
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on public services, infrastructure, and other activities as part of the country's total economic output. Higher percentages indicate governments play a larger role in the economy through spending on things like schools, roads, and healthcare. This affects the quality and availability of public services that citizens receive.

nodes.label: Currency exchange rate
nodes.description: This shows how many units of local currency equal one US dollar on average during the year. The number varies by country - for example, 100 Japanese yen or 0.85 euros per dollar. This rate affects how expensive imports are and how competitive exports are in global markets.

nodes.label: Currency Exchange Rate (Historical)
nodes.description: This shows how many units of a country's old currency equaled one US dollar on average, especially useful when countries have changed their currency. Higher numbers typically mean the local currency is weaker against the dollar. Stable exchange rates help maintain predictable international trade and investment, supporting economic growth and price stability for consumers.

nodes.label: Currency Exchange Rate (Historical)
nodes.description: This shows how many units of a country's currency equal one US dollar, with historical data adjusted for currency changes. Higher numbers mean the local currency is weaker compared to the dollar, while lower numbers mean it's stronger. This matters because exchange rates affect the cost of imports, exports, and international travel, directly impacting prices of goods and the country's economic competitiveness.

nodes.label: Currency Exchange Rate to US Dollar
nodes.description: This shows how many units of a country's currency equal one US dollar on average during the year (for example, 100 yen = 1 dollar). The number itself isn't good or bad, but it affects how expensive imports and exports are. Stable exchange rates help businesses plan and trade with other countries more easily.

nodes.label: Currency Exchange Rate with China
nodes.description: This shows how much local currency equals one Chinese yuan at current market exchange rates. A higher number means the local currency is weaker against the yuan. This matters because it affects the cost of trade with China, influencing prices of Chinese imports and the competitiveness of local exports to China.

nodes.label: Trade Balance in Goods and Services
nodes.description: This measures whether a country exports more than it imports (or vice versa) by calculating the total dollar value of all goods and services sold abroad minus those bought from other countries. Positive values mean the country exports more than it imports (trade surplus), while negative values mean it imports more than it exports (trade deficit). A trade balance helps show whether a country is earning money from international trade, which affects its overall economic health and ability to pay for foreign goods.

nodes.label: Trade Balance in Goods and Services
nodes.description: This measures whether a country exports more than it imports by subtracting total imports from total exports of goods and services, shown in the country's own currency. Positive values mean the country exports more than it imports (trade surplus), while negative values mean it imports more (trade deficit). A balanced trade relationship generally supports economic stability and growth.

nodes.label: Net Foreign Assets (Local Currency)
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country's banks and government have invested abroad minus what they owe to other countries, shown in the country's own currency. Higher values mean the country is a net lender to the world, while negative values mean it owes more than it owns internationally. This matters because it shows whether a country is financially dependent on others or has the resources to weather economic storms.

nodes.label: Business Loan Share
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of all loans in a country go to businesses (rather than to individuals or government). Higher percentages mean more credit is flowing to companies for investment and growth. This is important because business lending supports job creation, innovation, and economic expansion that benefits everyone.

nodes.label: Students Changing Lower Secondary Schools
nodes.description: This measures the rate at which lower secondary students (typically ages 12-14) move between schools or educational systems. Very high mobility rates can indicate problems like economic instability or poor school quality, while very low rates might suggest limited educational options. Moderate mobility can be normal and healthy for student development.

nodes.label: Students Changing Lower Secondary Schools
nodes.description: This measures the rate at which lower secondary students (typically ages 12-14) move between schools or educational systems. Very high mobility rates can indicate problems like economic instability or poor school quality, while very low rates might suggest limited educational options. Moderate mobility can be normal and healthy for student development.

nodes.label: Fixed telephone lines per 100 people
nodes.description: This counts how many traditional landline phones, including business phone systems, exist for every 100 people in a country. Higher numbers historically indicated better communication infrastructure, though mobile phones have largely replaced landlines in most places today.

nodes.label: Number of Landline Phone Connections
nodes.description: This counts all working landline telephone connections in a country, including traditional phones, internet-based calling, and wireless landlines. Higher numbers indicate more communication infrastructure, though this has become less important as mobile phones have grown. This still matters for emergency services, business communications, and internet access in areas where mobile service is unreliable.

nodes.label: Average Government Spending Per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government spends per person on public services like education, healthcare, infrastructure, and social programs. Higher values typically mean better public services and more government investment in citizens' well-being. This spending directly affects quality of life through schools, hospitals, roads, and safety programs.

nodes.label: Average Government Spending Per Household
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government spends per household on public services like schools, hospitals, roads, and social programs. Higher values generally indicate more government investment in public services that benefit families. This spending affects daily life through better infrastructure, education, healthcare, and community services.

nodes.label: Average Government Spending per Household
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on behalf of each household for public services like education, healthcare, infrastructure, and social programs. Values are in local currency per household per year, and higher amounts mean more government investment in public services. This matters because government spending on public services directly affects the quality of schools, hospitals, roads, and safety that families depend on.

nodes.label: Typical Government Spending Per Person
nodes.description: This shows the median amount of government spending per individual, meaning half of people receive more government spending and half receive less. Higher values indicate more government investment per person in public services, benefits, and programs. This matters because government spending on individuals directly affects access to education, healthcare, social services, and other programs that improve quality of life.

nodes.label: Median Interest Payments on Government Debt
nodes.description: This shows the typical amount a country pays in interest on money it has borrowed, with half of payments above and half below this amount. Higher values mean the government pays more to service its debt, measured in local currency. Lower interest payments mean more government money can go to schools, hospitals, and other services instead of debt payments.

nodes.label: Median Recreation and Entertainment Spending
nodes.description: This measures the middle amount that people in a country spend on entertainment, sports, hobbies, and recreational activities. Values are shown in local currency, and higher values mean people have more money available for fun activities after covering basic needs. This matters because it indicates how much discretionary income families have for improving their quality of life.

nodes.label: Median Military Spending per Person
nodes.description: This measures the middle amount that gets spent on defense and military expenses for each person in the country. Values are shown in local currency, and higher values mean more resources go toward national defense per capita. This matters because it shows how much of a country's resources are dedicated to security versus other public needs like healthcare or education.

nodes.label: Average Net Surplus of Household Non-Profit Institutions
nodes.description: This measures the average financial surplus (money left over after expenses) of non-profit organizations that serve households, like charities and community groups. Higher values mean these organizations have more resources available. Strong non-profits provide important services and support to communities.

nodes.label: Average Government Retirement Benefits
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of retirement benefits (like pensions or social security) that the government provides to retirees, adjusted to 1992 price levels to account for inflation. Higher values mean more generous retirement support. This matters because adequate retirement benefits help ensure older adults can maintain their quality of life after they stop working.

nodes.label: Average Defense Spending per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on military and defense for each person in the country. The amount is in local currency, with higher values indicating more military spending per capita. Higher defense spending can provide security but may mean less money available for education, healthcare, and other social programs.

nodes.label: Average Defense Spending per Person (Adults 20+)
nodes.description: This measures how much the government spends on military and defense for each adult aged 20 and older in the country. The amount is in local currency, with higher values indicating more military spending per adult. Higher defense spending can provide security but may mean less money available for education, healthcare, and other social programs that benefit adults.

nodes.label: Median Home Value per Person
nodes.description: This measures the middle value of housing wealth that people own, including the market value of homes and real estate. Values are shown in local currency, and higher values mean people have more valuable housing assets. This matters because housing is typically the largest component of family wealth and affects financial security and living standards.

nodes.label: Average Housing Value per Adult (1992 Prices)
nodes.description: This measures the average value of housing assets owned by adults aged 20 and older, adjusted to 1992 price levels to account for inflation. Higher values mean people own more valuable homes on average, indicating greater housing wealth and property market strength. This is important because housing is typically a household's largest asset and represents long-term financial security.

nodes.label: Housing Capital Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average value of housing and residential buildings available per person in a country, including homes, apartments, and other places people live. Higher values mean there is more valuable housing available for each person. This matters because adequate housing is essential for health, safety, and overall quality of life.

nodes.label: Housing Capital Growth Distribution
nodes.description: This measures how housing wealth (like home values and real estate investments) is distributed among different income groups over time. Higher values may indicate greater concentration of housing wealth among certain groups. This matters because housing is often people's biggest asset, and how it's distributed affects overall wealth inequality.

nodes.label: Total National Wealth
nodes.description: This measures a country's total wealth by adding up all its produced goods (like buildings and machines), natural resources, human skills and knowledge, and foreign investments, measured in 2019 US dollars. Higher values mean a country has more total wealth and resources available. This matters because wealthier nations typically can provide better living standards, infrastructure, and opportunities for their citizens.

nodes.label: Total National Wealth Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the combined value of all a country's assets (infrastructure, natural resources, and human skills) divided by population. Higher values indicate greater overall wealth per person, which typically means better opportunities for economic growth and improved living standards.

nodes.label: Average Property Value Per Household
nodes.description: This measures the average value of property (like houses, land, and other real estate) owned by households. Higher values mean families own more valuable property, which represents wealth and financial security. Property ownership helps families build wealth over time and provides stability through homeownership and investment assets.

nodes.label: Average Household Investment
nodes.description: This measures how much money the typical household invests in things like stocks, bonds, real estate, or business equipment each year. Values are in local currency, and higher amounts mean households are putting more money into investments that could grow over time. This is important because household investment helps build long-term wealth and funds economic growth.

nodes.label: Average Property Investment Gains
nodes.description: This measures the average profits people make from property investments like real estate or other assets. Higher values indicate that property investments are generating more income or increasing in value. Property gains can show economic health but very high values might also indicate inequality if only wealthy people can afford to invest.

nodes.label: Average Property Investment Gains by Government
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government makes on average from property and real estate investments. Higher values mean the government earns more from its property holdings. These earnings can be used to fund public services like schools and hospitals.

nodes.label: Average Property Income Gains
nodes.description: This measures the average increase in income that people earn from owning property, investments, or other assets over time. Higher values mean people are earning more money from their investments and property ownership. This matters because property income can provide financial security and help reduce poverty, especially for families who have been able to build wealth over time.

nodes.label: Average Property Investment Gains
nodes.description: This tracks the average financial returns people earn from property and capital investments over time. Higher values indicate better investment returns, which can increase wealth inequality if only some people own property. This measure helps understand how investment income contributes to overall economic inequality.

nodes.label: Government Housing Sector Contribution to Income
nodes.description: This measures how much the government's involvement in housing (through public housing, subsidies, and housing programs) contributes to the country's total national income. Higher values mean government housing activities make up a larger share of economic activity. This matters because it shows how much the government supports housing affordability and availability for its citizens.

nodes.label: Government's Economic Contribution to National Income
nodes.description: This measures how much the government sector contributes to the country's total income through its economic activities and services. Higher values mean government activities make up a larger share of the national economy. This matters because it shows the role of government in providing jobs, services, and economic activity that supports overall living standards.

nodes.label: Average Sector Economic Health Index
nodes.description: This measures the average economic performance and health across different sectors of the economy, like manufacturing, services, and agriculture.
