Higher values indicate stronger overall economic performance across sectors. This matters because diverse, healthy economic sectors provide more jobs and economic stability for families.

nodes.label: Average Sector Government Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average income earned by government workers across all sectors and departments. Higher values mean government employees typically earn more money. Government worker compensation affects the quality of public services and shows how much countries invest in their public workforce.

nodes.label: Average Non-Financial Corporation Sector Performance
nodes.description: This measures the average economic performance of non-financial businesses (companies that don't provide banking or insurance services) in a country. Higher values typically indicate stronger business performance and economic health. A thriving business sector creates more jobs and higher incomes for workers.

nodes.label: Average Sector Economic Performance
nodes.description: This tracks the typical economic performance across different industries or economic sectors within a country. Higher values generally indicate stronger economic activity and productivity across various industries. This matters because diverse, well-performing economic sectors provide more job opportunities and economic stability for communities.

nodes.label: Average Individual Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money earned by one person in a year before taxes. Values are usually shown in local currency or US dollars, where higher amounts mean people earn more on average. This shows how much purchasing power individuals have for basic needs and quality of life.

nodes.label: Average Income Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the typical income earned by an individual person, calculated by dividing total income by the number of people. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate better individual economic well-being. This matters because it shows the standard of living and purchasing power of the average person.

nodes.label: Average Household Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical income earned by an entire household (all people living together), not just one person. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate better household economic well-being. This is important because it shows the financial resources available to families for their daily needs and future planning.

nodes.label: Average Household Expenses
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money that households spend on goods and services. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts could indicate either higher living costs or greater purchasing power. This matters because spending patterns reflect living standards and economic health of families.

nodes.label: Average Property Income per Individual
nodes.description: This measures the average income that individuals receive from owning property, investments, or other assets (like rent, dividends, or interest), typically shown in local currency. Higher values mean people earn more from their investments and property. This matters because property income can provide financial security and indicates whether people have opportunities to build wealth beyond just working for wages.

nodes.label: Average Property Value per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average value of property and assets that individuals own, such as homes, land, or other real estate. Values are shown in dollars or local currency, where higher amounts indicate people own more valuable property. Higher property values suggest greater individual wealth and financial security, which contributes to overall economic well-being.

nodes.label: Average Income by Group (Individual)
nodes.description: This measures the typical yearly income for people within specific groups, like different age ranges or education levels. Values are in currency amounts, where higher numbers mean that particular group earns more money. This helps identify which groups of people are doing better or worse financially.

nodes.label: Average Income by Household Group
nodes.description: This measures the typical yearly income for households within specific categories, like different family sizes or geographic areas. Values are in currency amounts, where higher numbers mean that particular group of households earns more. This helps identify which types of families have better or worse financial situations.

nodes.label: Average Household Income Segment
nodes.description: This measures the average income level of households within specific economic groups or segments of the population. Higher values indicate that households in that group have more money to spend on their needs and wants. This helps show how different groups of people are doing economically and whether income inequality is growing or shrinking.

nodes.label: Average Individual Income Segment
nodes.description: This measures which income group or bracket the average person falls into, helping classify people by their earnings level compared to others in their country. Higher values typically indicate higher income segments. This matters because it shows what income level is typical for most people and helps understand economic inequality in society.

nodes.label: Average Income by Population Segment
nodes.description: This measures the average income within specific groups or segments of the population, often divided by income levels or percentiles. Higher values indicate that particular segment is earning more money. This is important for understanding income inequality and how different groups in society are doing economically.

nodes.label: Average Spending Per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person spends on goods and services like food, housing, clothing, and entertainment in a year. Higher values mean people can afford to buy more things and have a better standard of living. This indicator shows how well ordinary people are doing financially and whether they can meet their daily needs.

nodes.label: Average Individual Spending on Personal Goods
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person spends on personal items like food, clothing, entertainment, and other goods and services for their own use. Higher values indicate people can afford to buy more things, which generally means better living standards. This matters because it shows whether people have enough money to meet their basic needs and enjoy some extras.

nodes.label: Average Individual Final Consumption
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person spends on final goods and services that they actually use up or consume, like food eaten, clothes worn, or services used. Higher values indicate people are consuming more goods and services. This matters because higher consumption usually means people can afford more of what they need and want for a comfortable life.

nodes.label: Average Personal Consumption Spending
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person spends on goods and services like food, housing, transportation, and entertainment. Higher values indicate people are spending more on their daily needs and wants. This matters because higher consumption spending typically reflects better living standards and economic well-being.

nodes.label: Average Spending per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average person spends on goods and services like food, housing, and entertainment. Values are shown in dollars or local currency, where higher amounts typically indicate people have more money to spend on their daily needs. Higher consumption usually means people are financially better off and can afford a higher standard of living.

nodes.label: Average Accumulated Income Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of income the average person has built up or saved over time from their earnings. Higher values mean people are able to save more money and accumulate wealth rather than spending everything they earn. Accumulated income provides financial security and helps people weather tough times or invest in opportunities.

nodes.label: Total Household Wealth Accumulated
nodes.description: This measures the total value of assets and wealth that households have built up over time, including savings, property, and investments. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate greater household financial security. This is important because accumulated wealth provides families with economic stability and opportunities.

nodes.label: Average Foreign Investment as Share of Income
nodes.description: This measures how much foreign companies invest in a country compared to the total income of that country. Higher percentages mean more international businesses are investing locally. This matters because foreign investment can create jobs and bring new technology, boosting economic growth.

nodes.label: Average Foreign Business Investment
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money foreign companies invest in building factories, offices, and other business operations in the country. Higher values mean more international investment flowing into the country. This is important because foreign investment often brings jobs, new technology, and economic growth opportunities to local communities.

nodes.label: Average Foreign Direct Investment Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical income earned from foreign companies investing directly in the country's businesses and projects. Higher values show foreign investors are making more profit. This matters because profitable foreign investment encourages continued investment and economic development.

nodes.label: Average Foreign Investment Inflow Rate
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of foreign direct investment flowing into a country from international businesses and investors. Higher values indicate more foreign companies investing in local businesses, factories, and projects. Foreign investment can boost economic growth and create jobs for local workers.

nodes.label: Democracy Index: Regime Classification Uncertainty
nodes.description: This measures how unclear or uncertain a country's democratic status is - whether it's hard to classify as democratic, authoritarian, or something in between. Higher values indicate more ambiguity about the regime type, meaning the country has mixed democratic and authoritarian features. Clear regime types help citizens and international partners know what to expect from the government.

nodes.label: Direct Democracy Institutions Index
nodes.description: This measures how many direct democracy tools a country offers citizens, such as referendums, citizen initiatives, and recall elections. Higher values on the 0-1 scale indicate more opportunities for citizens to directly vote on laws and policies. More direct democracy matters because it gives ordinary people greater influence over the decisions that affect their daily lives.

nodes.label: Financial Development Index
nodes.description: This measures how developed and accessible a country's financial system is, including banks, stock markets, and credit availability. Higher scores indicate more advanced financial systems that better serve businesses and individuals. A strong financial system matters because it helps people save money, get loans for homes or businesses, and supports economic growth.

nodes.label: Financial Development Index
nodes.description: This measures the overall development of a country's financial system, including banks, stock markets, and access to credit and financial services. Higher values indicate more advanced and accessible financial systems. A well-developed financial system matters because it helps people save money safely, get loans for homes and businesses, and provides the foundation for economic growth.

nodes.label: Executive Legitimacy Ratio
nodes.description: This measures the relationship between how much power the chief executive (president or prime minister) claims to have versus how much the public and other institutions accept as legitimate. Higher values may indicate either strong popular support or concerning power concentration. Balanced executive legitimacy helps ensure leaders have enough authority to govern effectively while remaining accountable to citizens.

nodes.label: Legislature Funding Adequacy (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This is the raw expert assessment of whether the national legislature has adequate funding and resources to function effectively, before statistical processing. Values typically range from 0-4, where higher scores indicate better-funded legislatures. This original rating helps researchers understand how democracy experts view legislative capacity in each country.

nodes.label: Legislature Staff Quality (Expert Rating)
nodes.description: This is the original expert assessment of how qualified and competent the staff working for the national legislature are, before statistical processing. Values typically range from 0-4, where higher scores mean more skilled legislative staff. Competent staff help lawmakers draft better legislation and make more informed decisions for citizens.

nodes.label: Non-State Political Media Coverage
nodes.description: Measures how much media coverage is given to political groups and parties that are not currently in power. Higher scores indicate more balanced coverage that includes opposition voices. This matters because diverse media coverage helps citizens understand all their political options during elections.

nodes.label: Election Quality Barometer
nodes.description: This measures some aspect of electoral processes or democratic quality, likely rating how free, fair, or competitive elections are in a country. Higher scores typically indicate better democratic processes and election quality. Strong electoral systems matter because they ensure citizens can choose their leaders and hold government accountable.

nodes.label: Diagonal Accountability Index
nodes.description: Combines measures of how well citizens, media, and civil society can hold government accountable through oversight and criticism, on the original scale. Higher values indicate stronger accountability mechanisms. Strong accountability ensures government officials serve the public interest rather than personal gain, leading to better services and less corruption.

nodes.label: Horizontal Accountability Index
nodes.description: Combines measures of how well different government institutions (legislature, judiciary, etc.) check and balance each other's power, on the original scale. Higher values indicate stronger checks and balances between government branches. Strong horizontal accountability prevents any single institution from abusing power, protecting citizens from government overreach and corruption.

nodes.label: State Internal Authority (Average Score)
nodes.description: This measures the average level of government authority and control within the country's borders, including the ability to enforce laws and maintain order. Higher scores indicate stronger state capacity to govern effectively, which helps provide security and public services to citizens.

nodes.label: Democracy Satisfaction Rating
nodes.description: This measures how satisfied citizens are with how democracy works in their country based on public opinion surveys. Higher scores indicate greater satisfaction with democratic institutions and processes. This matters because citizen satisfaction with democracy reflects the health of political institutions and affects political stability and civic engagement.

nodes.label: Media Pluralism Index
nodes.description: This measures how diverse and independent the media landscape is in a country, including newspapers, TV, radio, and online sources. Higher scores (on a 0-1 scale) indicate more media diversity and independence from government control. This matters because diverse, independent media helps citizens stay informed and hold leaders accountable.

nodes.label: Freedom of Association Index
nodes.description: This measures how freely people can form and participate in organizations, unions, political parties, and other groups without government interference. The index ranges from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate greater freedom to associate. Freedom of association is vital because it allows people to organize, advocate for their interests, and work together to solve community problems.

nodes.label: Comprehensive Electoral Competition Index
nodes.description: Measures how competitive and open a country's elections are, including whether multiple parties can realistically compete and win office. Higher values (closer to 5) indicate more genuine electoral competition and democratic choice. This matters because competitive elections ensure leaders must work to earn votes, making them more likely to serve citizens' interests rather than their own.

nodes.label: Freedom of Association Index
nodes.description: Measures how freely people can form and join organizations, unions, political parties, and other groups without government interference. Higher values (closer to 4) indicate greater freedom to associate and organize. This matters because freedom of association allows people to work together to solve problems, advocate for their interests, and build stronger communities.

nodes.label: Legislative Constraints on Government
nodes.description: This measures how effectively a country's legislature (parliament or congress) can limit and oversee the executive branch's power. The index ranges from 0 to 1, where higher scores mean the legislature provides stronger checks on executive power. Effective legislative oversight is crucial because it prevents any one person or branch of government from becoming too powerful and abusing their authority.

nodes.label: Free and Fair Elections Index
nodes.description: Measures how free and fair a country's elections are, including whether citizens can vote without intimidation and whether elections are conducted honestly. Scored on a scale where higher values (closer to 4) indicate more free and fair elections. This matters because fair elections ensure people have a real voice in choosing their leaders and policies that affect their daily lives.

nodes.label: Free and Fair Elections Index (Extended Scale)
nodes.description: Measures how free and fair a country's elections are using a more detailed scale, evaluating vote buying, intimidation, and electoral integrity. Higher values (closer to 5) indicate more genuinely free and fair elections. This matters because fair elections ensure people can choose leaders who will represent their interests and work to improve their living conditions.

nodes.label: Average Total Income (Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the average total income earned by adults in a country, including all sources like wages, investments, and government benefits. Higher values indicate people earn more money on average. This matters because higher average incomes typically mean people can afford better housing, healthcare, education, and have more economic security.

nodes.label: Average Total Income (Adults Only)
nodes.description: This measures the average total income earned by adults from all sources including jobs, investments, and government benefits. Higher values indicate that working-age people have more money coming in from various sources. This is important because higher adult incomes typically mean better living standards and more opportunities for families.

nodes.label: Average Total Income Per Adult
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of total income (including wages, government benefits, and other sources) that each adult receives in a country. Values are typically in thousands of dollars per person, and higher values mean people have more money on average. This is important because it directly affects people's standard of living and ability to afford necessities.

nodes.label: Average Adult Total Income
nodes.description: This measures the average total income earned by adults in a country from all sources including wages, investments, and benefits. Higher values indicate greater prosperity among working-age people. This is important because adult income levels determine families' ability to afford housing, education, healthcare, and other necessities.

nodes.label: Average Total Income (Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money that adults earn from all sources including wages, business profits, and investments before paying taxes. Higher values indicate that people generally earn more money. This shows the overall economic well-being of adults in a country and their ability to afford goods and services.

nodes.label: Average Income of Working-Age Adults
nodes.description: This measures the typical yearly income earned by adults from wages, business profits, and investments. Higher values mean people in that country earn more money on average. This matters because higher average incomes usually mean people can afford better housing, healthcare, education, and have more opportunities to improve their lives.

nodes.label: Average Tax Burden on Working Adults
nodes.description: This shows how much working-age adults typically pay in taxes as a share of their total income from wages and investments. Higher values mean people pay a larger portion of their earnings in taxes. This matters because tax levels affect how much money families have left to spend on necessities and how much governments can invest in public services.

nodes.label: Average Social Benefits (Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the average value of social benefits and public assistance received by adults, including unemployment benefits, healthcare, and social security. Higher values indicate more generous social safety nets. This matters because social benefits help protect people during hard times and reduce poverty and inequality.

nodes.label: Adult Social Security Coverage
nodes.description: This measures the average social security and welfare benefits available to adults as a share of total income. Higher values indicate more comprehensive social safety nets and government support for citizens. This matters because strong social security systems help protect people during unemployment, illness, or retirement, reducing poverty and providing economic stability.

nodes.label: Average Adult Social Security Income
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of social security or welfare payments that adults receive from the government. Higher values mean more generous social safety net programs that provide financial support. Strong social programs help protect people from poverty when they lose jobs, become disabled, or face other hardships.

nodes.label: Average Social Benefits Per Adult
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of government social benefits (like unemployment insurance, disability payments, and housing assistance) that each adult receives. Values are typically in thousands of dollars per person, and higher values mean more social safety net support. This is important because it shows how well a country protects its citizens from economic hardship.

nodes.label: Average Savings Income Per Adult
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of income that adults earn from their savings accounts, certificates of deposit, and other low-risk savings vehicles. Values are typically in hundreds or thousands of dollars per person, and higher values indicate more income from safe investments. This matters because savings income provides financial stability and shows how much people can set aside for emergencies and retirement.

nodes.label: Average Adult Social Income
nodes.description: This tracks the average income that adults receive from social programs like unemployment benefits, pensions, and welfare. Higher values mean adults receive more support from social safety nets. This is important because social income helps protect people during economic hardships and reduces poverty.

nodes.label: Average After-Tax Income (Working-Age Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the average income that working-age adults keep after paying taxes and receiving government benefits. Higher values mean people have more money to spend on their daily needs. This directly affects people's standard of living and purchasing power for housing, food, and other necessities.

nodes.label: Average Social Benefits and Transfers
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money people receive from government programs like unemployment benefits, welfare, or social security. Higher values indicate more generous social support systems. This matters because these payments help protect people during hard times and reduce poverty.

nodes.label: Average Social Income Share (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures how income is distributed across all social groups in a country, showing the average share each group receives. Higher values indicate more equal income distribution among social classes. This matters because more equal income distribution is linked to better social stability and opportunities for all citizens.

nodes.label: Average Social Wealth Share (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures how wealth (assets like property, savings, and investments) is distributed across different social groups in a country. Higher values indicate more equal wealth distribution among social classes. This matters because more equal wealth distribution gives more people access to opportunities and financial security.

nodes.label: Average Social Welfare Benefits
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount people receive from government social programs like unemployment benefits, disability payments, and family assistance. Higher values indicate more generous social safety nets that provide greater financial support. This is important because strong social programs help protect families during difficult times and reduce poverty.

nodes.label: Average Social Program Coverage
nodes.description: This shows the typical level of access people have to social programs like healthcare, education assistance, and family support services. Higher values indicate broader and more comprehensive social program coverage. This matters because good social programs help ensure everyone has access to basic needs and opportunities to improve their lives.

nodes.label: Social Income Share After Transfers
nodes.description: This measures how income is distributed across groups after including government benefits, social programs, and public services. Higher values for lower-income groups indicate more effective redistribution. This matters because social transfers can reduce poverty and inequality, improving overall social cohesion and quality of life.

nodes.label: Average Social Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average income people receive from government programs like unemployment benefits, welfare, and social security across all income groups in a country. Higher values mean the government provides more financial support to its citizens. This shows how much countries invest in helping people meet their basic needs through social programs.

nodes.label: Average Social Income per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average income people receive from social programs like unemployment benefits, pensions, and welfare payments. Higher values mean more generous social safety nets that provide greater financial security. Strong social programs help reduce poverty and provide stability during economic hardships.

nodes.label: Average Social Income (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average income that people receive from social programs and government benefits across the entire population. Higher values mean people are receiving more support from social safety net programs. This matters because adequate social support helps ensure people can meet basic needs even during difficult times.

nodes.label: Average Factor Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of total economic output goes to different factors of production like labor (wages) versus capital (profits and investments). The values show how economic gains are split between workers and asset owners. This matters because it affects whether economic growth translates into better wages and living standards for working people.

nodes.label: Average Factor Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical income people earn from providing labor, capital, or land to the economy before any government subsidies or transfers. Higher values mean people are earning more from their economic contributions. This matters because factor income shows the underlying earning power people have from their work and investments to support their families.

nodes.label: Average Government Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average income that all government workers and officials earn in a country. Higher values indicate that people working for the government typically earn more money. Government worker pay levels can affect the quality of public services like education, healthcare, and administration that citizens receive.

nodes.label: Average Government Income Support (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of money people receive from government programs like welfare, unemployment benefits, or social security. Higher values mean the government provides more financial support to its citizens. This matters because government support can help reduce poverty and provide a safety net during hard times.

nodes.label: Average Government Social Support (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of social benefits and support programs the government provides to all people, including healthcare, education, and social services. Higher values mean the government spends more on helping its citizens meet basic needs. This is important because strong government social support can reduce inequality and ensure everyone has access to essential services.

nodes.label: Average Adult Government Income
nodes.description: This tracks the average income that adults receive from government sources like wages, benefits, and transfers in a country. Higher values indicate more government income per adult. This is important because government income distribution affects economic inequality and how much support citizens receive from public programs.

nodes.label: Average Adult Government Income
nodes.description: This measures the average income that working-age adults receive from government employment and programs. Higher values mean adults are earning more from government sources. This matters because government income can provide stable employment and support for families, contributing to overall economic security.

nodes.label: Average Adult Government Benefits
nodes.description: This measures the average amount that working-age adults receive in government benefits and transfers. Higher values indicate adults are getting more financial support from government programs. This matters because government support helps working-age people maintain their standard of living during unemployment or economic hardship.

nodes.label: Average Environmental Government Income
nodes.description: This measures the average income of government workers who focus on environmental protection and natural resource management. Higher values indicate these environmental workers earn more. Well-paid environmental staff can help ensure better protection of air, water, forests, and other natural resources that affect everyone's health.

nodes.label: Average Total National Income Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average total income per person including all sources - wages, investments, government benefits, and other economic activity. Higher values indicate better overall economic well-being across the population. This matters because total national income per person is a key measure of a country's prosperity and its citizens' financial well-being.

nodes.label: Average Total National Income Share
nodes.description: This measures how the total national income (all money earned in a country) is distributed on average across the population. Higher values indicate more equal income distribution overall. This matters because more equal income distribution means economic growth benefits are shared more widely, leading to better living standards for more people.

nodes.label: Average Total Income (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average income earned by everyone in the country from all sources including wages, investments, and government benefits. Higher values mean people generally have more money available for their needs. This is important because it shows the overall economic well-being and living standards of the entire population.

nodes.label: Average Total Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical total income earned by individuals or households, including wages, business profits, and investment returns, before taxes and transfers. Higher values indicate better overall economic opportunities and earning potential. Rising average incomes generally mean improved living standards and economic prosperity for the population.

nodes.label: Average Total National Income
nodes.description: This measures the average income across all people in a country from all sources combined. Higher values indicate greater overall prosperity and wealth. This is crucial because it reflects the general economic well-being and living standards that people can expect in that country.

nodes.label: Average Income After Taxes
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money people have after paying taxes but including government benefits like unemployment insurance or social security. Higher values mean the average person has more money to spend on their needs. This matters because it shows how much spending power people actually have for housing, food, and other essentials after government policies.

nodes.label: Average Net National Income
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of income available per person in a country after accounting for taxes, government benefits, and economic depreciation. Higher values mean people have more money available on average. This matters because it shows the actual financial resources people have for meeting their daily needs and improving their living conditions.

nodes.label: Average Consumption Spending per Adult
nodes.description: This measures how much money the average adult in a country spends on goods and services like food, housing, clothing, and entertainment each year. Higher values mean people can afford to buy more things and have a higher standard of living. This matters because consumption spending reflects how well people can meet their basic needs and enjoy life's comforts.

nodes.label: Average Consumption Level (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average amount that all groups in the population consume or spend on goods and services. Higher values indicate people are able to buy more things and have higher living standards. This is important because consumption levels directly reflect how well people can meet their daily needs and wants.

nodes.label: Market-Based Consumer Spending (All Population)
nodes.description: This tracks total consumer spending through market transactions across the entire population, measuring how much people spend on goods and services. Higher values indicate more economic activity and consumer purchasing power. This matters because consumer spending drives economic growth and reflects people's ability to meet their needs and wants.

nodes.label: Market Consumption Share
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of total consumption spending comes from a particular income group, as tracked by inequality researchers. Values are percentages, where higher shares by wealthy groups indicate consumption inequality. This reveals whether economic growth benefits are reaching all social classes through increased purchasing power.

nodes.label: Market-Based Consumption per Household
nodes.description: This measures how much households spend on goods and services they buy in the market (not including government services). Higher values indicate greater purchasing power and living standards. Consumer spending is important because it drives economic growth and reflects people's ability to afford necessities and luxuries.

nodes.label: Average Consumption Spending (All Adults)
nodes.description: This measures how much money all adults in a country spend on average for goods and services like food, housing, and entertainment. Higher values indicate people are spending more, which usually means they have higher incomes and living standards. Consumer spending drives economic growth and reflects people's ability to afford their wants and needs.

nodes.label: Market Net Wealth Distribution
nodes.description: This measures how wealth from market activities (like business ownership and investments) is distributed among adults in a country before taxes and transfers. Higher concentration means more wealth is held by fewer people. This matters because wealth distribution affects economic opportunity and social mobility for different income groups.

nodes.label: Market Income After Taxes - Middle Class Share
nodes.description: This tracks what percentage of total national income goes to different income groups from wages, business profits, and investments after taxes but before government benefits. Higher values for middle-income groups indicate a stronger middle class. This matters because a robust middle class typically supports economic stability and democratic governance.

nodes.label: Market Net Wealth
nodes.description: This measures the total net wealth held by individuals and businesses in market investments and financial assets. Higher values indicate more wealth accumulated in financial markets. This matters because financial wealth affects economic stability and people's ability to weather economic downturns.

nodes.label: Average Market-Based Wealth (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average wealth that people hold in market investments like stocks, bonds, and business ownership across the entire population. Higher values indicate people have more financial assets and investment wealth. This matters because having financial assets provides economic security and opportunities for families to build long-term prosperity.

nodes.label: Market Net Income for All People
nodes.description: This measures the total income people earn from jobs and investments after taxes and transfers, including everyone in the population. Higher values mean people have more money to spend after the government takes taxes and gives benefits. This matters because it shows how much money people actually have available for their daily needs and wants.

nodes.label: Total Market Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This tracks the total income earned by all population groups through market activities like jobs, business profits, and investments. Higher values mean more total income is being generated in the economy. This matters because higher market income typically means more jobs and economic opportunities for everyone.

nodes.label: Total Market Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the total income that all population groups earn through market activities such as wages, business profits, and investment returns. Higher values indicate a stronger economy with more income generation. This is crucial because total market income reflects the overall economic health and job availability in a country.

nodes.label: Total Market Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the complete market income earned by all population groups combined, including wages, profits, and investment income. Higher values indicate a more prosperous economy with greater income generation. Total market income is vital because it reflects the overall economic opportunities and wealth creation in a society.

nodes.label: Total Market Income
nodes.description: This measures the total income earned by all adults in a country from wages, business profits, and investments, before taxes and government assistance. Values are typically shown as income shares or averages. Higher values indicate greater overall economic activity and income generation, which generally means better economic opportunities for residents.

nodes.label: Total Market-Based Tax Revenue
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of taxes collected from economic activities like sales, business profits, and market transactions. Higher values indicate more tax revenue generated from market activity. This matters because tax revenue funds essential public services like education, healthcare, and infrastructure that improve quality of life.

nodes.label: Total Market Income Distribution
nodes.description: This tracks the complete distribution of all income from wages, profits, and investments across different income levels in the population before any government intervention. Higher concentration in wealthy groups indicates greater market inequality. This matters because the initial income distribution affects how much government policy is needed to ensure broad-based prosperity.

nodes.label: Total Market Income (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of income earned from market activities (like wages, business profits, and investments) by everyone in a country before taxes and government transfers. Values are typically in billions of dollars, and higher values indicate more total economic activity. This matters because it shows the overall size of a country's market economy and wealth generation capacity.

nodes.label: Total Government Market Income
nodes.description: This measures the total income that government entities earn from market activities, such as profits from government-owned businesses or investment returns on government funds. Values are typically in billions of dollars, and higher values mean more government revenue from business activities. This matters because it affects how much money governments have to spend on public services without raising taxes.

nodes.label: Total Market Income Distribution
nodes.description: This measures how income from market activities (wages, profits, investments) is distributed across the entire population before government redistribution. Higher values could indicate either more total market income or more unequal distribution. This matters because market income patterns affect economic inequality and social mobility.

nodes.label: Total Market Income Distribution
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of income earned from jobs, investments, and business profits across all income levels in a country, before taxes and government transfers. Higher values indicate more total market income being generated in the economy. This matters because it shows the overall economic activity and wealth creation that can potentially improve everyone's standard of living.

nodes.label: Total Pre-Tax Market Income
nodes.description: This measures the complete amount of income earned from all market sources like wages, business profits, and investments before any taxes or government transfers. Higher values show more total economic income being generated. This matters because it indicates the overall economic strength and opportunities available in a country for people to earn a living.

nodes.label: Total Household Tax Burden
nodes.description: This measures the complete amount of taxes paid by all households in a country, including income taxes, sales taxes, and other taxes that affect families directly. Higher values mean households are paying more total taxes. This matters because tax levels affect how much money families have left for housing, food, education, and other necessities.

nodes.label: Total Market Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the combined income that all people in a country earn from market sources like wages, business profits, and investments before government intervention. Higher values indicate a more prosperous economy where people earn more money from their economic activities. This reflects the overall strength of job markets and business opportunities.

nodes.label: Total Market-Based Income (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the total income that all people in a country earn from market activities like jobs, business profits, and investments. Higher values indicate the overall economy is generating more income through market transactions. This matters because market-based income shows how well the economy is working to provide earning opportunities for people.

nodes.label: Total Market Income for All Groups
nodes.description: This measures the total income earned by all people in a country from market activities like wages, business profits, and investments, before taxes and government transfers. Values are typically shown in dollars or as percentages, and higher values generally indicate a stronger economy. This helps researchers understand how much wealth a country's economy generates and how it compares to other nations.

nodes.label: Total Market Income for All People
nodes.description: This measures the total income people earn from jobs, businesses, and investments before government taxes and benefits are applied. Higher values mean people earn more money from work and investments. This matters because market income shows the economy's ability to create wealth and provide earning opportunities for people.

nodes.label: Sales Tax Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government collects from taxes on goods and services (like sales tax) as a percentage of the country's total income. Higher percentages mean sales taxes make up a bigger part of government revenue. This shows how much the government relies on taxing purchases versus other forms of taxation like income taxes.

nodes.label: Foreign Debt and Obligations
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar amount that a country owes to foreign lenders, investors, and other countries. Higher values mean greater financial obligations to overseas creditors. While some foreign debt can support development, excessive levels can strain government budgets and limit spending on public services that benefit citizens.

nodes.label: Foreign debt per person
nodes.description: This shows how much money the country owes to foreign lenders, divided by the population, in 2019 US dollars per person. Higher values mean each citizen's share of foreign debt is larger. This matters because high foreign debt can limit a government's ability to spend on education, healthcare, and other services that improve quality of life.

nodes.label: Trade as share of economy
nodes.description: This measures how much a country trades with other countries (both buying and selling) compared to the size of its total economy, shown as a percentage. Higher percentages mean the country is more connected to global markets. This matters because trade can bring economic opportunities, jobs, and access to goods and services that improve living standards.

nodes.label: Underground Economy Size (Advanced Economic Model)
nodes.description: This measures the size of a country's underground economy (unreported jobs, cash transactions, tax evasion) as a percentage of the official economy, calculated using an advanced economic model called Dynamic General Equilibrium. Higher percentages mean a larger underground economy relative to the official one. A smaller underground economy typically indicates better government services, law enforcement, and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Industrial Jobs Growth Rate
nodes.description: This tracks how fast the number of manufacturing and factory jobs is growing or shrinking each year. Values above 100 mean industrial employment is growing, while values below 100 mean it's declining. This is important because industrial jobs often provide steady income and economic stability for working families.

nodes.label: Underground Economy Size (Multiple Indicators Model)
nodes.description: This measures the size of a country's underground economy (unreported work, cash payments, tax avoidance) as a percentage of the official economy, estimated using a statistical model that combines multiple economic indicators. Higher percentages indicate a larger underground economy compared to the official one. Smaller underground economies usually mean better job opportunities, government services, and economic stability for citizens.

nodes.label: Bank Lending to Private Sector (% of GDP)
nodes.description: This measures how much money banks lend to private businesses and individuals compared to the country's total economic output. Higher percentages indicate that banks are actively lending money, which helps businesses grow and people make purchases. More bank lending usually supports economic growth by giving people and companies access to credit for investments and spending.

nodes.label: Bank lending as share of economy (%)
nodes.description: This measures how much money banks lend out compared to the size of the entire economy. Higher percentages usually indicate a more developed financial system where people and businesses can access loans for homes, education, and investments. Strong bank lending helps economies grow by making it easier for people to start businesses and make major purchases.

nodes.label: Regional Trade with Developing Countries
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's exported goods go to other developing countries in the same geographic region. Higher percentages indicate stronger regional trade ties with neighboring developing economies. Strong regional trade relationships can boost economic growth and development by creating closer economic partnerships with nearby countries at similar development levels.

nodes.label: Exports to Europe & Central Asia as Share of Total Exports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total exports (goods sold to other countries) go to lower and middle-income countries in Europe and Central Asia. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean the country relies more heavily on this region as a market. This matters because it shows how dependent a country's economy is on one specific region for selling its products.

nodes.label: Exports Outside Home Region as Share of Total Exports
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's exports go to lower and middle-income countries in other world regions (outside their own geographic region). Higher percentages indicate more diversified export markets across different regions. This matters because spreading exports across multiple regions reduces economic risk and can provide more stable income from international trade.

nodes.label: Exports to South Asia Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's exported goods goes to South Asian countries like India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages indicate stronger trade relationships with South Asia. This matters because having diverse export markets helps create jobs and economic stability by reducing dependence on any single trading partner.

nodes.label: Trade with Middle East & North Africa (Percentage of Exports)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's physical exports (like cars, food, or machinery) go to developing countries in the Middle East and North Africa region. Higher percentages mean the country trades more heavily with this specific region rather than spreading trade globally. This matters because it shows trade relationships and economic partnerships that can affect a country's economic stability and growth.

nodes.label: Trade with East Asia & Pacific (Percentage of Exports)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's physical exports (like electronics, raw materials, or manufactured goods) go to developing countries in the East Asia and Pacific region. Higher percentages indicate stronger trade ties with this economically important region. This matters because diverse trade relationships help countries build economic resilience and access growing markets for their products.

nodes.label: Total Export Value
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of all physical goods (like cars, food, or electronics) that a country sells to other countries, expressed in current US dollars. Higher values mean a country exports more goods and earns more money from international trade. This matters because export income helps fund imports, creates jobs, and supports economic growth and prosperity.

nodes.label: Trade as Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures the combined value of all goods a country imports and exports as a percentage of its total economic output. Higher percentages indicate the country is more connected to global trade, which can boost economic growth but also increase vulnerability to international economic changes.

nodes.label: Total value of human skills and education
nodes.description: This estimates the total dollar value of all knowledge, skills, and education that a country's working population will earn over their lifetimes, measured in 2019 US dollars. Higher values indicate a more educated and skilled workforce. This matters because countries with better-educated people typically have stronger economies and higher living standards.

nodes.label: Male Human Capital Value per Person
nodes.description: This estimates the economic value of skills, education, and future earning potential of men in the population, measured per person in 2019 US dollars. Higher values indicate men have more valuable skills and education that contribute to economic productivity. This matters because human capital drives innovation, economic growth, and higher living standards for society.

nodes.label: Human Capital Value per Person
nodes.description: This estimates the dollar value of each person's education, skills, and health - essentially measuring how much people's knowledge and abilities contribute to the economy. Higher values indicate a more educated and skilled population. Greater human capital means people can be more productive and earn higher incomes, leading to better living standards and economic development.

nodes.label: Human capital value (billions US$)
nodes.description: This estimates the total economic value of a country's population's education, skills, and health - essentially how much people's abilities are worth to the economy. Higher values indicate a more educated and healthy workforce. Strong human capital leads to higher productivity, innovation, and living standards.

nodes.label: Human Capital Index
nodes.description: This measures how much a child born today can expect to achieve in terms of education and health compared to the ideal of complete education and full health. The scale runs from 0 to 1, where higher values are better. This matters because human capital - people's skills and health - drives long-term economic growth and quality of life.

nodes.label: Women's Human Capital Value Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of women's education, skills, and knowledge per female person in US dollars. Higher values indicate that women in the country have more education and valuable skills on average. This matters because women's human capital directly affects economic growth, family welfare, and gender equality, as educated women contribute more to the economy and society.

nodes.label: Economic value of women's skills and education (current US$)
nodes.description: This estimates the total economic value of all the education, training, and work experience that women in a country possess. Higher values indicate women have more valuable skills and education, which typically leads to better job opportunities and higher incomes for families.

nodes.label: Economic Value of Men's Skills and Education
nodes.description: This estimates the total economic value of education, skills, and work experience that men in a country possess, measured in US dollars. Higher values indicate men have more valuable skills and education that can contribute to economic growth. Well-educated populations tend to have higher incomes and better living standards.

nodes.label: Male Human Capital Value Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of skills, education, and health of the average male in a country, expressed in US dollars per person. Higher values indicate males have better education and health, making them more productive workers. Strong human capital helps people earn higher incomes and contributes to economic growth.

nodes.label: Self-Employed Workers as Share of All Workers
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of all employed people work for themselves rather than for a company or employer. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages often indicate more informal work or fewer formal job opportunities. This matters because very high rates may suggest limited access to stable, well-paying jobs with benefits.

nodes.label: Self-Employment Income per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average profit that individuals make from running their own businesses, after subtracting business expenses from their earnings. Values are in local currency per year, and higher amounts mean self-employed people are making more money from their businesses. This matters because self-employment income reflects entrepreneurship and can provide financial independence and job flexibility.

nodes.label: Individual Self-Employment Earnings (After Expenses)
nodes.description: This measures how much money individuals earn from running their own businesses or working for themselves, minus their business expenses. Values are typically in local currency, with higher amounts indicating more successful self-employment. This shows economic opportunities for entrepreneurs and small business owners in a country.

nodes.label: Adjusted National Income After Resource Depletion
nodes.description: This measures a country's total income after subtracting the costs of using up natural resources and wearing out infrastructure, expressed in current US dollars. Higher values indicate stronger, more sustainable economic wealth that accounts for environmental costs. This gives a more realistic picture of whether a country's economy is truly growing or just consuming its natural assets.

nodes.label: Consumption Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total income is spent on goods and services by households, rather than saved or invested. Values range from 0-100%, with higher percentages meaning more income goes to immediate consumption. Balanced consumption levels support both current living standards and future economic growth through savings.

nodes.label: Median Retirement Benefits per Person
nodes.description: This measures the middle amount that retired people receive in pension payments and retirement benefits from government and employer programs. Values are shown in local currency per year, and higher values mean retirees have more financial security. This matters because it shows how well a country's retirement system supports people after they stop working.

nodes.label: Average Retirement Benefits per Person
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount each person receives in government retirement benefits like pensions or social security. Higher values mean more generous retirement support from the government, measured in local currency. Better retirement benefits help ensure older adults can maintain a decent standard of living after they stop working.

nodes.label: Average Social Security Benefits
nodes.description: This measures the typical amount of money people receive from government social security programs, which provide income support for retirees, disabled individuals, or unemployed workers. Higher values mean more generous government support for those who cannot work. Strong social security systems help ensure people can meet basic needs during difficult times.

nodes.label: Individual Income Comparison Index
nodes.description: This measures how an individual's income compares to a standard reference point, usually shown as a number where 100 represents the average or baseline. Values above 100 mean someone earns more than the reference point, while below 100 means they earn less. This helps compare income levels across different time periods or groups of people.

nodes.label: Mixed Income Per Person
nodes.description: This measures income that individuals earn from both employment and self-employment combined before taxes are taken out. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate better individual earnings from multiple sources. This matters because it shows how much people earn from diverse income streams, which can provide financial stability.

nodes.label: Average Mixed Income Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the typical income individuals earn from combining different sources like wages, business profits, and investments. Values are in currency units, and higher amounts indicate more diversified and successful earnings. This matters because diverse income sources provide financial stability and show economic opportunities available to people.

nodes.label: Average Individual Operating Income
nodes.description: This measures the average income a person earns from running business operations, after subtracting the basic costs of doing business but before taxes. Higher values mean people are earning more profit from their business activities. This matters because it shows how successful people are at generating income from entrepreneurial activities and business ownership.

nodes.label: Average Economic Output per Person
nodes.description: This shows how much economic value (goods and services) each person in the country produces on average per year. Higher values indicate a more productive economy and are typically measured in local currency. Higher economic output per person generally leads to better living standards and higher incomes for residents.

nodes.label: Average Private Financial Capital Income
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from private investments like stocks, bonds, and business ownership. Higher values indicate more investment income and wealth accumulation. This matters because investment income shows economic opportunity and financial security, helping people build wealth beyond just wages.

nodes.label: Average Private Income from All Sources
nodes.description: This measures the average income that individuals earn from private sources like wages, business profits, and investments, excluding government transfers. Higher values indicate greater private sector earnings. This matters because private income reflects economic opportunities and job market strength, affecting people's ability to support themselves without government assistance.

nodes.label: Average Private Income by Group
nodes.description: This measures the typical income earned by different groups from private sources like wages, business profits, and investments, excluding government transfers. Higher values indicate greater private income for that group. This matters because private income reflects job opportunities and economic mobility, which are key to long-term prosperity and independence.

nodes.label: Average Private Net Income
nodes.description: This measures the average private income people keep after taxes and transfers, representing actual take-home income from private sources. Higher values mean people have more disposable income for their needs and wants. This matters because net private income determines what families can actually afford for housing, food, education, and savings.

nodes.label: Average Private Income Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from private sources like jobs, businesses, and investments, excluding government benefits. Higher values indicate people are earning more from private economic activity. This matters because private income levels show how well the economy is providing opportunities for people to earn a living and improve their financial situation.

nodes.label: Female Suffrage Rights
nodes.description: This measures the extent to which women have the right to vote in national elections on equal terms with men. Higher scores indicate stronger voting rights for women. This matters because equal voting rights ensure that women can participate in choosing their government and influence policies that affect their lives.

nodes.label: Participatory Democracy Index
nodes.description: This measures how much ordinary citizens can actively participate in political decisions beyond just voting, through things like citizen councils, referendums, and direct consultation. Higher scores indicate more opportunities for direct citizen involvement in governance. This matters because greater participation gives people more control over decisions that affect their daily lives.

nodes.label: Voting Rights Coverage
nodes.description: Measures what percentage of adult citizens have the legal right to vote in national elections. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean more people can participate in elections. Broad voting rights ensure that government represents the will of the people, not just a small elite group.

nodes.label: Democratic Competition Index
nodes.description: Measures how democratic a country is based on free elections, civil liberties, and political competition. Values range from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate more democratic countries with competitive elections and protected rights. Democratic systems tend to provide better services and protect citizens' freedoms more effectively.

nodes.label: Political Participation Index Score
nodes.description: This measures how much ordinary citizens can participate in political processes like voting, joining parties, and influencing government decisions. Values typically range from 0-1, with higher scores indicating more opportunities for political participation. Greater political participation usually leads to more responsive government and better representation of citizens' needs.

nodes.label: Political Participation Index
nodes.description: This measures how much ordinary citizens can participate in politics through voting, political parties, and civil society organizations. The index ranges from 0 to 1, where higher scores mean citizens have more opportunities to participate in political decisions. Strong political participation is important because it ensures people have a voice in the laws and policies that affect their daily lives.

nodes.label: Gender Equality in Political Participation
nodes.description: This measures how equally men and women participate in political activities like voting, running for office, and influencing government decisions. Higher scores indicate greater gender equality in politics. Equal political participation matters because when both men and women have a voice in government, policies better reflect the needs of all citizens.

nodes.label: Academic Freedom Index
nodes.description: This measures how freely universities and researchers can pursue academic work without government interference, including freedom to research controversial topics and express findings. The index ranges from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate greater academic freedom. Academic freedom is important because it enables scientific progress, critical thinking, and the development of knowledge that benefits society.

nodes.label: Alternative Information Sources Index
nodes.description: Measures how much citizens can access diverse, independent news and information sources beyond government-controlled media. Higher values (closer to 4) indicate greater media diversity and press freedom. This matters because access to varied information sources helps people make informed decisions about their lives and hold their government accountable.

nodes.label: Academic Freedom and Political Independence Index
nodes.description: Measures how freely universities and researchers can operate without political interference or censorship of their work. Higher values (closer to 4) indicate greater academic freedom and independence from government control. This matters because academic freedom promotes innovation, critical thinking, and the knowledge development that drives social and economic progress.

nodes.label: Electoral Democracy Index
nodes.description: Measures the overall quality of electoral democracy, including free elections, freedom of expression, and fair political competition. Higher values (closer to 5) indicate stronger democratic institutions and processes. This matters because democratic systems tend to be more responsive to citizens' needs and better at protecting individual rights and freedoms.

nodes.label: Maximum Household Income Management
nodes.description: This measures the highest levels of household income management or financial capacity within a population. Higher values suggest better financial planning and income optimization among top-earning households. This matters because effective income management at high levels can indicate overall economic sophistication and financial system development.

nodes.label: Average Public Wealth-to-Debt Ratio
nodes.description: This measures the relationship between a country's public assets (what the government owns) and its debt (what it owes). Higher ratios mean the government has more assets relative to its debt, indicating stronger financial health. This matters because governments with better financial positions can invest more in public services like education, healthcare, and infrastructure.

nodes.label: Average Pre-tax Wealth (Bottom 50%)
nodes.description: This measures the average wealth (assets minus debts) of the poorest half of adults in a country before taxes are applied. Higher values mean even the least wealthy people own more property, savings, and investments. This matters because wealth provides financial security and opportunities, so higher wealth among the poorest indicates less inequality and better economic mobility.

nodes.label: Adult Wealth and Assets Measure
nodes.description: This measures some aspect of wealth or financial assets held by adults, though the exact definition depends on the data source. Higher values typically mean people have more savings, property, or investments. This matters because having wealth provides financial security and opportunities for the future.

nodes.label: Total Social Income (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of social benefits and government transfers (like unemployment benefits, pensions, and welfare) received by everyone in a country. Values are typically in billions of dollars, and higher values indicate more government social support. This is important because it shows how much a government invests in supporting its citizens' basic needs.

nodes.label: Tax Revenue Collection
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of taxes collected by the government from individuals and businesses in a country. Higher values indicate the government is collecting more tax revenue. This matters because tax revenue funds public services like education, healthcare, and infrastructure that are essential for everyone's quality of life.

nodes.label: Net Wealth Transfer Rate
nodes.description: This measures the rate at which wealth moves between different groups in society through transfers, taxes, or inheritance. Higher values indicate more wealth redistribution occurring in the economy. This affects income equality and social mobility by determining how wealth flows between rich and poor households.

nodes.label: Whooping Cough Cases Reported
nodes.description: This counts the number of confirmed whooping cough (pertussis) cases reported to health authorities each year. Lower numbers are better as they indicate fewer people getting this serious respiratory infection. This matters because whooping cough can be deadly, especially for babies, so tracking cases helps monitor public health and vaccination program effectiveness.

nodes.label: Diphtheria Cases Reported
nodes.description: This counts the number of people officially diagnosed with diphtheria, a serious bacterial infection that can cause breathing problems and heart damage. Lower numbers are better because they mean fewer people are getting sick. This helps track whether vaccination programs and healthcare systems are successfully preventing this dangerous disease.

nodes.label: Children Vaccinated Against Diphtheria, Tetanus, and Whooping Cough
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of children who received all three doses of the DTP vaccine, which protects against three serious diseases. Values range from 0-100%, with higher percentages being better. This matters because these vaccines prevent potentially deadly childhood diseases, so high coverage rates indicate good healthcare access and child protection.

nodes.label: Polio Vaccination Coverage Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of children who receive polio vaccines, which prevent a serious disease that can cause paralysis. Higher percentages mean more children are protected from polio. This is vital for public health because widespread vaccination prevents polio outbreaks and protects entire communities from this dangerous disease.

nodes.label: Hib Vaccine Coverage (3 doses)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of children who have received all three doses of the Hib vaccine, which protects against Haemophilus influenzae type b bacteria that can cause meningitis and pneumonia. Higher percentages are better because more children are protected from serious illness. Complete vaccination schedules are crucial for preventing dangerous childhood diseases.

nodes.label: Total Value of Non-Renewable Natural Resources
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of a country's non-renewable natural resources like oil, coal, natural gas, and minerals still in the ground. Higher values mean a country has more valuable natural resources that could be extracted and sold. This matters because these resources can provide income for development, but countries need to manage them wisely since they can't be replaced once used up.

nodes.label: Value of natural gas reserves (billions US$)
nodes.description: This estimates the dollar value of all natural gas deposits that a country can extract from underground, calculated at 2019 prices. Higher values mean more valuable gas resources that can boost national wealth. This matters because natural gas reserves can provide energy and income for a country, though they won't last forever.

nodes.label: Natural Gas Reserves Value
nodes.description: This measures the estimated dollar value of a country's underground natural gas deposits that can be extracted and sold. Higher values indicate larger or more valuable natural gas reserves. Countries with substantial natural gas wealth have an important economic asset that can provide energy security and export revenue to fund development and improve living standards.

nodes.label: Value of oil reserves
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of all oil still underground in a country, calculated in 2019 US dollars. Higher values mean the country has more valuable oil resources that could boost economic wealth. This matters because oil wealth can fund government services and economic development, though it's a limited resource that will eventually run out.

nodes.label: Natural Gas Resources Value per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of natural gas reserves divided by the country's population, showing how much natural gas wealth exists per citizen. Higher values mean more potential natural gas income per person. This matters because natural gas resources can provide significant revenue for development and energy needs, though countries need sustainable management strategies.

nodes.label: Coal Resources Value per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of coal reserves divided by the country's population, showing how much coal wealth exists per citizen. Higher values mean more potential coal income per person. This matters because while coal can provide economic benefits, countries increasingly need to balance this with environmental concerns and transition to cleaner energy sources.

nodes.label: Natural gas reserves value per person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of natural gas deposits in the ground per person in a country. Higher values mean more natural gas wealth per citizen. This matters because natural gas reserves can provide energy resources and economic income that can fund public services and development.

nodes.label: Value of Coal Reserves
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of all coal deposits that exist underground in a country but haven't been mined yet. Higher values mean a country has more valuable coal reserves, which can provide economic benefits through mining and energy production. Countries with larger coal reserves have more potential energy resources, though this also means greater environmental challenges.

nodes.label: Oil Resources Value per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of oil reserves divided by the country's population, showing how much oil wealth exists per citizen. Higher values mean more potential oil income per person. This matters because oil wealth can fund government services and development, but countries need to manage these resources well to benefit all citizens over the long term.

nodes.label: Value of Underground Metals and Minerals
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of metals and minerals (like iron, gold, and copper) still buried underground in a country. Higher values indicate more natural resource wealth that could boost the economy if extracted, but also greater dependence on non-renewable resources.

nodes.label: Gold Reserves Value Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of a country's underground gold deposits divided by its population, showing how much gold wealth each person theoretically has. Higher values indicate more valuable gold resources that could support economic development when extracted responsibly. This matters because natural resource wealth can fund education, healthcare, and infrastructure if managed well for long-term benefit.

nodes.label: Value of nickel resources per person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of nickel deposits in the ground divided by each person in the country, adjusted for inflation.
