Higher values mean more valuable nickel resources per citizen. This matters because nickel mining can provide jobs and government revenue, but these resources will eventually run out.

nodes.label: Value of zinc reserves per person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of zinc metal deposits in the ground divided by the country's population, shown in 2019 US dollars per person. Higher values mean more zinc wealth per citizen. This matters because zinc is used in construction and manufacturing, so these reserves can provide income and economic opportunities for the population.

nodes.label: Copper Resources Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the estimated value of copper deposits underground divided by population. Higher values mean more copper wealth per person, which can boost the economy through mining exports but also indicates dependence on a non-renewable resource that will eventually be exhausted.

nodes.label: Metals and Minerals Wealth
nodes.description: This measures the total value of non-renewable mineral resources like gold, copper, iron, and other metals in a country, expressed in 2019 US dollars. Higher values mean a country has more valuable mineral deposits that can be mined. This matters because mineral wealth can fund development projects and create jobs, though it requires careful management to benefit citizens long-term.

nodes.label: Mineral Wealth Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of metals and minerals (like gold, copper, and iron ore) available in a country divided by its population. Higher values mean each person theoretically has access to more valuable mineral resources underground. Countries with more mineral wealth per person often have stronger economies and more opportunities for mining jobs.

nodes.label: Gold reserves value
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of gold deposits and reserves that a country has in the ground. Higher values mean a country has more valuable gold resources that could be mined in the future. This matters because gold reserves can provide economic security and export earnings, though extracting them may impact the environment.

nodes.label: Value of nickel mineral reserves (2019 US$)
nodes.description: This measures the total economic value of nickel deposits that can be extracted from a country's land. Higher values mean a country has more valuable nickel resources, which can provide income through mining exports but will eventually be depleted since nickel is non-renewable.

nodes.label: Natural Resources Value Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total value of a country's natural resources (like oil, minerals, forests, and farmland) divided by the number of people living there. Values are shown in dollars per person, and higher amounts are generally better as they indicate more natural wealth available for each citizen. Countries with abundant natural resources per person often have more potential for economic development and higher living standards.

nodes.label: Individual Net Fixed Assets
nodes.description: This measures the average value of long-term physical assets like buildings, equipment, and machinery that individuals own, minus any depreciation or wear over time. Values are in local currency, and higher amounts mean people own more valuable long-term assets. This matters because fixed assets represent wealth that can provide income or security and can be passed down to future generations.

nodes.label: Industrial Equipment and Machinery Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total value of industrial equipment, factories, and machinery divided by the population. Values are typically in thousands of dollars per person, and higher values indicate a country has more industrial infrastructure. This matters because countries with more industrial capital can produce more goods and typically offer better-paying jobs.

nodes.label: Industrial Equipment Growth Rate
nodes.description: This measures how fast a country is building up its industrial machinery, factories, and equipment over time. Higher values mean faster growth in industrial capacity. This matters because more industrial equipment typically leads to better jobs, higher productivity, and improved living standards for workers.

nodes.label: Fixed Capital Investment Per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much money is invested per person in long-lasting assets like buildings, machinery, and equipment that aren't part of basic infrastructure. Higher values mean more investment in productive assets that can boost future economic growth. Countries with more capital per person typically have higher productivity and better-paying jobs.

nodes.label: Housing Investment Growth Rate
nodes.description: This tracks how fast a country is investing in new housing and housing improvements each year at the national level. Higher values mean more money is being spent on building and improving homes. This matters because adequate housing investment helps ensure people have decent places to live and can boost economic activity.

nodes.label: Total Built Capital Value
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of all human-made assets in a country, including buildings, roads, factories, and urban land. Values are in current US dollars, where higher amounts indicate more infrastructure and built wealth. Countries with more built capital typically offer better living standards through improved transportation, housing, and business facilities.

nodes.label: Capital Infrastructure Value Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of built infrastructure (like roads, bridges, factories, and buildings) divided by population, excluding city land values. Higher values indicate a country has more valuable infrastructure per person, which typically means better economic productivity and higher living standards.

nodes.label: Produced capital per person (current US$)
nodes.description: This measures the total value of human-made assets like buildings, roads, machinery, and urban land divided by the population. Higher values indicate a country has more infrastructure and productive assets per person, which typically supports higher living standards and economic productivity.

nodes.label: Greenhouse gas from buildings (million tons CO2 equivalent)
nodes.description: This measures how much nitrous oxide pollution buildings create each year from heating, cooling, and electricity use, converted to the same scale as carbon dioxide for comparison. Higher values mean more pollution from buildings. This matters because building emissions contribute to climate change and affect air quality where people live and work.

nodes.label: Nitrous Oxide Pollution from Factories
nodes.description: This measures how much nitrous oxide gas is released into the atmosphere from industrial processes like cement and chemical production, expressed in millions of tons of CO2 equivalent. Lower values are better as this gas contributes to climate change and ozone layer damage. Reducing industrial pollution helps protect the environment and public health.

nodes.label: Industrial Nitrous Oxide Emissions
nodes.description: This measures the amount of nitrous oxide gas released by factories and industrial facilities each year, converted to the equivalent warming effect of carbon dioxide. Lower values are better for the environment since nitrous oxide contributes to climate change. Reducing industrial emissions helps protect the environment and public health for current and future generations.

nodes.label: Agricultural nitrous oxide emissions
nodes.description: This measures nitrous oxide pollution from farming activities like livestock and fertilizer use, measured in millions of tons of CO2 equivalent. Higher numbers mean more agricultural pollution that contributes to climate change. This matters because farming emissions affect air quality and climate, which impact everyone's health and environment.

nodes.label: Agricultural Methane Emissions
nodes.description: This measures methane gas released by farming activities like livestock digestion, rice cultivation, and fertilizer use, converted to the equivalent warming effect of carbon dioxide. Lower values are better since methane is a potent greenhouse gas. Managing agricultural emissions is important for addressing climate change while maintaining food security for growing populations.

nodes.label: Factory Methane Pollution from Energy Use
nodes.description: This measures methane gas emissions from factories and industrial facilities burning fuels for energy, converted to equivalent carbon dioxide pollution levels. Higher values indicate more greenhouse gas pollution from industry, which contributes to climate change and environmental problems.

nodes.label: CO2 emissions from industrial processes (million tons)
nodes.description: This measures carbon dioxide released into the atmosphere from manufacturing activities like making cement, steel, chemicals, and electronics, not including the energy used to power these processes. Higher emissions contribute more to climate change, so lower values are generally better for environmental health.

nodes.label: CO2 Emissions from Buildings (million tons)
nodes.description: This measures how many million tons of carbon dioxide are released each year from energy use in residential and commercial buildings, including heating, cooling, and electricity. Higher values indicate more greenhouse gas pollution from buildings that contributes to climate change. Lower emissions suggest more energy-efficient buildings and cleaner heating systems.

nodes.label: CO2 emissions from factories and manufacturing
nodes.description: This measures how much carbon dioxide pollution comes from factories, power plants, and construction sites each year, measured in millions of tons. Higher numbers mean more industrial pollution that contributes to climate change. This matters because industrial emissions are a major source of greenhouse gases that harm the environment and public health.

nodes.label: Forest Protection Services Value Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the economic value per person of forests that protect against floods, erosion, and other natural disasters, in 2019 US dollars. Higher values mean forests provide more valuable protection services to each citizen. These forest services help protect communities from natural disasters and environmental damage.

nodes.label: Forest Timber Value
nodes.description: This measures the total economic value of timber resources in a country's forests, expressed in current US dollars. Higher values indicate more valuable timber resources available for harvesting and economic use. This matters because timber resources can provide jobs in forestry and construction industries while supporting economic development when managed sustainably.

nodes.label: Forest Protection Services Value
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of protection services that forests provide, such as preventing floods, filtering water, and storing carbon that would otherwise contribute to climate change. Higher values in US dollars indicate forests are providing more valuable environmental benefits. Healthy forests are essential for clean air, water, and protection from natural disasters.

nodes.label: Forest Water Services Value per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of water-related benefits that forests provide to each person in a country, such as clean water filtration and flood control. Values are in 2019 US dollars per person, where higher values indicate more valuable forest water services. Healthy forests that protect water supplies are crucial for clean drinking water and preventing floods.

nodes.label: Forest timber value per person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of timber resources (wood from forests) available per person in a country, adjusted for inflation to 2019 prices. Higher values mean more forest wealth per citizen. This matters because forests provide economic benefits while also supporting clean air, water, and wildlife that improve quality of life.

nodes.label: Value of forest water services per person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of water-related benefits from forests (like flood control and water filtration) divided by each person in the country. Higher values mean forests provide more valuable water services to each citizen. This matters because these natural services save money on water treatment and flood protection infrastructure.

nodes.label: Economic value of forest water services (current US$)
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of forests' ability to clean water, prevent floods, and regulate water flow in rivers and streams. Higher values indicate forests provide more valuable water-related benefits to society, which supports clean drinking water and reduces flood damage.

nodes.label: Value of forest recreation services per person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of recreational benefits from forests (like hunting, fishing, and tourism) divided by each person in the country. Higher values mean forests provide more valuable recreational opportunities to each citizen. This matters because outdoor recreation supports local economies and improves quality of life.

nodes.label: Forest Recreation Value per Person
nodes.description: This measures the economic value per person of forests used for recreation, hunting, and fishing activities, expressed in 2019 US dollars. Higher values indicate that forests provide more recreational and economic benefits to each citizen. This matters because access to recreational natural areas improves quality of life and can support local economies through tourism and outdoor activities.

nodes.label: Value of Fishery Resources
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of a country's fish populations and fishing industry, including both wild fish stocks and fish farming operations. Higher values indicate more valuable fishing resources that can support livelihoods and food security. Healthy fishery resources provide important protein sources and income opportunities, especially for coastal communities.

nodes.label: Value of Forest Recreation and Hunting Services
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of forests used for recreation, hunting, and fishing activities in US dollars. Higher values indicate forests that provide more economic benefits through tourism and recreational activities. These forest services support local economies and provide important recreational opportunities for communities.

nodes.label: Value of renewable natural resources
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value of natural resources that can renew themselves, like forests, farmland, and fisheries, in current US dollars. Higher values indicate more valuable renewable natural wealth. This matters because these resources can provide sustainable income and jobs while supporting long-term economic development without depleting permanently.

nodes.label: Agricultural Land Value
nodes.description: This measures the total economic value of a country's farmland and pastures for crops and livestock, in 2019 US dollars. Higher values indicate more valuable agricultural resources that can produce food and income. Valuable agricultural land helps ensure food security and provides livelihoods for farmers, supporting overall economic well-being.

nodes.label: Value of Agricultural Land Resources
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of a country's farmland and agricultural resources in US dollars. Higher values indicate more valuable agricultural assets that can generate income over time. Valuable agricultural land provides food security and economic opportunities for rural communities.

nodes.label: Value of Cropland as Natural Resource
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of a country's cropland (farmable land used for growing crops) in US dollars. Higher values indicate more valuable agricultural land resources, either because the country has more cropland or because that land is more productive and valuable. This matters because cropland is essential for food production and agricultural income, which directly affects a nation's ability to feed its people and support farmers' livelihoods.

nodes.label: Economic value of pastureland
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of land used for grazing livestock like cattle, sheep, and goats, expressed in current US dollars. Higher values indicate more valuable pastureland resources, often due to better land quality or higher livestock productivity. Countries with more valuable pastureland typically have stronger agricultural sectors that support rural livelihoods and food security.

nodes.label: Value of Agricultural Land per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of a country's agricultural land divided by its population, showing how much farmable land wealth each person has on average. Values are in current US dollars, with higher amounts indicating more valuable agricultural resources per person. Countries with more valuable farmland per person typically have better food security and agricultural export potential.

nodes.label: Farmland Value Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the dollar value of cropland available for farming divided by the country's population. Higher values mean each person has access to more valuable farmland, which supports food production and agricultural income. Countries with more farmland per person tend to have better food security and agricultural employment opportunities.

nodes.label: Agriculture, Forestry, and Fishing Output Value
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value that farming, forestry, and fishing activities contribute to a country's economy each year. Higher values indicate larger agricultural sectors that produce more crops, livestock, timber, and fish. This matters because agriculture provides food security, rural employment, and can be crucial for a country's export earnings and overall economic stability.

nodes.label: Total Value of Agricultural Production
nodes.description: This measures the total economic value created by farming, forestry, and fishing activities in a country's own currency. Higher values indicate larger or more valuable agricultural sectors, which provide food, jobs, and export income. A strong agricultural sector supports food security and rural livelihoods, though countries typically diversify their economies as they develop.

nodes.label: Agriculture's share of economy
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of a country's total economic output comes from farming, forestry, and fishing. Values typically range from under 5% in wealthy countries to over 30% in agricultural economies. This indicates how much a country depends on agriculture for jobs and income.

nodes.label: Livestock production level
nodes.description: This measures how much meat, milk, eggs, wool, and other animal products a country produces, using 2014-2016 as the baseline of 100. Values above 100 mean production has increased, while below 100 means it has decreased. Higher livestock production helps ensure food security and provides income for farmers.

nodes.label: Farm Crop Production Level
nodes.description: This compares how much food crops a country produces each year to the average amount produced during 2014-2016 (which equals 100). Numbers above 100 mean the country is growing more crops than during that period, while below 100 means less. Higher crop production helps ensure food security and can reduce hunger.

nodes.label: Cereal Grain Production
nodes.description: This measures the total weight of cereal grains (like wheat, rice, corn, and barley) harvested each year for food purposes. Higher production means a country can better feed its population and may have surplus to export. Strong cereal production is crucial for food security and helps protect people from hunger and malnutrition.

nodes.label: Permanent Farmland Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's land is used for permanent crops like coffee, fruit trees, or cocoa that don't need to be replanted each year. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean more land devoted to long-term farming. Countries with more permanent cropland often have more stable food production and agricultural income.

nodes.label: Fertilizer Use per Farm Area
nodes.description: This measures how many kilograms of chemical fertilizer are used per hectare of farmable land each year. Higher values mean farmers are using more fertilizer to boost crop growth, which can increase food production but may also indicate intensive farming practices. Proper fertilizer use helps ensure adequate food production to feed the population.

nodes.label: Agricultural Land as Share of Total Land
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total land area is used for farming, including cropland and pastures for livestock. Values range from 0% to 100%, with the ideal amount depending on the country's needs and geography. This matters because agricultural land determines a country's capacity to produce food and support rural livelihoods, affecting food security and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Fish caught annually (metric tons)
nodes.description: This measures the total weight of fish and other seafood caught by fishermen in a country each year, including commercial fishing and fishing for food. Higher amounts can indicate a productive fishing industry, but if too high, it might mean overfishing that threatens future fish populations and food security.

nodes.label: Land Used for Growing Grains
nodes.description: This measures how many hectares (about 2.5 acres each) are used to grow cereal crops like wheat, rice, corn, and barley for food. More land under cereal production can mean better food security and agricultural income. Adequate cereal production is essential for feeding the population and preventing hunger.

nodes.label: Food Production Compared to 2014-2016
nodes.description: This measures how much food a country produces compared to the average amount it produced in 2014-2016 (which equals 100). Values above 100 mean food production has increased, while values below 100 mean it has decreased. Higher food production helps ensure people have enough to eat and reduces hunger.

nodes.label: Natural Resource Depletion (% of national income)
nodes.description: This measures how much of a country's natural resources (forests, oil, gas, coal, minerals) are being used up each year, expressed as a percentage of national income. Higher percentages mean the country is consuming its natural wealth faster, which may not be sustainable for future generations. Lower values indicate more sustainable resource use.

nodes.label: Forest Loss as Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of forests cut down beyond what naturally grows back, expressed as a percentage of national income. Higher values indicate more forest depletion relative to the economy's size. This matters because excessive forest loss can harm the environment and reduce natural resources that provide long-term economic and environmental benefits.

nodes.label: Total Foreign Currency Reserves
nodes.description: This measures the total amount of foreign money and gold that a country's central bank keeps in reserve, like a national savings account. Higher reserves are generally better because they help protect the country during economic crises and maintain confidence in its currency. Strong reserves allow a country to stabilize its economy during tough times and ensure it can pay for essential imports.

nodes.label: Foreign Currency Reserves
nodes.description: This measures how much foreign currency (like US dollars or euros) a country's government keeps in reserve, excluding gold, reported in US dollars. Higher values mean the country has more financial cushion to handle economic emergencies or maintain its currency's value. Strong reserves help protect a country from financial crises and maintain economic stability for its citizens.

nodes.label: Mineral Resource Depletion Rate
nodes.description: This measures how much of a country's national income comes from using up mineral resources like gold, copper, and iron, expressed as a percentage. Higher values mean the country is depleting its mineral wealth faster relative to its total income. This matters because rapid resource depletion without reinvestment can harm long-term economic sustainability and future generations' prosperity.

nodes.label: Total International Reserves
nodes.description: This shows the total amount of foreign currency, gold, and other international assets that a country's central bank keeps as emergency funds. Higher reserves are generally better because they help protect against economic crises and currency crashes. This matters because countries with larger reserves can better maintain stable exchange rates and continue importing essential goods during tough times.

nodes.label: Mineral Resource Depletion Cost
nodes.description: This estimates the dollar value of minerals (like copper, gold, and iron) that a country extracts from the ground each year, representing the permanent loss of these natural resources. Higher values mean more intensive mining that depletes the country's mineral wealth. This matters because excessive depletion can harm long-term economic sustainability and environmental health.

nodes.label: State Control Over National Territory
nodes.description: Measures how much control the national government has over its entire territory and population. Higher values indicate stronger state control and presence throughout the country. When governments can effectively govern all areas under their authority, they can better provide essential services like security, healthcare, and education to all citizens.

nodes.label: Average Net Business Surplus for Nonprofits
nodes.description: This measures the average profit or surplus that nonprofit organizations generate after covering their expenses. Higher values indicate nonprofits are generating more extra funds that can be used for their missions. Healthy nonprofit surpluses help ensure these organizations can continue providing important social services and programs.

nodes.label: Average Net Economic Surplus Per Person
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of money left over per person after accounting for all income and necessary expenses in the economy. Higher values indicate people have more economic surplus available for savings and investments. This matters because economic surplus shows how well an economy provides for people's needs while still allowing them to build wealth.

nodes.label: Central Bank Regulatory Difference
nodes.description: This measures differences in central bank regulatory policies or approaches compared to a baseline or other countries. Higher values indicate greater regulatory divergence. This matters because central bank policies affect interest rates, inflation, and overall economic stability that impacts everyone's finances.

nodes.label: Natural resource income (% of economy)
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country earns from oil, gas, mining, and forests as a percentage of its total economic output. Higher percentages mean the economy depends more heavily on natural resources. While resource wealth can boost incomes, over-dependence can make economies vulnerable when resource prices drop.

nodes.label: Economic Growth Rate (annual %)
nodes.description: This measures how much a country's total economic output grew or shrank compared to the previous year, shown as a percentage. Positive values mean the economy is growing, while negative values mean it's shrinking. Higher growth rates generally indicate improving living standards, more jobs, and better opportunities for citizens.

nodes.label: Investment in buildings and equipment (% of economy)
nodes.description: This measures how much a country spends on building new factories, roads, schools, and buying equipment as a percentage of its total economic output. Higher percentages suggest a country is investing more in future growth. Strong investment rates help create jobs and improve living standards over time.

nodes.label: Mining Industry Profits as Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total economic output comes from profits from mining minerals like gold, copper, and iron ore. Values range from near 0% to over 20% for very mining-dependent countries. While mining can boost income, over-dependence on natural resources can make economies unstable when prices change.

nodes.label: Average Property Value Gains
nodes.description: This measures how much the average person's property (like houses, land, and buildings) increased in value over a certain period. Higher values mean property owners saw their assets become more valuable. This matters because property gains build household wealth and financial security, though rapid increases can also make housing less affordable for buyers.

nodes.label: Government Debt as Share of Economy
nodes.description: This measures how much money the central government owes compared to the size of the country's entire economy, expressed as a percentage. Higher percentages mean the government has more debt relative to economic output - for example, 60% means debt equals 60% of the country's annual economic production. High government debt can limit spending on public services and economic growth.

nodes.label: Total imports of goods and services
nodes.description: This measures the total value of goods, services, and investment income that a country purchases from other countries, measured in current US dollars. Higher values can indicate either strong domestic demand and purchasing power, or dependence on foreign products. The impact on living standards depends on whether imports complement domestic production or crowd out local jobs.

nodes.label: Total Export Earnings
nodes.description: This measures the total dollar value a country earns from selling goods and services to other countries, plus income from investments abroad. Higher values indicate stronger international economic activity and more foreign currency earnings. Strong exports provide jobs and income that help fund imports, government services, and economic development that improves citizens' quality of life.

nodes.label: Foreign Investment Assets
nodes.description: This measures the total value of investments and assets that a country owns in other countries, in constant 2019 US dollars. Higher positive values mean the country owns more foreign investments than it owes to other countries. Countries with more foreign assets have greater financial security and international economic influence.

nodes.label: Non-Technical Grants Received
nodes.description: This measures the dollar amount of free money, goods, or services that a country receives from other countries or organizations, excluding technical assistance. These grants don't need to be paid back and can support various development needs. Higher amounts indicate more international financial support, which helps countries fund important projects and services that improve people's lives.

nodes.label: Household Spending (constant 2015 US$)
nodes.description: This measures the total amount families and households spend on goods and services like food, housing, clothing, and entertainment. The amount is measured in constant 2015 US dollars, adjusted for inflation to compare across years. Higher values indicate people have more money to spend on their daily needs and wants, reflecting better living standards.

nodes.label: Foreign financial assets per person
nodes.description: This measures how much money and investments a country owns in other countries minus what it owes, divided by population and adjusted for inflation. Higher values mean the country is a net lender to the world. This matters because foreign assets can provide income and financial security that benefits the overall economy.

nodes.label: Government Spending on Services
nodes.description: This measures how much money the government spends on goods and services like employee salaries, supplies, and defense, expressed in current US dollars. Higher values mean the government spends more on public services and operations. This matters because government spending provides essential services like education, healthcare, and security that improve citizens' daily lives and wellbeing.

nodes.label: Foreign investments and assets (billions US$)
nodes.description: This measures the total value of investments, bank accounts, and other assets that a country owns in foreign countries. Higher values indicate more international financial connections and wealth stored abroad. Foreign assets can provide countries with income and financial security during economic challenges.

nodes.label: Foreign currency reserves in months of imports
nodes.description: This measures how many months a country could continue paying for imports using only its foreign currency reserves (like US dollars, euros, or gold). Higher values indicate better financial security - for example, 6 months of reserves is generally considered safer than 2 months. Countries with more reserves can better handle economic crises and maintain stable exchange rates.

nodes.label: Oil and Gas Revenue Value (2000 Baseline)
nodes.description: This measures the economic value of a country's oil and gas production using the year 2000 as a baseline for comparison. Higher values indicate greater oil and gas wealth relative to the economy. This matters because oil and gas revenues can fund development projects and government services, but heavy dependence on these resources can also make economies unstable.

nodes.label: Oil Price Index
nodes.description: This tracks the international market price of crude oil, which affects energy costs worldwide. Higher prices mean more expensive gasoline, heating, and transportation costs for consumers. Oil prices matter because they influence inflation, economic growth, and the cost of living for everyone.

nodes.label: Renewable Energy Use Rate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total energy consumption comes from renewable sources like solar, wind, and hydroelectric power. Values range from 0-100%, where higher percentages mean the country relies more on clean energy sources. This matters because renewable energy reduces pollution and climate change while often providing more stable, long-term energy costs for consumers.

nodes.label: Energy Resource Depletion Rate
nodes.description: This measures how much of a country's total income comes from using up energy resources like oil, gas, and coal that can't be replaced. Higher percentages indicate the economy depends heavily on resources that will eventually run out, making long-term economic planning more challenging.

nodes.label: Household Energy Consumption Distribution
nodes.description: This measures how much energy (in gigawatt-hours) households use for fuel needs like cooking, heating, and lighting, and how this energy use is distributed across the population. Higher values indicate greater household energy consumption. This matters because energy access affects quality of life, while energy distribution patterns show inequality in basic living conditions.

nodes.label: Household Energy Consumption
nodes.description: This measures how much energy households use for cooking, heating, and other home needs, measured in gigawatt-hours at the national level. Higher values can indicate either more energy access (good) or less energy efficiency (concerning). Adequate household energy access is essential for basic living standards and health.

nodes.label: Fuel Imports as Share of All Imports
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of all the goods a country buys from other countries consists of fuels like oil, gas, and coal. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean the country spends more of its import money on energy. Countries that import less fuel tend to have more energy independence and lower vulnerability to oil price changes.

nodes.label: Household Energy Use Per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much energy the average person uses at home for cooking, heating, and lighting. Higher values could indicate either better access to modern energy or wasteful consumption. This matters because adequate energy access is essential for basic needs, but excessive use can harm the environment and increase costs.

nodes.label: Industrial Fuel Consumption Per Person
nodes.description: This measures how much fuel (oil, gas, coal) industries use per person in a country each year. Higher values indicate more industrial fuel consumption per capita, which often reflects higher industrial activity but also higher pollution. This matters because it shows the balance between economic development and environmental impact in a country.

nodes.label: Climate Readiness Score
nodes.description: This measures how prepared a country is to effectively use climate adaptation investments and respond to climate change challenges. Scores typically range from 0-100, with higher scores indicating better readiness through factors like governance, education, and infrastructure. This matters because countries with higher readiness can better protect their citizens from climate impacts.

nodes.label: Climate Readiness Economic Capacity
nodes.description: This measures a country's economic ability to invest in climate change adaptation based on its GDP per capita. Higher scores indicate the country has more economic resources available to prepare for and respond to climate threats. Countries with stronger economies are better positioned to protect their citizens from climate impacts.

nodes.label: Climate Adaptation Capacity
nodes.description: This measures how well a country can prepare for and adapt to climate change impacts like floods, droughts, and extreme weather. Higher scores indicate better capacity to handle climate challenges through infrastructure, technology, and institutions. Countries with higher adaptation capacity are better positioned to protect their people and economy from climate-related disasters.

nodes.label: Healthcare Climate Adaptation Score
nodes.description: This measures how well a country's healthcare system is prepared to handle climate change impacts like heat waves, floods, and disease outbreaks. Higher scores indicate better preparedness and lower vulnerability. This matters because climate change increasingly threatens public health and healthcare infrastructure.

nodes.label: Private Bank Lending Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of total bank lending comes from private sector banks rather than government-owned banks. Higher percentages indicate more private sector involvement in banking. This matters because private bank competition often leads to better services, more business loans, and greater access to credit for families and entrepreneurs.

nodes.label: Women's Access to Family Planning
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women who want to plan or space their pregnancies and have access to modern family planning methods like contraception. Higher percentages indicate better reproductive healthcare and women's rights. This matters because it affects women's health, education, and economic opportunities, as well as family welfare.

nodes.label: Forest Land Use
nodes.description: This measures the amount of land covered by forests in a country, usually as a percentage of total land area. Higher percentages indicate more forest coverage, which is generally better for the environment. Forests matter because they provide clean air and water, prevent soil erosion, and support wildlife while also providing wood and other resources.

nodes.label: Poverty Line Growth Rate
nodes.description: This measures how much the official poverty line (the minimum income needed for basic living) changes each year, usually as a percentage. Higher growth rates mean it's becoming more expensive to meet basic needs. This is important because it shows whether the cost of essential goods like food and housing is rising faster than people's incomes.

nodes.label: Overall Development Index
nodes.description: This measures a country's overall level of development by combining economic, social, and human welfare indicators into a single score. Higher scores indicate better overall development and living conditions. This matters because it shows how well a country is progressing in improving the lives of its people across multiple areas.

nodes.label: Real Consumption Share
nodes.description: This shows what percentage of a country's total economic output goes to household consumption after adjusting for price differences. Higher values mean more of the economy serves consumer needs. This matters because it indicates whether economic growth is improving living standards for ordinary people.

nodes.label: Household Lending Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of all bank loans go to households (for mortgages, car loans, credit cards) rather than to businesses. Higher percentages indicate more consumer borrowing and household debt. This matters because high household debt can make families financially vulnerable during economic downturns.

nodes.label: State Control Over Armed Forces
nodes.description: Measures whether the national government has effective control over all major armed forces and militias within its territory. Higher scores indicate stronger state control over military groups. This matters because unified control of armed forces prevents civil conflict and ensures the military serves the public rather than private interests.

nodes.label: Government's Ability to Collect Taxes
nodes.description: Measures how effectively the government can collect taxes and generate revenue to fund public services and infrastructure. Higher values (0-4 scale) indicate stronger tax collection capacity and fiscal management. This matters because governments need tax revenue to provide essential services like healthcare, education, roads, and security that improve people's daily lives.

nodes.label: Alcohol Consumption Per Adult
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of pure alcohol consumed per person aged 15 and older each year, measured in liters. Higher values indicate greater alcohol consumption in the population. High alcohol consumption can indicate public health challenges and social problems that affect productivity and healthcare costs.

nodes.label: Executive: No Control of Head of Government
nodes.description: Measures whether other branches of government (like legislature or courts) have zero control over the head of government's actions. Higher scores indicate the executive operates without any checks from other government branches. This matters because unchecked executive power can lead to abuse of authority.

nodes.label: Executive: Judicial Dismissals (Data Quality)
nodes.description: This tracks how often experts couldn't answer questions about whether the executive branch dismisses or pressures judges. Higher values mean more experts didn't know or didn't respond to questions about judicial independence from executive interference. This measures the availability of information, not actual judicial independence.

nodes.label: Executive Respects Judicial Decisions (Ordinal Scale)
nodes.description: This measures how often the executive branch (president or prime minister) actually follows court rulings and judicial decisions, even when they disagree with them. The ordinal scale typically runs 0-4, where higher values mean greater compliance with court decisions. This matters because it ensures laws apply equally to everyone, including those in power.

nodes.label: Executive Respects Judicial Decisions (Average Score)
nodes.description: This is the average expert rating of how consistently the executive branch follows court orders and judicial rulings. The scale runs 0-1, where higher values mean the president or prime minister more often complies with court decisions, even unfavorable ones. This matters because it ensures the rule of law applies equally to all citizens, including government leaders.

nodes.label: Executive Control of Higher Government (Category 3)
nodes.description: This measures a specific level of how much the chief executive (president or prime minister) controls other high-level government positions and decisions. This category represents a particular degree of executive control on the survey scale. Balanced executive power ensures effective governance while preventing authoritarian control that could harm democratic institutions.

nodes.label: Executive Control: Head of Government Selection (Category 1)
nodes.description: This indicates whether the head of government (like a prime minister) is selected through a specific method, with the '1' representing one particular selection process. This measures one category of how countries choose their chief executive who runs day-to-day government operations. How leaders are chosen affects whether they truly represent the people's interests and needs.

nodes.label: Executive Removes Head of Government (Category 8)
nodes.description: This measures a specific way that a country's chief executive (like a president or prime minister) can be removed from power, focusing on one particular removal mechanism. The value represents whether this specific removal method exists or was used. Different removal mechanisms help ensure leaders can be held accountable when they abuse power or fail to govern effectively.

nodes.label: Head of State Removal Method
nodes.description: This measures one specific way (category 1) that a country's head of state can be removed from office, likely through constitutional or legal processes. This indicator tracks whether this particular removal method exists in the country's political system. Having clear, legal ways to remove leaders helps prevent abuse of power and maintains democratic accountability.

nodes.label: Executive Removal - Military Coup (Category 7)
nodes.description: Indicates whether the head of government was removed from office through a military coup (coded as category 7). This is a binary indicator where 1 means removal by military coup occurred, 0 means it did not. Military coups undermine democratic governance and often lead to political instability and reduced rights for citizens.

nodes.label: Executive Removal by Legislature (Category 5)
nodes.description: This measures a specific aspect of whether the legislature can remove the chief executive from office through legal procedures like impeachment. This represents the highest category of legislative power to check executive authority. Strong legislative oversight helps prevent abuse of power by government leaders.

nodes.label: Executive Theft from State
nodes.description: Measures how often the chief executive (president/prime minister) steals money or resources from the government for personal use. Higher values indicate more frequent theft by top leaders. Executive corruption wastes public resources that could be used for education, healthcare, and other services.

nodes.label: Executive Theft from State (Data Availability)
nodes.description: Shows how many experts didn't respond to questions about executive officials stealing from the state, not the actual level of theft. Lower values mean better data coverage, as more experts provided information about government corruption and embezzlement. Good data on government theft helps citizens and international organizations identify and address corruption.

nodes.label: Head of State and Government Combined
nodes.description: This measures whether the same person serves as both head of state (ceremonial leader) and head of government (actual executive power), typically coded as 0 for separate roles or 1 for combined. When one person holds both roles, they have more concentrated power. The separation of these roles can provide important checks on executive power and prevent authoritarian rule.

nodes.label: Executive Power: Head of State's Role in Government
nodes.description: This measures what role the head of state (like a president or monarch) plays in the country's government and how much real power they have. Different numerical values represent different types of leadership roles, from ceremonial figureheads to powerful executives. This matters because it shows who really makes important decisions that affect citizens' daily lives.

nodes.label: Political Equality: Gender Exclusion Index
nodes.description: Measures how much women are excluded from political power and participation compared to men. Higher scores indicate greater gender inequality in politics. This matters because when women have equal political representation, policies better reflect the needs of all citizens, not just half the population.

nodes.label: Federal vs Unitary Government Index
nodes.description: This measures whether a country has a federal system (power shared between national and state governments) or a unitary system (central government holds most power). Higher values indicate more federal characteristics with greater state or regional autonomy. This affects how close government decisions are to local communities.

nodes.label: Political Equality: Exclusion from Politics Index
nodes.description: This measures how much certain groups are excluded from participating in politics based on their identity, wealth, or social status. Values range from 0-1, where higher scores mean less exclusion and more equal political participation for all groups. This matters because when everyone can participate in politics equally, governments are more likely to represent all citizens' needs.

nodes.label: Direct Democracy Index
nodes.description: This measures how much a country allows citizens to directly participate in making laws through referendums, ballot initiatives, and citizen assemblies. The scale runs from 0 to 1, where higher values mean more opportunities for direct citizen participation in government decisions. Strong direct democracy gives people more control over policies that affect their daily lives.

nodes.label: Property Rights Protection Index
nodes.description: This measures how well the legal system protects people's rights to own property, businesses, and assets from seizure by the government or others. Higher scores (0-1 scale) indicate stronger property protections, which encourages investment and economic growth that benefits everyone.

nodes.label: Direct Democracy Index (Pluralist)
nodes.description: This measures how much citizens can directly participate in government decisions through tools like referendums, ballot initiatives, and citizen assemblies, from a pluralist perspective that values multiple viewpoints. The scale runs from 0 to 1, where higher scores mean more opportunities for direct citizen participation in lawmaking. Strong direct democracy gives people more control over policies that affect their daily lives.

nodes.label: Gender Development Index for Income
nodes.description: This measures how equally income is distributed between men and women, with values typically between 0 and 1, where 1 means perfect gender equality in earnings. Higher values indicate women earn closer to what men earn. This matters because income equality between genders reflects fair economic opportunities and helps families achieve better living standards.

nodes.label: Democratic Competition and Participation Index
nodes.description: Measures how democratic a country is by looking at political competition between parties and citizen participation in elections. Higher scores indicate more competitive elections and broader political participation. This matters because competitive democracy with high participation typically leads to better government responsiveness to citizens' needs.

nodes.label: Education System Democratic Values Input
nodes.description: This measures how much a country's education system incorporates democratic values like tolerance, critical thinking, and civic participation into teaching. Higher values indicate stronger emphasis on democratic education. Schools that teach democratic values help create citizens who can participate effectively in democratic society.

nodes.label: Education Index: Centralized Media Control (Central Estimate)
nodes.description: This composite index measures how much the central government controls educational media and information sources that students access. Higher values indicate more centralized control over educational content, textbooks, and media in schools. Government control of educational media can ensure consistent messaging but may limit students' access to diverse perspectives.

nodes.label: Horizontal Accountability Index
nodes.description: This measures how well government branches (like courts and legislatures) can check and limit the power of the executive branch. Values range from 0-1, where higher scores mean stronger checks and balances between government institutions. Strong horizontal accountability prevents any single leader or branch from becoming too powerful, protecting citizens from government abuse.

nodes.label: Educational Content Control Index
nodes.description: This composite index measures who controls educational content and curriculum decisions in a country's school system, from government agencies to local communities to individual schools. Values range from 0-1, where the scale reflects different levels of centralized versus decentralized control. Appropriate educational governance helps ensure quality schooling that meets both national standards and local needs.

nodes.label: Democratic Index: Media and Income Components
nodes.description: This is a composite score combining measures of media freedom and income-related aspects of democracy. Higher scores (0-1 scale) indicate better media freedom and more equal economic participation in democratic processes. This matters because free media and economic equality help ensure all citizens can participate meaningfully in democracy.

nodes.label: Electoral Democracy Index: Comprehensive Competition
nodes.description: This is a comprehensive measure of electoral competition, including multiple aspects of how fairly and competitively elections are conducted. Higher scores (0-1 scale) indicate more competitive and fair electoral processes. This matters because competitive elections give citizens real choices and hold politicians accountable for their performance.

nodes.label: Educational Freedom and Media Diversity Index
nodes.description: This combines measures of educational freedom and media diversity to show how openly information flows in society through schools and news outlets. The scale runs from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate more diverse viewpoints in education and media. Free flow of diverse information helps citizens make informed decisions about their lives and government.

nodes.label: Clientelism in Politics Index
nodes.description: This measures how much politicians use clientelism - giving money, jobs, or favors to voters in exchange for political support, rather than serving the public interest. The scale runs 0-1, where higher values indicate more clientelistic practices. Lower clientelism matters because it means politicians focus on policies that benefit everyone rather than just rewarding their supporters.

nodes.label: Presidential Power Constraints Index
nodes.description: Measures how much legal and institutional limits restrict a president's power, combining multiple related indicators. Higher values indicate stronger constraints on presidential authority through checks and balances, constitutional limits, and oversight mechanisms. Limited presidential power prevents abuse of authority and protects citizens from government overreach.

nodes.label: Government Corruption Index
nodes.description: Measures the level of corruption in government institutions, including bribery, misuse of public funds, and abuse of power for personal gain. Scores range from 0 to 3, where higher values indicate more corruption. Low corruption is essential because it ensures public resources go toward improving citizens' lives rather than enriching officials.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties Index
nodes.description: This measures the protection of basic personal freedoms like freedom of speech, religion, movement, and privacy from government interference. The index ranges from 0 to 1, where higher scores indicate stronger protection of civil liberties. Strong civil liberties are essential because they allow people to express themselves, practice their beliefs, and live their lives without fear of government persecution.

nodes.label: Civil Liberties Protection Index
nodes.description: Measures how well a country protects basic civil liberties like freedom of speech, religion, and movement. Scored on a scale where higher values (closer to 4) indicate stronger protection of individual rights and freedoms. This matters because civil liberties allow people to express themselves, practice their beliefs, and live without fear of government persecution.

nodes.label: Egalitarian Democracy Index
nodes.description: Measures how equally political power and resources are distributed across different social groups, including by income, gender, and ethnicity. Higher values (closer to 5) indicate more equal participation in democracy. This matters because when all groups have equal political voice, policies are more likely to benefit everyone rather than just the wealthy or powerful.

nodes.label: Agricultural Wealth and Finance Index
nodes.description: This measures the financial health and wealth accumulation in a country's agricultural sector, including farm assets, investments, and financial resources. Higher values indicate a stronger, more financially stable farming sector. This matters because agricultural financial strength affects food security, rural employment, and overall economic stability.

nodes.label: Economic Indicator (Consumption-Related)
nodes.description: This appears to be an economic indicator related to consumption or wealth distribution patterns among adults. Without more context, the specific measurement and scale are unclear, but it likely tracks economic well-being or spending patterns. Understanding consumption patterns helps assess living standards and economic health.

nodes.label: Economic Indicator (Wealth or Debt-Related)
nodes.description: This appears to be an economic indicator possibly related to wealth distribution or debt levels among adults, though the specific measurement is unclear. It likely tracks some aspect of financial well-being or economic inequality. Understanding wealth and debt patterns helps assess economic stability and inequality in society.

nodes.label: Average Capital Wealth Income (All Categories)
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from their wealth assets like investments, property, and savings across all population groups. Higher values indicate people are earning more money from their assets rather than just wages. This matters because wealth income often provides financial security and shows how well a country's economy allows people to build long-term prosperity.

nodes.label: Average Capital Income Per Adult
nodes.description: This measures the average amount of income that adults earn from owning assets like stocks, bonds, real estate, or business equity. Values are typically in thousands of dollars per person, and higher values indicate more wealth from investments. This matters because capital income often provides financial security and shows how wealth is distributed in society.

nodes.label: Average Agricultural Wealth
nodes.description: This measures the average value of agricultural assets like farmland, livestock, and farm equipment owned by people in a country. Higher values indicate people own more valuable farming-related wealth. This matters because agricultural wealth provides economic security and productive capacity, especially in rural areas where farming is a major source of livelihood.

nodes.label: Raw Materials Trade Volume
nodes.description: This measures how much a country trades in crude materials like metals, wood, cotton, and other unprocessed natural resources. Higher values can indicate either strong natural resource exports or high industrial demand for raw inputs. This matters because raw material trade affects jobs in mining, farming, and manufacturing sectors.

nodes.label: Manufactured Goods Trade Value
nodes.description: This measures the total value of manufactured products (like machinery, textiles, chemicals, and electronics) that a country imports and exports. Higher values indicate more industrial trade activity. This matters because manufacturing trade creates jobs, brings in foreign currency, and provides access to products that improve living standards and economic competitiveness.

nodes.label: Animal and Vegetable Oils Trade
nodes.description: This measures a country's imports and exports of animal fats and vegetable oils like palm oil, soybean oil, and butter. Values are typically in dollars or tons, with higher numbers indicating more trade activity. Strong trade in these essential food ingredients reflects agricultural productivity and food security.

nodes.label: Beverages and Tobacco Trade
nodes.description: This measures the value of beverages and tobacco products that a country imports and exports. Higher values indicate more international trade in drinks, alcohol, and tobacco products. This trade activity contributes to the economy but also reflects consumption patterns that can affect public health, especially regarding alcohol and tobacco use.

nodes.label: Number of Physiotherapists
nodes.description: This counts the total number of licensed physiotherapists working in a country's healthcare system. Higher numbers relative to population indicate better access to rehabilitation services. This matters because adequate physiotherapy services help people recover from injuries, manage chronic conditions, and maintain mobility and quality of life.

nodes.label: Hepatitis B Vaccination Coverage
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of people (usually infants) who have received the hepatitis B vaccine, which protects against a liver infection that can cause lifelong illness. Higher percentages are better because more people are protected from disease. Good vaccination coverage helps prevent outbreaks and keeps communities healthy.

nodes.label: Labor Force Participation - Basic Education
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of people with basic education who are either working or actively looking for work. Higher percentages mean more people with basic education are participating in the job market rather than staying home or in school. High participation indicates these workers can find opportunities, supporting economic growth and household incomes.

nodes.label: Labor Force Participation - Basic Education, Women
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women with basic education who are either working or actively seeking employment. Higher rates indicate more women are participating in the formal economy rather than only doing unpaid household work. Greater female workforce participation boosts family incomes and promotes gender equality in economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Electric Power Consumption per Capita
nodes.description: This measures how much electricity each person uses on average per year, typically measured in kilowatt-hours. Higher consumption often indicates industrial development, better living standards, and access to modern appliances and technology. However, very high consumption may also suggest energy inefficiency or waste.

nodes.label: Labor Force Participation Rate - Intermediate Education
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of people with intermediate education (like high school or technical training) who are either working or actively looking for work. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher rates generally indicate a more engaged workforce and better economic opportunities for educated people. Higher participation rates usually mean the economy is making good use of its educated workers.

nodes.label: Female Mortality Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many women die per 1,000 women in a given age group each year, often focusing on maternal mortality (deaths during pregnancy and childbirth). Lower numbers are better because they indicate that fewer women are dying from preventable causes. Lower female mortality rates reflect better healthcare systems, nutrition, and living conditions.

nodes.label: Female Labor Force Participation (Intermediate Education)
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women with intermediate education levels (like high school) who are working or actively seeking work. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages mean more educated women are participating in the economy. Higher female participation typically leads to stronger economic growth and better family incomes.

nodes.label: Female Labor Force Participation Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of women age 15 and older who are working or actively looking for work. Values range from about 10% to 90% across different countries. Higher participation rates typically indicate better economic opportunities for women and contribute to stronger overall economic growth and family prosperity.

nodes.label: Self-Employed, Female (% of female employment)
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of working women are self-employed, meaning they run their own businesses or work for themselves rather than for an employer. Values range from 0% to 100%, and the meaning of higher or lower rates depends on the context - it could indicate entrepreneurship opportunities or lack of formal job options. This shows how women participate in the economy and their access to different types of work.

nodes.label: Labor Force Participation Rate, Basic Education, Male
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of men with basic education (elementary or some secondary school) are either working or actively looking for work. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher rates generally indicate more economic opportunity. This shows how well the economy provides job opportunities for men with limited formal education.

nodes.label: Adult Literacy Rate
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of adults (usually 15 years and older) who can read and write simple statements about their daily life. Values range from 0% to 100%, with higher percentages being better. Higher literacy rates enable people to access better jobs, healthcare information, and participate more fully in society.

nodes.label: Access to Clean Energy and Lighting
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of people who have access to clean, modern energy sources for cooking, heating, and lighting instead of relying on wood, coal, or kerosene. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because clean energy is safer and healthier. Access to clean energy reduces indoor air pollution and prevents respiratory diseases, especially in women and children.

nodes.label: Electricity Production from Hydroelectric Sources
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total electricity comes from water-powered generators like dams and river turbines. The rate is expressed as a percentage of total electricity production. Higher percentages indicate cleaner, renewable energy sources that reduce pollution and provide sustainable power for economic development.

nodes.label: Government Debt as Percentage of GDP
nodes.description: This measures how much money a government owes compared to the total value of goods and services the country produces in a year. It's expressed as a percentage where higher values mean more debt relative to economic size. Very high debt levels can limit a government's ability to provide services and invest in development.

nodes.label: Electricity Production from Oil Sources
nodes.description: This measures how much of a country's electricity comes from burning oil, usually shown as a percentage of total electricity production. Higher percentages mean the country relies more heavily on oil for power generation, which can be expensive and creates more pollution. Countries with lower oil dependence for electricity often have more diverse and cleaner energy sources.

nodes.label: Primary Teacher-Student Ratio
nodes.description: This measures how many elementary school students there are for each teacher, shown as a ratio like 25:1 or just as the number 25. Lower numbers are better because they mean smaller class sizes, which typically allows teachers to give more individual attention to each student. Smaller classes are linked to better learning outcomes and educational quality.

nodes.label: Primary Education Expenditure
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country spends on primary education, usually as a percentage of total government spending or GDP. Higher values indicate greater investment in elementary schooling. Countries that invest more in primary education typically see better literacy rates, economic growth, and opportunities for their citizens to escape poverty.

nodes.label: Adult Literacy Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of adults (typically 15 years and older) who can read and write simple sentences. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages indicate more educated populations. Higher literacy rates are essential for economic development, democratic participation, and individuals' ability to access information and opportunities.

nodes.label: Trade in Services
nodes.description: This measures the total value of services (like banking, tourism, consulting, or technology support) that a country buys from and sells to other countries, usually in US dollars or as a percentage of GDP. Higher values often indicate a more modern, diversified economy that can compete globally in high-skill sectors. Strong service trade can boost economic growth and create better-paying jobs.

nodes.label: Tax Revenue (% of GDP)
nodes.description: This measures how much money a government collects in taxes compared to the total size of the country's economy, expressed as a percentage. Higher percentages mean the government collects more taxes relative to economic output, which can fund more public services like schools and hospitals. The ideal level varies, but adequate tax revenue helps governments provide essential services to their citizens.

nodes.label: Unemployment Rate - Basic Education, Men
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of men with basic education who are actively looking for work but cannot find jobs. The value is expressed as a percentage, where higher numbers indicate more unemployment and economic problems. High unemployment among men with basic education signals limited job opportunities for less-skilled workers, which affects family income and community well-being.

nodes.label: Female Unemployment Rate with No Education
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women with no formal education are unemployed and actively looking for work. The rate is expressed as a percentage, where higher values indicate more unemployment among uneducated women. Lower rates are better as they show that even women without formal education can find jobs, indicating inclusive economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Unemployment Rate - No Education
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of people without formal education who are actively looking for work but cannot find a job. Values can range from near 0% to very high percentages, where lower rates are better because they mean more uneducated people can still find employment. High unemployment among uneducated workers often indicates limited opportunities for people without schooling, which can increase poverty and inequality.

nodes.label: Youth Unemployment Rate - No Education
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of young people (typically ages 15-24) without formal education who are looking for work but cannot find a job. Lower percentages are better because high youth unemployment can lead to social problems and wasted human potential. When educated young people can't find work, it often signals economic problems and can lead to emigration or social unrest.

nodes.label: Youth Unemployment Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of young people (typically ages 15-24) who are actively looking for work but cannot find jobs. Values range from 0% to over 50%, where higher percentages indicate more young people struggling to find employment. High youth unemployment can lead to social problems and waste human potential, while low rates suggest young people have good opportunities to start their careers.

nodes.label: Male Unemployment Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of men who are actively looking for work but cannot find jobs. Values typically range from 2% to 30%, where higher percentages indicate more men struggling with joblessness. Lower male unemployment generally means stronger economic conditions and better opportunities for families to earn stable incomes.

nodes.label: Neonatal Mortality Rate
nodes.description: This measures how many newborn babies die within their first 28 days of life per 1,000 live births in a country each year. Lower numbers are better, indicating fewer baby deaths and better healthcare for newborns. Countries with lower neonatal mortality rates typically have better hospitals, medical care, and support for pregnant mothers.

nodes.label: Unemployment Rate, Female, ILO Estimate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women who want to work cannot find jobs, using international labor organization standards. Values range from 0% to 100%, where lower percentages are better, indicating more women can find employment. Lower female unemployment rates suggest a healthier economy with better job opportunities for women.

nodes.label: Internet Revenue
nodes.description: This measures the total revenue generated from internet services in a country, typically expressed in current US dollars. Higher values indicate a larger digital economy and more internet-based business activity. Strong internet revenue shows a country's digital economy is developing, which creates jobs and improves access to online services for citizens.

nodes.label: Male Secondary Education Completion Rate
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys successfully finish high school or secondary education. The rate is expressed as a percentage, where higher values indicate more boys are completing their education. Higher completion rates lead to better job opportunities, higher incomes, and stronger economic development for the whole country.

nodes.label: Education Expenditure per Student - US Dollars
nodes.description: This measures how much money a country spends on each student's education per year, converted to US dollars for comparison between countries. Higher amounts are generally better because they indicate more resources for teachers, books, facilities, and educational programs. Greater spending per student often leads to better educational outcomes and higher graduation rates.

nodes.label: Energy Use Per Capita
nodes.description: This measures how much energy each person uses on average, typically measured in kilograms of oil equivalent per person per year. Values range from about 300 to over 20,000, where higher numbers indicate more energy consumption. Moderate energy use often reflects decent living standards, but extremely high use may indicate inefficiency or environmental concerns.

nodes.label: Renewable Energy Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total energy consumption comes from renewable sources like solar, wind, water, and biomass instead of fossil fuels like oil and coal. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are generally better for the environment. Countries with higher renewable energy use typically have cleaner air and contribute less to climate change.

nodes.label: Rural Population Growth Rate
nodes.description: This tracks how fast the rural (countryside) population is growing each year, expressed as an annual percentage. Positive values mean rural areas are gaining people, while negative values mean people are leaving for cities. This indicator helps show migration patterns and whether rural communities are thriving or declining, which affects agricultural development and rural services.

nodes.label: Total Population Growth Rate
nodes.description: This tracks how fast a country's total population is growing each year, expressed as an annual percentage. Positive values mean the population is increasing, while negative values indicate population decline. Population growth affects job markets, healthcare needs, and economic planning, influencing everything from school construction to pension systems.

nodes.label: Total Population
nodes.description: This measures the total number of people living in a country at a given time, usually counted in millions. The number itself isn't good or bad, but population size affects everything from economic growth to resource needs and environmental impact. Understanding population helps governments plan for housing, schools, healthcare, and jobs.

nodes.label: Life Expectancy - Men
nodes.description: This measures the average number of years a newborn boy is expected to live if current death rates remain the same. Values are expressed in years, with higher numbers indicating better health outcomes. Longer male life expectancy reflects better healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions, showing overall quality of life improvements.

nodes.label: Life Expectancy at Birth
nodes.description: This measures the average number of years a newborn baby is expected to live if current health conditions and death rates stay the same. Values are expressed in years, with higher numbers being better. Longer life expectancy indicates better healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions that allow people to live healthier, longer lives.

nodes.label: Female Life Expectancy
nodes.description: This measures how many years a newborn girl is expected to live based on current health conditions and mortality rates. Values typically range from about 50 to 85 years, where higher numbers indicate better healthcare, nutrition, and living conditions. Higher life expectancy reflects better quality of life and more developed healthcare systems.

nodes.label: Gross Enrollment Rate - Tertiary Education
nodes.description: This measures the total number of students enrolled in universities and colleges as a percentage of the population in the typical college-age group. Values above 100% are possible when many older or younger students also attend. Higher enrollment rates indicate better access to higher education, which leads to more skilled workers and economic growth.
