nodes.label: Female Gross Enrollment Rate in Tertiary Education
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of women of college age (typically 18-23) are enrolled in higher education like universities, colleges, or technical schools. The rate is expressed as a percentage and can exceed 100% when students outside the typical age range also enroll. Higher rates indicate better access to higher education for women, which leads to greater economic opportunities and gender equality.

nodes.label: Female Primary School Enrollment Rate
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of school-age girls who are enrolled in primary school, which can exceed 100% when older or younger children also attend. Higher values indicate more girls are receiving basic education. Better female education leads to improved health outcomes, reduced poverty, and stronger economic development for entire communities.

nodes.label: Gross Enrollment Ratio, Tertiary, Male
nodes.description: This measures how many males are enrolled in higher education (colleges and universities) compared to the total number of males in the typical college-age group, expressed as a percentage. Values above 100% are possible when older or younger students also attend. Higher enrollment rates indicate better access to higher education for men in that country.

nodes.label: Net Enrollment Rate in Secondary Education - Male
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of boys of high school age are actually enrolled in secondary school. The rate is expressed as a percentage and stays at or below 100% since it only counts students of the official age range. Higher rates mean more boys are getting secondary education, which is crucial for developing job skills and economic opportunities.

nodes.label: Net Enrollment Rate - Secondary Female
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of school-age girls who are actually enrolled in secondary school (typically ages 12-17). Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better because they show more girls are getting an education. When more girls attend secondary school, it leads to better health outcomes, economic opportunities, and overall development for families and communities.

nodes.label: Employment Rate
nodes.description: This shows the percentage of working-age people who currently have jobs, whether part-time or full-time. Higher percentages indicate more people are employed rather than unemployed or not looking for work. High employment rates mean more families have income and the economy is creating enough jobs for people who want to work.

nodes.label: Employment in Industry
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total workforce has jobs in manufacturing, construction, mining, and utilities. The rate is expressed as a percentage of total employment. Higher percentages often indicate economic development and industrialization, as countries typically move workers from agriculture to industry as they develop economically.

nodes.label: Male Employment in Industry
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of working men have jobs in manufacturing, construction, mining, and utilities. The rate is expressed as a percentage of total male employment. Higher percentages often indicate industrial development and typically provide stable, middle-class wages that support economic growth and family well-being.

nodes.label: Female Employment in Non-Agricultural Sectors
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of working women who have jobs outside of farming, such as in manufacturing, services, or office work. Higher percentages typically indicate more diverse economic opportunities for women and suggest a more developed economy. When women can work in various sectors beyond agriculture, it often leads to higher incomes and greater gender equality.

nodes.label: Employment Rate by International Labour Organization Standards
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of working-age people who have jobs, calculated using international standards that make it easy to compare between countries. Values typically range from 40% to 80%, where higher rates are generally better because they indicate more people are productively employed. High employment rates usually mean stronger economies and better living standards for families.

nodes.label: Female Employment in Industry
nodes.description: This measures the percentage of working women who have jobs in manufacturing, construction, mining, and utilities rather than agriculture or services. Values typically range from 5% to 35%. Higher industrial employment for women often indicates economic development and diversification away from agriculture toward higher-paying manufacturing jobs.

nodes.label: Middle Class Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of total national income goes to middle-income earners, showing how wealth is distributed across society. Higher values indicate a stronger middle class with a larger share of economic resources. A strong middle class typically indicates more economic equality and opportunities for social mobility.

nodes.label: Middle Class Pre-tax Income
nodes.description: This measures the average income earned by middle-income adults (typically the 40th to 90th percentiles) before taxes, including wages, business profits, and investment returns. Higher values indicate the middle class is earning more money. This matters because a prosperous middle class drives economic growth and political stability in most countries.

nodes.label: Middle Class Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total income goes to middle-income earners. Higher values indicate a larger, more prosperous middle class with a bigger share of national income. This matters because a strong middle class typically indicates a healthy economy with good opportunities for most people to achieve financial stability.

nodes.label: Middle Class Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total income goes to the middle class (middle-income earners). Higher values indicate a larger, more prosperous middle class. This matters because a strong middle class typically indicates a healthy economy with good opportunities for social mobility and stable living standards.

nodes.label: Middle-Class Income Share (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average income level of middle-income earners as part of the overall population's income distribution. Higher values suggest a larger or more prosperous middle class with decent-paying jobs. This matters because a strong middle class typically indicates a healthy economy with opportunities for most people to achieve financial stability.

nodes.label: Middle Class Pre-tax Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average income that middle-class people earn before paying taxes, including wages and investment returns. Higher values mean middle-class families have more money coming in before taxes. This is important because middle-class income levels show how well a country's economy is working for typical families.

nodes.label: Middle Class After-tax Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures how much money middle-class people actually take home after paying all their taxes. Higher values mean middle-class families have more spending power for their daily needs. This shows the real financial situation of typical families and their ability to maintain a decent standard of living.

nodes.label: Middle Class Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what portion of total national income goes to middle-class earners across the entire population. Higher values mean the middle class receives a larger share of the country's wealth. A strong middle class is important because it drives economic growth, political stability, and social mobility.

nodes.label: Middle Class Tax Burden
nodes.description: This tracks the tax obligations or after-tax income of middle-class earners across the population. The interpretation depends on whether it measures taxes paid (higher = more burden) or after-tax income (higher = better). This matters because middle-class tax levels affect spending power and economic growth.

nodes.label: Middle-Income Share of National Income
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total income goes to middle-class households. Higher percentages (closer to 100%) indicate a stronger middle class and more equal income distribution. A healthy middle class is important for economic stability and social mobility opportunities.

nodes.label: Middle Class Income for All Groups
nodes.description: This measures the income levels of middle-class households across all demographic groups in a country. Values are typically shown in dollars or as percentages, and higher values generally indicate a stronger and more prosperous middle class. A healthy middle class is important for economic stability and social well-being, as these families drive consumer spending and economic growth.

nodes.label: Total Economic Output per Person
nodes.description: This measures the total value of all goods and services produced in a country divided by its population, showing average economic productivity per person. Higher values indicate a more productive economy and typically higher living standards. This matters because countries with higher economic output per person generally have better jobs, wages, and opportunities for their citizens.

nodes.label: Market-Based Social Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the average income that all people earn from social programs that operate through market mechanisms rather than direct government payments. Higher values indicate more income from these market-based programs. This shows how well social programs are working to provide financial support while using market approaches.

nodes.label: Market-Based Social Spending (All Categories)
nodes.description: This measures total spending on social programs that work through market mechanisms rather than direct government provision. Higher values indicate more market-based social investment. These programs can help people access services like healthcare and education while supporting economic growth.

nodes.label: Market Social Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This tracks the total social income earned through market activities across all population groups, measuring economic activity and income distribution. Higher values indicate more market-based social income being generated in the economy. This matters because it shows how well the economy is creating income opportunities for all social groups.

nodes.label: Market Social Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This tracks social income generated through market mechanisms across all population groups, measuring how economic activity translates into social benefits. Higher values suggest better integration of market activity with social outcomes. This matters because it shows how well the economy serves broader social needs beyond just profit.

nodes.label: Market-Based Social Wealth Share
nodes.description: This measures how wealth from market activities (business, trade, investments) is distributed across social groups before government intervention. Higher values indicate more equal market-generated wealth distribution. This matters because it shows whether a country's economy naturally creates opportunities for all social groups or concentrates wealth among the few.

nodes.label: Market-Based Social Capital Income Share
nodes.description: This measures how income from investments and capital (like profits from stocks, real estate, or business ownership) is distributed across social groups through market forces alone. Higher values indicate more equal distribution of investment income. This matters because it shows whether investment opportunities and returns are accessible to all social groups or concentrated among the wealthy.

nodes.label: Market Income Before Taxes and Transfers
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from jobs, businesses, and investments before the government takes out taxes or adds benefits like welfare. Higher values indicate people earn more from market activities. This matters because it shows how well the economy provides income opportunities before government intervention.

nodes.label: Market Social Income Growth (All Groups)
nodes.description: This tracks how much income from both jobs and government benefits is changing over time for all income groups. Higher values mean people's total income is growing faster. This matters because steady income growth helps families improve their living conditions and plan for the future.

nodes.label: Market Social Income Share
nodes.description: This tracks the share of total income earned by a specific social group before taxes and government transfers, as measured by the World Inequality Database. Values are typically percentages, where changes over time show whether income inequality is increasing or decreasing. This helps understand how fairly economic growth is distributed across society.

nodes.label: Social Market Income Distribution
nodes.description: This tracks how income is distributed in the population through market mechanisms combined with social policies. Higher values typically indicate more equitable distribution through social programs. This matters because balanced income distribution supports social cohesion and ensures broader access to opportunities and resources.

nodes.label: Social Benefits from Market Income
nodes.description: This measures social benefits and transfers that people receive, calculated relative to market-based income levels. Higher values indicate more generous social programs compared to average earnings. This affects quality of life by providing financial support for healthcare, education, and basic needs.

nodes.label: Market Income Including Capital Gains (All Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the total income people earn from jobs, investments, and business profits (including one-time gains from selling assets) across all adults in a country. Higher values indicate people are earning more from market activities. This shows how much economic activity generates income for people before government taxes and transfers.

nodes.label: Average National Income (All Adults)
nodes.description: This measures the average total income available to all adults in a country, including wages, profits, and government transfers. Higher values indicate people have more income available overall. This provides a broad picture of economic prosperity and how much money flows to individuals in the economy.

nodes.label: Market Factor Income Share
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of a country's total income from wages, profits, and investments goes to a specific income group before taxes and government transfers. Higher percentages mean that group captures more of the economic value created by the market. This matters because it shows how fairly the benefits of economic growth are distributed among different income levels.

nodes.label: Market-Based Income Distribution
nodes.description: This measures how income from wages, profits, and investments is distributed among people before government taxes and transfers. Higher values may indicate greater income inequality or concentration. This matters because the distribution of market income affects overall fairness and economic opportunity in society.

nodes.label: Market Income from Capital and Business
nodes.description: This measures the total income that comes from owning capital (like stocks, bonds, real estate) and running businesses, before taxes and government transfers. Higher values indicate more income flowing to capital owners rather than workers. This matters because it shows how much of a country's economic gains go to property and business owners versus employees.

nodes.label: Market Income Share - All Income Groups
nodes.description: This measures how total income from wages, business profits, and investments is distributed across all income levels in a country before taxes and government transfers. Higher values for wealthy groups indicate greater income inequality. This matters because extreme concentration of market income can limit opportunities for economic mobility and social stability.

nodes.label: Market Income from Industry (All Population)
nodes.description: This measures the average income people earn from industrial jobs and businesses like manufacturing, construction, and mining. Higher values indicate that industrial sectors are providing better-paying jobs to workers. This matters because strong industrial income often indicates a developing economy that can provide stable, well-paying employment.

nodes.label: Market Income Inequality (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures how unequally income from jobs, businesses, and investments is distributed among all people in a country before government transfers. Higher values indicate bigger gaps between rich and poor from market activities alone. This is important because high inequality can lead to social tensions and limit opportunities for people from lower-income backgrounds.

nodes.label: Market Income Before Taxes
nodes.description: This measures income that people earn from jobs, businesses, and investments before any taxes are taken out or government benefits are added. Higher values indicate people are earning more from their economic activities. This matters because market income shows the underlying economic opportunities available to people for supporting themselves and their families.

nodes.label: Market Income (All Groups)
nodes.description: This measures the total income that all people earn from market activities like jobs, businesses, and investments, before government taxes or transfers. Higher values indicate a stronger economy where people earn more from their work. This shows how well the private economy is providing income opportunities for residents.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 21501
nodes.description: This tracks household expenditures on a specific category of goods or services, based on international purchasing power comparisons. Higher spending levels typically indicate people have more disposable income for this category. This is important because it reveals living standards and what goods or services people can access in their daily lives.

nodes.label: Household Spending Category 21505
nodes.description: This measures how much households in a country typically spend on a specific category of goods or services (the exact category would need to be identified from ICP documentation). The values show spending amounts, usually in international dollars for comparison across countries. Understanding household spending patterns helps show people's living standards and priorities.

nodes.label: Spending on Recreational and Cultural Services
nodes.description: This measures how much money people in a country spend on entertainment, sports, cultural activities, and recreational services. Values are typically in dollars per person or as a percentage of total spending, and higher values indicate more discretionary spending. This matters because it reflects people's quality of life and their ability to afford activities beyond basic necessities.

nodes.label: Personal Care Spending
nodes.description: This tracks household spending on personal care items like cosmetics, toiletries, and grooming services. Higher values indicate people are spending more on personal care products. This matters because personal care spending reflects disposable income and cultural priorities around health and appearance.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 21502
nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 21504
nodes.description: This measures how much money households in a country spend on a specific type of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values are typically shown as dollar amounts or percentages of total spending. Higher values indicate that people in that country spend more money on this particular category of items, which helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 26652
nodes.description: This tracks household spending on a particular category of goods or services as part of international price studies. Higher amounts indicate greater expenditure on this specific category. Understanding spending patterns helps policymakers know what matters most to families' daily lives.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 26603
nodes.description: This measures how much money households spend on a specific category of goods or services, used to compare living costs between countries. Higher values mean people spend more money on this particular category. This helps understand what people can afford and how they prioritize their spending across different countries.

nodes.label: Price Comparison Category 42104
nodes.description: This measures the relative cost of a specific category of goods or services when comparing prices between different countries using international classification systems. Values show how expensive this category is compared to other places. This matters because price differences affect how much people can buy with their income and their overall standard of living.

nodes.label: Healthcare Spending
nodes.description: This tracks total household spending on medical services, medicines, and health-related goods as part of consumption. Higher values show families are spending more on healthcare. This matters because healthcare spending reflects both health needs and access to medical services in a country.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 26591
nodes.description: This measures how much money households spend on a specific category of goods or services, based on international price comparison studies. Higher values mean people in that country spend more money on this particular category. This helps economists compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 20183
nodes.description: This tracks household spending on a specific category of goods or services, measured using international price comparison methods. Higher spending typically reflects greater purchasing power and access to these particular goods or services. This is important because spending patterns reveal quality of life and what necessities or luxuries people can afford.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison - Category 20064
nodes.description: This measures how much money people in different countries spend on a specific type of goods or services, with prices adjusted to allow fair comparisons between nations. Higher values indicate more spending in this category. This helps understand living costs and spending priorities across different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 20182
nodes.description: This tracks household spending on a specific category of goods or services within the International Comparison Program's classification system. Values represent expenditure amounts in local currency, with higher numbers showing increased spending on this category. Spending patterns help economists understand living standards and consumer priorities across different countries.

nodes.label: Spending on Personal Care Services
nodes.description: This measures how much money people spend on personal care services like haircuts, beauty treatments, and wellness services, adjusted for international price differences. Higher spending often indicates higher disposable income and access to service industries. This reflects people's ability to spend on services that improve personal well-being beyond basic necessities.

nodes.label: Spending on Insurance Services
nodes.description: This measures how much money people spend on various types of insurance, including health, auto, home, and life insurance. Values are typically in dollars per person, and higher values can indicate either better insurance coverage or higher insurance costs. This is important because adequate insurance protects people from financial disasters due to accidents, illness, or property damage.

nodes.label: Recreation and Culture Spending
nodes.description: This measures household spending on entertainment, sports, cultural activities, and recreational goods. Higher values show people are spending more on leisure and cultural activities. This matters because recreation spending indicates disposable income levels and quality of life beyond basic needs.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison Category 20165
nodes.description: This measures price levels for a specific category of goods or services used in international comparisons of living costs. The values help determine how expensive this category is in different countries. This matters because it helps accurately compare living standards and purchasing power across nations.

nodes.label: Household Spending Category 42620
nodes.description: This measures how much households in a country typically spend on a specific category of goods or services (the exact category would need to be identified from ICP documentation). The values show spending amounts, usually in international dollars for comparison across countries. Understanding household spending patterns helps show what people prioritize and can afford in their daily lives.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 42654
nodes.description: This measures household expenditure on a specific type of good or service used in international cost-of-living comparisons. Higher values mean households spend more money on this particular category. This helps economists understand what people buy and how expensive different items are across countries.

nodes.label: International Price Comparison Category
nodes.description: This tracks the relative prices of a specific category of goods or services across different countries for international economic comparisons. The values help economists understand cost differences between countries for this particular type of spending. This data helps determine how much purchasing power people have when buying similar items in different countries.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category
nodes.description: This represents another specific category of household spending tracked in international comparisons, though the exact goods or services aren't specified. These categories help economists understand what people prioritize in their spending across different countries. Spending patterns reveal important information about living standards and economic development.

nodes.label: Consumer Spending Category 42097
nodes.description: This measures how much households spend on a specific category of goods or services, as tracked by the International Comparison Program (ICP). The values show spending amounts in local currency, with higher values indicating more money spent on this particular category. This helps compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Spending Category 41907
nodes.description: This represents spending on a specific category of goods or services as part of international price comparisons between countries. The exact category depends on the classification system, but higher values mean more money is spent in this particular area. This matters because it helps compare living standards and spending patterns across different countries.

nodes.label: Working-Age Population
nodes.description: This counts the total number of people between ages 15-64, which represents the main working-age population in a country. Higher numbers indicate more people available to work and contribute to the economy. This matters because a larger working-age population can drive economic growth and support older and younger generations who depend on workers for support.

nodes.label: Measles Vaccination Rate for Toddlers
nodes.description: This measures what percentage of children between 12-23 months old have received the measles vaccine. Values range from 0% to 100%, where higher percentages are better and indicate stronger public health systems. High vaccination rates protect children from a dangerous disease that can cause brain damage or death.
